<SLUG> BC-CBO-DEBT-WIZARDS-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL SEERS, TELLING NATION'S FISCAL FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kathy Gramp peered beneath the stacks of paper on
her desk and poked through the drawers, an expression of bafflement
on her face. Her calculator was at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's here somewhere,'' she insisted, rolling her eyes. She
seemed to appreciate the strangeness of this particular piece of
equipment vanishing, given her job. Ms. Gramp is one of the workers
at the Congressional Budget Office who crunch the numbers that tell
the country's financial fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Ms. Gramp, who refers to herself as ``chatty Kathy''
and points to the strands beneath her headband when she mentions
``senior, gray-haired analysts,'' tries not to take her task, or
herself, too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   On a wall just outside her office, she and her colleagues have
hung various symbols and objects that they jokingly refer to as the
real tools of their predictive trade. There is a Ouija board, a
crystal ball, a bag of tea leaves, a pair of dice and,
incongruously, a plastic replica of a breakfast food.
</P>
<P>
   ``A waffle,'' Ms. Gramp explained. ``We waffle.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true only to a point. But Ms. Gramp's comic riff
underscored a larger reality.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the lofty, quasi-mystical budget numbers that
sporadically rise from the nation's capital sit scores of everyday
people like Ms. Gramp _ scattered, self-effacing and fully aware of
the intrinsic, inevitable flaws in their convoluted guessing game.
</P>
<P>
   That game produced some especially startling results last week.
Revising calculations they had made earlier in the year, officials
at both the CBO and the White House's Office of Management and
Budget, which produces its own set of figures, announced that the
federal surplus over the next 10 years would, in fact, be hundreds
of billions of dollars larger than they had previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the total surplus over that period was projected to be
about $2.9 trillion, roughly $1 trillion of which was up for
legislative grabs.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers almost instantly altered the political landscape.
There were fresh hopes and refined designs for the long-term fiscal
survival of Social Security and Medicare. There was new momentum
for sweeping tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   And there were, for the confounded observer, several questions:
How did this happen, and who were the instigators?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gramp is one, although her piece of the pie is minuscule.
One of about 200 people employed by the budget office, she analyzes
and projects how much the federal government will spend each year
on an array of programs related to science, basing her estimates in
large part on the spending caps that Congress enacted in 1997 and
mathematical formulas that predict when the people who receive
federal grants are likely to actually cash those checks. (Believe
it or not, some wait a while.)
</P>
<P>
   To produce a complete portrait of federal expenditures in the
future, her figure joins comparable estimates from people who
specialize in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Deb _ she does national parks and wetlands and
endangered species,'' Ms. Gramp said one recent afternoon as she
navigated a warren of offices on the fourth floor of a building
relegated to a distant corner of Capitol Hill: a congressional
Siberia of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a transportation analyst behind you,'' Ms. Gramp added
as she rounded a corner.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the puzzle is revenue, also known as taxes,
and that is where the indefatigable economy has produced income for
the federal government that has been exceeding expectations for the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Kasten works in this area, and he does so somewhat
invisibly, which is a judgment not on his influence or personality
but on his desktop. Every square millimeter has a leaning tower of
paper rising from it, and the shortest tower is at least 2 feet
tall. Only the top of Kasten's scalp can be seen from the door of
his office.
</P>
<P>
   Kasten has a doctorate in economics from the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, but he concedes that his job has as much
to do with arithmetic as with abstruse economic theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need for this,'' Kasten explained, ``is a little bit
of economic training, a lot of common sense and something like an
instinct for numbers, so you can spot new trends.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what Kasten does _ and what is done by the economic
forecasters in the CBO and the OMB, who provide the template for
him and other players in this process _ is extrapolate from the
present into the future, using history as a guide and making
informed judgments about changes on the horizon to tweak that model
and amend their calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Penner, a former director of the Congressional Budget
Office, explained: ``I might look at what these equations tell me,
but I might stare at an equation and say, `Well, we've never had a
stock market like the one we're having now.' I'm going to adjust
the results. I'm going to assume that consumption will be a little
higher.' That's a judgment. That's where the art comes in.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The further that analysts gaze into the future, the faultier
their assumptions are bound to be; they cannot, for starters,
anticipate new legislation that may affect the economy, tax
revenues and expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reischauer, another former director of the budget office,
said that a 10-year projection ``is our best judgment of where we
will end up if we remain on automatic pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reischauer added, ``Our whole political system is designed
to fly the plane, not to allow it to continue on automatic pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there are the unexpected pockets of turbulence.
Lately, they have been happy spasms. For example, in early 1994,
the OMB projected a federal budget deficit for 1998 of $190.5
billion. Instead, the federal government had a $69 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong _ or, rather, right? Joseph Minarik, the chief
economist for the OMB, explained that additional revenue was
brought in by an unexpectedly surging economy, a dizzying stock
market and ``the power of compound interest.'' On top of all that,
the federal government tightened its spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future is uncertain,'' Minarik said with a smile and a
shrug. ``I cannot quarrel with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Minarik, who once worked as a tax analyst for the Congressional
Budget Office, has a doctorate in economics from Yale. But
economics degrees are not prerequisites for peering into the fiscal
future.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Holland, who interprets the probable impact of economic
forecasts on the federal budget for the CBO, has a master's degree
in public policy from Carnegie-Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his job, he said, boils down to numerical calculations,
but not the kind that require a supercomputer or other arcane
technology. He often works with Lotus software on a Dell computer,
and to break the occasional monotony, he plays rock music over the
speakers attached to the machine. The stack of compact discs on a
cabinet in his office include Aerosmith, Blondie and the
Pretenders.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gramp is just down the hall, in a section of the budget
office noted for its ersatz art gallery. For every kind of federal
outlay that the analysts there study, there is a corresponding
framed poster of a famous painting or print.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Van Gogh's ``Fishing Boats on the Beach at
Sainte-Marie-de-la-Mer'' represents federal expenditures on
fisheries and water transportation. Georgia O'Keefe's ``Cliffs
Beyond Abiqui'' symbolizes spending on public and Indian lands.
</P>
<P>
   Outlays for national disasters have no visual analogue. ``We're
still trying to find a good picture of a tsunami,'' Ms. Gramp said.
</P>
</TEXT>
