<SLUG> BC-NY-FATHER-SLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED IN FATHER'S DEATH WANTED TO DIE TOO, OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 49-year-old man accused of killing his ailing
father in a Brooklyn hospital on Saturday _ before brutally
attacking his sister and his father's elderly hospital roommate _
told investigators that he had wanted to put his father out of his
misery and to die in the attempt, a law enforcement official said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Joseph Raineri Jr., told investigators that he had
attacked his father, who was suffering from cancer of the liver,
out of mercy, the official said. When it was done, according to the
official, Raineri said he had hoped to goad police into killing
him, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``His plan was to have the police shoot him,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The attack took place at Victory Memorial Hospital in the Dyker
Heights section of Brooklyn at noon on Saturday. Armed with a knife
and a hammer, Raineri went to visit his father, Joseph Raineri Sr.,
74, and slashed his throat, police said. Police said the young
Raineri then turned the knife on his sister, Linda Raineri, 46,
seriously wounding her, and after that, beat his father's roommate,
Michael D'Ambrose, 88, with the hammer.
</P>
<P>
   D'Ambrose _ who was mistakenly reported dead in some editions of
The New York Times on Sunday _ was in fact seriously injured, and
remained in very critical condition Sunday at Lutheran Medical
Center in Brooklyn, said Paul-Anthony Magadia, a hospital
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman who was asked about D'Ambrose's condition by
a New York Times reporter on Saturday evening said D'Ambrose had
died of his wounds at 6:40 p.m., police officials said Sunday. But
when the Police Department learned shortly after 9 p.m. that
D'Ambrose was still alive, though brain-dead, no one contacted The
Times with the corrected information, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The young Raineri, an unemployed taxi driver, lived with his
father and sister in a small second-floor apartment on 64th Street,
and had grown distraught over his father's deteriorating medical
condition, police said. After the attack, Raineri told
investigators that he believed that D'Ambrose had somehow been
bothering his father in the hospital, the law enforcement official
said.
</P>
<P>
   So after Raineri killed his father, the official said, he also
decided to attack D'Ambrose. The official said Raineri also told
investigators that he decided to attack his sister because he did
not approve of the way she lived her life.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Raineri was awaiting arraignment on charges of
murder and attempted murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
