<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS AVOID SWEEP, BEAT BRAVES, 7-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets were doing just about everything
they had not been able to do against the Atlanta Braves the three
previous times they met. The Mets had scored. They had even led.
And they were still three innings away from being swept at home
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets did not disappoint the holiday crowd of 32,699 at
Shea Stadium. They fought back. Edgardo Alfonzo smacked a three-run
home run off John Smoltz in the seventh inning to wipe out a
two-run deficit, and the Mets held on for a 7-6 victory over the
first-place Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets took the final game of a three-game series despite Orel
Hershiser, their starter, having allowed four home runs. Two of
them came off the bat of Bret Boone, who narrowly missed a third.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo had narrowly missed a homer to straightaway center
earlier in the game. When he stepped to the plate with one out in
the seventh, the Mets were eight outs away from falling six games
back of the Braves. Rey Ordonez, who had singled to lead off the
inning, and Brian McRae, who had walked, were on second and third
after Rickey Henderson had sacrificed them there. Alfonzo is Mets
manager Bobby Valentine's favorite hitter with runners in scoring
position. Again, he showed why.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Andruw Jones had crashed into the center-field
fence to rob Alfonzo of extra bases. This time, after Alfonzo
drilled a 93 mph fastball to the left of the 410 sign in
straightaway center, Jones leapt again, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz nearly walked into the Braves' dugout off of third base
as he watched the flight of the ball. He knew what was coming.
Atlanta manager Bobby Cox would soon be on his way to take him out.
</P>
<P>
   But it was too late. Dennis Cook tossed a scoreless eighth for
the Mets, and Armando Benitez, in his first save opportunity since
John Franco went on the disabled list Saturday, closed the victory
out by striking out Boone, Chipper Jones and Brian Jordan in a
perfect ninth.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets were four games behind the Braves instead of six.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser had allowed consecutive 400-plus foot home runs to
Boone and Jones with one out in the first.
</P>
<P>
   It had been three games plus an inning since the Mets had scored
against Atlanta pitching. And with Smoltz, the National League's
leader in earned run average (3.03) facing them, the prospect of an
offensive outburst did not seem promising.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Braves took the 2-0 lead, the Mets put a rally
together in their first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson fouled off a pair of full-count pitches before
blooping a single to right that dropped in front of three Braves.
Alfonzo worked a full-count walk. John Olerud blasted a one-hop
infield single off Jones' glove at third. And the Mets had loaded
the bases for Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza has been struggling with runners in scoring position.
Since May 15, he had been just 5 for 43, a miserable .116. But
Piazza took a ball and then ripped a line drive over second base
for a two-run single. The Mets had scored their first runs against
Atlanta in 29 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura then surprisingly pushed a bunt up the third base
line. Jones barehanded the ball and easily threw Ventura out at
first. But Ventura was awarded a sacrifice, as Olerud and Piazza
moved to second and third. And when Benny Agbayani drove Olerud in
with a grounder to second, the Mets had a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser pitched a decent second after allowing a first-pitch
lead-off double to Randall Simon, who was eventually stranded at
third. And the Mets tacked on a two-out run in the bottom of the
second, when Henderson blooped another single to right, just inside
the line, and scored on Alfonzo's double to right center.
</P>
<P>
   But it soon became obvious that Hershiser had little on his
pitches in the heat. Boone, whose first homer had cleared the fence
in the back of the bullpen in left, opened the third with another
homer to cut the Mets' lead to 4-3. Jones then drew a walk. Alfonzo
did not get in front of a one-hop smash from Brian Jordan that was
scored as a single with Jones advancing to third. And Ryan Klesko
lofted a sacrifice fly to center to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser struck out Andruw Jones on a sinker. But Hershiser
left his first pitch to Simon up. And Simon, who had missed a home
run by a matter of feet in the second, did not miss this time. His
two-run drive landed near the base of the scoreboard in right for a
6-4 Braves lead.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, Hershiser hit Eddie Perez on the left
shoulder with a change-up. Perez started to make his way to the
mound as Hershiser apparently explained that he was not trying to
hit him. That made sense. The 40-year-old right-hander did not hit
too many spots Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets survived Hershiser's problems. Alfonzo saw to that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
