<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM CARRIES WOMEN'S SPORTS ON WEARY LEGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ It's official now, which should make FIFA,
U.S. Soccer, ESPN, Nike, Adidas, little girls, big boys, women and
soccer fans across the 50 United States extremely happy:
</P>
<P>
   They can do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Women's World Cup team can show up for huge games like
Sunday's semifinal with dead legs and mental fatigue and still hold
up its end of the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   What bargain is that?
</P>
<P>
   Well, only to carry the world's largest-ever women's sporting
event on their shoulders and, while they're at it, to keep their
composure and natural good looks intact while the audience grows
bigger and more intrigued each step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is history in the making,'' Mia Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are bigger things happening here than just us winning a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the home team may not have been extraordinarily skilled
or superlatively organized, but it was just a tad less tired than
Brazil, so there you go. That was a big enough advantage,
especially on the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   America loves a party, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The United States won 2-0. The dread of the deadly semifinal _
where the U.S. women were eliminated in the 1995 Women's World Cup
in Sweden _ is over with.
</P>
<P>
   And afterward, someone asked U.S. goalkeeper Briana Scurry what
was her immediate reaction to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Excitement? Exhaustion? Relief?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Scurry said with a smile, meaning she was all of the
above and perhaps more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be in the final and it's going to be great to
have five days to recuperate.''
</P>
<P>
   It was tough to tell if the U.S. women's big date next Saturday
at the Rose Bowl or the five days of rest, massages and California
sun were making Scurry smile so wide.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the women have arrived at their promised land, even
if Sunday's effort won't be the subject of any tear-jerking,
awe-inspiring highlight films.
</P>
<P>
   The United States reversed a trend of early game ineffectiveness
and scored a goal on Cindy Parlow's header just five minutes into
the match before it was clear that neither the Americans nor the
Brazilians had fared too well in their cross-country travels.
</P>
<P>
   The jittery and usually artistic feet of the Brazilians were
slowed to a fox trot, especially in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the smatterings of yellow-shirted Brazilian fans _ ever
moving and dancing to drums and samba beats in the packed Stanford
Stadium stands _ could cajole any extra juice from the fleet and
dangerous Brazilian players named Tania and Katia, Pretinha and
even star striker, Sissi.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 73,123 spectators (12,000 of whom bought tickets
between Friday and Sunday's 1:30 p.m. kickoff) who took their place
in Hamm's history lesson were not deterred by the obvious lack of
fresh legs in this game.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Hamm, the darling of this tournament, could muster a
rush to the goal that resulted in any pyrotechnics _ as she had as
if on cue during the United States' made-for-TV opener two weeks
ago at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's drives all died deep in the box Sunday, as the crowd
sighed and hoped out loud. But Hamm was caught trying one too many
spins or cuts before being tackled or knocked off the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did Hamm work up a dramatic offensive rush _ and that
one ended with Hamm being upended by Brazil's Elane, creating the
penalty kick that Michelle Akers so deliberately knocked into the
back of Brazil's net.
</P>
<P>
   Even that goal was created by the match's overall fatigue
factor.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Tony DiCicco had noticed that Brazil's Juliana was
not keeping pace with Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew she was falling off so if we could get behind her, Mia
would have a chance to go one-on-one with Elane,'' DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to look at the tape to see about that foul, but to
us, it looked like a foul and frankly, those are the types of
situations where you're going to get those types of calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Akers' goal on the penalty kick in the 80th minute sealed
the U.S. win _ and the United States players did not hesitate in
accepting that not all of their achievements have to be as pretty
as, well, them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most nerve-racking game, the semifinal. We were a
tired team,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the perky crowd empathized with the fact that both
Brazil and the United States had each battled in tough quarterfinal
matches just three days earlier _ three time zones away.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was pounded by Germany on Thursday night and
Brazil was dogged by Nigeria in games in Washington, D.C., where
the president was on hand and during which sports talk radio jocks
(mostly male) across the country confessed they were getting
seriously caught up in World Cup fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game, it's a long tournament and you're going
to have a game like this,'' Shannon MacMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the team has all but pledged that things will be
different during the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play our best game for 90 minutes,'' Akers said.
</P>
<P>
   But for a team that has given the summer and the sporting
landscape such a feeling of freshness and beauty, it earned the
right to just gut one out.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
