<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RECORD DAY FOR SPRINTERS IN STAKES AT BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Temperatures soared but records fell at Belmont
Park on Sunday, as the two featured holiday races produced a stakes
record and a track record.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes record was set in the $150,000 Tom Fool Handicap by
Crafty Friend, a 6-year-old horse who had won just one race in each
of the last two years. This time he started fast and finished fast,
prevailing by three-quarters of a length over Affirmed Success, the
favorite, who had five lengths on Artax, the second favorite. And
he certainly confused the standing in racing's sprint division.
</P>
<P>
   The horses broke from the gate 1-2-3 and stayed in that
alignment: Crafty Friend guarding a thin lead for all seven
furlongs, with Affirmed Success at his heels and Artax stalking.
They flew the first quarter of a mile in 22 3/5 seconds, half a
mile in 44 4/5 and three-quarters in 1:08 flat. At the finish,
Crafty Friend, with Richard Migliore riding, had his biggest lead
of the race.
</P>
<P>
   He ran the seven-eighths of a mile in 1:20 3/5, two-fifths of a
second off the track record for the distance but one-fifth of a
second faster than the record for the race, set in 1978 by J.O.
Tobin and equaled in 1993 by Birdonthewire. He paid $10.80 for a $2
bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   John Kimmel, who began training Crafty Friend last spring after
Wally Dollase was relieved of the role by Thoroughbred Corp., has
turned the horse around. Since then, he ran first in an allowance,
second to Sir Bear in the Metropolitan Mile and first in the Tom
Fool on Sunday after passing up the Iselin Handicap at Monmouth
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing was, he likes this track,'' Kimmel said. ``He
runs game when he's here. In the Met Mile, he got outrun in the
last sixteenth of a mile. My intuition said seven-eighths. He
showed he's a classy animal.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Affirmed Success, his trainer, Richie Schosberg, said,
``He gave a game effort but just didn't get the job done.'' Jorge
Chavez, who rode the favorite, said: ``The heat may have hurt him a
little bit. I tried to stay close to the winner, but he was too
good.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ernie Paragallo, the owner of Artax, said, ``He was in
perfect striking position, but just didn't fire.''
</P>
<P>
   A Very Fast 2-Year-Old
</P>
<P>
   Record speed was also flashed in Sunday's other stakes at
Belmont, the Tremont, a sprint won in the past by such stars as Man
o' War, Buckpasser, Hansel, Alydar and Kelly Kip.
</P>
<P>
   The track record for five and a half furlongs was set at 1:03 by
Raise A Cup in 1973 and later equaled by Ruffian in 1975 and Salt
Lake in 1991. Now add the name of More Than Ready to this roster of
superfast 2-year-olds. He not only won the Tremont on Sunday but
also broke the record when he flashed the distance in 1:02 2/5
after leading all the way and showing an awesome burst of speed in
the homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he is 3, More Than Ready will be more than ready. He
made an early debut in April and won; he raced again in May and
June and won. And with his victory on Sunday, he made it 4 for 4
with half his juvenile year to go. He is owned by James
Scatuorichio and trained by Todd Pletcher, who said the Saratoga
series was next on his target list.
</P>
<P>
   With John Velazquez riding, More Than Ready finished 4{ widening
lengths in front of Afternoon Affair, who had nearly six lengths on
King Kokand. He paid $3 for a $2 bet to win, earned $65,040 and
faced Saratoga with a perfect record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fighter,'' Pletcher said. ``He was just on cruise
control today. We've spaced his races about a month apart. Our plan
has been to have him ready for the Sanford on July 29 or the
Saratoga Special on August 18 and ultimately the Hopeful on
September 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Frisk Me Now Triumphs
</P>
<P>
   Frisk Me Now, racing for the 36th time in a busy and successful
career, won for the 12th time when he prevailed Sunday in a
homestretch duel in the $350,000 Philip H. Iselin Handicap at
Monmouth Park in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old bay, owned by Carol Dender and trained by her
husband, Bob Durso, outran Call Me Mr. Vain and Black Cash, while
the favored Littlebitlively finished out of the money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
