<HEADLINE>
U.S. VICTORY MEANS TICKETS SHOULD GO QUICKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Those hoping to purchase Women's World Cup
tickets for Saturday's U.S.-China championship match at the Rose
Bowl better hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament organizers announced that more than 70,000 tickets
have been sold for the doubleheader, which include's a third-place
match between Norway and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. clinching a championship berth Sunday, Women's
World Cup president Marla Messing expects the remaining tickets for
the 92,000-seat stadium to be sold out early in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always optimistic that we could sell out the Rose Bowl
if the U.S. reached the final,'' said Messing. ``With our total
over 70,000, it is very realistic to expect that game will be sold
out now.''
</P>
<P>
   The day begins with the Brazil-Norway match at 10:15 a.m. At the
conclusion of that game, singer/actress Jenn
</P>
</TEXT>
