<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TO PLAYERS: AVOID BLAME GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Manager Davey Johnson emerged Sunday after a
one-hour meeting in the Los Angeles Dodgers clubhouse with a
message: Point fingers and they might get broken.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose laid-back approach has not brought the expected
results from his slumping team, was looking for a change. He has
held few meetings this season, most of them encouraging player
input.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a day after his team dropped 10 games under .500 for the
first time since 1992, Johnson had the floor. He didn't detail the
minutes of the meeting, but his point was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy messes up, we have to pick him up, not bury him,''
Johnson said. ``That's the media's job.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson doesn't read the papers, a lesson he learned managing
the New York Mets for 6{ seasons. Johnson said the idea for a
meeting came to him when he awoke at 2 a.m. Sunday. He sensed the
frustration of falling 9{ games behind San Francisco in the
National League West has hurt the players' concentration.
</P>
<P>
   __ On the mend: Mark Grudzielanek is in a hurry to get back and
help the slumping Dodgers. But the shortstop, disabled since June 1
with a broken right hand, continued his rehab assignment with
Single-A San Bernardino, going 2 for 4 Sunday against the Lancaster
JetHawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been killing me the last five weeks knowing I'm part of
(the Dodgers) but also knowing there's nothing I can do to help out
or even take part of the blame,'' said Grudzielanek, who is 3 for
14 in three rehab games and could remain in San Bernardino for a
couple of days more.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick hits: Raul Mondesi left Sunday night's game after six
innings with tightness in his right leg. Mondesi, who went 0 for 3
with two strikeouts after going 3 for 3 on Saturday, was replaced
in right field by Todd Hollandsworth. . . . Sunday's Fireworks
Night crowd of 54,731 was the seventh-largest regular season crowd
in Dodger Stadium history. . . . Despite the sellout, the game was
not televised because it was played during the window reserved for
ESPN's ``Sunday Night Baseball.'' It was just the eighth Dodgers
game not televised this season. When the Dodgers came to Los
Angeles in the late 1950s, they only televised the nine games
played in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
