A9340 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-05 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 Rookie Halama throws fine nine in blanking Rangers  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It's never easy with the Mariners, and Sunday
night was no different. John Halama got two quick outs in the ninth
inning, but then came a double. A walk. A hit by pitch. And a visit
from manager Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was down to his last hitter,'' Piniella said of his rookie
left-hander. ``But he pitched so well that he deserved the
opportunity to pitch a complete game and a shutout.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama took advantage of that chance. He got Lee Stevens on a
groundout to second on the next pitch, securing a 6-0 victory over
the Texas Rangers and bringing the M's within five games of the
division leaders. The largest regular-season crowd in the history
of The Ballpark in Arlington _ 47,204 _ had to wait until the
post-game fireworks show to have any fun.
</P>
<P>
   This night was all Halama's.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole game went at his pace,'' said veteran starter Jamie
Moyer. ``He didn't only have command of his pitches, he had command
of the game. As a pitcher, that's exactly what you want, that total
control of the game. We scored early and his attitude was, `That's
it, boys. Jump on.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have climbed aboard ever since Halama joined the
rotation, winning seven of his eight starts. Halama is 5-0 with a
2.91 earned-run average as a starter, and Sunday's effort was the
Mariners' first shutout and complete game since last September,
when Moyer blanked Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   For Halama, the win was hard-earned. He had thrown nine innings
in Oakland Monday, allowing one run but getting a no-decision. It
was 87 degrees at game time, and there are easier places to match a
career-high 126 pitches than Texas. Piniella said he'll scale back
Halama in his next start, scheduled for Saturday in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out of gas,'' Halama said. ``I have like nothing. The heat
just kicks you.''
</P>
<P>
   But the exhaustion couldn't keep Halama (7-2) from smiling
afterward, or pumping his fist slightly after the final out. He was
humble, as usual _ ``I'm not going to dominate a team,'' he said _
but acknowledged he did want to finish what he started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very determined,'' said Halama, who will send the game
ball home to his parents in Brooklyn. ``I wanted it, I would say
just as much as my teammates wanted me to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   No teammate showed that more than Charles Gipson. The rookie
came in for defense in the eighth inning, and turned a single _ and
potential two-on, no-out situation _ into a fielder's choice by
throwing out Stevens at second.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with two outs and two on in the ninth, Gipson dodged a
fleeing ball boy and dove head-first across the chalk line for a
foul ball. He didn't get the ball, but did tear his pants and
bloody his leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to go hard for him,'' Gipson said of Halama. ``It
was 6-0, he was going for a complete game, and here in Arlington,
with the guys they have, you give them chances and they can come
back on you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Mariners who came back on the Rangers this series,
storming from seven runs down to win Saturday and overcoming two
deficits before losing on Friday. The M's trail Texas by the same
margin they did before the teams met at the Kingdome June 25, but
in taking four of six the last two weekends, Seattle has kept the
Rangers from running away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to play good ball and stay in the race, stay
close,'' said designated hitter Edgar Martinez. ``You never know
what's going to happen later. It's the end of the first half, and
if we play a lot better in the second half, we'll be in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners did not have to come back Sunday. Alex Rodriguez
singled home David Bell in the first inning, and Martinez followed
with a three-run homer off the first pitch from veteran Mike Morgan
(9-6).
</P>
<P>
   Martinez came into the game having swung at the first pitch just
33 times in 301 plate appearances; at 11 percent, the lowest figure
in the American League. But there is an element of surprise to his
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when it's a guy I'm familiar with, I have an idea of
what they've got,'' Martinez said. ``A lot of times I'll still take
the first pitch, but in this situation I just thought it was
appropriate to be aggressive. They were throwing me first-pitch
strikes the whole series.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama used first-pitch strikes effectively, and they helped him
to the shutout. Moyer said he looked at the scoreboard at one point
and noticed Halama had thrown 16 balls and 54 strikes. ``That's
pitching,'' Moyer said.
</P>
<P>
   And Halama kept pitching until the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me something,'' said first baseman David Segui. ``He
was tired, he walked a guy and hit a guy, but he wasn't going to
let (Piniella) take him out. He earned a lot of respect today _ not
that he didn't have it before, but that's a tough team to shut
down, and he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
