<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILMAN KRAFT, 73, PUBLISHER ON THE ARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gilman Kraft, the owner of Playbill magazine in the 1960s and
more recently the owner and president of Performing Arts magazine
in California, died on June 27 at a hospital in Los Angeles. He was
73 and lived in Beverly Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, according to a statement released by
Performing Arts magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft was born in Union City, N.J., on April 22, 1926, and
worked during World War II as a linguist with the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Columbia College in 1947, Kraft started
the Reader's Subscription, a book club, and enlisted Lionel
Trilling and Jacques Barzun as editors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957, he took over the then-flagging Broadway program service
Playbill, which he owned and operated for nearly 10 years. He was
also the publisher of Show magazine in 1965 and 1966.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, he moved to Los Angeles and started Performing Arts
magazine, which serves the San Francisco Opera and Ballet, the
Pasadena Playhouse and more than 40 other venues in California. He
also worked as a real estate investor.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Ruth; two sons, Richard of Bel Air,
Calif., and Frank Pelosa of Reseda, Calif.; two daughters, Dana
Kitaj of Westwood, Calif., and Susan Pelosa of Agoura Hills,
Calif., and eight grandchildren.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
