<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TARLOFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANK TARLOFF, 83, SCREENWRITER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Tarloff, an Academy Award-winning screenwriter who was
blacklisted during the McCarthy era, died on June 25 at his home in
Beverly Hills, Calif. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Tarloff, along with S.H. Barnett and Peter Stone, won an Oscar
in 1964 for the screenplay of ``Father Goose,'' a comedy drama set
in the South Pacific during World War II and starring Cary Grant.
He was also the author of several books, including ``A Guide for
the Married Man,'' which he adapted for the screen.
</P>
<P>
   His many television credits included ``Make Room for Daddy,''
``I Married Joan,'' ``The Andy Griffith Show'' and ``The
Jeffersons.''
</P>
<P>
   During the years he was blacklisted, Tarloff lived in London.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Lee Barrie; a daughter, Julie Owen,
and a son, Erik, both of Berkeley, Calif., and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
