A9361 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-BRAZIL-BOS &LR;      07-05 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WIN A KEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ You didn't think Uncle Sam's nieces (and
mamas) were going to lose to Brazil on the Fourth of July on home
soil did you? Just because it happened to his nephews here five
years ago to the day didn't mean history would repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't mean the US women's soccer team didn't have to
sweat mightily Sunday afternoon to reach the World Cup final that
everybody but themselves seemed to take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who we play in the final,'' said defender Brandi
Chastain, after the Americans had shut out the samba sisters, 2-0,
before 73,123 at Stanford Stadium to earn a Saturday date with
China in the Rose Bowl. ``I'm just excited to be going.''
</P>
<P>
   The US, which has lost only one home match in three years and
was 8-1-1 against Brazil, didn't figure to lose this one. But it
wasn't until Michelle Akers slammed home a penalty kick in the 80th
minute that the Yanks felt sure they were going to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sweet and you want to savor it,'' said Akers, who played
the full 90 minutes despite taking a savage beating. ``This World
Cup has been a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   For 75 minutes, after they got a gift goal when Brazilian keeper
Maravilha bobbled a cross directly onto Cindy Parlow's forehead,
the Americans nursed a lead that threatened to vanish at any
moment. And if it hadn't been for keeper Briana Scurry, who saved
them literally one-handed, the US could have gone to overtime _ or
gone home for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got to be the best game I ever played,'' said the former
University of Massachusetts star, who made half a dozen stops,
including an outstretched palm job on a blast from Nene in the 56th
minute that would have tied the match. ``I feel awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Awesome and relieved. After coming from behind twice to defeat
Germany in the quarterfinals, the Americans were hoping for an
easier go with the Brazilians, who'd had to go to overtime to beat
the same Nigerians whom the US had blitzed, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   And after five minutes, it looked that the hosts might be in for
a holiday spree after Maravilha coughed up Julie Foudy's cross and
Parlow, sitting on the doorstep, headed it in for a gimme. ``We
knew she was weak in the air,'' said Parlow. ``So we crashed the
goal after every shot.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were no more gimmes, and well before halftime the
Yanks knew they were in for a match. Scurry had to come steaming
out to grab Pretinha's shot in the 30th minute, then Akers had to
pounce on a loose ball in the area in the 33d and clear it over the
crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Akers, the team's 33-year-old alpha female with the flowing
mane, played with a fierce urgency all day. In the first half
alone, she survived a headknocking with Katia that put both players
on the ground and a cleat to the face from Sissi that briefly put
Akers off the field. But each time, she got up and kept prowling.
</P>
<P>
   After a dozen knee surgeries and countless concussions, Akers
takes mere run-of-play mayhem for granted. ``It gets to the point
where you're so beat up,'' she shrugged, ``that another little ding
isn't going to stop you.''
</P>
<P>
   So Akers was still on the field at crunch time and when Mia Hamm
was pushed down in the penalty area by Brazilian captain Elane, it
was Akers who got the call for the PK.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm had seen precious little of the ball until supersub Shannon
MacMillan came on for Parlow in the 62d minute to shake things up.
Finally, she came dashing toward the goal with the ball. ``And the
next thing I knew, I was on the ground,'' Hamm said. ``I don't know
what it looked like, but . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians were howling no foul, but Finnish referee
Katriina Elovirta pointed to the spot. Up came Akers, whose penalty
kick tied the Norwegians and set up MacMillan's `golden goal' that
put the US in the Olympic final three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God we were ahead by a goal this time,'' Akers mused.
But she calmly blasted the ball cleanly to Maravilha's left and her
teammates were in the Cup final again. So they took their thank-you
lap, then flopped down delighted but depleted in the locker room.
Pasadena may be just down the road, but the topography is brutal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
