<HEADER>
A9363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-B     07-05 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'LEARY HOMER IGNITES RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Halfway through the Red Sox' first season without No.
42, who would have believed that if anyone needed a sympathy card,
it would be Mo Vaughn?
</P>
<P>
   But here sit the Sons of Jimy Williams, their midseason record
only two games off what it was a year ago (47-34 instead of 49-32)
after Bret Saberhagen, working quickly in breath-sapping heat,
coolly dispatched the White Sox, 5-2, Sunday in the rubber game of
this three-game set.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this time, they were 10 games behind the Yankees.
That deficit stands at three after Saberhagen, pitching into the
eighth inning for the first time since he first showed off his
stitched-spackled-and-stapled shoulder in a Red Sox uniform two
summers ago, allowed just five hits, walked no one, and threw just
70 pitches before giving way to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe produced three ground balls in the eighth, Tim
Wakefield worked the ninth for his eighth save, and the Sox, again
playing without Nomar Garciaparra but borne aloft on the shoulders
of Troy O'Leary _ and when did you ever think you'd entertain that
idea? _ headed for Florida and four games with the troublesome
Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really shows we have some guys who want to win and know
how to win,'' said center fielder Darren Lewis after the Red Sox
seized the lead on O'Leary's two-run home run in the third and
expanded on it in unglamorous but effective fashion to dispose of
Chicago. ``We didn't use Mo's absence as an excuse. We accepted it
as a challenge as a group, that we can play this game. We've got
guys who do a lot of little things that don't show up in a box
score, and we've had guys who have stepped in and played very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has stepped up more than O'Leary, who accepted Jaime
Navarro's invitation to swing at a 3-and-0 meatball with Mike
Stanley aboard on a two-out double in the third and hit it deep
into the right-field seats for his 17th home run, giving the Sox a
2-1 lead that they never gave back.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro, showing better judgment than he did on the mound,
didn't bother to stick around and explain why he gave O'Leary
anything to hit with first base open and Lou Merloni on deck. One
can only guess, but maybe it's because Navarro has as much trouble
believing this about O'Leary as many of those about to read the
following words:
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, who now is tied with Garciaparra for the club lead in
RBIs with 57, has driven in more runs than Vaughn did by the midway
point last season.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn after the team's first 81 games: .327, 21 HRs, 16 2Bs, 56
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary at the same point this season: .309, 17 HRs, 20 2Bs, 57
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   With stats like that, O'Leary is liable of being accused
Garciaparra's protection in the Sox lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' Lewis said at the notion that the man known as Yummy
has outproduced the Hit Dog. ``I mean, that's tremendous, the fact
that he's been able to improve himself from last season. It seems
like every year he's getting to be a better player offensively and
defensively, which is definitely a big boost for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's picking us up offensively, especially with Nomar and Val
(John Valentin) out, and showing that he's growing as a player.
That's a credit to his perseverance in trying to become a better
player.''
</P>
<P>
   The little things to which Lewis alluded generated the other
three Sox runs. The rookie third baseman, Wilton Veras, scored some
big points with both his teammates and manager when he followed
Jason Varitek's double by rolling out to the right side. Varitek
took third on the play and scored on Lewis's infield out to make it
3-1 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid is hitting .180 (actually, .214) and he gets the
runner over,'' Jimy Williams said. ``He helped us win. There's no
stat for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni's infield hit knocked in the fourth run in the fifth,
and an inning later, Lewis drew a two-out walk, stole second, and
scored when Ray Durham kicked Jose Offerman's ground ball, one of
two errors made by the White Sox second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who hung a curveball to Paul Konerko in the second
inning that Konerko relocated to the left-field bleachers, was hurt
again in the fifth by Konerko, who hit a leadoff double and came
around to score Chicago's other run.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise, he set down the White Sox in order in four
innings and had retired nine in a row before giving up a double to
the first Chicago hitter in the eighth, Brook Fordyce. Since coming
off his second stint on the disabled list, Saberhagen has won three
straight starts, which for the Red Sox means he's gone from
stepping on glass to practically walking on water, a role
exclusively held by Pedro Martinez until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about Pedro for a reason,'' Saberhagen said. ``He's
the best pitcher I've seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't win with just one guy. George Brett wasn't able
to carry us to championships (in Kansas City) by himself. We had
other good guys to pick him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis puts it another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this point we've surprised a lot of people,'' he
said. ``And the reason why we're the way we are is we take the game
seriously and do whatever we can to win a ballgame, period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's us,'' Williams said. ``There's only one reason to play,
and that's to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
