<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS A HIGH FLYER AT WIMBLEDON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Pete Sampras is no longer the best male tennis player
in the world. He is merely the best male tennis player in world
history.
</P>
<P>
   A day after being displaced by Andre Agassi as No. 1 for the
moment, Sampras became co-No. 1 of all time. His 6-3, 6-4, 7-5
defusing of his American compatriot and longtime nemesis in the
Wimbledon final on Centre Court Sunday enabled Sampras to tie
Australian Roy Emerson for the most Grand Slam titles, 12.
</P>
<P>
   On a lesser level, but only slightly, Sampras's sixth crown in
seven years guarantees that he will enter the millennium as the
most prolific Wimbledon male of the 20th century. He broke a tie
with Bjorn Borg and Laurie Doherty, and on the all-time list he
trails only Willie Renshaw, who won seven Wimbledons in the 1880s.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also made it a banner star-spangled day on the Fourth of
July, joining his former Palos Verdes, Calif., neighbor Lindsay
Davenport, the women's winner, in an all-American first dance
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at the Champions Ball.
</P>
<P>
   All of which was a tad unimaginable for the 27-year-old, who
also tied Ivan Lendl's record of 270 weeks total at No. 1 until the
ATP Tour computer awarded the top spot to Agassi before Sunday's
festivities began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still spinning a little bit, to be honest with you,'' said
Sampras. ``I haven't thought about (the record) much, and just
getting off the court, it's a little overwhelming to have won what
I've won. I don't know how I do it, I really don't, to be honest
with you. It's going to take time to sink in, a couple of weeks to
have it all sink in, but now it's just getting over with the match
and I'm still spinning.''
</P>
<P>
   He left Agassi reeling. Despite the seedings _ Sampras No. 1,
Agassi No. 4 _ the 29-year-old from Las Vegas seemed the clear
favorite off recent efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who had fallen as low as No. 142 during his brief tenure
as Mr. Brooke Shields, has been on a phenomenal roll in recent
months, beginning with his startling victory in the French Open,
which made him only the fifth man ever to capture the career Grand
Slam (Australian, French, Wimbledon, US), the one distinction
Sampras can't yet claim. And he had appeared invulnerable on the
way to his first All England Club final since he won here in 1992,
whipping such luminaries as 11th seed Gustavo Kuerten and No. 2
Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sampras, who played only one match in six days
because of the plague of rain here, looked rusty in Friday's
quarterfinals, where he got a gift when seventh seed Mark
Philippoussis was forced to retire with a knee injury after taking
the first set; and unimpressive in a four-set semifinal victory
over No. 6 Tim Henman Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras elevated his game when it mattered, and Agassi was
no phoenix this time. He is the most flamboyant shotmaker in the
game and he played extremely well Sunday. But Sampras is a
metronome, and when he's in his rhythm, as he was in this match,
any challenge is folly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, to a degree,'' said Agassi, who was trying
to become the first man since Borg to win the French and Wimbledon
in the same year. ``I was certainly trying to figure out what I
could do. I could have served better, but he actually pressured me
into having to serve a little bit bigger because he was hitting
over all his shots. I expected him to be a little more conservative
with his backhand, and he was snapping it and taking chances and he
was hitting and he was making it. I maintained a focus and
intensity, but I just couldn't stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who broke Agassi at 4-3 in the first set, in the first
game of the second, and at 5-5 in the third, played like a man on a
mission, belying his phlegmatic nature. He wound up with a nasty
cut on his right arm, the product of a couple of belly flops _ one
successful, one not _ and his second serve and forehand returns
were pulverizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, in the middle of the second set, I was on
fire,'' said Sampras, who first faced Agassi in a junior tournament
in Northridge, Calif., at age 10 and has beaten him in three of
their four Grand Slam final encounters, previously winning the 1990
and '95 US Opens and losing the '95 Australian. ``From all aspects
of my game, serving to my groundstrokes, I was playing in the zone.
It's not easy to maintain that on grass, especially playing him,
but it was as well as I could play, plain and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi could only concede the point, as he had to do so many
times on Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's accomplished more than anybody else has, no question
about it,'' said the runner-up. ``The guy's dominated on grass and
he's finished the year No. 1 six years in a row (yet another
record). His achievements speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The achievements read like this: six Wimbledon titles, four US,
two Australian. That makes 12. Which adds up to 1, no matter what a
machine may say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
