</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT DISPATCHES GRAF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It wasn't necessarily the stature of her conqueror,
6-foot-3-inch Lindsay Davenport, that made Steffi Graf realize she
is no longer the towering presence at Wimbledon. It wasn't
necessarily the authority with which Davenport dispatched her, 6-4,
7-5, in Sunday's women's final on Centre Court that prompted Graf
to announce immediately afterward that her playing days are
finished at the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
   It was just . . . what?
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old grande dame of her tennis generation couldn't,
or wouldn't, be specific after revealing that her 10th final had
been her last Wimbledon match _ a day after she declared she would
contemplate her future only well after this fortnight concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Graf was both vague and testy after following the course of her
fellow German idol, Boris Becker, in making this a farewell
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be back here as a player,'' she said after her 14th
Wimbledon, 10th Wimbledon final, and only third Wimbledon final
loss. ``I will not comment on anything other than that. I haven't
had enough time to think about those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet she apparently had reached the decision before she took
Centre Court Sunday, sometime after she made the French Open her
22d Grand Slam title _ and bid adieu to Paris in the wake of that
final. ``I decided before (the match),'' she said, indicating the
loss had no bearing.
</P>
<P>
   She was asked what objectives she might have now that she's
written off France and England, and whether she would compete in
the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we talk about today?'' she said. ``I'm not going to go
into anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   She'd given a hint of her withdrawal symptoms Saturday when she
begged out of the mixed doubles with John McEnroe, because of a
thigh problem.
</P>
<P>
   She said it didn't affect her Sunday _ but it certainly affected
the celebrated McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very calm but he wasn't so happy,'' she said. ``It was
a very difficult decision for me, and when I talked to him, it
wasn't easy. He said, `Come on, we could win this.' I was trying to
tell him it would be a little difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf proved more elusive to the press than she did to Davenport,
who asserted her status as the world's top-ranked player, which she
had reclaimed by reaching the final after previous No. 1 Martina
Hingis got bounced in the first round by qualifier Jelena Dokic.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, who won the US Open last September but never had
gotten past the quarterfinals here, showed the salutary effects of
a regimen that has reduced her waistline and upgraded her stamina
and mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Her aggressive serves kept Graf off guard, and she won the only
two service breaks _ in the first game of the match, when she
nailed a forehand winner after two deuces; and with the score 5-5
in the second set, when Graf popped a forehand return into the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   A game later, when Graf returned Davenport's serve into the net
on match point, the Californian cupped her hands over her eyes in
elation. As a youngster in Palos Verdes, the daughter of a former
Olympic volleyball player _ whose height and athleticism she
inherited _ used to tune in religiously to NBC's ``Breakfast at
Wimbledon,'' even though it meant dining at dawn. She'd always
wanted to partake of the feast, and Sunday the breakfast of
champions was hers.
</P>
<P>
   But poor Davenport, who became the first American-born woman in
the final since Zina Garrison in 1990, hasn't been able to claim a
headline to call her own here. On Saturday, her semifinal victory
over Alexandra Stevenson was overshadowed by the fact that Julius
Erving had acknowledged the previous evening that Stevenson is his
daughter. In fact, Davenport had been asked more questions about
Stevenson and inflammatory comments made by Alexandra's mother,
former Boston television reporter and part-time freelance
journalist Samantha Stevenson, than she had about herself.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday her ultimate moment was upstaged by Graf's exit.
Still, the 23-year-old Davenport, who seems like the normal product
of a normal upbringing by normal parents _ which makes her a rarity
on the women's tour _ was too delighted to worry about any
sideshows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels incredible,'' she said. ``After I won, I was in more
shock than anything. I didn't know quite what to do. I would always
say that my best chances were always on hard court. And after
struggling here for a couple of years and not playing so well on
this surface, to win here, to not lose a set, to beat Graf and
(1998 champion Jana) Novotna (in the quarterfinals), who are the
best grass-court players we have _ all of that combined just makes
it the most amazing win.''
</P>
<P>
   So amazing that after her 1-hour 15-minute triumph, interrupted
for 31 minutes by rain, Davenport didn't even mind when she had to
curtsy to make eye contact with the Duke and Duchess of Kent, who
presented her with the gold champion's plate.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, who already has enough of those to serve dinner for seven,
settled for silver. Then she went for the gold watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
