<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, July 5. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
NAVAJOGOP (Phoenix) _ The Arizona Legislature had just approved
money for a Navajo Nation college, and Elmer Milford wanted to say
thanks. The 20-year veteran of the Navajo Tribal Council marched
into Jeff Groscost's office, whipped out a pen, and changed his
voter registration _ to Republican. It must have drawn a smile from
Groscost, who has been quietly courting Navajo leaders for months.
He pushed two key bills sought by the tribe and has encouraged
Navajos to switch parties, arguing they could get more
legislationpassed with the GOP in power. Democrats say the notion
is laughable, that the idea of a conservative politician winning
over perhaps the most Democratic area of the state is ridiculous.
But for Milford, it made sense. By CHRIS MOESER. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FIREWORKS (Peoria, Ariz.) _ A popular fireworks display got off to
an accidental start Sunday in Peoria, sending five pyrotechnic
workers to the hospital, two with possibly life-threatening
injuries, and canceling the show. The explosion happened at 5 p.m.,
about an hour after crews started setting up for the 9 p.m.
extravaganza at the Peoria Sports Complex. The event, staged by the
city for four years, was expected to draw as many as 20,000
spectators. But stacks of fireworks that workers from the Salt Lake
City-based Lantis Fireworks had unloaded in a field suddenly
started detonating, police and fire officials said. White smoke
quickly covered the entire field, said Glendale photographer Chris
Powell, who had been setting up his camera at the La Quinta hotel
across the street. By LISA GONDERINGER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
