<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9372 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINSCOLUMN-BOS     07-05 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE AMERICAN DOUBLE AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Betsy Ross and John Hancock always get a call when you
talk about great Independence Day mixed doubles pairings. But don't
overlook Lindsay Davenport and Pete Sampras. What better place than
King George III's hometown for Lindsay and Pete to show the same
Yankee Doodle Dandiest spirit by waving the stars and stripes and
writing their names large?
</P>
<P>
   They did it at Wimbledon, performing their own stamp act on the
Fourth of July, Davenport stamping on Steffi Graf, 6-4, 7-5, before
Sampras did the same to Andre Agassi, 6-3, 6-4, 7-5. They were a
couple of cannon crackers, exploding all over Centre Court with
shots that could have re-cracked the Liberty Bell.
</P>
<P>
   When an afternoon shrouded by smoky and lavender clouds
concluded, Sampras had become the Wimbledonian Man of the Century
with his sixth title, a tour de force of such breathtaking
virtuosity that 13,813 jaws dropped with regularity throughout the
arena. Plus Agassi's.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport was standing as tall as Bunker Hill, the loftiest of
this playpen's female champs. At 6 feet 3 inches she looked down on
Sampras Sunday &UR;  &LR; night as they shared the opening dance at the
Wimbledon ball, and maybe she led.
</P>
<P>
   And Graf completed the German retreat begun by Boris Becker _
they were the Sampras and Davenport of 1989 _ by saying
``Nimmerwiedersehen!'' to the Big W. That's a long version of
bye-bye forever, but after 14 glorious years and seven titles, she
could say anything she wants for as long as she wants to her
saddened public.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California, once upon a time the world's tennis
vineyard where numerous Wimbledon champions grew, had a double once
again, the first since Billie Jean King and Stan Smith in 1972.
``We're both Palos Verdes kids,'' whoops Sampras, who now lives in
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Where have Long Lindsay and Pyrotechnical Pete been hiding
during the fortnight? They've seemed undercover agents while
everybody else got the attention and ink. How could anybody as
imposing as Davenport walk around unnoticed? Good-natured, pleased
to be ignored, and clearly ``feeling better about my chances than
ever before,'' although local bookmakers listed her at 10-1 at the
outset, she was not the story _ until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   She'd had a scare from unknown Barbara Schett in the fourth
round, dodging five set points in a 7-6 (9-7), 6-1 win, but when
you look back on her accomplishments Davenport was merely
phenomenal. Not since the original Martina (Navratilova) in 1990
had a champ won all 14 sets played. To go in with Graf and escape
with your serve unscathed is unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   She was airtight, grabbing the only two break points Graf put on
view, banging her groundies audaciously, powerfully, and precisely,
and startling Graf with nifty volleying. Davenport stooped to
conquer. More nimble than ever, she got down to deal effortlessly,
productively with Graf's scything, turf-skimming backhand, a tough
order for anybody, especially with a two-handed backhand. Her
smart-bomb serving made Graf lose a guessing game.
</P>
<P>
   But if Davenport had to make way for water, the half-hour rain
interruption at a critical moment, ``Pete could walk on water
today,'' according to Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   The shower chased the women as Davenport was about to serve at
4-5, 30-15 in the second set. ``It could have gotten away from me
there,'' she said. ``The delay was good. I got refocused in the
dressing room.''
</P>
<P>
   She lost the first point upon returning (two points from
dropping the set, 30-all), but won a nine-stroke rally, whanged a
service winner, and seized the last two games and the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one choky moment, a lousy backhand on the first match
point _ but why recall that?'' Davenport said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras wasn't required to walk, run, or swim on water. Grass
was the medium, but there's nothing medium about Sampras when he
sniffs the chlorophyll. He's mammoth with a Wimbledon title at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   For almost two weeks Sampras had been Clark Kent crouched in the
phone booth, patiently waiting to reveal himself as the S-man while
critics talked about his decline and fall. Then he fell on Agassi,
who'd been the man of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need some luck to go all the way,'' Sampras said, ``and I
got it when Mark Philippoussis broke down (hospitalized with a torn
cartilage after winning their first set Friday). I began to get the
feel against Tim (Henman, semifinals).''
</P>
<P>
   Crash! Sampras departed the phone booth without bothering to
open the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on fire,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   The grass of Centre was haggard, but it was all his. As far as
Sampras was concerned it could have been the liquid of the Sargasso
Sea or the Everglades. It was still fairly green and Sampras was
beating the yellow balls black and blue. He was serving tons,
giving new definition to volleys from all angles and positions,
punishing backhands and forehands.
</P>
<P>
   He was the consummate master of Centre. But Agassi did not let
him off lightly, despite the straight sets score. He competed so
fiercely and formidably that it was the best and hardest of
Sampras's half-dozen finals, the finest final from both ends since
the John McEnroe-Bjorn Borg epics of 1980-81.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi scored knockdowns _ literally _ but Sampras came up with
bloodied arms from diving volleys on his way to the knockout. Every
time Agassi had a chance to turn things around _ and there were
plenty _ Sampras launched a grenade to get off the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't come up with better stuff than him. I couldn't
weather his storm. I couldn't stop him,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, the shotmaking wizard ``brings out the best in me,''
said Sampras. Sunday he pushed Sampras to reveal his greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Sampras beat a 29-year-old adversary. But this young Greek
god chasing history also caught up with a 62-year-old named Roy
Emerson, now sharing the record of 12 Grand Slam titles. Moreover,
he surpassed his rivals in this fading century: 43-year-old Borg
and long-dead 123-year-old Laurie Doherty, both winners five times.
</P>
<P>
   Can't you hear Laurie's brother, Reggie, chortling at that great
center court in the ozone: ``Sorry, bro, but that SOB Sampras
finally knocked you out of the books.'' Then, looking over at
138-year-old Willie Renshaw, seven-time champ between 1881 and
1889: ``Look out, Willie. Sampras'll get you next.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, on an adjoining cloud, Betsy Ross, flapping her flag,
is saying to John Hancock, ``Pete's autograph may just be bigger
than yours.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
