<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAVAJOGOP-AZR &LR;      07-05 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVAJOGOP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS VIEW NAVAJOS AS A NATURAL CONSTITUENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Arizona Legislature had just approved money for a
Navajo Nation college, and Elmer Milford wanted to say thanks.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year veteran of the Navajo Tribal Council marched into
Jeff Groscost's office, whipped out a pen, and changed his voter
registration _ to Republican.
</P>
<P>
   It must have drawn a smile from Groscost, who has been quietly
courting Navajo leaders for months. He pushed two key bills sought
by the tribe and has encouraged Navajos to switch parties, arguing
they could get more legislation passed with the GOP in power.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say the notion is laughable, that the idea of a
conservative politician winning over perhaps the most Democratic
area of the state is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   But for Milford, it made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``People up here tease me a little bit,'' said Milford, who
lives in Fort Defiance. ``But in order to get anything done down
there, you can get more things done as a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Navajos have switched parties, but Groscost can point to
other successes. While Democrats napped in 1998 and failed to get
any candidates on the ballot in District 3, Groscost helped elect
Rep. Tom Gordon, R-Peach Springs, only the third Republican to
serve the district since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The other new member? Rep. Sylvia Laughter, D-Kayenta, whom
Democrats carp is the 41st member of the House GOP caucus. It was
Groscost, not Democrats, who encouraged Laughter to run; he knew
her from their days at Mesa High School.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost says his interest in the region can be traced to his
childhood, when his family sponsored a Navajo child, Rosie Bingham,
who lived with his family and attended school in Mesa. Bingham has
accompanied Groscost on several of his four trips to the Nation
since he became speaker.
</P>
<P>
   But it also says a lot about his political plans, both as Sen.
John McCain's adviser for the Arizona presidential primary and
possible bids in several years for Congress or statewide office.
</P>
<P>
   A NATURAL CONSTITUENCY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Navajo Nation is becoming more important politically. Half
of the Nation's 250,000 residents are ages 18 to 30, and 20 percent
are under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost says Navajos should be a natural constituency for
Republicans. Parts of Navajo culture are very socially
conservative: the tribe has twice voted down gaming, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Navajos want greater sovereignty from the federal government,
Groscost said, including property rights, an issue that also
resonates with conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their ideology and views very closely mirror some very
conservative Christian sects,'' Groscost said. The Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints has a significant presence on the
reservation, giving Groscost, a Mormon, another connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go after people who should be natural constituencies
because their ideology or core beliefs mirror those of our party,''
says Groscost, pointing out that the party is making similar
efforts in the Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason we're putting more emphasis here than (with
Hispanics) is because it is a population that we think we can show
them easily what we can do because it is a contained population and
a universe we can impact.'' &QL; 
GREAT DIVERSITY OF VIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Iverson, an Arizona State University history professor
and an expert on Navajo culture, said it would be wrong to look at
Navajos monolithically. There is great diversity of political and
religious views among tribal members, just like other people in
Arizona. Many Navajos, for example, strongly favor a strong federal
government, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And like other voters, many Navajos have very little loyalty to
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they can have some success,'' Iverson said of
Groscost's efforts. ``Given the disorganization of the Democratic
party. . . . This is a target that's been ripe for the picking.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last legislative session, Groscost helped Gordon,
Laughter, and Sen. Jack Jackson, D-Window Rock, pass legislation
for Dine College in Tsalie.
</P>
<P>
   The college, which specializes in teaching and preserving Navajo
customs and culture, needed money to shore up crumbling buildings
on the Hogan-shaped campus. The bill allows the college to keep
$17.25 million in state sales taxes generated on the reservation
for education needs.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost also backed a resolution that asks the federal
government to allow former Navajo Nation President Peter Macdonald
to finish his prison term in Arizona, and he supported changes in
the welfare system that Navajos wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In May, he spoke at the college's graduation, where he was
warmly greeted by Navajos who were surprised to see a House speaker
visit there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Groscost was the first speaker to ever come to Navajo land and
sit down with us,'' said Peter Belletto, the superintendent of the
Ganado Unified School District. Groscost visited the Navajo Nation
last year to lobby leaders like Belletto to support the Students
FIRST legislation, the state's new school construction law.
</P>
<P>
   `HE'S KEPT HIS WORD' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Navajo Nation President Kelsay Begay also gives Groscost high
marks for listening to Navajo concerns and then getting things done
at the Capitol. He appreciates that Groscost has treated the tribe
as a nation within a nation. The two men have become friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mentioned Dine College at that very first meeting. He's kept
his word on that because he's been very supportive of the college.
Him showing up at that graduation only verifies that he's very
concerned about the education of Navajo children,'' Begay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Dine College bill) has enhanced the state-Navajo
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But is it enough to convince Navajos to become Republicans?
Begay says it helps, but that more gestures are needed. Groscost
and other Republicans need to spend more time on the reservation,
talking with people, explaining why they should switch parties.
</P>
<P>
   Few people outside tribal leadership, Begay said, would
recognize Groscost's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking at an educational process at some point. But the
Navajo Nation being predominantly Democratic _ it's going to be a
job _ a big task. But I can always wish him luck on this,'' said
Begay, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the first time that Arizona has responded in a
favorable gesture as far as funds. It's going to take a lot more
effort on Arizona's part to convince someone to switch.''
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS POINT TO CARR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arizona state Democratic Party Chairman Mark Fleisher agrees,
saying the Republican Party is still ``a pretty White group.''
</P>
<P>
   He points out that the Arizona Democratic Party recently named
Gwen Carr, who is a Native American, as its new executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party is still the party of diversity,'' he
said. ``The Republicans are trying to get Native Americans and
AfricanHispanics behind them, but the Democratic Party has fought
the battles those communities care about.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferlin Clark, a vice president of Dine College, says the
question of party registration highlights tensions between
traditional and modern Navajo values. He argues that traditional
Navajo values are very much in line with conservative Republican
philosophy. But Navajos have long voted Democratic because the
party more strongly advocates equality and diversity issues.
</P>
<P>
   But he adds that he hasn't seen too many prominent Democrats in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken it for granted,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests Navajos would be better served at the Capitol if
they maintain representation in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost recognizes that Republicans have a battle ahead to
convince Navajos to even consider the Republican Party. He vows to
continue to work with the tribe next year. And he insists his
motivation isn't politics, although he clearly sees an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be thrilled if they switched. But you're talking about
a culture that thinks not in terms of quarterly reports but in
decades and centuries. These people are still very upset at Kit
Carson for burning the peach trees in Canyon de Chelly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I expect someone to switch to Republican because we did
something good this year? No. What I do expect is that we start
changing some of the culture of distrust between the cultures, and
we start figuring out ways that people down in Phoenix can help the
problems up here instead of making them worse.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Moeser can be reached at (602) 444-8069 or at
chris.moeser(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
