r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLAN     07-05 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELTON RETURNS TO FRUSTRATE GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The hottest team in Major League Soccer was
beaten by one of its own Sunday night. Well, Welton used to be one
of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy saw its season-best winning streak snapped at four
games as Miami _ the team with the worst record in the league _
pulled out a stunning 2-1 victory in front of 60,433 fans at the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Welton, who was traded from the Galaxy to Miami five weeks ago,
scored the decisive goal in the 64th minute, catching a snoozing
Galaxy defense while just avoiding being offside. Welton sneaked
past three defenders while receiving a feed from substitute Nelson
Vargas, then rifled a rising shot that beat keeper Kevin Hartman
and sunk the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe wishing to send a message to his former teammates, Welton
then scooped up the ball and walked off to the side of the net,
prompting an irate Mauricio Cienfuegos to chase him down and snare
the ball away as time wound down.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy striker Carlo Hermosillo almost knotted the score in the
waning minutes, but his shot from the goal mouth was batted away by
Miami keeper Garth Lagerwey, preserving the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy controlled much of the play in the opening half,
buzzing around on Miami's half of the field almost at will. L.A.
fired 10 shots to only two for the Fusion. But for all its
domination before intermission, the Galaxy almost had nothing to
show for it.
</P>
<P>
   A defensive breakdown in the 13th minute pinned coach Sigi
Schmid's squad to a 1-0 deficit it faced for most of the half.
Diego Serna intercepted defender Robin Fraser's errant clearing
pass at the top of the box, quickly unleashing a low right-footed
shot inside the near post that beat Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   A hail of boos rained down on the Galaxy, a sound not heard in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy drew even in the 38th minute, however, as Roy Myers
capped a nice passing sequence. Myers, left unmarked on the edge of
the penalty box, received a soft pass from Danny Pena and dribbled
in two strides before blasting a shot that landed in the right
corner of the net.
</P>
<P>
   On the painfully long list of blown chances for the Galaxy was a
point-blank shot squandered away by a slumping Cobi Jones in the
20th minute. Jones, last year's U.S. Soccer Player of the Year and
MLS MVP, fired an in-close shot squarely at goalie Garth Lagerwey.
</P>
<P>
   Directing it slightly to either the right or the left would have
put the Galaxy on the board. Jones, who knocked home 19 goals last
season, has scored just twice in 1999. After blowing this chance,
the fan favorite gazed to the heavens in disbelief _ a disturbing,
familiar sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just having no luck and that's part of the game,'' said
Schmid, coming to his forward's defense. ``If I told you I wasn't
concerned about his inability to score, I'd be lying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been fortunate that others like Mauricio (Cienfuegos)
and Carlos (Hermosillo) have taken up the slack. Otherwise, Im
concerned that Cobi would be letting too much of this (frustration)
get to him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 0151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0036 </DOCNO>
