<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9380 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-METROS     07-05 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-METROSTARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION ON THE BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution took an important step toward
establishing an identity Sunday. They set the tone with an
aggressive start, displayed resourcefulness, and held off a
disastrous MetroStars team, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   They reached the halfway point in the season with 18 points in
16 matches, a pace that would give them their second-best record in
four seasons, and likely be worth a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Joe-Max Moore scored twice and former MetroStars striker
Giovanni Savarese scored once for the Revolution. But the
MetroStars kept things close as reserves Nansha Kalonji and Petter
Villegas combined for a spectacular goal in the 84th minute, after
two brilliant saves earlier in the half by Walter Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a great first half and had a 2-0 lead,'' Zenga said.
``But we lost concentration for 10 minutes, and it's normal to do
that. We're third in the conference, but it's not easy in the MLS.
We played at 4 o'clock, now we have two games at 1 o'clock. It's
crazy. It's normal to be fatigued, but we feel confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga conducted his postgame press conference sitting on a stage
in front of Foxboro Stadium, obviously affected by the 90-degree
heat and high humidity.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution pressed forward at the start, and took the
initiative. The midfield played cohesively with John Harkes and
Ivan McKinley in holding positions. But they were vulnerable to
counterattacks, especially when the MetroStars went through Tab
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Gori limited Ramos for a while, but was slowed by a right
knee bruise suffered in training last week and departed after 62
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The physicality of play, combined with the heat, turned the game
into a battle of attrition. Dan Calichman and Ted Chronopoulos both
departed because of exhaustion. MetroStars coach Bora Milutinovic
rejuvenated his team with Villegas and Kalonji, then brought
defender Kevin Knight in as an attacker in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A MetroStars error led to Moore's first goal in the 21st minute.
Mike Petke struggled to control a pass just outside the penalty
area, allowing Chronopoulos to steal. Chronopoulos found Moore, who
converted his seventh goal of the season from about 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese scored six minutes later, following an effective
buildup through McKinley. Moore laid off to Jair, who sent a hard
shot off the right post, and Savarese calmly scored on the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution appeared vulnerable defensively. Ramos looped
a pass to Mark Chung, who controlled the ball with his right foot,
stepped around Calichman, and finished with his left foot in the
29th minute. The MetroStars nearly tied six minutes later, but
Zenga saved a Chung shot off an Eduardo Hurtado feed. Zenga made
his best saves off a Chung header and a Hurtado breakaway in the
21st minute of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game the Revolution likely would not have won a year
ago. But they are changing expectations, and are being helped by
the failure of teams such as the MetroStars, who have won twice in
regulation time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well for the first 20 minutes and capitalized on
their mistakes,'' Chronopoulos said. ``With New York being in our
division, this was like a 6-point turnaround.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
