<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEORIA, ARIZ., FIREWORKS EXPLODE, 2 WORKERS BADLY BURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GONDERINGER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ A popular fireworks display got off to an
accidental start Sunday in Peoria, sending five pyrotechnic workers
to the hospital, two with possibly life-threatening injuries, and
canceling the show.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion happened at 5 p.m., about an hour after crews
started setting up for the 9 p.m. extravaganza at the Peoria Sports
Complex. The event, staged by the city for four years, was expected
to draw as many as 20,000 spectators.
</P>
<P>
   But stacks of fireworks that workers from the Salt Lake
City-based Lantis Fireworks had unloaded in a field suddenly
started detonating, police and fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   White smoke quickly covered the entire field, said Glendale
photographer Chris Powell, who had been setting up his camera at
the La Quinta hotel across the street. He had hoped to capture
images from the evening show for his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of shooting into the sky, the fireworks launched across
the field, low to the ground, Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must've been 50 to 60 explosions,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   An empty field to the north of the stadium caught fire, and a
white van suddenly turned into a fireball, he said. Black smoke
blended with white.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion shook the windows of the house of Gena Zestrijan,
who lives a half-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at home in the back yard with the kids in the pool and I
just started hearing, `Boom, boom,' and I knew it was fireworks,''
Zestrijan said.
</P>
<P>
   Peoria fire crews arrived minutes later and extinguished the van
and the field. Two workers were airlifted to the Maricopa County
Medical Center burn unit. They have critical burns over 75 percent
of their body, a fire official said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are withholding the victims' names until family
members have been notified.
</P>
<P>
   A third employee suffered less serious burns. Two other workers
were sent to Arrowhead Medical Center for smoke-inhalation
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The city canceled the night's festivities, said Kelly Corsette,
Peoria's public information officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, we don't have any more fireworks left, and that
was the whole purpose of the show,'' Corsette said.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb squad was planning to search a parking lot and the area
around the explosion to make sure no hazards remained.
</P>
<P>
   The city has used Lantis Fireworks for other events, Corsette
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a professional outfit, they are fully certified,''
Corsette said. It's too early to say whether Sunday's accident
would cause the city to look elsewhere next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really knows what happened here,'' Corsette said.
</P>
<P>
   Many spectators didn't get the news until they showed up at the
Peoria Sports Complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed, but we'll try to find a different place,''
said Glendale resident Rob Gassert, who was accompanied by his
wife, Heather, and their children Robbie and Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, I hope the two people involved will get well
soon,'' he said. ``I think their health is more important than
fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   The city is issuing refunds of the $5 admission to those who go
to Peoria City hall or call (623) 412-7137. &QL; 
Republic writers Gil Hoffman and Brent Whiting contributed to this
article.Lisa Gonderinger can be reached at (602) 444-7967 or
lisa.gonderinger(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
