 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2554 -- July 5, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2554 -- July 5, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. A NUCLEAR CONFLICT CAN HAVE NO VICTORS Pakistan's atomic
tests made South Asia more secure, writes its foreign secretary,
and helped prod India and Pakistan to better relations and talks on
Kashmir. By Shamshad Ahmad. From Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,000
words.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
'ALL ARE BUT PARTS OF ONE STUPENDOUS WHOLE' Stephen J. Gould, a
professor of zoology at Harvard, who is the author, most recently,
of ``Questioning the Millennium,'' queries why humans need to see
themselves as separate and superior to the natural world and why,
for example, anyone would doubt the existence of a sophisticated
mental life in chimpanzees. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
WHICH THREATS SHALL WE HEED? Nato's poorly planned adventure in
Kosovo has brought a critical question to the fore : Just how
should Americans define their national interest in the information
age? The Soviet Union is gone, and an information revolution has
transformed the nature of power. Few 'A list' threats to American
security loom large today. Global telecommunications have made
humanitarian crises in far-flung places impossible to ignore. But
before the U.S. embarks on another costly human rights crusade,
Americans should recognize that moral values are only part of a
foreign policy. Other essential priorities remain. If Washington
neglects to handle the ``A list,'' the consequences for global
peace and prosperity will be dire. By Joseph S. Nye Jr. From
Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
THE MAN AFTER MANDELA During the 27 years that Nelson Mandela was
serving time in apartheid jails, his successor, Thabo Mbeki, was
also serving time, ``like a cosmic wanderer, driven by the winds to
land where they will,'' as he once wrote to a friend. Mbeki was
living in forced exile. Like Mandela, the decision to become a
freedom fighter would be as much destiny as it was choice. By
Charlayne Hunter-Gault. From Emerge magazine. 2,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand) A.
Rough Justice What is a jury supposed to do when the prosecution's
expert witness flatly contradicts a scientist appearing for the
defence? Are court-appointed neutral experts the answer? By Nell
Boyce. 1,500 words. B. Left Brain, Right Brain If you thought one
side of your brain was cold and logical and the other creative and
emotional -- think again! By John McCrone. 4,500 words. C. Coral
Grief Dust from African deserts may be spreading disease across the
world's coral reefs, say researchers who also blame the fallout for
a global rise in respiratory infections. By Fred Pearce. 500 words.
D. Gamma Force They're scary, awesome and hard to control. Nuclear
lasers a million times more powerful than their conventional
cousins are no longer a crazy dream. By Marcus Chown. 4,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
WHAT'S DOING IN VEVEY About every 20 years, the quaint Swiss
village of Vevey, on the northeastern shore of Lake Geneva, honours
a new generation of winemakers. Last held in 1977, the Fjte des
Vignerons has been sponsored by the local brotherhood of
winegrowers since the 17th century. This summer, more than half a
million visitors are expected to descend on tiny Vevey (population
16,000) for an 18-day extravaganza, from July 29 to August 15. By
Corinne LaBalme. From New York Times Way to Go! 1,800 words +
photos + map.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo 19h00 BST
Wednesday July 7)
</P>
<P>
   A. Vaccination Against Alzheimer's Disease? A step towards a
clinically practical treatment against Alzheimer's disease is
reported in the latest issue of Nature. By Henry Gee. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. Accident Theory Up In Smoke? When regular smokers quit, their
mood and mental abilities deteriorate within hours. This is
measurable in the laboratory - but is it systematically evident in
daily life? If it can be shown that sudden cessation of smoking
contributes to 'air rage' on long-haul flights, or poor performance
in a smoke-free workplace, then airlines and employers might have
to think about supplying nicotine patches to their addicted
passengers or colleagues. By Henry Gee. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________
Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81
