<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     07-05 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 11)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE OTHER SIDE OF SILENCE. MEN'S LIVES AND GAY IDENTITIES: A
TWENTIETH-CENTURY HISTORY &LR;  By John Loughery. John Macrae/Owl/Holt,
$15.95. This provocative chronicle of gay male life in the United
States from 1919 to the early 1990s combines extensive archival
research with interviews and a broad knowledge of 20th-century
letters. ``Loughery writes uncluttered, calm, controlled,
exceptionally intelligent prose,'' Warren Goldstein wrote in The
New York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITIES OF THE PLAIN: VOLUME 3, THE BORDER TRILOGY &LR;  By Cormac
McCarthy. Vintage International, $13. The concluding volume of the
author's sweeping cowboy saga brings together the two leathery
heroes from the earlier novels on a New Mexico ranch in the 1950s,
when the mythic West, and an entire way of life, are fading away.
Much of the plot involves romance: between one of the heroes and a
beautiful whore, and between ranchmen and their horses. McCarthy
``once again provides a terrific read,'' Sara Mosle wrote in 1998.
``He is perhaps the greatest writer since Melville on the subject
of work. ... What would be mind-numbing description in less
competent hands is here completely riveting.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SKY: A MEDITATION ON FLIGHT &LR;  By William
Langewiesche. Vintage Departures, $12. These thoughtful essays by a
commercial pilot explore both the risks and the joys of flying, in
the process offering the reader a fresh way of perceiving the
world. ``Langewiesche brings knowledge and passion as well as
careful eloquence to his subject,'' James R. Gaines wrote in the
Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EAST TO THE DAWN: THE LIFE OF AMELIA EARHART &LR; , by Susan Butler
(Da Capo, $17.95), is a well-researched biography of the former
social worker (and truck driver) who in 1928 became the first woman
to fly across the Atlantic. In 1997 the reviewer Emily Wortis
Leider found the book to be overly adoring, but said that ``Butler
shows a mastery of aviation history, and considerable
sophistication about the technology of flight and navigation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIS TIME: NEW AND SELECTED POEMS &LR;  By Gerald Stern. Norton,
$14. This collection of verse, some of it reprinted from earlier
volumes, won a National Book Award in 1998. One critic called
Stern's book ``remarkable for its generosity of spirit, manifested
in a warm surrealism that is often turned with humor toward his own
past as a way of understanding the recurrent questions of growing
old.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ICY SPARKS &LR;  By Gwen Hyman Rubio. Penguin, $12.95. In this
poignant first novel, a hyperarticulate 10-year-old girl who is
both an orphan and a victim of Tourette's syndrome struggles to
come of age in rural Kentucky in the '50s. ``Rubio is a writer of
uncommonly warm and tender vision, often comic, brimming with love
and hope,'' Tara Bayton wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXPLAINING HITLER: THE SEARCH FOR THE ORIGINS OF HIS EVIL &LR;  By
Ron Rosenbaum. Harper Perennial, $16. Does Hitler represent a
uniquely evil force or a grotesque perversion of basic human
nature? The author, an essayist and journalist, combs through the
many outposts of Hitler theory _ and the motives of the theorists
themselves _ to shed light on that enduring question. ``He has a
sympathetic ear, a knack for classification and a sharp, critical
mind,'' Michael R. Marrus wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BETWEEN DIGNITY AND DESPAIR: JEWISH LIFE IN NAZI GERMANY &LR; , by
Marion A. Kaplan (Oxford University, $14.95), relies on memoirs,
letters and interviews to create an intimate account of the social
isolation and unending acts of humiliation that plagued German
Jewry. Last year the reviewer Deborah E. Lipstadt called this ``a
devastatingly powerful book'' that reveals how ``genocidal violence
can have its genesis in the smallest expressions of prejudice and
hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOST IN TRANSLATION &LR;  By Nicole Mones. Delta, $12.95. The
daughter of a racist American politician becomes intoxicated by
China (and Chinese men) and joins an expedition in search of the
bones of Peking Man. Last year the reviewer Lisa See called this a
``thought-provoking, sometimes disturbing and undeniably
entertaining'' first novel about race, taboo and cultural
attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WOMAN OF ROME &LR;  By Alberto Moravia. Steerforth Italia, $16.
Adriana, the sympathetically drawn heroine of this Italian novel,
is a beautiful woman making her way in Mussolini-era Rome for whom
prostitution is not a desperate act but her natural vocation. In
1949 the reviewer William Fense Weaver found Adriana to be
``fascinating and original, as are all the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPLIT: A COUNTERCULTURE CHILDHOOD &LR;  By Lisa Michaels.
Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $13. A young poet and essayist recalls
growing up as the daughter of a Weatherman imprisoned in 1969 and a
gentle hippie mother with whom she migrated to California. The
result is ``an intelligent and vivid memoir of what it was like to
be literally a child of the '60s,'' Adam Goodheart wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MISSING WOMEN AND OTHERS: STORIES &LR;  By June Spence. Riverhead,
$12. Many of the characters in this first collection are women
mired in perpetual states of transition: recent divorce, recovery
from alcoholism, boring jobs or waiting out a lover's prison term.
``Spence has a canny eye and a pointed sense of humor,'' Laura
Miller wrote in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
