<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE06-COX     07-05 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST LANGUAGES: SURVIVAL OF THE MOST ARTICULATE
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Understanding how a small number of pre-human
grunts and other sounds grew into complex modern languages is a
problem that has intrigued scientists for ages.
</P>
<P>
   Mathematical biologists in Princeton, N.J., now suggest that the
need to eliminate confusion would have pushed ``protolanguages'' of
modern humans' ancestors along increasingly complex paths, leading
to the development of modern verbal communication.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Nowak and David Krakauer of the Institute for Advanced
Study outline a mathematical theory to explain how language could
have developed as a natural extension of the evolution that led to
the development of living species.
</P>
<P>
   Linguists and neurobiologists have speculated for years about
the origin of languages. Some have tried to describe a naturally
occurring ``language instinct'' that caused human ancestors to
start exchanging information through recognizable sounds. Others
have speculated that some pre-existing activity, such as mutual
grooming, could have provided the environment in which audible
communication began.
</P>
<P>
   The random appearance of traits such as keener eyes or faster
feet increased the likelihood that the offspring of creatures with
those traits would survive, according to the theory of natural
selection propounded by Charles Darwin more than a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of audible signals _ such as a sound meaning
``leopard,'' for example _ would also have improved the chances
that human ancestors would survive and have offspring to whom they
could teach the signal, say Nowak and Krakauer in an article
appearing Monday in the Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the keener eyes or faster feet, however, the sound for
leopard requires more than the ability of one creature to produce
it. A second creature must understand it.
</P>
<P>
   This requirement for cooperation tends to inhibit innovation and
is the first barrier to language evolution, Krakauer said in a
telephone interview. But the pressure of the need to eliminate
mistakes would overcome the resistance to innovation and push the
protolanguage to label more and more things and events with sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the system would reach the first of a pair of
``error thresholds,'' Krakauer said.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of new sounds to describe additional objects
increases the power of this protolanguage, but it also increases
the probability of making mistakes by confusing different sounds,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The need to avoid such mistakes is a key force pushing the
development of language, according to the theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to overcome the error limit is by combining sounds
into words,'' Krakauer said.
</P>
<P>
   This process, which permits construction of an essentially
unlimited number of words, eventually takes the developing language
to its second error threshold.
</P>
<P>
   The second limit is defined not by the ear's ability to
distinguish among a huge number of similar sounds, but by the
mind's capacity for memorizing all of the words for all of the
different facts that need to be communicated.
</P>
<P>
   The natural response to the second threshold, Krakauer said, is
to develop rules for constructing sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grammar emerges in the attempt to convey more information by
combining these words into phrases or sentences,'' Krakauer and
Nowak say in the article. ``Simply naming an object will be less
valuable than naming it and describing its action. A leopard can be
stalking, in which case it is a serious risk, or merely sleeping
and thereby posing a lesser risk.''
</P>
<P>
   That way, instead of memorizing a forever-growing list of words,
the people who use a language must memorize a fairly large list of
words and a few rules for combining those words into meaningful
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The theory does not try to compute how rapidly this evolution of
communication would occur.
</P>
<P>
   Krakauer said he and Nowak are at work on further mathematical
models which will incorporate other variables, such as the relative
importance of different words.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute for Advanced Study is an independent center
founded in 1930 to support study in a range of areas. Among its
earliest scholars was Albert Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
