<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9534 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-EVIDENCE-REV     07-05 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-EVIDENCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCENE OF THE CRIME: KOJAK WOULD RECOGNIZE KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ Kosovo is a huge crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Homicide and arson are at the heart of the charges, and at first
blush the evidence seems obvious, scattered across the landscape in
the form of burned-out buildings and bodies. The bodies keep
turning up, day after day, and are expected now to number 10,000 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   But meeting the exacting standards of a court of law _ even an
international tribunal focused on the highly emotional category of
war crimes _ is a different matter. For there are still specific
criminal acts to be proved, and a chain of evidence to be
established before Yugoslavia's top leaders can be held to account
for the killing that went on here. And these are cold scenes _ the
bodies burned, deteriorated, buried or in some instances even
stolen by the departing Serbs to destroy evidence. The sites have
been open to the elements, sometimes for more than two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like working a massive homicide,'' said Art Eberhart of
the FBI, ``except usually you have a pristine site. You are there
within 24 hours and nobody has touched anything. You tape it off
and attempt to recreate the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   At many of the sites under investigation here, the houses had
been burned to a shell, with rafters, second story and roof tile
now just piles of bits of rubble 6 to 10 inches thick, Eberhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to excavate by hand, tile by tile,'' said Bill
Rodriguez, a forensic anthropologist on the FBI team. ``There were
no intact sites because of burning. Everything had collapsed on
itself. Even to get at the evidence you have to excavate very
carefully. You can't go in there willy-nilly or you'll destroy the
evidence. There are hundreds of bone fragments, burned, highly
fragmented. They could be crushed in your hand very easily.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, another important difference, said detectives
and other investigators from a half-dozen countries working for the
International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia. The
question to be answered in Kosovo is not exactly who pulled the
trigger or struck the match in each case.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, these investigators are trying to corroborate the
accounts of witnesses about the pattern of the killings by Serb
forces, to establish that war crimes and crimes against humanity
did, in fact, occur. That is what would back up the indictment
already issued against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
four other Serbian leaders. They are accused of command
responsibility for a campaign of terror and violence against
Kosovo's Albanians that included deportation, murder and
persecution, all crimes against humanity. A fourth count cites the
commission of murder as a violation of the laws of war.
</P>
<P>
   The forensic teams have initially been assigned to the six sites
mentioned in the indictment. But they are uncovering new evidence
of mass killings every day; many will not be fully investigated,
officials say. Others might figure in new indictments, possibly of
lower-ranking figures on whom pressure could be applied to obtain
their testimony against Milosevic and others up the chain of
command.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to link, say, shell casings to a specific
individual,'' said Eberhart, who headed one of two FBI forensic
teams investigating sites in Djakovica, where the Serbs
concentrated some of their greatest fury against ethnic Albanians.
``We're trying to show that a crime occurred here, in order to
support the witness statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officers are normally wary of eyewitnesses, knowing they
can often be contradictory, their stories clouded by emotion or
inaccurate observations. But in Kosovo, the investigators have been
struck, as have journalists, by the accuracy of the refugees'
accounts. On the ground, the crime scenes are precisely what has
been described. ``Everyone you talk to has a story,'' said Chris
Whitcomb, another FBI agent on the team. ``And when you see the
evidence, you know they are not exaggerating.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen miles away, in a field by a stream near the village
of Bela Crkva, John Bunn, chief superintendent of Scotland Yard,
concurred. He is heading a 16-member British team investigating
mass graves in a chain of villages along a 10-mile stretch of
highway between Djakovica and Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   ``The witness accounts are very, very good, and they're true, no
doubt about that,'' said Bunn, a portly figure who prefers to be
called ``detective,'' and looked as if he had stepped out of an
Agatha Christie novel in his shin-high black rubber gardening
boots. He had been camped in a tent by the stream, where executions
had been described by Isuf Zhenigi, a survivor. The detective
pointed out two mounds of earth where, with the help of tearful
villagers, he had exhumed 34 bodies,
</P>
<P>
   ``At a crime scene, there is always something for you to find,''
Bunn said, brushing aside the difficulties in matter-of-fact tones.
``We can establish cause of death, we can still work out the last
few minutes of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   But difficulties abound, among them the proliferation of bodies.
Conversely, the French team went to a remote hillside by the
village of Izbice expecting to find 160 bodies at a well-documented
mass grave _ it had been photographed by satellite _ only to find
that the Serbs had dug it up and made off with the corpses.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI mounted one of the most elaborate forensic efforts in
Kosovo, with a 65-person team that included a security patrol from
its hostage rescue unit and 107,000 pounds of equipment, including
humvees, trucks, tents and communications equipment. There were
graphic artists and demolition experts. Each site _ they examined
seven in addition to the two originally assigned _ was photographed
and videotaped at each stage of the investigation. Elaborate charts
that resembled architectural drawings were made, and evidence
collected in grocery store-sized paper bags, labeled by location.
Generators powered an X-ray machine, which was needed because the
victims' flesh had deteriorated. Still, the team had to improvise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exposure to the elements really puts you behind the ball,''
said Rodriguez, one of two experts on loan from the Armed Forces
Institute of Pathology. ``Trying to play catch-up on something so
old is difficult. Much of the material is literally burned up. The
FBI had some really good improvisers and they scavenged raw
materials, doors, bed frames to create a makeshift morgue. There
was no running water, no ventilation, the smell was staggering,
flies all over you. It was very difficult to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a serial killer, one agent said, kills only a dozen or so
victims. This crime was different; the indictment says it involved
leaders of a nation who issued orders for their army, police and
wild bands of ultranationalists to kill thousands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved these crimes, I have no doubt about that,'' said
Eberhart as the FBI team packed up last week. ``Unless you've seen
it with your own eyes, you would never believe it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 0914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0065 </DOCNO>
