<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ON THE SOCCER FIELD: BRAZIL AVERTS ITS EYES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Across the United States right now, the
Women's World Cup of soccer is the sports event of high summer,
attracting stupendous crowds and frenzies of attention usually not
seen there for any kind of soccer, or any women's sport, let alone
both.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil met the United States on Sunday, July 4, in the
semifinals, but you would hardly have known it from the coverage
here in Rio.
</P>
<P>
   While Sissi and Katia (Brazilian soccer players use only one
name) are heading toward their confrontation with Mia Hamm and
Julie Foudy, Brazilian sports pages are focused almost entirely on
the prospects of their men's soccer team winning the Copa America
and the reasons why its coach, Wanderley Luxemburgo, left the top
goal scorers Romario and Edmundo off the squad.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer may be the king of sports here, but only the men's
version of the game seems to wear the crown. Not one of this year's
matches of the Brazilian national women's team has been televised
live, sponsors have shied away from any association with the team,
and hard-core fans who can recite the entire roster of the 1950
men's World Cup squad are hard-pressed to name even one of the
current World Cup women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, women's soccer still doesn't have a chance in
Brazil,'' Armando Nogueira, one of the country's leading sports
commentators, said when asked about the lack of interest here.
``The best woman player in Brazil will never be as popular as the
worst male player, and the main reason is that women have been
idolized as delicate objects of desire, incapable of playing a
physical-contact, body-to-body sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Renata Cordeiro, 29, is one of Brazil's few female
sportscasters, working for the SporTV cable channel as a soccer
specialist. She recalls that when she was a teen-ager, her best
friend asked that soccer be added to their school's physical
education curriculum. ``Absolutely not,'' was the answer that came
back. ``Soccer is not an appropriate activity for girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Such attitudes can be encountered all over Latin America, where
the passion for soccer is exceeded only by the deeply ingrained
machismo that governs the social roles of daily life. And
everything is accentuated in Brazil, which has won four men's World
Cups, more than any other country. Since the days of Pele, it has
prided itself on grooming the world's best players and playing the
most inventive and flashy version of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Brazil, soccer has a strong gender demarcation that makes
it a masculine domain par excellence,'' said Dr. Roberto da Matta,
a prominent anthropologist and sociologist. ``It is a sport that
contains all of the various elements that are traditionally used to
define masculinity: conflict, physical confrontation, guts,
dominance, control and endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the verbs used in popular speech to describe possession
of the soccer ball are also the kinds of words used in the street
to describe sexual intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, all nouns in Portuguese have a gender, and the most
common word for ball, ``bola,'' has connotations as feminine as the
voluptuous roundness of the ball itself, which to many Brazilian
males evokes the breasts and buttocks of a woman's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see players out on the field kissing or caressing the ball
all the time,'' Ms. Cordeiro pointed out. ``There really is an
erotic component to this, and it is all tied up with the idea of
the man subduing the ball just as he would a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The gender taboos extend not only to playing the national game
but also to seeing it performed. The stadium, with all its
ritualized public violence and swagger, both in the stands and on
the field, has traditionally been seen as off-limits to women. On
June 27, as part of a campaign to change that image, free tickets
were distributed to 8,000 women who were among the crowd of more
than 100,000 that attended the national championship between
Botafogo and Juventude at Maracana stadium here. But the notion of
actually going to a game remains anathema to many women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been to Maracana, and there is no way you could
ever get me to go there,'' said Leticia Carvalho de Almeida, a
34-year-old dental technician and mother of two daughters,
wrinkling her nose in disgust at the idea. ``Just to think of all
those stinking sweaty men shouting curse words, fighting and
pouring beer and urine all over each other makes me nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   In such an environment, the assumption at the popular level is
that any female athlete has somehow been masculinized and her
femininity compromised. The basketball star Hortensia got around
that problem by posing nude for Playboy; other basketball and
volleyball players, plagued by rumors that they are lesbians,
prefer to appear with boyfriends or husbands and children, their
faces made up and their hair coiffed, in glossy photo layouts for
gossip magazines like Caras or VIP.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that has held women's soccer back is that
there aren't any beautiful women yet who play the game,'' Nogueira
said. ``The volleyball authorities have made an investment in
sensuality that has really paid off for them, and women's soccer
needs to use those marketing methods. They should be trying to
increase the charm quotient instead of imitating men on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that Brazilians are interested in this Women's
World Cup at all, they seem more fascinated by the powerful U.S.
team, which has demonstrated the dominance and mastery they admire,
than by their own. As play was beginning, the weekly newsmagazine
Isto E ran a profile not of the home squad, but of ``the Yankee
girls'' and Ms. Hamm. Taking Brazil's flashiest male player as a
reference point, the article described Ms. Hamm as ``a kind of
Ronaldinho, but with better hips, a more agile game and an ability
to score lots of goals.''
</P>
<P>
   For female fans like Ms. Cordeiro, that focus has led to an
unexpected problem. As a Brazilian who knows and has interviewed
many of her country's top female players, she is naturally hoping
for a championship, or at least a good showing, by Brazil's team.
``It would really help the development of the game for women
here,'' she said. ``Brazilians expect their teams to win it all,
and if we could do that, it would build support and interest and
force the men to take the women's game seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a woman, she is also ``thrilled by the way the Americans
play, the skill and nimbleness with which they dribble and pass the
ball and score goals,'' she conceded. ``They've proven once again
that women are capable of great things if they are just given some
sort of opening.''
</P>
<P>
   Da Matta, though, cautions that no matter who wins the cup,
Americans have no grounds to feel superior. ``The fundamental point
to remember is that all societies, not just Brazil, have these
blind spots, and that such cultural differences persist despite all
the talk of globalization,'' he said. ``For example, in your
country you have lots of women playing soccer, tennis, volleyball
and even baseball. But where are your female football players?''
</P>
