<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3159 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-INTERNET-DOCTORS-RE     07-05 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-INTERNET-DOCTORS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM M.D. TO I.P.O: CHASING VIRTUAL FORTUNES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every Tuesday and Thursday morning at 8, Dr.
Domenica Vacca, an obstetrician-gynecologist who quit practicing
medicine two years ago when her son was born, arrives for work at a
white-shingled three-story building in Owings, Md. For the next
eight hours, she sits in front of a computer and holds private
electronic conversations with people seeking her advice on
everything from herpes to menopause.
</P>
<P>
   In her part-time job with Ask the Doc, a service offered free by
AmericasDoctor.com, Dr. Vacca traverses delicate legal territory. A
lengthy on-screen disclaimer informs her questioners that the
company's Internet doctors _ it employs more than 100 _ ``will not
engage in any conduct that involves the practice of medicine.''
They will not diagnose illness, prescribe medication, keep a
medical record of the conversation or even reveal their identities.
But they do provide something the callers' own doctors often can't
give: peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a lot of questions on menstrual irregularity,
pregnancy,'' Dr. Vacca says. ``A lot of questions on sexually
transmitted diseases, women coming on saying I have this pain or
that discharge, what could it be? And they will actually say, `I
can't get through to my doctor.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when managed care has put greater distance between
doctors and their patients, the Internet is filling the gaps.
According to Scott Reents, an analyst with Cyber Dialogue, a New
York company that tracks Internet commerce, last year an estimated
22 million Americans went online for medical information, mostly
about specific diseases and drugs. That number is projected to jump
to 33 million by next year.
</P>
<P>
   All that growth translates into what Reents called ``a
free-for-all'' on the World Wide Web, where thousands of sites are
offering some type of health information. Investment money is
pouring in; Dr. C. Everett Koop, a U.S. surgeon general in the
1980s, became a 1999 Internet millionaire when his Web site,
DrKoop.com, went public. Healtheon, the medical records giant, has
snapped up WebMd, a small Internet health information company, in a
deal valued at more than $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even Dr. George Lundberg, who as the editor of the Journal of
the American Medical Association, once cautioned that ``science and
snake oil may not always look all that different on the Net,'' has
gone electronic. After being dismissed from the journal in January,
he became editor in chief of Medscape.com, an information site for
doctors. Medscape will launch a consumer site this month, which
Lundberg said would ``set the standard'' for Internet health
information.
</P>
<P>
   With so much money at stake, and so many patients hungry for
information, experts say it was inevitable that doctors would begin
not only offering advice over the Internet but using the Web to
practice medicine. And they have, in ways that make many medical
experts, and even some Internet health entrepreneurs, a little
queasy.
</P>
<P>
   Some have set up Web sites for the sole purpose of prescribing
and selling hot-ticket prescription drugs like Viagra to patients
they have not met _ a practice that has drawn the attention of
state and federal regulators, who regard it as unethical, though
not illegal. The American Medical Association says doctors who
prescribe drugs to people they have never physically examined
should face disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ashamed to call them a part of my profession,'' said Dr.
Nancy Dickey, a former president of the association.
</P>
<P>
   Others are finding novel ways to diagnose and treat over the
Net. Dr. Daniel Carlin, a Massachusetts emergency medicine
specialist, founded WorldClinic to treat people living and
traveling abroad. Carlin, who has worked as a volunteer in Afghan
refugee camps, outfits his patients with kits that include
prescription medication. He keeps their medical records on file,
and patients who need him quickly can send an electronic message
and his beeper will go off. Soon, Carlin said, his Web site will
offer links to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and
other reliable sources of information. Last year, he drew
international attention when, via e-mail, he helped save the arm of
a Russian sailor who had been injured in a yacht race 1,000 miles
off the coast of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberdocs.com practices medicine at home. For a fee of $50 to
$100, the Web site provides board-certified specialists who engage
in private electronic chat sessions, which the company calls
``virtual house calls,'' to treat minor illnesses. The doctors can
prescribe any drugs except controlled substances, including
narcotics. Dr. Tom Caffrey, who founded the company in 1996, five
years after graduating from medical school, said he has diagnosed a
case of shingles, sent someone to the emergency room for heart
disease and refilled blood pressure medication _ all online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you're at work, you're feeling sick,'' said Caffrey. ``Do
you have four hours to go to the emergency room? Can you get an
appointment with your doctor who is jerking you around? Here's a
way for patients and doctors to talk again.''
</P>
<P>
   Caffrey says he wants Cyberdocs to lay the groundwork for the
next technological revolution, when video conferencing becomes
commonplace. The doctors at Cyberdocs, which is insured for
malpractice, work only within their specialties, and only on
patients who live in states the doctors are licensed in. ``We're
trying to do real medicine,'' Caffrey said, ``under the limitations
of the present technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the company is crossing the line. Why have
virtual visits, they ask, when there are plenty of American doctors
available? ``It is difficult for me to imagine that any physician
is doing this for other than monetary return,'' said Dr. David
Rothman, a medical historian at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   And why, some critics ask, would anyone attempt to diagnose a
patient's illness without a physical exam or even the simplest
tests, like blood pressure monitoring?
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole contractual relationship between a doctor and a
patient is that you actually see, touch, feel, smell a patient to
get as much data as you can to be accurate in your diagnosis and
treatment,'' said Dr. Bruce Dan, medical director of Medcast, a
private online service for doctors. The telephone is more
productive than an online chat, he says. ``You can hear the tenor
of the patient,'' Dan said.
</P>
<P>
   There are no professional standards for doctors working on the
Web, and experts say even those patients who sign on just looking
for a free opinion should be cautious. ``We don't know who's out
there giving the advice,'' said Dr. Arthur Caplan, director of the
Center for Bioethics at the University of Pennsylvania. ``You may
be getting advice on your allergies from a pathologist. On your
psychological problems from a gastroenterologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Someday, Caplan predicted, these problems will be erased by
technology. ``We will have certification and standards for doctors,
link-ups to televised images and readouts from microchips that may
be in your body,'' he said. ``I think that world will come, but it
ain't here by a long shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
