</P>
<P>
   Still, it could be worse _ and was. Vodka consumption has been
slowly falling since drinking peaked in 1994. That year, the
drowning rate among men was 30 percent higher than was reflected in
the 1997 statistics.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL WINES
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fed Raises Interest Rates Just a Tad, Just in Case
</P>
<P>
   There is little evidence of inflation. But there is enough fear
of it that the Federal Reserve raised interest rates a notch, to
make sure the economy does not get derailed by a spiral of rising
wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter point increase in the Fed's benchmark rate, to 5
percent, was enough to bring protests from business, labor and
other critics of tight monetary policy. But the Fed sugarcoated its
decision by suggesting it might not have to raise rates again this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Eases Restrictions On Computer Exports
</P>
<P>
   A month ago it seemed as if reports of Chinese spies and
technology leaks would result in a crackdown on high-technology
exports to China. Wrong. Under pressure from Silicon Valley,
President Clinton announced that he would make it far easier to
ship high-performance personal computers and microprocessors to
China, Russia and other nations. In an era when supercomputer
speeds can be reached on a $2,000 laptop, the president concluded,
it makes sense to control only the most rarified technology. The
Republicans, including Texas Gov. George W. Bush, seemed to agree.
The Silicon Valley, by the way, is a wellspring of campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Fewer Gay Men in New York Are Contracting AIDS
</P>
<P>
   The largest survey of the sexual health of gay men in New York
City has found a significant reduction in their levels of risky
sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Greater use of condoms and safer sex helped explain a sharp drop
in the number of gay men now infected with the AIDS virus (about
one in seven from about one in three in 1985), said officials of
the New York City Health Department who conducted the survey last
year in a partnership with the Gay Men's Health Crisis.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   A Long-Ago Slight And a Murdered Child
</P>
<P>
   It's a staggeringly upside-down tale. By all accounts, Ronald
Shanabarger of Franklin, Ind., married in anger, conceived a child
in anger and looked on in anger as his son was born. As
quick-flaring angers go, his was ancient: Before he married, his
wife-to-be had refused to cut short her vacation cruise when his
father died, and he silently vowed revenge.
</P>
<P>
   The anger burned on, and when his son was 7 months old, he
suffocated him in his crib. Then, haunted by the image of the
child's face, he confessed.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Backs 2000 Bill
</P>
<P>
   All spring, President Clinton urged Democrats in Congress to
oppose a Republican bill to limit lawsuits arising from Year 2000
computer failures. Detrimental to consumers, he said, and a
precedent for restraints on litigation. Most Democrats obliged,
despite pressure from the computer industry and other businesses
constituents. After Republicans made some small concessions, the
president changed his mind. The Senate and House quickly approved
the agreement, and Clinton promised to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats were furious, feeling the president had cut a
deal behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., ``we can dare hope
that this will be the last case of triangulation of the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM
</P>
<P>
   An Official Welcome Back For the Resurgent Bald Eagle
</P>
<P>
   The bald eagle, the symbol of American freedom, was officially
removed from the list of animals threatened with extinction. At a
White House ceremony, President Clinton credited efforts under the
Endangered Species Act for the bird's return.
</P>
<P>
   Some 500,000 bald eagles soared in American skies 200 years ago,
but by 1963, only 417 breeding pairs remained in the continental
United States. Hunting and pesticides that weakened eggshells were
among the causes of their decline. The eagles were put on the
endangered species list in 1967, and upgraded to threatened four
years ago, following years of efforts to improve their habitats and
reintroduce eaglets to the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Mitral Valve Problems Are Not So Serious After All
</P>
<P>
   As many as 28 million Americans who were told they are in danger
of stroke, heart failure and other problems because of mitral-valve
prolapse probably do not have to worry. A new study showed that
about 2.4 percent of the population _ not the 5 percent to 15
percent previously estimated _ have the condition, an abnormally
long, floppy valve that can cause blood leakage in the heart. And
in those who do have it, it was found no more likely to cause the
feared complications than those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Law Dies, and Mourners Are Few
</P>
<P>
   With little fanfare and no mourning, the independent counsel law
died after 21 years during which prosecutors appointed under the
statute rummaged through the public and private lives of Republican
and Democratic presidents, and scores of lesser officials.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, the statute, first enacted as an important
post-Watergate reform, was widely perceived as an abusive legal
bludgeon that had failed in its purpose of separating politics from
law in investigations of administration officials. Kenneth Starr's
wide-ranging investigation of the Clintons helped create that
perception.
</P>
<P>
   Responsibility for investigations of high-ranking government
officials now reverts to the Justice Department, where Attorney
General Janet Reno assumes much broader authority over when and
whether to seek outside prosecutors in high profile cases.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell Pleads Guilty
</P>
<P>
   Webster Hubbell walked out of a federal courthouse last week
with a remarkably good deal; he pleaded guilty to a felony count of
lying to regulators and a misdemeanor count of failure to pay
taxes, and avoided jail time even though he has already served time
for a felony.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel who struck the deal,
seemed even more pleased. It brought him closer to the end of his
difficult five-year investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Also a winner: Hillary Rodham Clinton, whose conduct would have
been explored at a Hubbell trial at the same time she is expected
to begin a Senate campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 1001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
