<HEADER>
A9575 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-PARENTS-LIFEBEA     07-05 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-PARENTS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK MONEY WITH AGING PARENTS BEFORE DISASTER STRIKES
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a man pondering a pile of medical bills 
 By Martha Nolan McKenzie 
 c.1999 New York Times Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Kimbrell watched his mother's health gradually fade. First
she suffered a series of strokes. Next came heart surgery, and then
Tressie Lee Potter, who is now 73, was diagnosed with Alzheimer's.
Still, a year ago when Kimbrell had to move her in with him and
take over her affairs, he was totally unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Kimbrell, a 58-year-old carpenter for a construction company in
Spartanburg, S.C., spent seven frustrating months locating the
financial documents that were scattered throughout his mother's
small ranch-style house. He found her checkbook underneath a pile
of videotapes, overdue bills behind the television set and her will
in the pocket of her Sunday coat. He has yet to locate the title to
her car or her insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know anything about her financial situation, and it
was real tough finding anything out, since I didn't have power of
attorney,'' said Kimbrell.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 ''Fiscal Fitness'' survey by Phoenix Home Life Mutual
Insurance Company in Hartford, Conn., found a third of respondents
with living parents had little or no knowledge of their parents'
financial situation, and 42 percent had not discussed financial
issues with their aging parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many parents would sooner show their children their
gallbladder surgery scars than show them their checkbook,'' said
Charles Alkire, a certified financial planner in Sarasota, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But not exchanging the information can lead to an outcome the
parents never intended. Instead of leaving an inheritance for their
children, parents could end up needing to be subsidized by them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone always quotes the Cornell University study that said
about $10.3 trillion is going to flow down from aging parents to
their children, but that study is seriously flawed,'' said Jerry
Potts, director of marketing for a Boston-based mutual fund
company. ''It didn't factor in longer life spans. It didn't factor
in health care costs, and it didn't factor in inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   For many individuals, the transfer of wealth will be the other
way, continued Potts, whose firm offers a specialized program for
adult children with aging parents. Often people assume that
Medicare will shoulder the biggest burden _ health care costs _ but
that's not always true. One thing Medicare generally won't cover is
long-term care, a topic parents may be very reluctant to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   If children are likely to be subsidizing parents, their own
financial plan should incorporate that need, according to financial
advisers. ''You can go through and do estate planning, save for
retirement, get all your investments in order, but if you ignore
your parents, all that could be wasted effort,'' said Potts. ''I
don't know of too many kids who could just say 'Sorry, you're on
your own' if their parents got sick or needed help. It can wipe out
a generation of wealth, and that's not being overly dramatic. It's
a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a fact that discussing money with parents won't be
easy, unless the family is unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ''Often parents won't cooperate, because they just can't believe
that their ducks aren't in order,'' said Joan Gruber, who owns a
financial planning firm in Dallas that specializes in helping adult
children deal with the issues of aging parents. ''Their idea is
they have a will and a power of attorney, so they are squared away.
But the will might be 20 years old and written in another state,
and the power of attorney might not be durable.'' That is, it might
not remain effective if the parent becomes disabled or incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   What can be done to avoid the problems Kimbrell and others have
faced? Financial experts offer the following tips:
</P>
<P>
   Broach the topic with sensitivity to the parents' needs and
feelings. Ease into the conversation by passing on a newspaper
article on the topic, or mention that you've started planning your
estate or preparing a will and you'd like to talk to them about how
they handled these issues. .
</P>
<P>
   ''Present it as it is _ a joint dilemma for you and your parents
to resolve together,'' said Susan C. Richards, a certified
financial planner and author of ''Protect Your Parents and Their
Financial Health...Talk With Them Before It's Too Late'' (Dearborn
Financial Publishing, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Assemble the emergency paperwork. This includes a durable power
of attorney, a durable medical power of attorney, a living will and
a last will and testament. A durable power of attorney can allow
you to do such things as pay bills, deposit Social Security checks,
and make other financial decisions for a disabled or incompetent
parent. A durable medical power of attorney allows you to make
medical decisions on your parents' behalf. Without these documents,
you would have to go to court to be named guardian of an
incapacitated parent. And a living will expresses your parent's
wishes regarding the use of extraordinary measures that would delay
death in the event of a terminal illness. These documents need to
be reviewed and updated periodically, preferably by an elder law
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Gruber calls these legal papers a passport to sanity _ when they
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Address your parents' health care needs. Make a list of the
names, addresses and phone numbers of all their physicians, their
pharmacy, their Medicare or Medicaid identification numbers and the
name and policy number of any additional insurance coverage.
Educate yourself about what Medicare will and won't cover to
determine if your parents need a supplemental policy. The
''Medicare &AMP; You Handbook,'' published by the Health Care Financing
Administration, can help.
</P>
<P>
   Find out if they have a long-term care policy. Does it cover
in-home care? If they don't have coverage, have they thought about
how they might meet those costs? A geriatric care manager _ a
professional who specializes in assisting older people and their
families with long-term care arrangements _ can describe the care
options available in your area and the costs involved.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a personal inventory. Parents should list the name,
address and phone number of their accountant, attorney, banker,
stockbroker, all insurance agents, the employee benefits
administrator and religious adviser. The list should include all
account numbers; the whereabouts of the safe-deposit box and key;
important documents, such as birth certificates, trusts, wills,
deeds, car titles, bonds, Social Security cards, powers of attorney
and stock certificates; and burial instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Determine your parents' net worth and whether it is likely to
sustain them. Spreadsheet programs are available that allow you to
merge assets and liabilities with estimated returns on investments
and rates of inflation and tell you how long the money should last.
Financial advisers will also do this.
</P>
<P>
   Simplify the finances. ''A lot of parents have overly
complicated finances,'' said Richards. ''They have a CD here and
another one there. They have a rollover IRA somewhere else. Their
money is just scattered everywhere. It's really helpful if you can
talk your parents into having just one broker, one banker or one of
those master accounts where you just get one statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial advisers recommend approaching parents when they are
in their 60s _ about the time they retire. It's a natural time,
since they likely will be taking stock to plan for life after work.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are very difficult conversations to have, and it's
tempting to put it off, but you need to do it,'' said Richards.
''Do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   (Martha Nolan McKenzie writes for the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
