<SLUG> BC-SINGER-MARY-CHAPIN-CARPENTER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADE FOR MUSIC: MARY CHAPIN CARPENTER LOOKS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of country singer Mary Chapin Carpenter.) 
 By MARGY HOLLAND  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Mary Chapin Carpenter has never been one to follow the pack.
Even when she does a greatest-hits album, it's got to be a little
different.
 &HT;    ``Party Doll And Other Favorites,'' released in May, is a
greatest-hits collection done Carpenter's way. When Sony Music
suggested that her seventh Sony album be a retrospective, the
singer/songwriter says, she didn't want to simply sign off on a
potpourri of old singles.
 &HT;    ``I saw it as the opportunity to veer widely from the formula,''
she says. ``The formula for greatest-hits records, from what I've
been able to see, is seven or eight of the best-charting songs.
Then you add maybe two new songs, and that's the greatest-hits
record.
 &HT;    ``I thought, `Well, let's try to be humble here and assume you
don't have an opportunity every day to release a greatest-hits
record to begin with,''' she says. ``Why not make the most out of
that opportunity, not do the formula and make it much more than a
greatest-hits record?''
 &HT;    The resulting album offers old favorites such as ``I Feel
Lucky,'' ``Passionate Kisses'' and ``He Thinks He'll Keep Her,''
but most of the recordings are live, not the original studio
versions that first became hits.
 &HT;    Beyond the tried-and-true, ``Party Doll And Other Favorites''
also includes songs from special projects, such as ``10,000 Miles''
_ written for the film ``Fly Away Home'' (1996) _ as well as two
new Carpenter-penned songs. Then there's the title track, ``Party
Doll,'' a Mick Jagger tune which Carpenter regularly performs in
her live shows but had never recorded for an album.
 &HT;    ``It seems to me that, in the last few years, I see artists
who've had maybe one or two records out, then the next record's a
greatest-hits, and I think, `Well, that's not very long of a life
there,''' Carpenter says.
 &HT;    ``I think a lot of times it's more an excuse on the part of the
record company to promote some filler or buy some time for
something else,'' she adds. ``I think in each case you have to be
careful to look at it and see what it really is for. Is it really
something of a retrospective, or is it an excuse for something
else?''
 &HT;    Of course, a retrospective collection also has implications as
far as her career is concerned. The singer/songwriter admits to
having been taken aback when she recently heard the album described
by a journalist as ``a midcareer record.''
 &HT;    ``My reaction was, `It is? I'm still getting started!'''
Carpenter says. ``But then I realized he was absolutely right. I've
been doing this for 10 years, at the very least, with a record
company, and many years prior to that, so I better get current with
myself and realize I'm not just starting out.''
 &HT;    Upon reflection, she decided to flaunt the fact that she's made
it this far, while still keeping oriented toward the future.
 &HT;    ``You know,'' she adds, ``if it's midcareer, then there's a lot
ahead of me, too.''
 &HT;    Given her five Grammy awards, three platinum albums and 12
top-10 singles, Carpenter found choosing the material to be
included on ``Party Doll And Other Favorites'' to be no easy task.
Revisiting a decade's worth of songs, she admits, was a trip down
memory lane, and not always a pleasant one.
 &HT;    ``Did I cringe? Were some cringe-worthy things there?
Absolutely,'' Carpenter says, laughing. ``There were things there
I'd sooner forget, and there were other things that I was just
delighted by that I had forgotten about and that I was proud of.
 &HT;    ``On the one hand, it was really humbling to go back,'' she
says, ``humbling from the standpoint of I sort of was reacquainted
once again with a lot of these projects or opportunities or events
that I'd gotten to participate in, and it was like, `Wow, that was
great.'
 &HT;    ``Then, on the other hand, it was like, `Where did all that time
go?' It was kind of bittersweet, too.''
 &HT;    Those years haven't been spent exclusively in the recording
studio or on tour, either. Carpenter has performed at a
presidential inauguration and for American troops in the Middle
East, as well as put substantial time and money into a variety of
groups promoting environmentalism, literacy and social change.
 &HT;    ``I think you owe it to yourself to do it,'' she says. ``And
that's not a guilt trip, but rather an invitation to get back more
than you give.
 &HT;    ``It's not hard to merge what you love with what's important to
you,'' Carpenter adds. ``What I love, obviously, is playing music,
and what's important to me are the various issues that I align
myself with, and to be able to merge them is simple.''
 &HT;    In the end, she says, she's never been able to come up with an
acceptable excuse for simply sitting on her hands when others need
help.
 &HT;    ``You realize you're in trouble if you think you're too busy or
that you haven't got the time or you're too tired,'' she says,
``because the minute you get out there, you're energized. All the
stuff that makes you feel too busy falls away, and you meet people
who change you.
 &HT;    ``It's not about politics,'' Carpenter concludes. ``It's
humanist _ it has nothing to do with politics, but it has
everything to do with just being a human being.''
 c.1999 Margy Holland  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Margy Holland is a Nashville, Tenn.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Mary Chapin Carpenter, consult
the Sony Music Website at www.sonymusic.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
