<HEADER>
A9586 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAYE-DIGGS-IN-THE-WOO     07-05 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAYE-DIGGS-IN-THE-WOOD-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOCK ON `WOOD': TAYE DIGGS MAY HAVE FOUND HIS BREAKOUT ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Taye Diggs with Richard T. Jones and
Omar Epps in a scene from ``The Wood.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Looking at handsome, hardbodied Taye Diggs today, it's hard to
believe that he was a nerd in high school.
 &HT;    He swears he was, though. Subtract some extra pounds of muscle,
add thick black glasses with tape on the sides, and that was him.
 &HT;    ``I had no friends,'' he says. ``Girls laughed at me. I was
never picked for any sports team.''
 &HT;    The girls stopped laughing some time back. As Diggs relaxes in a
suite at Los Angeles' posh Four Seasons Hotel, the lobby below is
filled with a swarm of women who've gathered in hope of catching a
glimpse of the man who gave Angela Bassett a whole new angle on
life in last summer's hit, ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' and
gave ``Go'' (1999) some of its go.
 &HT;    If they get that glimpse, they won't be disappointed. Biceps
bulge from Diggs' black T-shirt. His waist narrows as if it had
been created by a Disney animator. His hair is cut centimeters from
his scalp to frame a face that makes women melt.
 &HT;    It's the body of a man recently named by People magazine as one
of its ``Sexiest People Alive.'' But inside, Diggs insists, still
lurks the shy, insecure youth he was.
 &HT;    ``As a former nerd, it was a strange moment for me when People
magazine called to say that you are one of the most beautiful
humans on the planet,'' Diggs recalls. ``I had a good laugh about
it, but it was also gratifying on another level.
 &HT;    ``I've gone from nerd to sexiest man alive,'' the actor says,
laughing. ``There are days when you want to go back to that high
school, find your former tormentors and say, `OK, do you want to
re-evaluate?'''
 &HT;    Needless to say, it's all ``Stella's'' fault.
 &HT;    ``It's funny,'' he says, ``but for the first time in my life
brothers come up to me and say, `Taye, you've made my life
miserable with this movie. You were so sensitive and my girlfriend
thinks you're the perfect man. I can't measure up.'''
 &HT;    They can relax, though. In ``The Wood,'' opening July 16, Diggs
is anything but perfect, especially where women are concerned. His
character is a yuppie sort who bails out on the day of his wedding.
Suffering a bad case of pre-wedding jitters, he joins his best
friends (Omar Epps and Richard T. Jones) to look back on their past
relationships with women, their families and each other in a series
of flashbacks.
 &HT;    The title, incidentally, derives from Inglewood, Calif., where
writer/director Rick Famuyiwa grew up.
 &HT;    Diggs was offered a slew of scripts after ``Stella,'' but ``The
Wood'' was a natural, he says.
 &HT;    ``I had a very easy time with this character, because I related
to his situation of being at an age where you're making major life
decisions,'' Diggs says.
 &HT;    ``It was good for me to participate in this flick,'' he adds,
``because it made me realize you can really, truly, always have a
good time on a film set. I didn't necessarily have a great time
filming `Stella' or `Go.'''
 &HT;    Which isn't to say, he hastens to add, that he didn't like the
people he was working with.
 &HT;    ``I just found that these movies required a different style of
acting _ it wasn't very loose,'' he says. ``On `The Wood,' it
wasn't even acting. It was more like hanging out.''
 &HT;    The chemistry between the three buddies clicked almost
immediately, he adds. He recalls a scene in which his character
strips naked and use a garden hose to shower off before his
wedding.
 &HT;    Yes, ``Stella'' fans, it's another chance to see Diggs in the
altogether impressive.
 &HT;    ``I wanted it to be me in that scene. I'm not at the point where
I would ask for a butt double,'' he says, laughing. ``I don't
believe in star trips.''
 &HT;    On the day the scene was shot, however, he arrived to find Epps
and Johnson also in the buff _ a detail not called for in the
script.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to provide a little support for our brother,'' Epps
says in a separate interview. ``Plus we didn't want the women to
think that Taye was the only beefcake in this film.''
 &HT;    Actually, Diggs never aspired to beefcake status. Growing up in
Rochester, N.Y., and later in New York City, he saw himself as a
Broadway star, in preparation for which he earned a bachelor's
degree in musical theater from Syracuse University.
 &HT;    All set to pay his dues upon returning to New York _ he'd even
gotten a job serving pizza _ he was forced to cut short his
starving-actor days when, only a month after hitting town, he was
cast in the Broadway musical ``Carousel'' (1995). A year later, he
was playing Benny the landlord in the critically acclaimed musical
``Rent'' (1996).
 &HT;    Diggs stayed with ``Rent'' for almost two years, also appearing
in the soap opera ``Guiding Light'' and in guest roles on series
such as ``Law and Order'' and ``New York Undercover.''
 &HT;    Then came ``Stella'' and stardom _ but not necessarily
happiness, even when he was signed by Hollywood's top talent reps,
the Creative Artists Agency.
 &HT;    ``CAA sent me boxes of scripts right away, just to prove they
were working very hard for me,'' Diggs says. ``But not one of the
scripts really fit. Some of these scripts weren't really available
for me.
 &HT;    ``I finally had to tell them, `Look, don't send me this stuff
unless I'm absolutely right for it.'''
 &HT;    ``The Wood'' seemed absolutely right. So did his upcoming film,
``The Best Man'' _ which, coincidentally, casts Diggs as another
20-something guy worried about marriage. His character has also
written a tell-all book about the participants of a large wedding.
 &HT;    ``People at the wedding find out who slept with who and who was
a dog to women,'' Diggs says, smiling. ``It's all my fault.''
 &HT;    As for what's next, the actor isn't sure _ and he likes it that
way.
 &HT;    ``At this point, I want to take my career in segments,'' he
says. ``Right now I'm going through a stage where I just want to
have a good time. I want to try to avoid as much stress and as much
hype as possible. I don't want to worry about finding that Academy
Award-winning role _ I just want to have fun because I'm young now.
 &HT;    ``I realize that this business can be very stressful if you
approach it the wrong way,'' Diggs says. ``I'm just trying to walk
very softly and stay on my feet. I just enjoy the good things about
Hollywood, because the bad things will come no matter what.''
 &HT;    If things get rough, he adds, there's always the advice his
friend and co-star Bassett gave him on the set of ``How Stella Got
Her Groove Back.''
 &HT;    ``One day,'' he recalls, ``Angela pulled me aside and said, `Two
bits of advice: Don't believe your own hype and stay grounded.''
 &HT;    It was good advice.
 &HT;    ``Each day,'' Diggs says, ``I say to myself, `One second you're
the It Kid, and the next second you're on unemployment.'''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
