<SLUG> BC-MYRICK-AND-SANCHEZ-DIRECT-BLAIR-WITCH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOMSTICKS NEED NOT APPLY: THE SCARY NEW WORLD OF `THE BLAIR WITCH
PROJECT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Daniel Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez,
directors of ``The Blair Witch Project.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Now, that's horror.
 &HT;    ``The Blair Witch Project,'' an ultra-low-budget horror flick
starring three unknowns and directed by two unknowns, will open on
July 16. Also opening that day is a somewhat higher-profile film,
``Eyes Wide Shut.'' Its stars are the somewhat better-known Tom
Cruise and Nicole Kidman, its director the late, legendary Stanley
Kubrick.
 &HT;    ``Blair Witch's'' co-creators, writer/directors Daniel Myrick
and Eduardo Sanchez, reject any idea of challenging the Warner
Bros. ``event movie,'' of course.
 &HT;    ``We're not competing with Kubrick,'' Sanchez says hastily. ``I
wouldn't dare say that.''
 &HT;    ``I'm not even pretending to nip at Kubrick's feet,'' Myrick
says. ``We're just thrilled we got `Blair Witch' made and that
someone's releasing it.''
 &HT;    The funny thing is that, in its own way, ``Blair Witch'' is
enjoying as much buzz as ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' Since it scared the
bejabbers out of audiences at the Sundance Film Festival and set
studio executives clamoring for distribution rights, horror
aficionados have psyched themselves up by visiting the film's
website _ at www.blairwitch.com _ and immersing themselves in the
expansive ``Blair Witch'' mythology.
 &HT;    So what is ``The Blair Witch Project?''
 &HT;    It's a faux documentary about three film students who, in 1994,
vanish in Maryland's Black Hills Forest while shooting a
documentary about an evil legend called the Blair Witch. A year
later, locals unearth their footage, which depicts five harrowing
days spent by the filmmakers, lost in the woods and terrorized by
forces unseen.
 &HT;    ``This is a horror film,'' Myrick says over breakfast at New
York's Paramount Hotel. ``Some people cringe when they hear the
term `horror,' but when I think of horror I think of leaving the
theater with some residual effect of psychological fear.
 &HT;    ``That's what `The Exorcist' (1973) and `The Shining' (1980) did
for me. The heart of our film is to scare you. That was our goal.
 &HT;    ``I think the `Scream' films are good,'' he adds, ``but they're
running their course. Movies work in cycles, and `Blair Witch'
comes back to what Hitchcock did, which was scare you
psychologically. None of our film's horror is on camera ... we've
let the audience imagine their own horror.''
 &HT;    The 35-year-old Myrick and the 30-year-old Sanchez weren't the
film's directors in any traditional sense, nor is its script a
standard screenplay. They positioned their actors _ Heather
Donahue, Joshua Leonard and Michael Williams _ out in the woods,
handed them cameras and sound equipment, and told them to improvise
their dialogue.
 &HT;    ``We set up the situations for them to act in naturally,''
Sanchez says. ``When the tent shakes and they hear voices at 3 in
the morning, that's us. Dan and I were the Blair Witch, and they
were really tired and scared.
 &HT;    ``We tried to push the actors to that threshold of what was real
and what was not. That's why we used their real names.''
 &HT;    ``We needed to logistically create a system that allowed us to
use this improv setup,'' Myrick adds. ``We had a Global Positioning
System and so did the actors, and that let us program points in the
woods where we wanted them to go. They could just hike through the
woods and film each other.
 &HT;    ``At different checkpoints, we had little baskets with spare
batteries, extra tapes, a little food and directing notes. Ed and I
were in fatigues, and we'd shadow the actors to observe their
performances.
 &HT;    ``At the end of the day we'd collect the tapes, analyze what was
going on and adjust our directing notes,'' he says. ``The actors
got individualized notes, and were instructed not to read each
other's notes.
 &HT;    ``For the most part, directing was casting the right people and
guiding them through this world,'' he concludes. ``After we
wrapped, there was the editing process, which required wrangling
eight days of footage and getting it down to about 90 minutes.''
 &HT;    ``The film was not directed in a traditional way,'' Sanchez
says. ``We more or less wrote the script during the editing
process. If somebody else edited the footage, they probably
would've found two or three other movies in there.''
 &HT;    Myrick and Sanchez had worked together for eight years, since
meeting in 1990 at the University of Central Florida in Orlando.
But after collaborating on several short films and unproduced
scripts, they were ready to call it quits if ``Blair Witch'' went
unnoticed.
 &HT;    ``We've had our series of failures _ more than I want to
count,'' Myrick says with a sardonic grin. ``We were at the stage
where we really were thinking, `If this doesn't make it, I'm going
back to bartending.' It was our last hurrah, in a sense.''
 &HT;    The world will have to make do with two fewer bartenders.
``Blair Witch'' was accepted into Sundance, and as soon as it had
its first screening, the only question was which distributor would
come up with it. Eventually, it was Artisan Films which made the
best offer.
 &HT;    Now there's no escaping ``Blair Witch.'' It's on every must-see
list, and a terrifying number of ``Blair Witch'' tie-ins are on the
way, including a Sci-Fi Channel mock-documentary called ``Curse of
the Blair Witch,'' airing on July 12. And there's a comic book, a
Penguin Books ``investigative report'' and even ``Josh's Blair
Witch Mix,'' a CD compilation featuring 1980s tunes supposedly on a
cassette in the tape deck of Joshua Leonard's car at the time of
his disappearance.
 &HT;    Detractors are already crying ``Sellout!'' Naturally, Myrick and
Sanchez think otherwise.
 &HT;    ``I guess somebody could see it as selling out, but everything
we're doing is complementary to the film,'' Myrick says. ``It's all
part of the mythology we've built around the film, and it's just
made it more fun for everyone who's gotten involved.
 &HT;    ``People are embracing the film and thinking of it as their
own,'' he adds. ``They're saying, `This is my little secret' or
telling friends about it or adding to the mythology that's already
there.
 &HT;    ``That's what amazes me more than anything.''
 &HT;    Even before ``Blair Witch'' faces real-world audiences, its
creators are benefiting from its buzz. Myrick and Sanchez are
busily scripting ``Heart of Love,'' an ``off-the-wall screwball
comedy'' that Artisan will finance.
 &HT;    ``We've been tinkering with ideas for years,'' Myrick says,
``and now we're really writing the script. `Blair Witch' was just a
fluke of an idea that happened to come together as a movie, but
we've wanted to make `Heart of Love' for a long time.''
 &HT;    And, of course, Hollywood is beckoning.
 &HT;    ``We're getting a lot of bad scripts sent to us now,'' Sanchez
says with a laugh. ``The industry probably thinks of us as this new
horror team, but we're not.
 &HT;    ``If `Blair Witch' comes out and does gangbusters, we'll have
more options,'' he says, ``though we'll probably still do `Heart of
Love' next. If `Blair Witch' tanks, we'll have to be a little less
selective.''
 &HT;    Myrick nods in agreement.
 &HT;    ``I think we're in a good position,'' he says. ``Even if `Blair
Witch' doesn't make millions and millions of dollars, our investors
are already happy.
 &HT;    ``We'd just go back and make the smaller films we want to
make,'' Myrick says. ``The best thing about `Blair Witch,' as Ed
said, is that it's given us options.
 &HT;    ``We just have to be smart now about our next steps.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Blair Witch Project,''
consult the film's official Website at www.blairwitch.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
