<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONNY-OSMOND-LOOKS-BACK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE DOESN'T MIND IF YOU CALL HIM `DONNY': DONNY OSMOND COMES TO
TERMS WITH FAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Donny Osmond with Marie Osmond in a
scene from ``The Donny and Marie Show.'') 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donny Osmond doesn't care what you think of him.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, he'd rather you liked him. But it doesn't matter that
much to him _ and that very fact is something special for Osmond,
who not so long ago was so consumed with the desire to please that
it derailed his career and nearly ruined his life.
</P>
<P>
   We all remember the squeaky-clean kid who sang with his
brothers, soared to solo fame, scored huge television ratings
alongside sister Marie, suffered through a long spate of anonymity
_ including renaming himself ``Don Osmond'' _ and then reinvented
himself with four solid years of success in the Tim Rice/Andrew
Lloyd Webber musical, ``Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor
Dreamcoat,'' before reuniting with his sister for a successful talk
show, ``Donny &AMP; Marie.''
</P>
<P>
   Few, however, have witnessed the flip side of that
bright-and-smiling image, a history of self-doubts, debilitating
fears and serious reversals of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 41-year-old father of four is setting the record
straight with his candid autobiography, ``Life Is Just What You
Make It'' (Hyperion, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   LOUDON: Was it tougher than you expected to tell your own story?
</P>
<P>
   DONNY OSMOND: Much tougher. I decided that if I was going to
take the time to do this, I really had to dig deep, to disclose the
real Donny Osmond and what I've been through in my life.
</P>
<P>
   I also wanted to share all the big experiences and explore the
roller coaster of show business. I'm working on my fourth or fifth
career _ most people are lucky just to have one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You credit Andy Williams and Jerry Lewis as major influences
in your formative years.
</P>
<P>
   OSMOND: Andy really helped me as far as my singing was
concerned. I learned how to sing just by listening to him.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry helped me so much with timing, and with comedy in general.
My brothers and I were regulars on his variety show around 1967 or
'68. He'd play a character called Ralph Rotten, and he wanted me to
play Ralph Rotten Jr. I learned more from him during that season
than I can ever imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There was a time, around age 12 or 13, when you were arguably
the most famous person in the world ...
</P>
<P>
   OSMOND: That reminds me of a story. It was around 1973 or '74,
at the very height of the teenybopperdom. I got a letter addressed
to just ``Donny Osmond.'' No address, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It came from Sweden, and I guess some Swedish postman said,
``Donny Osmond? Oh, yeah, send it to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   When it got to the States, somebody at the post office must've
said, ``Osmond? That's Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   When it arrived in Utah, the postmaster here said, ``Oh, I get a
lot of these, I know where to send it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so a fan letter arrived from halfway around the world, with
nothing on the envelope but my name. That's better than Santa
Claus!
</P>
<P>
   But along with that comes a lot of responsibility. I always had
to suppress my feelings. I had to maintain a certain kind of
boy-next-door image because I was Donny Osmond. I would get letters
from fans saying, ``Donny, you can't say that!'' or ``Donny, you
can't do that!''
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad that, just before ``Joseph'' opened for the fourth
time in Toronto, I had what they called a nervous breakdown, but it
was more of an anxiety attack.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Didn't a therapist help you through that?
</P>
<P>
   OSMOND: Just before the Toronto opening, Geraldine Ross flew in
to help get me back on stage. She's the same lady who got Barbra
Streisand back on stage _ Barbra suffered from a very similar
thing, perfectionism, type A personality.
</P>
<P>
   So I walked on stage before they let the audience in, and there
was a group of ushers sitting in the theater getting briefed. And I
was having a major panic attack.
</P>
<P>
   I turned my back on them and started talking to Geraldine about
it. Ten or 15 minutes went by and she asked, ``Are you still having
the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``Yes!'' I said it was because I knew the ushers were
staring at me and talking about me.
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``Turn around, muster up enough energy to turn and
face them.''
</P>
<P>
   So I turned around _ and they were gone. There was nobody there!
It was all in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   I was blowing things so far out of proportion, and that was the
toll of all those years of suppressing my real feelings for the
sake of maintaining an image.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Given all the trouble it's been to you, how can you find any
humor in your teen-idol image?
</P>
<P>
   OSMOND: I remember back in 1989, when I released ``Soldier of
Love.'' I wanted so badly to get back on the charts, and worked so
hard for it. Slowly it started to happen, and all these radio
stations wanted me to appear on their morning ``zoo'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   Those morning hosts can be scathing, and every time I went in to
promote my music they'd just let me have it _ bugging me about
``Puppy Love'' or the purple socks or whatever. And it would drive
me crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day I realized that I had to go in there and make fun
of myself before they had a chance to. And it totally defused them.
They'd realize, ``Hey, this guy doesn't take himself seriously, we
can have fun with his image.'' And we'd sing ``Puppy Love'' and
move on.
</P>
<P>
   You can't take yourself too seriously, and you can't worry about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The talk category has become one of the most competitive in
television. What prompted you and Marie to enter the fray?
</P>
<P>
   OSMOND: I didn't want to do another variety show, because that
doesn't work anymore. And I really didn't want to do anything with
Marie, and she felt the same way toward me, because we both wanted
to focus on our individual careers.
</P>
<P>
   But when Dick Clark wanted to produce this thing, it suddenly
seemed right. Marie and I deliberated for a long, long time about
it. We realized that it was going to be a tremendous amount of
work, but we finally agreed because it felt so right.
</P>
<P>
   And a few weeks ago we found out that the ratings were going
through the roof and we've been picked up for next season, so
things couldn't look better.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has your family read the book?
</P>
<P>
   OSMOND: Yes, they have. As a matter of fact, my father called me
after I sent him the final manuscript. He said, ``I can't believe
you went through this kind of life.'' My own father!
</P>
<P>
   Q: You seem to have come through it with flying colors, though.
What's your secret?
</P>
<P>
   OSMOND: Every case is different, but for me it was just
perseverance and realizing that the business I'm in is fleeting.
The ups are really, really up, and the downs are really, really
down. I've lived a life of extremes.
</P>
<P>
   What I've learned from it all is that you can't really base your
happiness on outward success, because you never know how long it's
going to last. So I've learned to appreciate my family more,
particularly my wife and children.
</P>
<P>
   That's the only place true happiness can come from.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ont.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Donny &AMP; Marie,'' consult the
show's official Website at www.donnyandmarie.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
