<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT-PEPSI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE CAUTION HELPS JARRETT WIN PEPSI 400
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Winning a Winston Cup championship
requires an abundance of skill and not a small amount of what can
best be described as racing luck.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett is the odds-on favorite to claim his first title
because he has both in abundance this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett used that combination to win the Pepsi 400 last night at
Daytona International Speedway. His skill behind the wheel and the
skill of his pit crew got him to the front, and the good fortune of
a caution flag with two laps to go kept him there when the No. 88
Quality Care Ford was dangerously close to running out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been close,'' Jarrett said. I think we could
have made it, but they cut it awful close.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with plenty in the tank, Dale Earnhardt and Jeff Burton
might have caught him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hooked up,'' Earnhardt said. ``If it had stayed green,
I think we could have caught Jarrett. We just ran out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the race ended under the yellow flag brought out when
Jeremy Mayfield hit the wall in Turn 4 in the 157th of the 160
laps.
</P>
<P>
   As Mayfield hit the wall, the leaders already were at the
start/finish line. They had to race back around for a full, 2
1/2-mile lap before the caution was in effect. Jarrett remained in
front, followed by Earnhardt and Burton, to clinch his third
victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett extended his lead in the points standings to 177 over
Bobby Labonte, who finished fifth, and 229 over Mark Martin, who
was 17th. The standings are unofficial until they are certified by
NASCAR today. Jarrett and crew chief Todd Parrott also showed that
they intend to aggressively pursue the championship, not passively
let it come to them.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of caution periods _ there was only one in the first 147
laps _ turned the race into one of pit strategy. The leaders had to
make one last round of green-flag stops, but couldn't afford to
stay in for long. Would they take four tires or two? Gas only, and
if so one 11-gallon can or two?
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace was in first, followed by Mike Skinner, Jarrett,
Tony Stewart, Bobby Labonte and Earnhardt when the lead pack came
in at the end of the 144th lap.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett was in barely long enough for a splash of gas before
heading out again, this time in first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a stop,'' he said. ``They said they were going to give me
four seconds of fuel, but there's no way I was stopped for four
seconds. It worked out. That got us the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in position to win the race, if he had enough fuel. A
longer stop would have ensured he had enough gas to finish the race
and protect his position in the points standings, but would have
left little chance of seeing the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows we're here to win races,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt stayed in for two tires, and the seven-time Cup
champion had lost contact with the lead pack when he exited the
pits.
</P>
<P>
   But then Earnhardt got lucky. The second caution of the night
came out for the 148th lap because a gas catch can was loose on the
track. Earnhart was able to close in, as was Burton, who wasn't in
contact with the lead pack when he also took on two tires during
his pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   When the green flag came out with 10 laps to go, Earnhardt was
seventh and Burton 10th. Because they had the only two cars with
fresh rubber, they quickly were able to move up. With three laps to
go, they were second and third, and Burton was waiting for
Earnhardt to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was committed to going with Earnhardt, Burton said. We both
had two tires. The 88 didn't put on tires. If he'd gone off a
cliff, I'd have gone with him.''
</P>
<P>
   He never got the chance. The caution came out, and Jarrett was
able to coast for the final two laps.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he didn't coast until after taking the checkered flag.
He kept his Ford on the flat apron during those last two laps,
trying to conserve every drop of fuel, and ran out on the
backstretch of his victory lap.
</P>
<P>
   He coasted back around to pit road, and needed a push from the
pit crew to get to victory lane.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
