<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FIZZLE ON THE FOURTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers' stirring, ninth-inning victory
Friday served as this summer's best tease yet.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared the Seattle Mariners would become little more than a
colored speck in the Rangers' rearview mirror as late as the fifth
inning Saturday, but those pesky rascals from the Pacific Northwest
refused to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers gagged on a seven-run, fifth-inning lead Saturday
and then allowed left-hander John Halama to throw the Mariners'
first complete-game shutout since September 1998 during last
night's 6-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   At least Quality Care Network sponsored a spectacular Fourth of
July fireworks display afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers supplied the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel really good about this,'' Mariners manager Lou
Piniella said afterward. ``We won against a tough team, and our job
coming in here was to stay in contact with Texas. Naturally, if
they would have swept us, we would have been a ways back. Texas is
a good ballclub, though, and they've been in first place almost
since Day 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's victory and Saturday's fifth-inning lead, though, gave
the Rangers the opportunity to extend their advantage on the
second-place Mariners to nine games in the competitive American
League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we wanted to do, but it didn't happen that way,''
Rangers second baseman Mark McLemore said. ``They came out
swinging, and we faced some tough pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Mariners trail by only five games as the Rangers open a
six-game road trip tonight in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a long season to go,'' Rangers catcher Ivan
Rodriguez said. ``We've still got 80 games left.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama, whom the Mariners acquired with right-hander Freddy
Garcia and infielder Carlos Guillen in the July 31, 1998, trade
that sent left-hander Randy Johnson to the Astros, silenced his
opponents on this evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers managed only six hits, and designated hitter Rafael
Palmeiro produced the only one worth extra bases with his two-out,
ninth-inning double. The Rangers loaded the bases during their
final at-bat, but Halama (7-2) preserved the shutout and improved
to 5-0 with a 2.91 earned-run average in eight starts since joining
the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a dose of our own medicine tonight,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``He made a lot of quality pitches. He really
didn't give us anything to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-hander Morgan (9-6) would not fare as well.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez and designated hitter Edgar
Martinez supplied Halama with all the run support the left-hander
would need during their four-run first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman David Bell scored on Rodriguez's one-out single,
and Martinez cleared the bases one pitch later with a three-run
homer on a sinking, two-seam fastball from Morgan that neither sank
nor jammed the right-handed hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got it up, and Edgar did what he's supposed to do with
it,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much ended any chance of the Rangers burying the
Mariners this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with an awful lot of intensity,'' Seattle's
Rodriguez said. ``It was a huge night for us. Anytime you can get a
two-game swing against somebody in your own division, it's a big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers shrugged it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played pretty decent in the first half, but we need to get
better in the second half,'' Palmeiro said. ``I think we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-hander Jeff Zimmerman agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very evenly balanced division, and there are a lot
of great offensive teams,'' Zimmerman said. ``We still have what it
takes to win this division.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
