r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-T     07-05 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS FANS JUST EXERCISING THEIR RIGHT TO BE WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Manny Ramirez, his bucket head and his bucket full of
RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The American League All-Star team starts with two players: the
best player in the known universe and the best run-producer in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have Ken Griffey Jr. and Juan Gonzalez on the team,
then you get around to selecting Ramirez, Ivan Rodriguez, Roberto
Alomar and one really, really good shortstop to be named later.
</P>
<P>
   Blame Cleveland that it's not being that way. Somehow sniffing
the fumes from century-old factories along the Cuyahoga River have
left Indians fans with the delusion that not only Ramirez and
Alomar should be starting the All-Star Game but Travis Fryman and
Wil Cordero as well.
</P>
<P>
   So, urged on by Indians management, they have denied themselves
the other pleasures of their fair city _ like sunbathing along Lake
Erie and scarfing down pirogies in the Slavic Village _ and spent
their time punching All-Star ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Good for them.
</P>
<P>
   They were given the vote and they used it _ perhaps somewhat
irrationally at times, but so what?
</P>
<P>
   The best way to pick the starting lineups for the All-Star Game
is by letting the fans do it. The obvious danger is that highly
deserving players will be snubbed by overzealous fans in certain
cities, and it's a sure bet that nobody from the Montreal Expos
will be elected anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   But the worse thing that could come from the Gonzalez debacle is
a move to take away the vote from the fans. Refine the process,
yes. Give it to somebody else, no.
</P>
<P>
   The usual knee-jerk reaction in these cases is for the players
to say they should do the voting, because they know better than
anybody who deserves to be an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe that for a second.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, ``USA Today'' paid me to poll the players on
their All-Star selections, and the players were no more discerning
than your average laid-off Cleveland steel worker. The players
round up the usual suspects faster than anybody with no clear idea
who's truly deserving.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of experts? How about the Society of American Baseball
Research, a group that spends much of their collective waking hours
studying the national pastime. SABR even has its headquarters in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Well, ``Baseball Weekly'' asked SABR to vote for the top 100
players of the century and the 800-plus electorate proceeded to
vote Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig and Ted Williams as the top three
players.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, SABR is not the most ethnically diverse group going.
Ruth, yes. Gehrig and Williams over Hank Aaron and Willie Mays? No.
</P>
<P>
   The most vital function of All-Star voting is it keeps fans
connected to the game. Given that the average baseball player could
buy his own Cleveland steel mill, that's becoming more and more
difficult to do.
</P>
<P>
   Especially since baseball is an industry that prides itself on
alienating customers: what with strikes, charter seat licenses,
prohibitive concession stands and increasingly lopsided
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Severing fans from the All-Star selection process would only be
one more blow.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez should be disappointed by his meager All-Star vote
totals. Sometimes there is no accounting for taste, which is why
you have Fox television, the new Comiskey Park, Uma Thurman playing
Emma Peel and a second Austin Powers movie.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes you have to endure what's infernally painful for a
process that _ in the long run _ is good for the game.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
