<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Jul 6:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ NATO and Russian negotiators resolve a
dispute over the role of Russian peacekeepers in Kosovo, clearing
the way for more Russian troops to be sent to the troubled Yugoslav
province. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FUNERAL (Bela Crkva) _ The surviving villagers of Bela
Crkva pay their last respects to more than 60 victims of a March 25
massacre there. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (Lahore, Pakistan) _ A news analysis on the
Kashmir talks in Washington. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Political developments; what
Cabinet appointments tell us about the Barak government. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ASSESS (Mexico City) _ A news analysis on the state
elections and what they say about the presidential election next
year. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DRIVEBY-SHOOTER (Bloomington, Ind.) _ A profile of Benjamin
Nathaniel Smith, 21, the man who went on a two-day shooting spree
in two states. By Pam Belluck and Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Hazard, Ky.) _ President Clinton's so-called
poverty tour begins in Appalachia. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   WEICKER-POLITICS (Hartford, Conn.) _ Lowell Weicker, the former
senator, talks about running for president as a third-party
moderate candidate. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PETS-AT-WORK (New York) _ Fido at the office? More people are
taking their dogs to work, with some companies even designating
days to bring in the pooch. But not everyone in the workplace is
happy about the pet-friendly trend. By Lisa Foderaro.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-WOMEN (Washington) _ Vice President Gore's efforts to
appeal to female voters. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ENVIRON (Washington) _ Republican senators have loaded a
spending bill with anti-environmental riders. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-ART-PROTEST (Santa Ana, Calif.) _ Vietnamese in Los
Angeles protesting a museum exhibit of vietnamese art. not only
does it come from vietnam, and is therefore sponsored by the
Communists, but some of the images themselves themselves are
considered offensive. adding to the controversy, the museum agreed
for a short time to cancel the exhibit, but then got calls and
protests from anit-censorship people and other museums, and
reopened the exhibit. By Verne G. Kopytoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL-ELF (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Total Fina, Europe's
third-biggest oil company, makes an unsolicited, $43 billion offer
for rival Elf Aquitaine, in what would be France's largest takeover
ever. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   3M-OUTLOOK (St. Paul, Minn.) _ Try as it may, the Minnesota
Mining and Manufacturing Corp. is having trouble shaking Wall
Street's perception of the company as a boring, low-technology
drone whose glory days ended with Scotch tape and Post-it notes.
The problem, however, is not just image: earnings have been
sluggish in the last two years, and the company's management has
come under increasingly sharp criticism. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE-MAILBOXES (Undated) _ New Postal Service regulations
require that private mailbox addresses must bear the label PMB, for
private mailbox. Otherwise it will be marked ``Undeliverable as
Addressed'' and returned to the sender. And mailbox renters must
disclose their home addresses. The changes have prompted protests
from people who receive their mail through stores like Pakmail and
Mail Boxes Etc. Store owners and mailbox renters say the new rules
invade their privacy and pose a financial threat to their
businesses. By Michael Brick.
</P>
<P>
   NTT-COMPETE (Tokyo) _ Junichiro Miyazu heads Asia's biggest
company, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp., and he is about to
make it even bigger. Miyazu intends to use a new law to transform
Japan's telecommunications giant into a global player to battle
with the likes of AT&AMP;T. The new law, which took effect July 1
reshapes NTT and permits it for the first time to compete directly
in overseas markets. By Cheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, financial markets in the United States are closed for the
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis's ``Abroad at Home.'' Thomas L. Friedman is on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
