<HEADER>
A9653 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     07-05 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, July 6:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOLPHIN-VIOLENCE (Undated) _ The image of the peaceful,
playful dolphins is now being destroyed. Following a trail of
bloody clues, researchers have discovered that dolphins are far
from the happy, peaceful creatures humans think they know. Growing
evidence shows that the big animals are killing fellow mammals in
droves, wielding their beaks as clubs and slashing away with rows
of sharp teeth. Dolphins have been found to bludgeon porpoises to
death by the hundreds. Unlike most animal killers, which eat their
prey, dolphins seem to have murderous urges unrelated to the need
for food. By William J. Broad. (2200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SLEEP-PARALYSIS (Tokyo) _ Sleep paralysis, a disorder
involving a perceived evil in bed or a hurtling through a long
tunnel, is the result of a disconnect between brain and body as a
person is on the fringe of sleep. It is turning out to be
increasingly common, affecting nearly half of all people at least
once. Moreover, a growing number of scholars believe that sleep
paralysis may help explain many ancient reports of attacks by
witches and modern claims of abduction by space aliens. By Nicholas
D. Kristof. (1850 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORPHAN-PLANETS (Washington) _ Several Earth-like planets,
created billions of years ago during the formation of our solar
system, may be wandering in deep space harboring conditions that
could sustain some form of life, according to a new theory proposed
by a prominent planetary scientist. By Warren E. Leary. (1000
words)
</P>
<P>
   DERTOUZOS-FUTURE (Undated) _ In the 1970s, Dr. Michael L.
Dertouzos forecast that one-third of all American homes would soon
have personal computers. In 1980, he announced the coming of a
worldwide Internet culture. He looks backward and forward in a
conversation. In Q&AMP;A format. By Claudia H. Dreifus. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIGHTHOUSE-MOVE (Undated) _ On the move of the Cape Hatteras
Lighthouse, now under way. By Cornelia Dean. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on
folding proteins, a newly discovered species of deer in Myanmar and
the Cassini's second flyby of Venus. By Henry Founrtain. (700
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPOUNDED-DRUGS (Undated) _ Although that practice of
compounding, where a pharmacist mixes and measures ingredients to
fill capsules, has largely given way to ready-made products, it is
still used to prepare individual prescriptions for people who need
something not commercially available. But compounding seemed to
take on a new meaning last week, when advocates for people with
hepatitis C announced that a pharmacy could save customers a lot of
money _ as much as $900 a month _ on an expensive medication by
compounding it. The announcement seemed to take the FDA by
surprise, coming as it is trying to develop new rules to keep
compounding within certain limits. Officials say they are trying to
keep compounding, meant to make small amounts of medicine for
individual patients, from crossing the line to large-scale
manufacturing. In addition, some compounded medicines are
essentially new drugs that have not been proved or tested. By
Denise Grady. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERN-READING (Undated) _ A pot-boiler called ``The House
of God,'' is a novel that all the medical interns are reading. It
details the steamy side of medicine, and was written 21 years ago.
By Wendy Marston. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health column: Despite the
new Lyme disease vaccine, problems persist with prevention of the
disease, which has been diagnosed in 48 states. The vaccine is just
78 percent effective and it may cause some problems, but the
prevailing attitude among experts is that the vaccine is
worthwhile. By Jane E. Brody. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HERBS-SURGERY (Undated) _ Alarmed by what they see as the
potential for mishaps with patients taking herbal remedies for
everything from depression to memory loss, anesthesiologists have
begun urging people to stop taking the herbs and supplements before
having surgery. By Eric Nagourney. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-KICKBOXING (Undated) _ Kickboxing is a way to up the
cardio and down the assailants. It's a mix of tae kwon do, the
Korean system of self-defense that concentrates on kicking; karate,
the Japanese discipline that focuses on hand motions and postures,
and Marquess of Queensberry boxing with a touch of good old
American aerobics. It all cooks up to a sort of martial arts lite.
By Andrea Higbie. (925 words)
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Many women suffering from urinary tract infections may be able
to skip a trip to the doctor's office, be safely diagnosed and
receive prescriptions by telephone, according to a study published
in the current issue of the American Journal of Medicine. (400
words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A study that tracked 803 middle-aged men with strokes found
that African-American patients were less likely than whites to get
a diagnostic test to determine whether they were eligible for a
surgical procedure meant to prevent recurrent strokes. (380 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROSTATE-GUIDELINES (Undated) _ New guidelines issues for
prostate cancers are creating controversy. By Nancy Beth Jackson.
(560 words).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: In the search
for extraterrestrial intelligence (SETI) what kinds of signals
would be considered evidence of transmission by intelligent life?
How would scientists respond? (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
