</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LIGHTHOUSE-MOVE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELOVED HATTERAS LIGHTHOUSE ON A SLOW JOURNEY FROM THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By CORNELIA DEAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse was commissioned in 1870, it
was about 1,500 feet from the sea. By this year, the sea had crept
almost to its base. Now it is being moved inland, a decision that
did not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   Some nearby residents suggested the Corps of Engineers wall off
the lighthouse and let the sea move in around it. But geologists
said the structure's foundation was so shallow the lighthouse would
tip over if it lost its island base. Also, it was resting on heavy
pine beams that last for decades _ but only as long as they are
under fresh water, below the island's water table. Otherwise they
are subject to rot or attack by marine organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of a move suggested building rock piers to extend into
the surf and trap sand in front of the lighthouse, widening its
protective beach. But regulations bar such armor because it can
cause erosion of neighboring beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Still others felt it would be better to let the beloved
lighthouse fall to the ocean than to subject it to the indignity of
being hoisted up on jacks and moved.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, advocates of the move prevailed. Though moving a
208-foot, 128-year-old lighthouse looks daunting, they said, the
technology is off the shelf; it works more or less like the track
system that moves the space shuttle from its assembly building to
the launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   But because the lighthouse will travel over ground that is not
level to a site six feet higher than its original home, engineers
have installed a system of hydraulic jacks to keep it level.
Instruments mounted on the structure allow engineers to monitor its
position precisely.
</P>
<P>
   And, if all goes well, by August there will once again be at
least 1,500 feet of sand and scrub pine between the lighthouse and
the waves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
