<HEADER>
A9718 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FITNESS-KICKBOXIN     07-05 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-KICKBOXING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KICKING AWAY POUNDS AND ASSAILANTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANDREA HIGBIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time I hopped around in an exercise class, George Bush
was in the White House and Spandex ruled.
</P>
<P>
   These exercise classes _ aerobics, step, jazz aerobics, jazz
step, jazz aerobics step _ were excruciatingly repetitive and
boring. I abandoned them and their Paula Abdul music mixes with
glee when I met my (Stair)master and, on alternate days, took to
the streets running.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with some trepidation, understandably, that I prepared
to re-enter the realm of group sweat. I settled on kickboxing.
Exercise, and fun, with a purpose: self-defense. I could up my
cardio and down my assailants at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Martial Arts and Fitness in Bloomfield, N.J., seemed a good
place to start. Dave Vanderhoff, co-owner, chief kickboxing
instructor and black belt, believes in kickboxing: for
self-defense, for losing pounds and inches and for just plain fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep your hands up and you're kicking,'' he said. ``It's
constant motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Kickboxing is a mix of tae kwon do, the Korean system of
self-defense that concentrates on kicking; karate, the Japanese
discipline that focuses on hand motions and postures; and Marquess
of Queensberry boxing with a touch of good old American aerobics.
It all cooks up to a sort of martial arts lite.
</P>
<P>
   Kickboxing originated in Thailand (muay Thai), and is rapidly
becoming popular in the United States, mainly on the East and West
Coasts. In fact, the owners of U.S. Martial Arts have recently
opened a branch in Wayne, N.J., called Can-Do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids make up most of the traditional martial arts classes
these days,'' Vanderhoff said of karate and tae kwon do. ``Most
adults don't have time to commit three years to achieving a belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not a kid anymore and certainly not an adult with time on
my hands, off I went, ready to kick in the name of reportage.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 on a Sunday morning (ouch from the get-go) the big, bright
kickboxing room was already filled with 25 lean, mean female
machines in their 20s and 30s as well as a smattering of
fridge-hugging mamas crowding their late 40s. They wore sweats,
clean-soled sneakers or just socks and, like me, less and less as
the hourlong class continued, stripping down to jogging bra and
shorts. There were also two men, one of whom left the floor,
panting, only 25 minutes into the class to lie down and recuperate
in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what felled him: the constant one, two, three, kick,
punch, kick, kick, kick action and the relentless, hard-driving
repetitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very fast-paced,'' Vanderhoff said. He did not
exaggerate.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to be in fairly good shape, if not in fighting form.
Kickboxers-to-be are free to work out at their own pace, learning
the movements and improving as they go along, as they would in any
martial arts or exercise class. It is more fun, of course, to keep
up with the instructor. (And even to try to surpass him.)
</P>
<P>
   The preferred music mix is 140 to 160 beats per minute,
Vanderhoff says. He enjoys power mix CD's, especially ``Aerobics
Power Mix 27,'' with its thumpy, club music from Umboza, Dynamic
Bass, Promise, 2 Unlimited, Angelina, Marmalade, Undercover,
Bronski and Mission. No Paula Abdul within hearing range this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want the music to lull at all,'' he said. Trust me,
it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Rena Lampe, an instructor complete with headset microphone to
issue her commands, began sweating (and this was sweating, beyond
mere perspiring and glowing) a few minutes into her class. You know
you're in for it when the leader is so hard she's hard on herself,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The action over all is aerobics-esque, '80s-ish even. It's
particularly apparent with the dance mixes and the hooting and
hollering deep into the workout, but with the Asian ``hi-YAH!''
instead of the American ``woo-HOO!'' Unless you are in a match
against an opponent (think Jean-Claude Van Damme's movie
``Kickboxer''), kickboxers polish their skills by competing with
themselves, kicking and punching the air.
</P>
<P>
   The last 10 minutes of class were devoted to sit-ups _ dozens
and dozens of them _ and thigh and glute work, the toning chaser
after the big sweat, the gravy on this tough meat-and-potatoes
workout. The word on the mat is that the more you sweat, the better
the workout. And sweat you do.
</P>
<P>
   You feel as if something, something good but painful, is
happening. Rena instructed us to ``take it easy today and take a
short walk tomorrow.'' Though I ignored her advice, meeting my
Master the next morning, my body is on fire until Tuesday morning,
when I go back for more.
</P>
<P>
   I  &UR; feel  &LR; tough. I love it!
</P>
<P>
   Miles, my 5-year-old son, watched the classes. ``You're cool,
Mommy,'' he said approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   I  &UR; feel  &LR; cool. Invincible.
</P>
<P>
   And just as soon as my arms and back stop aching, I'll be ready
to disable any assailant (if he's unarmed, under 5 foot 10 and
weighs less than 200 pounds). Then I'll challenge him to a sit-ups
contest. I know I'll win.
</P>
<P>
   The Next Step
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Martial Arts in Bloomfield, N.J., charges $8 per class,
$69 for 10 classes or $118 for 20 classes. For more information,
call, (973) 893-9400.
</P>
<P>
   The World Kickboxing Association (www.worldkickboxing.com) and
the International Kickboxing Federation (888-453-5425,
www.ikfkickboxing.com) offer information about instruction, classes
and events in the United States and other nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
