<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PROSTATE-GUIDELINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVIGATING THE OPTIONS FOR PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By NANCY BETH JACKSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A man facing prostate cancer can find himself lost in a forest
of contradictory treatment options even before the final diagnosis
is in.
</P>
<P>
   To help negotiate the often still-uncharted terrain, the
American Cancer Society and the National Comprehensive Cancer
Network, a coalition of 17 top cancer centers, have issued
diagnostic and treatment guidelines based on how prostate cancer is
most commonly treated and diagnosed today.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to laying out details about the disease and
therapies, including side effects, the report offers a flow chart
called variously an algorithm, decision tree, and a clinical
pathway to show where decisions will lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deluge of information, but the problem is that it's
just facts without structure,'' said Dr. Rodger Winn, associate
professor of community oncology at the University of Texas M.D.
Anderson Cancer Center and chair of the National Comprehensive
Cancer Network guidelines steering committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of the guidelines,'' he said, ``is to lay out the
options and help individuals understand what the choice means.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees that the guidelines do that.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society translated the original network
guidelines for oncology professionals into a more user-friendly
text, but it may still be difficult to understand for some.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Scardino, head of the prostate cancer program at
Memorial Sloan-Kettering in New York and a member of Winn's
committee, has reservations about just how user-friendly the
guidelines are for a controversial, complex and evolving disease.
</P>
<P>
   Scardino finds the guidelines, particularly the flow chart, more
useful for other doctors than for patients. He considers them a
legitimate effort to get out a well-reasoned consensus of
possibilities based on current information, but he does not
encourage using the document as a patient's starting point.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Luton, a prostate cancer activist in Atlanta, reviewed the
text to make it more accessible to laymen. He argues that ``nothing
like this has been out there before. This is remarkable input.''
</P>
<P>
   When he asked for something to read about prostate cancer after
his case was diagnosed in 1989, his doctor replied, ``You'll just
have to listen to what I have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The prostate cancer guidelines follow by four months a similar
document for the diagnosis and treatment of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But the prostate cancer guidelines may be less clear-cut and
more controversial because research in prostate cancer is less
conclusive than breast cancer studies, Scardino suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at the difference of what we know about breast
cancer and what we know about prostate cancer, the knowledge base
in breast cancer is clearly superior,'' he said. ``We're so much
farther along than we were 10 years ago, but we sure do need more
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Prostate Cancer Treatment Guidelines for Patients, (Version 1,
July 1999) can be accessed through www.cancer.org or www.nccn.org.
A copy may also be obtained by calling (800) 227-2345 or (888)
909-6226.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines will be updated annually and more frequently
online if research indicates major changes in the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
