<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIGOTT-ICEMAN-NYT     07-05 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGOTT-ICEMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM `JEWEL IN THE CROWN' TO A MAN OF MANY FACETS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By MERVYN ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Pigott-Smith's 14 episodes of fame came in the mid-1980s,
when his portrayal of the sadistic police superintendent Ronald
Merrick in ``The Jewel in the Crown'' made him the villain British
and American television viewers loved to hate. In the ensuing 14
years, Pigott-Smith has had a busy career, but fame has not been
part of it. And, he said, he doesn't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fame is a difficult commodity to handle, and I was never
really interested in it,'' Pigott-Smith said. The 52-year-old
actor, looking trim and fit in denim shirt, jeans and open sandals,
chatted over tea and pastry at a hotel coffee shop down the block
from the Brooks Atkinson Theater, where he is portraying the failed
anarchist Larry Slade in the critically hailed revival of Eugene
O'Neill's ``Iceman Cometh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fame changed my life completely because for a while I was in a
position to choose what I did,'' he said. ``I miss that aspect. But
I always felt uncomfortable with it. People used to say to me,
`Tim, you're a star now.' But I'm a character actor. I guess I
still have a certain celebrity status because people remember
`Jewel in the Crown' very potently. But it was a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Pigott-Smith is one of a cast of 19 in ``The Iceman Cometh,''
among them Kevin Spacey in his Tony-nominated role as Hickey, the
salesman of death who arrives in 1912 at Harry Hope's skid row bar
_ the No Chance Saloon, the Bedrock Bar, the End of the Line Cafe _
to rouse its drunken denizens from their pipe dreams. The
production, directed by Howard Davies, was first presented at the
Almeida Theater in London.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 14 years, Pigott-Smith has starred in London in
Michael Frayn's ``Benefactors,'' in a role Simon Jones later did on
Broadway. He acted in a series of plays directed by Sir Peter Hall
at the National Theater, playing Leontes in ``The Winter's Tale''
and Octavius in ``Antony and Cleopatra'' with Dame Judi Dench. He
ran a theater company, Compass, touring all over England with ``The
Royal Hunt of the Sun,'' ``Julius Caesar'' and ``Amadeus'' (he
played Salieri) and directing for the first time. And he starred on
British television in a series called ``The Chief,'' in which he
played a chief constable.
</P>
<P>
   He also tried his hand at the movies. ``Everybody wants a movie
career,'' he said. ``I found that pretty elusive. I did make a
movie with Martin Sheen about a nuclear scientist who has a
religious experience. I don't even know what it was called. I don't
think it was ever released.''
</P>
<P>
   Another attempt was more successful: He portrayed the husband of
Emma Thompson's character in ``The Remains of the Day'' in 1993.
``I do small parts in movies now and then,'' he said. ``But really
that was the last movie I made. I get offered work that I just
don't want to do. But I'm also at an age when I get offered less
work. Because you hit your 50s and suddenly you're not playing the
leading roles. Because they're written for people much younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home, he said, audiences these days are often more familiar
with his voice than his face. ``I earn a lot of money in England
doing voice-overs, especially in documentaries,'' he said. ``Turn
on the Discovery Channel here and you'll hear my voice a lot. It
subsidizes my vice of acting in the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Pigott-Smith looks quite different now from the way he did as
Ronald Merrick. For his current role he shaved the top of his head
and grew a full beard _ a beard that has more than a few flecks of
gray. ``My normal hair is thin, but not completely bald,'' he said.
``I haven't cut my hair or beard since early February, when we came
here to do the play, and I won't cut it until we finish. It helps
me get into being Larry, who's a much older person.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Larry who first gives voice to O'Neill's thesis, that
``the lie of a pipe dream is what gives life to the whole
misbegotten mad lot of us, drunk or sober.'' Larry declares that
his own pipe dreams are all dead and buried and that he eagerly
awaits the ``fine long sleep of death.'' But, of course, that too
is a lie, and in fact he clings to life with all his might.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry doesn't believe he's attached to anything,''
Pigott-Smith said. ``He thinks he has denied everything. You have
to demonstrate to the audience very early on that he's as
self-deceived as the rest of the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the actors in the play, Pigott-Smith is onstage for
all or almost all of its four acts, for more than four hours. ``On
Saturdays, when you do it twice, you get so involved in the world
of the bar that it's hard to remove yourself when the evening is
over,'' he said. ``The lights go down, and sometimes I don't know
where I am. Sometimes it feels as if I'm in a real bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Pigott-Smith was born in Rugby, a small town not far from
Stratford-on-Avon, but his family soon moved to Nairobi, Kenya,
after his father, a journalist, got a job with The East African
Standard. They returned to Leicester, an industrial town in the
Midlands, where he went to school for 10 years. Then his father was
hired as editor of a weekly newspaper in Stratford-on-Avon, and
after the family moved there in 1962 the teen-age Tim was
introduced to the Royal Shakespeare Company.
</P>
<P>
   He began to immerse himself in theater. After Stratford Grammar
School, he worked in the paint shop and props department of the
Royal Shakespeare Company. He went off to Bristol University, and
then to the Bristol Old Vic Theater School. He acted in classical
theater with the Royal Shakespeare Company, playing Dr. Watson in
the company's 1974 New York ``Sherlock Holmes'' _ his only previous
Broadway experience _ before moving increasingly into television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iceman Cometh'' is on Broadway for a limited run, through
July 17, and Pigott-Smith said he did not know what he would be
doing next. ``I think Kevin Spacey wants to film the play for
television, and I would love to do that,'' he said. ``Aside from
that I don't really care, as long as it's good work.'' He will
probably head home to see his wife of 27 years, the British actress
Pamela Miles, and their son, Tom. ``Pamela and I did `Sherlock
Holmes' together,'' he said. ``I was Watson and she was the French
maid.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been back to India only once since ``The Jewel in the
Crown,'' which was seen in 1984 and 1985 on American public
television and was adapted from Paul Scott's ``Raj Quartet,'' a
series of novels about the waning days of British rule in India.
The latest trip was to do documentary work in Calcutta. He said he
still had a deep affection for India and hoped to return again.
</P>
<P>
   Pigott-Smith also has a nontheatrical career, as a writer. He
wrote scripts for the Calcutta documentaries and has a contract to
do three children's books while in New York. ``I enjoy writing,''
he said. ``Maybe that's my father's journalistic gene coming out.
The children's books have to do with Sherlock Holmes. I just
finished the first draft of the first. So I've been using my time
here quite gainfully.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has a new hobby. ``About a month ago I learned how to
Rollerblade,'' he said. ``I haven't told my wife yet, let alone my
producer. Sometimes I Rollerblade to work, but it's most lovely in
the park, and it's really quite safe there. I do it quite
carefully, and I wear all the gear.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. ``I'm a survivor,'' he said. ``Not a speeder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
