<HEADLINE>
MEDICINE'S STEAMY SIDE, FOR AND ABOUT INTERNS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Ohio, Wis., Mass., Calif.)  (nk) 
 By WENDY MARSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first of July marks the day that hospitals open their doors
to the new crop of interns, a number of them clutching dog-eared
copies of a pot-boiler novel called ``The House of God.'' Published
21 years ago, the book chronicles a year in the life of an intern
training at one of the best hospitals in the country, which the
author will not identify.
</P>
<P>
   Though the book is virtually unknown outside the health care
field, despite an introduction by John Updike, it is passed from
one intern to the next and has sold more than two million copies.
</P>
<P>
   A few years after its publication, ``The House of God'' inspired
a heated exchange in the letters column of The New England Journal
of Medicine. Some physicians saw the book as being contemptuous of
chronically ill patients and disparaging of older doctors. Others,
however, defended it as an honest portrayal of modern medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Dr. Anne Hudson Jones of the University of Texas
Medical Branch in Galveston, wrote in The Lancet, a British
journal, that ``The House of God'' and Sinclair Lewis'
``Arrowsmith'' were this century's pivotal medical novels. ``It's
an underground classic on medical campuses,'' Dr. Hudson Jones said
in an interview. ``But it was scandalous when it came out. A lot of
doctors, especially older ones, were concerned over the language
and the attitude toward patients in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel, published in paperback by Dell, was written by Dr.
Stephen Bergman, the year after his own medical internship when he
was a psychiatry resident at Harvard. Bergman wrote under the pen
name Samuel Shem. (Now a professor of psychiatry at Harvard, he
said he used a pen name to protect his psychiatric patients.) In
his book, he detailed gory deaths, multiple medical errors and
steamy sex scenes with voluptuous and willing nurses; the novel is
a curious mix of a much grimmer ``E.R.'' and an Erica Jong sex
comedy. The main character in the book, an intern named Roy G.
Basch, learns the true laws of medicine, including ``Gomers don't
die.'' The term Gomer refers to the elderly and chronically ill
patients and stands for ``Get Out of My Emergency Room.'' Although
Bergman, 54, admits that rampant sex in a hospital has abated since
the 1970s, the rest still holds true. ``All the horrific parts are
real,'' he said. ``It's the `Catch-22' of medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Other doctors agree. Dr. James Siy, 32, an internist in
Milwaukee, says: ``We still divide patients into Gomers and Dying
Young. That's a large part of the sadness of medicine that still
exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the same way his characters did,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Word of mouth has been the book's driving force. A pulmonary
specialist, Dr. Laurence Martin, 55, of Mount Sinai Hospital in
Cleveland, invokes it in a hospital survival guide, which he
distributes to residents and interns. ``Most doctors wish they had
written it themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all share that desire. Dr. Matthew Spitzer, 30, a family
practitioner in San Francisco, resisted reading ``The House of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I avoided it throughout medical school because I thought I
wasn't a cynical doctor. But when I read it at the end of fourth
year, I thought, `well, basically my life is this book.'''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, though unimpressed with Dr. Bergman's writing, believes
that the novel does a service. ``The book is really a piece of
trash, but it's true. It's what your family doesn't want to hear
and your friends don't want to know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
