<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CURE AS CLOSE AS THE NEAREST PHONE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ohio, Wash., N.C.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many women suffering from urinary tract infections may be able
to skip a trip to the doctor's office, be safely diagnosed and
receive prescriptions by telephone, according to a study in the
current issue of The American Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of all American women are plagued by uncomplicated
urinary tract infections, also known as cystitis. The irritating
symptoms include an urge to urinate frequently, burning sensations
and sometimes bleeding during urination. The disorder is often
diagnosed with a urine test and treated with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Michigan Medical Center and the
University of Washington in Seattle wanted to find out if the urine
test could be eliminated, because most women who have had the
condition know the symptoms, which are generally easily recognized
by doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In the study of 3,889 patients treated for the disorder in a
two-year period, nurses at 24 clinics used a set of guidelines to
help determine if patients suffered from the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Two clinics did not use the guidelines and served as controls.
</P>
<P>
   Forty percent of patients who called after the guidelines were
put into effect received telephone diagnosis and treatment. Of
these, 64 percent who described suffering from urinary tract
symptoms were given urinalysis, compared with 85 percent before the
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also reported no significant difference between
the number of women who needed follow-up care for recurring urinary
tract infections or other potentially misdiagnosed ailments among
cases that had been treated before or after the guidelines took
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the appropriate clinical settings, this telephone-based
approach is safe, conventional and cost effective,'' said Dr.
Sanjay Saint, assistant professor of internal medicine at
University of Michigan Health System and lead author of the study.
``Women can get faster and equally effective help, saving time and
money that is wasted on urine tests and doctor visits.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Nicolette Horbach, an associate clinical professor at
Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine, cautioned, ``In
simple uncomplicated UTI in low risk patients, phone treatment is
appropriate, but it can't be used with all patients,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN CASES OF STROKE, UNEQUAL TREATMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A study that tracked 803 middle-aged men who had suffered
strokes found that African-American patients were less likely than
whites to get a diagnostic test to determine whether they were
eligible for a surgical procedure meant to prevent recurrent
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the current issue of Stroke, the journal
of the American Heart Association, did not pinpoint a single cause
for the discrepancy. In fact, the researchers ruled out economic
considerations because all the patients were being treated in
Veterans Administration hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, stroke victims are evaluated using either
ultrasound or angiography to determine if there are dangerously
high levels of plaque on the walls of the carotid arteries, which
supply blood to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery called carotid endarterectomy has become a common method
for reducing such plaque buildups.
</P>
<P>
   But in the study, only 67 percent of the African-American
patients underwent carotid testing, compared with 79 percent of
white patients.
</P>
<P>
   The study's lead researcher, Dr. Eugene Oddone, who holds titles
at the Veterans Administration Medical Center in Durham, N.C., and
at Duke University Medical Center, said that earlier studies had
found even greater disparities, but that this was the first to show
that a gap remained even after physiological differences between
the races were taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   Oddone speculated about two possible reasons for the disparity.
``There may be a racial difference in the way treatment options are
communicated to patients by their physicians,'' he said, adding
that the communication could lead more black patients to decline an
endarterectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors believe that blacks are more likely to have plaque
buildups in their brain arteries, making them poor candidates for
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Oddone said, African-Americans who were
tested were operated on at roughly the same rate as whites.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
</TEXT>
