<HEADLINE>
`INVESTIGATIVE REPORTS': IN SEARCH OF THE REASONS FOR ANTI-GAY
VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Wyo., Ark., Idaho, Ark.) (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If any question remains of the viciousness of recent physical
attacks on gay people, Tuesday night's graphic pictures from
Wyoming, Arkansas and Idaho should settle the matter. Whether they
signal a rise in such crimes, however, or in the depth of the
incidents of rage that have stunned the nation is less certain, and
``Anti-Gay Hate Crimes'' offers more resurgence than evidence.
</P>
<P>
   This episode of ``Investigative Reports'' suggests, not
implausibly, that an increasing public acceptance of gay men and
lesbians has invited a backlash that has brought fresh eruptions of
violence. But the question of whether the young men who have been
convicted of murders and assaults represent something more than
individual aberrations requires stronger evidence than the
sometimes propaganda-thick psychological tags that are provided.
</P>
<P>
   There are troubling examples, however, of the heated language,
mostly from the religious right, that is probably provoking
congregations to take literally the inveighing about homosexuals'
being damned for eternity. With preachers transmitting charges that
gay people are corrupting the nation by doing the devil's work, it
is easy for impressionable youths to conclude that tormenting
schoolmates is a road to salvation. One Arkansas boy tells of being
assaulted by eight other boys and in effect being driven out of his
school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the dispute over what to do about ``hate crimes'' except
to deplore them could use more reasoned discussion than is provided
here. Should seemingly victimized groups be signaled out for
special protection from what after all are already crimes? Is
``hate crime'' a category of offense that calls for especially
severe punishment? Tuesday night's pictures, though they turn the
stomach, contribute little to deeper analysis.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   INVESTIGATIVE REPORTS WITH BILL KURTIS: Anti-Gay Hate Crimes
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Tuesday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Kate Davis and David Heilbroner, producers. Produced for A&AMP;E by
Q-Ball Productions. Michael Cascio, executive producer for A&AMP;E;
Bill Kurtis, series executive producer and anchor.
</P>
</TEXT>
