<HEADER>
A9754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVISIBLE-BOOK-REVIEW     07-05 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVISIBLE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INVISIBLE WORLD': THINKING TOO MUCH ABOUT SOUR RELATIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, the central characters in David Gates' polished
new collection of stories seem a varied lot: women caught in
suffocating marriages to pompous, self-absorbed men; a middle-aged
gay man who finds himself taking care of his sister's young son
after she goes into rehab; an elderly retiree who is recuperating
from a devastating stroke that has left him completely dependent on
his wife, and a divorced father who re-encounters his ex-wife while
keeping vigil at his daughter's hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact ``The Wonders of the Invisible World'' often feels as
though Gates were trying to challenge himself by writing from a
multiplicity of viewpoints _ young and old, straight and gay, male
and female _ all rendered with meticulous emotional detail and an
astringent sense of the absurdities and self-indulgences of
contemporary life.
</P>
<P>
   On closer examination, however, the people in this volume have a
lot in common with one another and with the narcissistic heroes of
Gates' two novels, ``Jernigan'' (1991) and ``Preston Falls''
(1998). Many are inveterate readers, using books not to connect
with the larger world beyond but to shut themselves away inside
their own heads. Most are afflicted with a terminal sense of irony.
And all tend to think too much: about themselves, their
relationships and the day-to-day workings of the world.
</P>
<P>
   When Billy is entrusted with the care of his young nephew, he
finds himself relieved ``that he hasn't found the boy's narrow
nates and teensy penis at all arousing,'' while ``at the same time,
he's irked with himself for being relieved'' _ after all, he
doesn't assume that straight men ``reflexively slaver over girl
children in their care.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Bad Thing'' the narrator muses over her husband's
ability to quit smoking, thinking that ``a man who could pick up a
thing and then just drop it'' could easily leave their marriage,
even though she is ambivalent above their relationship herself. In
``The Crazy Thought,'' Faye wonders why people use the expression
``moral support:'' ``Was the assumption that people's morals needed
help in time of stress? Or was it moral of you to lend support?
This was one of those things that flew apart if you looked too
closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Under such self-scrutiny, these people find their lives
succumbing to the centrifugal forces of rage, resentment and
alienation. Divorce is a fixture in these stories; so are adultery,
alcoholism and betrayal. The anxious heroine of ``Saturn,'' a woman
who is trying ``to get less crazy'' as she enters middle age, jumps
in her car to visit her lover and pulls over at a rest stop to
phone him, only to call her husband by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The neurotic narrator of ``Beating'' worries about her
passive-aggressive husband's sanity, while she spends her free time
watching a videotape of ``Beauty and the Beast'' over and over
again. The aging filmmaker in ``The Intruder'' picks fights with
his handsome young boyfriend, whom he blames for undermining his
capacity to work.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these people seem destined to spend the rest of their
lives in these sour relationships, using Freud to deconstruct their
problems glibly while allowing inertia and willful pride to trap
them in their delusions. Others find their marriages unraveling at
warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   The self-absorbed narrator of the title story has a desultory
affair and suddenly finds himself living alone in Manhattan while
his ex-wife raises their daughter in Massachusetts. The wronged
wife in ``A Wronged Husband'' abruptly leaves her feckless spouse
after telling him a bizarre lie about her sister's dying.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gates' characters are less romantic than the people in
Richard Yates' fiction, they share a similar sense of
disappointment and a similar inclination to use alcohol as an
escape. Smart, self-conscious and overly articulate, they spend
their days measuring the disconnection between their dreams and the
daily grind of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   In Gates' case, he delineates his characters' predicaments with
a pitch-perfect ear for their defensive humor and bitter wordplay
and a coy knowledge of their undeveloped hearts. At times, however,
he is so deft at uncovering their pretensions and self-delusions
that a certain authorial smugness creeps into his narration: as a
result the reader can come away feeling superior to his characters,
irritated with their solipsistic mind games and self-inflicted
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Because each tale is so nimbly crafted, this problem is less
noticeable when the stories are read one by one than when they are
read straight through as a collection. The parts of ``The Wonders
of the Invisible World'' are greater than the whole.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE WONDERS OF THE INVISIBLE WORLD'
</P>
<P>
   Stories
</P>
<P>
   By David Gates
</P>
<P>
   258 pages. Alfred A. KnopfBertelsmann(DG). $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
