<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GISELLE-BALLET-REVIEW     07-05 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GISELLE-BALLET-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL SIMPLICITY AND CLARITY AT THE KIROV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Youth triumphed at the Metropolitan Opera House on
Saturday when the Kirov Ballet presented two performances of
``Giselle,'' with Maya Dumchenko, a rising star in the Russian
company, in the title role in the afternoon and Natalya Sologub, a
junior corps dancer, taking on the role in the evening. This was
dancing whose ravishing simplicity and clarity captured the essence
of the somewhat stylized Kirov production and of the company's
style in general.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dumchenko's Giselle and Andrian Fadeyev's Albrecht were
innocent children lost in a situation beyond their control in a
strongly danced first act. But there was a great deal more to Ms.
Dumchenko's layered, pristine performance, which achieved its
effects through dancing alone.
</P>
<P>
   Revealingly, there was no released, cascading hair in the mad
scene, a startling break with tradition. Ms. Dumchenko did not need
that dramatic touch. In a gradually building performance, she
subtly foreshadowed what was to come in the next act. This was a
Giselle who almost unnoticeably led a somewhat passive Albrecht
through their first-act tragedy, much as she would later save him
from death at the hands of the vengeful, ghostly wili maidens. Ms.
Dumchenko's delicately expressive arms seldom etched a shape but
seemed to evaporate, like graveyard mist, as a gesture peaked.
</P>
<P>
   Her mad scene was filled with suggestions of near-death
exhaustion: a torso that tilted as if needing to be cradled, a
sinking into the ground as soft as a sigh. That delicacy continued
in the second act. Disembodied-looking turns fluttered rather than
spun through their unerring course. Arabesques bloomed spaciously
rather than striking a shape.
</P>
<P>
   There was a fascinating unquiet to the imperceptible changes in
pacing in her dancing here. Small touches in the characterization
of Fadeyev, who had danced as Albrecht earlier last week, softened
all this into something closer to human emotion, most notably when
he follows the airborne Giselle with his arms moving like wings in
attempted flight.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening performance Ms. Sologub was an almost too-knowing
mortal Giselle. Vyacheslav Samodurov, replacing the injured Farukh
Ruzimatov, opted for the interpretation of Albrecht as a worldly
cad, which made for little needed contrast in a rather dull first
act. But Ms. Sologub more than made up for that as the spirit
Giselle, in dancing that mixed slow measure with an almost wild
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   This was more the eery wraith than the lovingly redemptive
spirit of 19th-century ballet legend, a quality expressed in purely
physical terms. One will not soon forget, for instance, the
slightly fugitive right foot in Ms. Sologub's unearthly sautes
passes or hopping jumps backward. Samodurov might be forgiven for
looking merely polished in his dancing and sensitive in his
partnering in the face of all this mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Anton Korsakov, a teen-age corps dancer who has become a New
York audience favorite, stood out for the ease and classical
fluency of his beautifully finished dancing in the first-act pas de
deux, performed with an impressively centered, delicate Yuliya
Kasenkova at the matinee and with Irina Zhelonkina in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   This production's intriguingly natty Hilarion was danced by Ilya
Kuznetsov (at the matinee) and Nikolai Godunov (in the evening).
The compelling lead casts were completed in the afternoon by
Tatyana Amosova as Myrtha, Veronica Part as Moyna and Dariya
Pavlenko as Zulma and Elvira Tarasova, Sofiya Gumerova and Ms.
Pavlenko in the evening. Boris Gruzin conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
