<HEADER>
A9769 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUGHDOWNS-AZR &LR;      07-05 1543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGH DOWNS TO BE ANCHORED AT ARIZONA STATE 
</HEADLINE>
 DOWNS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In 20 years, Hugh Downs plans to give his wife, Ruth,
a gift of diamonds for their 75th wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   On their 100th, he says, he'll fly her to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Green cheese is about the only thing the veteran journalist
hasn't tried during 60 years of broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   In a stellar career that began before the age of television,
Downs has reported from the North Pole and the South Pole and
broadcast from the Battleship Missouri. He swam with a school of
great white sharks and allowed TV cameras to film his knee
replacement operation.
</P>
<P>
   He has written nine books.
</P>
<P>
   He interviewed the Rev. Martin Luther King, Jr. (``I realized he
was not working for the Black race but for the human race'') and
British physicist Steven Hawking (``He's considered as smart as
Einstein'').
</P>
<P>
   He has hosted game shows and talk shows and morning shows,
``Live from Lincoln Center'' and prime-time TV news magazine
``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, he holds the Guinness record for most hours logged on
network commercial television.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Downs belongs to the people.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Ruth Downs who will enjoy the lion's share of his time
when her husband of 55 years retires from regular broadcasting this
fall, disengaging from co-anchor Barbara Walters after two decades
of ``20/20'' _ the team that saved the ABC news magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement is a relative term.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bringing his assistant out here, so I know he doesn't
intend to do nothing,'' Ruth says with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is Arizona. After owning homes in Carefree and
Scottsdale, the couple are relinquishing all of their houses from
New York to the Mediterranean and building a new one in Paradise
Valley. It should be completed by October, when Downs officially
leaves the air.
</P>
<P>
   Helping to spark the move is his entry into the world of
academia as Arizona State University in Tempe upgrades its
communications department and christens it the Hugh Downs School of
Human Communication.
</P>
<P>
   Valley of the Sun philanthropist Jeanne Herberger instigated the
naming of the school after her longtime friend, believing ``his
profile lends itself to the naming of the school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His philosophy is more in tune with human communications
rather than as a newscaster,'' she says. ``His interests are broad
_ in space, in how we communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Herberger first became acquainted with Downs when he served on
the board of the Phoenix Symphony, one of her pet projects. They've
been friends ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a friend of his, you're a friend forever,'' she
says. ``He's a special person to have in your life. He'll be a
leader in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Herberger broached the idea with Downs several years ago, and
earlier this year, ASU President Lattie Coor popped the question
over lunch. Downs was flattered and paused only to consider how he
could best accommodate the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great respect for the university, but I want to fit it
into my life,'' Downs says as he and Ruth share a smoked salmon
pizza at the Ritz-Carlton bistro in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Not wishing to simply lend his name to the school, he pondered
the offer for a month before accepting. Now, he intends to be more
than an absentee benefactor, lecturing occasionally _ as he did in
1972 _ and auditing classes himself.
</P>
<P>
   The honor puts Downs in the same league as another famous
broadcaster _ longtime pal Walter Cronkite, whose name is on ASU's
school of journalism and telecommunications. Cronkite and Downs
once vied to be the first Journalist in Space, an ambition cut
short when the first Schoolteacher in Space, Christa McAuliffe,
lost her life in the Challenger disaster. &QL; 
Ohio native  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of former astronaut and Sen. John Glenn,
civilians have not been invited to fly in space since.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, by the way, is also a buddy of Downs. They're both 78 and
natives of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Although Downs once trained for space flight, experiencing 36
minutes of weightlessness, most of his assignments have been more
down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a homemaker/schoolteacher and a tire and battery
salesman, Downs graduated from high school in Lima, Ohio, in 1938,
winning a scholarship to a small liberal-arts school, Bluffton
College in Bluffton, Ohio. After a stint in the Army that saw no
battle and a couple of radio jobs, he landed a job as a staff
announcer for WWJ in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The producer on his weekly show was a comely young woman named
Ruth Shaheen. It was not love at first sight, they agree.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine now that this gracious, soft-spoken man was
something of a rogue in his younger days _ imbibing, carousing,
eating poorly, smoking two packs a day, showing up for work
bleary-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the normal human condition was to feel bad,'' he
says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the venerable host of ``Concentration'' and ``Today,''
sidekick on Jack Paar's ``Tonight'' show, one of the two most
trusted men in broadcasting?
</P>
<P>
   Believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it wasn't confined to Friday nights,'' he confesses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the phlegmatic Scotch Irishman became attracted to the
lively young woman from Illinois who remembers when Ronald Reagan's
mother was her baby-sitter.
</P>
<P>
   Engaged to another girl, Downs made a bold move _ drove to his
girlfriend's house, broke off the engagement (she heaved his ring
at him) and dashed back to propose to Ruth, buying out a florist's
wares on the way.
</P>
<P>
   To his dismay, she didn't say yes. But she didn't say no either,
and eventually they became de facto engaged, then married in
February 1944. They now have two grown children, one who lives in
Santa Fe and one in the Berkeley area.
</P>
<P>
   The couple moved to New York in 1957 when Downs teamed with Paar
on NBC's late-night show and then hosted the network's ``Today''
show from 1962 to 1971. That's when the Downses began spending more
time in Arizona and ``learned to laugh at people who would leave in
April because of the terrible heat,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Once they settle in Paradise Valley, they'll endure the terrible
heat along with their neighbors, minus the occasional summer
vacation on the Aegean and visits to their children.
</P>
<P>
   From 1971 to 1977, Downs took a break from regular broadcast
appearances, although in 1976 he hosted a public-television series
on aging called ``Over Easy.'' He also worked for a California
think tank and headed the National Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The genial journalist couldn't stay away from television for
long. When ABC's fledgling news magazine ``20/20'' flopped after
its 1978 debut, hosted by two unknowns, then-network news President
Roone Arledge phoned the tried-and-true Downs, who had been filling
in for David Hartman at ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Arledge sent up an SOS _ save our show.
</P>
<P>
   Downs was not at all reluctant to abandon his early-morning
wake-up call: ``I remembered why I had quit the ``Today'' show.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, he didn't expect to stay at ``20/20'' for 20 years. He
and Ruth reserved a room at New York's Regency Hotel for two weeks
and ended up living there for 18 months as the popularity of
``20/20'' grew under Downs' capable helmsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if we lasted five years we'd be lucky,'' he says,
``and then I thought if we lasted 10 years . . .
</P>
<P>
   Downs hosted the show solo until 1984, then welcomed Barbara
Walters when news teams became trendy. She's still there, too,
bagging the celebrity interviews while her co-host goes off on his
adventures _ such as helping scientists in 1982 move the geographic
center of the South Pole to its proper position and marking it with
a tattered green flag.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a rich career, and we will read all about it as Downs
gathers material for an eventual memoir. His assistant, not Downs,
has been keeping notes all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a methodical person,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Downs' memorabilia is housed at the University of
Wyoming, which boasts an impressive archives department. Other
souvenirs of a life on the edge of history were lost several years
ago when a plumbing leak flooded his Carefree home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was almost apologetic,'' he says of his bequest to the
University of Wyoming. ``I had such a mound of junk.''
</P>
<P>
   His own college education has been motley _ a little Bluffton, a
little Wayne State University, some classes in gerontology at
Hunter College and New York's Mount Sinai Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, ASU awarded him an honorary doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   Downs had been considering retirement since signing his last
contract three years ago. That runs out in October, although he
might leave sooner. His choice of a replacement would be ABC's Tom
Jarriel.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement will not be a time of leisure, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Golf?
</P>
<P>
   ``I only play golf when someone is a guest at my house and wants
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Downs is hoping to have more of her husband to herself _
far from the broadcast studio, far from the golf links, far from
historic figures, closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Downs appears ready for a new phase in his life, agreeing he's
done just about everything.
</P>
<P>
   Except, ``I haven't gone to the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Check back in 45 years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COMPOUNDED-DRUGS-     07-05 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPOUNDED-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FIGHT OVER THE OLD ART OF DRUG COMPOUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A generation ago, when people took prescriptions to the local
drugstore, there was a good chance that the pharmacist, rather than
just pulling a prepackaged item off the shelf, would actually mix
and measure ingredients to fill capsules or create ointments or
cough syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Although that practice, ``compounding,'' has largely given way
to ready-made products, it is still used to prepare individual
prescriptions for people who need something not commercially
available. They may be allergic to a preservative or dye in a
certain medication, for instance, or need a dose or a drug mixture
that is not mass-produced.
</P>
<P>
   Some drugstores, calling themselves compounding pharmacies,
specialize in filling such prescriptions, and a trade group, the
International Academy of Compounding Pharmacists, based in Houston,
has 1,300 members in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But compounding seemed to take on a new meaning last week, when
advocates for people with hepatitis C announced that a pharmacy in
Pittsburgh could save customers a lot of money _ as much as $900 a
month _ on an expensive medication, Ribavirin, by compounding it
into capsules from bulk powder instead of buying the finished
capsules from the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement seemed to take officials of the Food and Drug
Administration by surprise, coming as they were trying to develop
new rules to keep compounding within certain limits. Officials say
they are trying to keep compounding, meant to make small amounts of
medicine for individual patients, from crossing the line to
large-scale manufacturing. In addition, some compounded medicines
are essentially new drugs that have not been proved or tested, and
FDA officials say they are trying to find ways to protect people
from unsafe concoctions.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding exists in a gray zone of government regulation,
though, and even as the FDA works on new rules, concerns have been
raised that some pharmacies may already be stretching the
definition of compounding too far. And some pharmacies have
challenged the drug agency's authority to control them. Last
November, a group of compounding pharmacies sued the agency in
federal district court in Nevada, and won a temporary restraining
order saying that the agency could not stop stores from advertising
specific compounded products.
</P>
<P>
   Patients may have been delighted by last week's announcement
about Ribavirin, but the company that markets the drug, the
Schering-Plough Corp., of Madison, N.J., was not pleased at the
prospect of losing customers to a compounding pharmacy, Fisher's
Specialty Pharmacy Services, in Pittsburgh. Pharmacists at the
store said that on July 9, when Schering-Plough's patent on using
Ribavirin to treat hepatitis C runs out, they would buy the drug in
powder form from another source and pack it into capsules to fill
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Stein, a pharmacist at Fisher's, said that although
Schering-Plough still has patent rights that prevent manufacturers
from marketing generic forms of Ribavirin, those rules do not apply
to compounding pharmacies. A spokeswoman for the compounding
pharmacies' trade group said that other drugstores would follow
Fisher's example.
</P>
<P>
   But Schering-Plough, which took in $214 million from Ribavirin
during the last year, issued a statement suggesting that the
compounders were violating its rights.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials said that they were looking into the case to
determine whether any rules were being broken but that they
probably would not stop the compounding pharmacies unless the drug
they dispensed turned out to be unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stein said that Fisher's staff would be standing by at the
store on July 9, waiting to fill orders. ``We'll be up late,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, compounding was technically illegal, because it
often created drugs not approved by the FDA. However, recognizing
that some patients had needs that only compounding could address,
the drug agency looked the other way, exercising what officials
call ``enforcement discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, Congress passed the FDA Modernization Act, which
includes provisions meant both to protect compounding and to help
regulate it. The act exempts compounding from FDA rules for new
drugs, as long as the practice meets certain conditions. For
instance, compounded products must be prescribed by a doctor and
made for individual patients. Ingredients must be either approved
by the FDA, or on a special list of unapproved substances that are
allowed nonetheless. Pharmacies may not solicit prescriptions. Also
the act says that products that are essentially copies of
commercially available drugs may not be compounded ``regularly or
in inordinate amounts.'' But regularly and inordinate have not yet
been defined.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has an advisory committee on compounding, headed by Dr.
Randy P. Juhl. The committee has met twice to develop rules on
compounding, in October and May. At the first meeting, Juhl
described compounding as an ``ancient art,'' and said it could be
of great value to people who cannot use available products.
</P>
<P>
   But he also noted a downside, telling the committee, ``There in
the past have been drug products and drugs of questionable quality
and safety, and there have been some who have hidden behind the
guise of pharmacy compounding to conduct what amounts to
large-scale manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Axelrad, a lawyer who is director of the FDA's regulatory
policy staff, told the committee that in one case, a business
``compounded'' more than 300,000 doses a month of commercially
available asthma medicines for 6,000 patients in various states.
</P>
<P>
   ``These patients were exposed to the risks of an unapproved new
drug manufactured without ordinary pharmaceutical quality controls
when an approved product was available,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Ms. Axelrad said, a company with a pharmacy
license stockpiled hundreds of bulk ingredients for compounding,
but some were more than a year old, and 11 were undated, so it was
impossible to tell whether they had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Larry Sasich, a pharmacist who works for Public Citizen
Health Research Group, a consumer organization, said the 1997
provisions on compounding had weakened the laws that should protect
consumers by creating a loophole for unapproved substances created
by pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Roberts, a pharmacist from Leesburg, Va., painted a
different picture of compounding, describing a case that he said
was typical of his work with cancer patients. He said a home nurse
had telephoned him at 2 a.m., desperate because her patient, a
woman with bone cancer, was suffering from intense pain. The
patient also had severe nausea, from the high doses of morphine
that had already been tried.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts went to his store, selected six drugs to control pain
and nausea and blended them into rectal suppositories. The formula
worked, freeing the patient of pain and nausea for the next few
weeks, which was all that remained of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what compounding pharmacists and compounding can do to
make a difference in people's lives,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials said that they did not know when new rules on
compounding would be made final but that the agency had already
received several thousand comments on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
