<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9772 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REDDEN-CINCOLN-CENTER     07-05 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDDEN-CINCOLN-CENTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CENTERPIECE IN PLACE, LINCOLN CENTER FESTIVAL DIRECTOR IS
`EXTRAORDINARILY RELAXED'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Conn., Italy, Minn. Pa., N.Mex., Cyprus)   By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The day after his appointment as director of the
Lincoln Center Festival was reported last year, Nigel Redden got a
phone call at 4:30 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bit of a problem, it seemed, with the festival's
featured performance, the 20-hour Chinese opera ``The Peony
Pavilion.'' As he soon learned, there was enough of a problem to
cancel the production a week or so before it was scheduled to
begin, something not quite on the level of putting on a wedding
without bride or groom but a pretty sizable torpedo in the hull of
a fully scheduled arts festival.
</P>
<P>
   Both Redden and ``The Peony Pavilion'' are back for a second
shot at it, and if putting on 113 performances of 34 productions in
18 days would seem daunting to most people, last year's experience
seems to have left him with an odd sense of serenity about his
first full year of planning and presenting the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to last year, this feels extraordinarily relaxed,''
Redden said as a paper Chinese doll used in the performance
glowered above him on an upper shelf in his office. ``By the time
last year's festival came around, I'd been spending 12 days in
China, spending the days working there and the nights talking to
people here, so by the end, I was one of the walking wounded. We
have our problems, but they don't compare to what happened last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Most conspicuous at this year's festival, which starts Wednesday
and runs through July 25, will be ``The Peony Pavilion,'' the world
premiere of a production of all 55 scenes of the epic kunqu opera
directed by Chen Shi-Zheng. Other highlights include House Full o'
Praise, a nine-concert overview of African-American gospel music;
four programs honoring the composer Steve Reich; the world premiere
of a work by Robert Wilson, ``The Days Before: Death, Destruction
and Detroit III;'' a series of plays by the Irish dramatist Brian
Friel; dance programs devoted to the work of Merce Cunningham; the
Nederlands Dans Theater's American premiere of Jiri Kylian's ``One
of a Kind,'' and Kayassine, a French trapeze spectacle featuring 12
aerialists.
</P>
<P>
   If festivalgoers will also get some clues about where Redden
plans to take the four-year-old festival and how he plans to pull
off one of the more taxing balancing acts around, putting on both
the Lincoln Center Festival in the summer and the Spoleto Festival
U.S.A. in Charleston, S.C., each spring.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Redden, 48, has been doing a fair amount of
balancing for most of his professional life. Born in Cyprus, the
son of American diplomats, he has spent most of his career throwing
together elements as disparate as Chinese opera and American gospel
at festivals in the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the unifying thread is festivals,'' he said. ``I've
probably worked at as many as anyone I can think of. And ever since
I first worked as an interpreter at Spoleto in Italy at the age of
18, what I've always found extraordinary is the juxtaposition of
things that are quite separate and distinct and how that leads to
personal connections that are extremely evocative and intuitive.
It's a very valuable way to look at a piece of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Redden studied art history at Yale. Since he graduated in 1972,
he has worked with Harvey Lichtenstein at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music, at La Mama in Manhattan, at Spoleto in Italy and its
offspring Spoleto U.S.A., and at places as diverse as the National
Endowment for the Arts, the Walker Art Center in Minneapolis, the
Santa Fe Opera and the American Music Theater Festival in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   He was general manger of Spoleto U.S.A. from 1986 to 1991, when
he left after a dispute with the festival's organizer, Gian Carlo
Menotti. He helped start the Lincoln Center Festival in 1994 as a
consultant and returned to Spoleto as general director after
Menotti left. Redden returned to Lincoln Center as artistic
director in January 1998 after John Rockwell, the initial festival
director, was appointed editor of the Arts &AMP; Leisure section of The
New York Times. Redden was named director of the festival on June
16 last year.
</P>
<P>
   He said the two festivals were so different that running both at
the same time posed less of a conflict than it might seem.
``They're very different festivals,'' he said. ``Charleston is a
small town of 75,000 people, and in some ways the festival creates
its own context. The performances envelop the town in a way Lincoln
Center cannot envelop New York. There have been times when I've
wished some things could be done at each of them, and if something
works for both places, great, we'll do it at both places if we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoleto, he said, is more intimate and strives for both variety
and works that speak to Charleston's history, particularly its
place in African-American history. His goal for the Lincoln Center
Festival, he said, is to present ambitious works, often on a grand
scale _ ``Peony Pavilion'' being a good example _ that would not
otherwise be seen in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He does not want ``Peony Pavilion'' to dominate the festival and
says he doesn't think it will. Still, it is hard not to focus on
the opera, which was canceled last year when Chinese officials
balked at Chen's production, calling it ``feudal, absurd and
pornographic in a way that is unacceptable to Chinese viewers and
artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The work will be performed in what are called marathon weekends
throughout the festival, with viewers able to buy tickets for
individual episodes or for all six episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will surprise a lot of people,'' he said. ``There
are people who think of Chinese opera as grating and difficult to
listen to, somehow unpleasant, but in fact kunqu opera and music is
much easier on the Western ear than Peking opera. It's surprisingly
lyrical, and the production is sumptuous. We had to design the
festival as if `Peony Pavilion' was not going to happen, so I think
it's first-rate without it, but I'm certainly glad we're able to do
it this year.''
</P>
<P>
   As diverse as the different parts of the festival are, what
unites many of them this year, he said, is what they say about the
history of artistic forms and references. Thus, the gospel
offerings reflect an American tradition that is a revealing
contrast to the Chinese one. ``The Cave,'' a collaboration by Reich
and the video artist Beryl Korot, who are married, reworks the
Biblical story of Abraham. One of Redden's favorites is ``Voila
Voila'' by the French-Vietnamese choreographer Ea Sola, which
reworks traditional Vietnamese dance forms in a modern context.
Redden presented a different Ea Sola work in Charleston in 1996.
There is much personal history too in the Merce Cunningham program
tied to his 80th birthday and the Brian Friel Festival, which
coincides with the playwright's 70th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``History informs a fair amount of what's going on in this
festival,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's fare tends toward challenging works. But he said
that was both the mandate of the festival and the kind of art he
was attracted to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things we've demonstrated is that you can
do serious fare in the summer,'' he said. ``I'm not the right
person to do a summer pops festival. I wouldn't know where to
begin. But if these are serious works, I think they're works people
will enjoy. This isn't about taking medicine. It's about some of
the revelations that serious works of art can provide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
