<P>
   DETECTIVE-POLITICS (Undated) _ Driven by an almost insatiable
demand for negative information in today's world of bruising
politics, private investigators are playing a larger _ though
mostly hidden _ role in the public arena, digging up dirt on
everyone from regulators to national and small-town officials.
President Clinton's use of detectives is widely known, but they
have also been used by the likes of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, Henry
J. Hyde and David N. Dinkins. The private investigators' reports
usually are aimed at discrediting critics and disposing of
opponents, but they are also used to identify and, if possible, to
fix potential embarrassments. Today's breed of investigators
include former police officers, as always, but also former FBI
agents, ex-CIA employees, former prosecutors and, in a trend that
raises new ethical questions, ex-journalists, who can tap old news
contacts to get negative information published. By Douglas Frantz.
(3500 words with an abridged version at about half that length.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (Lahore, Pakistan) _ News Analysis: Once he gets
home from his Washington tete-a-tete with President Clinton, Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif is likely to find it difficult to deliver on
his assurance to the Americans that he will seek the withdraw of
Pakistani-backed forces from the Indian side of the cease-fire line
in the disputed territory of Kashmir. Sharif's sudden decision to
call on the president on Sunday and his commitment to take
``concrete steps'' to restore the cease-fire line were seen here,
not as a breakthrough that would help end a limited, undeclared war
between India and Pakistan, but as a sell-out of the Kashmiri cause
or another probably ill-fated move in a diplomatic game of chess.
By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FUNERAL (Bela Crkva) _ The surviving villagers of Bela
Crkva pay their last respects to more than 60 victims of a March 25
massacre there. By John Kifner.
