two key posts in his Cabinet and keeping a third for himself, Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak appeared Monday to be trying to
consolidate his hold on power as he completed his government. Most
analysts here are saying that Barak, 57, a highly decorated former
general, is acting very much like a military commander. He is
flanking himself with a foreign minister and a finance minister who
are not expected to challenge or overshadow him. By Deborah Sontag.
