<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER 20 QUESTIONS ABOUT ADVERTISING, MARKETING AND THE MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time again to ask 20 questions about advertising, marketing
and the media.
</P>
<P>
   _ Will a new print campaign for Tanqueray gin by Deutsch Inc.,
which features images of British icons like English bulldogs, Union
Jack flags and Prince of Wales plaid fabric, ever include a
beefeater?
</P>
<P>
   _ Would the Public Broadcasting Service raise more money during
its August pledge drive by showing a scheduled program called
``Lawrence Welk's Songs of Faith'' or by offering to keep it off
the air in exchange for generous donations?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that Gateway Inc. is running commercials that feature the
song ``Who Are You'' by the Who, the Dell Computer Corp. is running
commercials using the song ``Magic Bus'' by the Who and the Nissan
Motor Corp. is running commercials featuring the song ``Won't Get
Fooled Again'' by the Who, will another marketer weigh in with the
album ``The Who Sell Out''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Was it a coincidence that an advertisement in the June 14
issue of People magazine for Everest Powerful Mint Gum, a new
product being sold by the Wm. Wrigley Jr. Co., ran adjacent to an
article by Sir Edmund Hillary, the New Zealander who conquered
Mount Everest?
</P>
<P>
   _ Couldn't Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. have double-checked the media
plan for a radio campaign to promote a contest to give away trips
to the Women's National Basketball Association All-Star Game _ to
be played at Madison Square Garden July 14 _ so that the spots
describing how the prizes include ``airfare for four to New York''
would not have run on New York stations?
</P>
<P>
   _ Has a line from a commercial entered the vernacular faster
than ``Chicks dig the long ball,'' the phrase uttered by Atlanta
Braves pitcher Greg Maddux in a humorous spot by Wieden &AMP; Kennedy
for Nike?
</P>
<P>
   _ In ads for Yoplait yogurt, sold by General Mills, was it
really necessary for the slogan at the bottom of the page, ``C'est
si bon,'' to be followed by the English translation ``It is so
good''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Was anyone who attended the 46th International Advertising
Festival in Cannes, France, disappointed when they realized that a
news release announcing that ``Keith Richards will be jury
president'' actually meant to refer to Keith Reinhard, chairman and
chief executive at the DDB Worldwide Communications Group unit of
Omnicom Group?
</P>
<P>
   _ Couldn't the marketing geniuses at the Heinz Frozen Food Co.
or its parent, H.J. Heinz, have come up with a better brand name
for a product line than Bland Farms?
</P>
<P>
   _ Is Spring Hill Suites, a chain of all-suite hotels being
introduced by the Marriott Corp., an effort to capitalize on the
good feelings about Spring Hill, Tenn., that have been generated by
the popular campaign from Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney for the Saturn
division of the General Motors Corp.?
</P>
<P>
   _ And if that is the case, will Marriott open a Spring Hill
Suites hotel in Spring Hill?
</P>
<P>
   _ Did executives at Philip Morris worry that a print ad for
Virginia Slims _ showing a woman smoking in a bathtub surrounded by
scented candles under a headline that includes the word
``aromatherapy'' _ suggests that special efforts are required to
mask the stench of cigarette smoke?
</P>
<P>
   _ Wasn't it clever of Canon to run radio spots for its copiers
teasing efforts by the Xerox Corp. to protect the Xerox name, which
pretended to remind consumers that unauthorized use of the Xerox
trademark _ as in referring to copies as ``Xeroxes'' _ is
prohibited?
</P>
<P>
   _ Did DaimlerChrysler ask The Washington Post for a refund after
an ad for the E-Class Mercedes-Benz _ showing the front end of the
car under the headline ``Deer freeze in headlights. Apparently, so
do people'' _ ran in the same issue as an article about complaints
about new ``ultra-bright headlights'' on cars including
Mercedes-Benzes that began with the words ``This is what deer must
feel like''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Who will be the first business journalist to suggest that the
Campbell Soup Co., the Hershey Foods Corp. and the Kellogg Co. _
packaged-goods mainstays struggling with sluggish growth rates and
changing consumer tastes _ merge to form an advertising and
marketing powerhouse?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that S.C. Johnson &AMP; Son has renamed the Dow Bathroom
Cleaner product line as Scrubbing Bubbles after the characters in
the brand's ads, will Diageo rename its Pillsbury frozen baked
goods after Poppin' Fresh and will the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. rename
Charmin bathroom tissue after Mr. Whipple?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the gibes about the prurient interest in lesbians among
straight men be renewed by a print ad showing two women in a
romantic embrace _ promoting Disaronno amaretto liqueur, imported
by the Bacardi-Martini USA unit of Bacardi Ltd. _ appearing in
Playboy magazine as well as in publications read by gay men and
lesbians?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that Ikea has given the name Selling to a new area rug,
will shoppers ask clerks at Ikea stores ``Are you selling the
Selling?''
</P>
<P>
   _ And will the Ikea clerks respond by asking ``Will you be
buying the Selling, or are you just looking?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Will an adorable girl whose tongue has been taken over by the
Pepsi-Cola marketing department tell an advertising columnist in
the voice of Joe Pesci that ``you ask a lot of questions for
someone from Brooklyn''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
