<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, July 6, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave along the Atlantic Seaboard will reach its crest
Tuesday as a final push of torrid air from the Southwest precedes a
cool front. With abundant, though hazy sunshine, readings will rise
from near 80 degrees at sunrise to surpass 100 degrees by 3 p.m. in
many sections from southern New England to the Carolinas. Sultry
breezes will gust over 20 mph in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Very humid air returning to northern New England will encounter
a shallow cool air mass along the Maine coast. Another cluster of
thunderstorms will develop in the mountains as the advancing sticky
air is lifted. Clouds and scattered thundershowers will keep
readings below record levels across the interior Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing drier air will trigger scattered thunderstorms from
the eastern Great Lakes to the central Plains. One or two of the
storms will be potent with large hail and damaging winds. Much more
comfortable weather is expected from the Northern Plains to the
Middle West with sunny skies, but still above seasonal readings.
</P>
<P>
   The South will remain sultry. Several patches of thunderstorms
will erupt in the steamy air mass. A few storms will form over the
southern Appalachians with more storms likely where sea breezes
push well inland in Texas. Florida will notice only widely
separated storms.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon storms will erupt over the southern Rockies. The
remainder of the West will be dry with cooler air reaching the
Northwest along with some clouds. The Southwest deserts will remain
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Head Start
</P>
<P>
   Despite mostly clear skies and virtually calm winds, the
temperature only fell to 78 degrees at Harrisburg, Penn., at
daybreak on Monday. Large amounts of water vapor in the lower
atmosphere over the Northeast absorbed the heat being emitted from
the ground during Sunday night. This absorbed infrared energy was
then emitted back toward the surface, keeping temperatures
unusually high. The record nighttime minimums, such as
Harrisburg's, gave a boost to Monday's temperatures, sending values
over 100 degrees in some sections. Tuesday will feature a repeat
performance along the East Coast. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9776 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT06-COX-1STLED     07-05 0450
