<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-05 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: BLAIR CLARIFICATION
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to shore up wavering Protestant support for his
blueprint for setting up the new Northern Ireland government this
month, Prime Minister Tony Blair told the House of Commons that
Sinn Fein would have to give up its cabinet positions if its IRA
allies did not disarm on schedule. Blair issued the clarification
in a speech arguing that the plan, negotiated in Belfast last week,
was the best opportunity for peace this generation of Britons would
ever have.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: A ROYAL APPEAL
</P>
<P>
   The son of Italy's last king, Victor Emmanuel, 62, says he will
appeal his status of forced exile from Italy to the European Court
of Human Rights in Strasbourg, saying that as a result of the ban
he was refused permission to enter Italy to hand over aid for
Kosovo refugees. Under the 1948 Constitution male heirs of the
House of Savoy are barred from Italian soil.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: FEDERAL POLICE CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry has named Adm. Wilfrido Robledo to head
the Federal Preventive Police, a new 10,000-officer force created
in January. The previous commissioner, Omar Fayad, served only 95
days before his transfer to become customs chief. The new force's
responsibilities remain unclear. In February Clinton administration
officials predicted that the new force would make a valuable
contribution to the drug war, but it now appears the agency will
have no antidrug jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: MENEM CURRENCY PLAN
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before a bankers' group, President Carlos Saul Menem
proposed that the members of the Mercosur trade union _ Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay _ create a common currency to
consolidate ``the stability of the region and dispel the ghosts of
devaluation.'' He said the Argentina peso, the value of which is
pegged to the dollar, could be accepted as the common currency.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: TELEPHONE PROBLEMS
</P>
<P>
   Telephone service has been severely disrupted by the
introduction of competition to domestic long-distance service, with
fewer than one in four calls being successfully completed since a
decades-old monopoly ended. Officials attributed the problems,
which made normal communications between Sao Paulo and Rio de
Janeiro almost impossible, to a combination of technical problems
with software and callers' unfamiliarity with the privatized
system.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SUHARTO SUES TIME
</P>
<P>
   Former President Suharto, 78, filed a lawsuit accusing Time
magazine of defaming him when it reported in its Asian edition in
May that he and his family had accumulated $15 billion in assets
during his 32-year rule. Speaking to reporters at his home, Suharto
said he would donate any damages he wins to the Indonesian people,
``especially to help the poor ones.''
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA: HUN SEN'S VOW ON ARMY
</P>
<P>
   On the second anniversary of an armed coup in which he seized
full power, Prime Minister Hun Sen told a gathering of solders,
``My genuine intention is to keep the armed forces away from
political conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: POLITICIZED EULOGY FOR NKOMO
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe used a eulogy for Vice President Joshua
Nkomo as an opportunity to attack whites, the United States,
Britain and the International Monetary Fund for ``opposing
Zimbabwe's revolutionary dreams'' by freezing aid and refusing to
pay for its land-seizure plans. Acknowledging that the death of
Nkomo, a liberation leader, could raise tensions between his own
ruling Shona tribe and Nkomo's Ndebeles, he also called for
national unity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
