<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9787 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-LIMA-HNS &LR;      07-05 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-LIMA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOSE Lima likes to consider himself an entertainer first,
baseball player second. So if there is a stage nearby, he usually
will find it.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the time on a humid April morning when he accompanied
Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. and other corporate executives to a
naming ceremony for the club's new downtown ballpark, Enron Field,
slated to open next season. After the formal presentation, Lima
decided to get loose. With a luncheon crowd of 3,000 at his
disposal, Lima stole the show, hopping onto a nearby stage,
grabbing a microphone and singing the lyrics to La Bamba.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had them spellbound,'' McLane recalls. ``They were just
amazed. A lot of time an athlete's singing and dancing is so-so. He
had them in the palm of their hands with his warmth and charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time back in 1995 when he was a young pitcher
in Double-A for the Detroit Tigers. Lima had thrown a no-hitter,
and a week later a man approached him with a small request. His
5-year-old son was a big fan of Lima's, and the father invited him
to the birthday party. Lima attended the party.
</P>
<P>
   While there's an unwritten rule in baseball that starting
pitchers don't talk with reporters _ or anyone, for that matter _
before they take the mound, Lima will carry on a conversation with
anyone who'll listen. He is usually the first player signing
autographs and stays until the last fan is gone or he runs out of
ink. As manager Larry Dierker once said, ``If you don't have his
autograph, you haven't tried.''
</P>
<P>
   And he can always be found singing and holding his infant son,
Jose Jr., born last Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the baby cries he sings a song and the baby doesn't cry
anymore,'' said his wife, Melissa.
</P>
<P>
   He has been nicknamed the Mambo King, which is perfect for a guy
who pops his favorite compact disc into the stereo and shakes
across the clubhouse floor to the merengue beat. ``Parate a batear
que te voy a alimar.'' The words to the debut single off his second
CD, titled El Mambo de Lima, translate to ``Step up to the plate,
I'm going to strike you out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, this is a good life. I love to pitch, and I love to
sing,'' Lima says.
</P>
<P>
   He's threatening to top both charts.
</P>
<P>
   When Lima isn't putting the final touches on his CD, he is
making sweet music on the mound. By this time next week, the
26-year-old who is quickly becoming one of baseball's newest
sensations could be preparing for his biggest performance _ the
June 13 All-Star Game in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a turnaround for a guy whose future was uncertain at the
start of last season. Before last season, Lima had a 9-22 career
record and the Astros were on the verge of releasing him. Since
then, he has been the most consistent member of the Astros'
rotation with a 27-12 record. He went 16-8 in his first season as a
full-time starter and carried the momentum over to this year,
becoming the league's first 11-game winner.
</P>
<P>
   He has the league's attention. Last year during a start against
Milwaukee, Lima allowed two runners to reach base with no outs. He
got the next two batters on strikeouts and ended the inning with a
groundout, pumping his fist and sidestepping off the mound in
jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner (Bud Selig) called me and asked, `Who is that
guy?''' McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has given Lima and his family financial security, but
his love has always been his music. The oldest of seven children,
Lima began performing in nightclubs in the Dominican Republic at
age 11 and won his first competition at 13. He took music classes
for five years before eventually being signed by the Tigers in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played but I liked music better,'' Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   Lima says he might never have continued playing baseball if not
for his father, Francisco Rodriguez, a former player himself in the
Dominican amateur leagues. So he kept his father happy, playing in
fields and vacant lots around their neighborhood just outside the
city of Santiago before eventually joining a team in the Dominican
youth league.
</P>
<P>
   ``During his early teens people kept telling us that he was good
and we should encourage his talent,'' said his mother, Nurys Lima.
``His dad then began to encourage him and spend more time with him
and his baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Things have never been the same. Lima brought his act to the
United States and the big leagues. His seven years in the Detroit
organization were marked by one trial after another to prove he
could be a successful pitcher. He struggled to records of 5-11 and
8-13 during his first four years. He was part of the Tigers'
100-loss season in 1996, but not even that can be described as the
darkest time of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Lima went through a divorce shortly after being traded
to the Astros in a 10-player swap, and his inability to get batters
out again had his future in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a lot of stuff. I went through a divorce, and
that was tough for me,'' Lima said. ``I didn't want to go to court
and be fighting. I got over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before things got better, they would only get worse. Coming off
a 1-6 record in 1997, his first season with the Astros, Lima
struggled during spring training last year and did nothing to
convince management he was ready to take his career to the next
level.
</P>
<P>
   In one spring training exhibition, he gave up nine runs in three
innings against Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the worst days of my life,'' Lima said of the
eventual 15-0 loss. ``I almost got released. Do you think I'll ever
forget that day?''
</P>
<P>
   McLane sat in the stands with general manager Gerry Hunsicker
and team president Tal Smith shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `Geez, what in the world are we going to do with
Jose Lima?''' McLane said. ``We laugh about it now, but we were all
shaking our heads. Sometimes your best decisions are no
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that he could no longer rely solely on a 90-mph
fastball and lethal changeup to challenge hitters, Lima worked with
pitching coach Vern Ruhle and added a sinker and slider to his
repertoire. With the Astros' rotation unsettled because of injuries
to two starters, Lima walked into Dierker's office during spring
training and pleaded for an opportunity to start. In his first
start of '98, Lima held the Colorado Rockies to one run and four
hits in seven innings. By mid-May, he had become the NL's first
six-game winner.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lima has not been endearing to all who have played
against him. He has been the center of controversy during the past
year-and-a-half for his exuberant display of emotion following a
strikeout or good play. Milwaukee pitcher Steve Woodard called
Lima's showmanship ``the weakest act in baseball'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   Others have defended his emotional style, calling it refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very talented and loyal guy,'' said Joe Klein, Lima's
agent. ``He's not showing anyone up. He just gets into it. He feels
blessed and doesn't take anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden turnaround? Lima credits maturation and his
family for his change of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's changed my whole life. It's the best thing to happen to a
person,'' Lima said. ``I think I'm blessed to have my wife Melissa
and my champion (Jose Jr.). It's amazing how your life can change
so quickly when you see another human being coming. My son changed
my whole life, and I have a great woman; she's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima met his wife while on a road trip to Seattle in 1996.
Melissa had attended a Mariners game when Lima spotted her walking
to her car in the parking lot as he boarded the team bus. She asked
for an autograph. ``I was so embarrassed. I didn't know what to
say,'' Melissa said.
</P>
<P>
   The righthander has been featured in national publications
throughout the first half, has been a frequent guest on Jim Rome's
nationally syndicated radio show, and this week was part of a
segment on Houston couples on a local morning television show.
</P>
<P>
   But the increase in popularity hasn't changed the Lima's way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think about it. People ask, `That's your
husband, isn't that cool?''' said Melissa, who says her favorite
player is Randy Johnson from his days with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   With all his success on the mound, Lima is hoping to become a
bigger hit on the music scene. He leads a 13-piece band called La
Fuga, or The Escape. Lima writes lyrics wherever he finds
inspiration, and some of his songs relate to baseball, like the new
cut La Gozadera or The Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to try and create my own stuff,'' Lima said. ``I'm
making some new songs that are going to be awesome. It's something
that just comes out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, Lima and his family will move into their new
five-bedroom, two-story house near Pearland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to when I sign my big deal,'' he said. ``I
can take care of everybody. I've taken care of my whole family.
When I go back there, I let them know that no matter what, I'm
still their brother. Whatever they need from me I'm going to take
care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   He signed a one-year, $1.95 million contract that goes to $2.15
million if he makes 31 starts or pitches 215 innings. He could be
in line for an even bigger payoff next year as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having all the money hasn't changed who we are,'' Nurys Lima
said. ``Now we live differently because we didn't have as much and
now we pretty much have everything we ever wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means Lima can have the best of both worlds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
