   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
July 6. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-CLASH-TWOTAKES (Kansas City, Mo.) _ On Kansas City's
West Side, new people are moving into what has long been a working
class, largely Hispanic community. Sometimes, longtime residents
are being displaced after spending their lives in close-knit
neighborhoods. A look at a clash of cultures. By MATT STEARNS.
Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPLANE-BUILDER (BATES CITY, Mo.) _ Andy Anderson has flown for
more than 70 years. He's barnstormed and crop-dusted all over the
country. But, in a way, he hasn't traveled far. The grassy runway
he uses now isn't much different from that Iowa field where he
soared 20 feet above the ground when Hoover was president. In the
evenings, after a day of cutting metal and gluing wood for wings
and fuselages, Anderson flies. As he soars above cornfields and cow
pastures, he thinks what he would like to build next; what he could
do to make a plane fly better. By DONALD BRADLEY. Story will move
in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-SCOUTS: (Kansas City, Mo.) _ A little more than a decade
ago, Boy Scouting had all but disappeared from the inner city. But
an urban scouting program began in 1988 that has raised the number
of urban scouts in the 19-county area from 300 to 9,000. By ERICA
WOOD. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   JESSE-JAMES: _ (Undated) A Texas court this month is expected to
decide on whether to allow the exhumation of what some people think
is the real Jesse James. By JERRY BERRIOS. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-EDUCATION: (BLUE SPRINGS, Mo.) _Remember how arts were the
first thing cut in the movie, ``Mr. Holland's Opus?'' Well, the
thinking about arts programs is changing. More are being beefed up,
and there's no better example than the summer arts academies
springing up in Independence, Blue Springs and elsewhere. Educators
are realizing that a fair number of artsy kids will drop out of
school if their gifts aren't validated. By MARA ROSE WILLIAMS.
Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
