<HEADER>
A9791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-525&AMP;A     07-05 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK, PUTTING OLD-TIMERS IN CABINET, CONSOLIDATES HIS POWER BASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., 7th graf, in double parentheses, should be set in brackets) 
(HLW) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ By appointing loyal old-timers to two key posts in
his Cabinet and keeping a third for himself, Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak appeared on Monday to be trying to consolidate his hold
on power as he completed his government.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts here say that Barak, 57, a highly-decorated former
general, is acting very much like a military commander. He is
flanking himself with a foreign minister and a finance minister who
are not expected to challenge or overshadow him.
</P>
<P>
   While this could lead to a more disciplined, even accomplished
government, some believe that it also could portend an autocratic
leadership style for Barak, who will serve as his own defense
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ehud Barak did not distribute senior portfolios to members of
his faction,'' Sima Kadmon, a political analyst, said in the daily
Yediot Ahronot on Monday. ``He cloned himself for all the major
roles.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Barak made appointments to key social
ministries _ Justice, Education and Interior _ that signal a clean
break with the past. They also hold a promise of democratic-minded
reform in institutions that deal with touchy issues, like the
religious-secular power struggle, the question of who is a Jew and
the future constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, after completing his ministerial appointments on Monday,
is expected to be sworn in with his Cabinet on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ((President Clinton, who was traveling in Kentucky on Monday,
briefly interrupted a tour of an electronics factory to speak to
Barak on the phone for about 12 minutes, a White House spokesman
said. But they did not set a date for Barak to visit Washington.))
</P>
<P>
   Barak faced his first defeat on Monday, a frustration to his
efforts to shore up his control. His party, One Israel, voted down
his hand-picked choice for the powerful role of speaker of
Parliament _ an obscure and inexperienced politician, Shalom
Simchon, who one analyst said was being set up to serve as Barak's
``suicidal Shiite soldier on the Parliament podium.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the party _ a reconstituted version of the old Labor _
selected an ambitious Labor Party veteran, Avraham Burg, who is
unlikely to be malleable. Yaron Ezrahi, a political scientist, said
that while it is too early to gauge how Barak will conduct himself,
the Cabinet appointments are telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the Cabinet as Barak's business card,'' he said. ``It
tells us two things. First, that he takes very seriously his role
as leader of change. And second, in the ministries in which he
wants to have direct influence, that he has a strong tendency to
surround himself with people who are so loyal that they will not
get in his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak on Tuesday named Avraham Shochat, 63, of his own One
Israel Party to be finance minister for the second time,
disappointing much of the business sector.
</P>
<P>
   David Levy, 61, was appointed foreign minister for the third
time on Sunday, leaving professional diplomats somewhat
indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are considered somewhat outmoded in their fields, and
neither is considered likely to forge bold initiatives without
explicit direction from above.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When news of Shochat's appointment leaked out on Sunday, the Tel
Aviv stock exchange immediately dipped downward.
</P>
<P>
   This was a sign that many investors fear that his reputation as
a policy maker who would prefer to stimulate the economy with
government spending, expanding the deficit, rather than to continue
the departing government's increasingly successful battle against
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   His admirers, however, saw as positives the rapid growth rates
and surging foreign investments that characterized his previous
term. And Shochat, in brief comments on Monday, indicated that he
might pick up where he left off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to reassure the business community,'' Shochat said on
Monday, ``that we're going to pursue a very responsible policy that
will be good for the economy, a policy of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Barak named Yossi Beilin, a leftist political
scientist and one of the most independent thinkers in his party, to
be justice minister. A high-minded champion of civic culture,
Beilin will take over a Justice Ministry that was considered
tainted by the departing minister, Tsahi Hanegbi, who has been
under investigation for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives Beilin, who has worked hard to build a
relationship with the ultra-Orthodox, a key role in managing
relations between the judiciary and the religious sector. And he
will have a strong hand in shaping the evolving constitution _ a
very sensitive issue for the Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   In another appointment of a progressive, Barak previously named
Yossi Sarid, leader of the leftist Meretz Party, to take over the
Education Ministry from the religious party that has been in
control.
</P>
<P>
   He also took the Interior Ministry, which handles delicate
issues involving citizenship and Jewish identity, from the
ultra-Orthodox Shas Party and gave it to Natan Sharanky, the
Russian immigrant leader.
</P>
<P>
   Barak on Monday appointed Shlomo Ben-Ami, an intellectual who
was the top vote-getter in the party's internal primaries, to be
internal security minister, in charge of the police. Ben-Ami is not
a law enforcement specialist; his strengths are foreign and social
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Some perceived this as an insult, but others believed that
Ben-Ami could make needed reforms in the police culture while
expanding his domain to include social issues like relations
between Israeli Arabs and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Shas will control the Religious Affairs, Health, Labor and
Welfare, and Infrastructure Ministries. And the settlers' party,
the National Religious Party, will run the Housing Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is facing severe criticism from women's groups. Although
he pledged to include more women in his government than any
previous leader, he ended up appointing only one _ Dalia Itzkik of
One Israel, who will be environment minister.
</P>
<P>
   Further, he appointed no Arab politicians as ministers or deputy
ministers, although Israeli Arab voters, a crucial bloc, supported
him nearly unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   Barak intends to expand his Cabinet of 18 members to 24 members
after taking office, so it is possible he will include more women
or an Arab at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, it seems likely that he has interpreted his resounding
election victory as a personal rather than a party mandate, and
that he is constructing a system that allows him maximum control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
