<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM HELPS WOMEN DEVELOP BASIC JOB SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judy Wells wants more.
</P>
<P>
   She has worked the last several years as a library assistant and
dreams of becoming an administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get a better-paying job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells now feels ready to make that change. Last week, she
completed a new program provided by the Women's Employment Network
that is specially designed to help women in low-paying jobs develop
the skills they need to acquire better-paying positions.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit organization provides job-readiness training and
ongoing support services to help low-income women find and keep
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Its new Job Upgrade for More Pay program meets two nights a week
and covers such topics as interviewing and resume writing, dressing
for respect, handling office politics and stress and time
management. The program is free for low-income working women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program helps low-income working women to increase their
salaries so that they can better support themselves and their
families,'' said Abigail S. McMahon, director of community resource
development for the network.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Educational Testing Service found that
many women could improve their prospects of moving into the middle
class with minimal training because plenty of jobs are available.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the economy is strong enough to absorb
everyone now on welfare. However, two-thirds of the women on
welfare lack the skills needed to escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it is almost impossible for these women to obtain
this training. Most people get additional job training or advanced
educational degrees as their careers and salaries progress.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income women, many of whom support their families on minimum
wage, cannot afford the additional training they need.
</P>
<P>
   The network's program helps women like Wells develop these
skills so that they can move into jobs with better salaries and
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who attended college for two years, said the program not
only taught her new skills, but helped her recognize that she
already had a lot of experience.
</P>
<P>
   Women who participate in the program also can receive additional
computer training during a four-week computer course at the Women's
Employment Network.
</P>
<P>
   The next session of the program begins July 12, and runs for
four weeks on Monday and Tuesday evenings. Call (816) 822-8083,
Ext. 124 for more information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
