<HEADER>
A9793 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DETECTIVE-POLITICS-AR     07-05 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETECTIVE-POLITICS-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE INVESTIGATORS PLAYING BIGGER ROLE IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ill., La., Maine, Texas)  (Eds: An abridged version of this story,
DETECTIVE-POLITICS-ABRIDGED, is also being filed.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeding an almost insatiable demand for negative information in
today's world of bruising politics, private investigators are
playing a larger _ though mostly hidden _ role in the public arena,
digging up dirt on everyone from regulators to elected national and
small-town officials.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's use of private detectives has been widely
reported. But an examination by The New York Times found that over
the past decade they have moved into every corner of public life,
hired by politicians and their surrogates ranging from Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., to the House Judiciary Committee chairman, Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and from the former mayor of New York, David
Dinkins, to aspirants for local city councils.
</P>
<P>
   The private investigators' thick reports usually are aimed at
discrediting critics and disposing of opponents. But they are also
used defensively, to identify and, if possible, to avoid potential
embarrassments.
</P>
<P>
   Today's breed of investigators include former police officers,
as always, but also former FBI agents, ex-CIA employees, former
prosecutors and, in a trend that raises new ethical questions,
ex-journalists, who can tap old news contacts to get negative
information published.
</P>
<P>
   Operating with little regulation or accountability, the
detectives spy on opponents by posing as reporters, or by sending
in operatives who work as volunteers in the campaign. In a world
where sensitive computer data can flow freely despite privacy laws,
some routinely obtain protected information ranging from phone
records to medical histories.
</P>
<P>
   They track down ex-spouses and former associates and employees,
often concealing the reason they are asking questions, and they go
through trash from offices, campaign headquarters and homes, a
practice known as ``Dumpster diving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a garbage pail I won't get in, not an angle I
won't aim a hidden camera,'' said Larry Preston Williams, a former
police intelligence officer in New Orleans, who sends every
statewide candidate in Louisiana an offer to dig up ``white lies''
and other information about opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take cases from Republicans, Democrats, conservatives,
liberals,'' Williams said. ``It's all information.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how frequently private detectives are used in
political campaigns. The Federal Election Commission says it cannot
monitor campaign spending on them because payments are routinely
lumped with fees to lawyers. And journalists who cooperate with
detectives often promise confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has, however, begun to examine some of
the techniques that private investigators and information brokers
use to obtain confidential information. In April the Federal Trade
Commission filed a landmark suit against a Colorado investigator
over the use of deceptions known as pretexts to obtain information
about private bank accounts, and on June 25 state authorities
indicted him on racketeering charges. Congress is considering
legislation to outlaw pretexts.
</P>
<P>
   Personal attacks have been part of political campaigns since the
nation's inception. But for most of this century unwritten rules
kept within bounds what was called ``opposition research.'' The
typical investigator was a campaign worker or occasionally a
moonlighting police officer. Inquiries focused on public
information such as voting records and court cases.
</P>
<P>
   Those rules vanished after allegations of marital infidelity
drove Gary Hart out of the race for president in 1988. Campaigns
veered into nastier and more personal areas, and as they did,
professional investigators replaced the amateurs and techniques got
more aggressive. Today, even candidates reluctant to get into the
muck say they feel compelled to respond in kind.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Monks, a candidate who hired detectives in a Republican
primary for the Senate from Maine, defended the need for full
disclosure, even if the information is painful and personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is thought of as being worse for calling attention to
these things,'' Monks said. ``I think it's wrong for people to run
for office without making a disclosure of material facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy offered a similar rationale for hiring private
investigators to scrutinize his most recent opponent, Mitt Romney.
``Opposition research is part of the modern campaign process,''
said a spokesman, Will Keyser. ``In 1994, Sen. Kennedy's record was
an open book and his opponent's was largely unknown. It was
important and appropriate for the campaign to conduct thorough
research into all the available public information.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Rollins, a veteran Republican political consultant who
acknowledges using private investigators, said, ``Most people today
are trying to find as much dirt as they can. There may be less
tendency to push the button on the personal stuff, but the digging
is going right on.''
</P>
<P>
   This demand for dirt in politics arises during a boom era for
private investigators in the business world. Started by the
corporate takeovers of the early 1980s and fueled by computers,
corporate investigators have become an essential part of the
information economy.
</P>
<P>
   Annual revenues have quintupled to $5 billion since 1980,
according to one industry association, and investigators are
pivotal players in everything from hostile takeovers to hiring
executives and ferreting out internal fraud. The spillover into
politics was natural.
</P>
<P>
   But the best-known firms from the world of corporate snooping
say they avoid the political arena for fear that fallout from the
cases would damage their reputations and antagonize better-paying
business clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you that we haven't looked up a name for
someone in politics, but it is the policy of the company that we
don't do political work,'' said Michael Cherkasky, president of
Kroll Associates, the world's largest corporate investigative firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things that we tend not to do because they
are dirty,'' he said. ``We don't do matrimonial, we don't do
criminal defense and we don't do political.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hershman, chairman of Decision Strategies Fairfax
International, another large firm, said his investigators examined
the backgrounds of vice presidential possibilities for the Dukakis
and Clinton campaigns, but with their knowledge and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken a strong policy position on not doing political
opposition research, and I am personally against opposition
research, which I believe adds to the scourge of negative
campaigning,'' Hershman said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few major firms that solicits political cases is
Investigative Group International, the Washington company run by
Terry Lenzner, a former Watergate prosecutor. Though best known as
an investigator for Clinton's lawyers, he has also worked for
Republicans, including former Rep. Michael Huffington in his losing
Senate race in California against Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Lenzner created a division called Campaign
Facts to specialize in political investigations. He also maintains
a tiny law firm, Terry F. Lenzner PC, which several former
employees said is used partly to provide politically sensitive
inquiries an extra layer of confidentiality through attorney-client
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Lenzner was subpoenaed by Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel, to testify before a grand jury about inquiries
into Clinton's critics and two of Starr's prosecutors. Lenzner said
he was not a target of the grand jury but, stung by the
controversy, now even he is considering cutting back on political
work.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lenzner said political cases represent only a
fraction of the firm's revenue, though he defended such work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I perceive it to be analogous to a hostile takeover case where
we are hired by a company to gather information to convince
shareholders to vote for our client,'' he said. ``You are looking
at substantive issues that are relevant to the voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, the House Judiciary chairman, turned to a private
detective when a critic was trying to draw attention to his role in
a failed savings and loan.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the detective, Ernie Rizzo, a former police
officer in a Chicago suburb, provided details of his work for Hyde
for the first time _ and described his disdain for politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are the easiest people in the world to set up,''
Rizzo said. ``They're all whores. You stay with them for a week and
you'll catch them doing something _ women or money or something.
Forget about the millions spent in political campaigns. You don't
need that. Everybody got to the top by stepping over somebody. Find
the weakest link and attack it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo, as a lone operator, is typical of detectives who handle
political work. A character who would be at home in a Damon Runyon
story, he is outgoing and flashy; his holographic business card is
emblazoned with the image of a spy and six phone numbers, including
one for his boat.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo said he was hired in late 1995 by James Schirott, a lawyer
defending Hyde in a federal suit against him and other former
directors of Clyde Federal Savings and Loan. The thrift's 1990
failure cost taxpayers $67 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schirott, he said, told him the congressman was concerned about
a man turning up at hearings on the suit. Hyde wanted to know who
he was and what he knew. The lawyer gave Rizzo a name, Tim
Anderson, and an address in Libertyville, a suburb of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I did was I pulled phone records,'' Rizzo
explained. ``I saw Anderson was making 30 or 40 calls a day to the
media. I told Hyde, but he still didn't know who he was. I saw the
media calls, so I decided to pretend I was from the media.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he telephoned Anderson, claiming to be a producer for
``20/20,'' the ABC news program. Anderson agreed to meet him near
O'Hare International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a target's phone records is often the starting point of
an inquiry, investigators say. While Rizzo was convicted of illegal
wiretapping in 1977 for taping conversations in divorce cases,
privacy experts say phone records fall into a gray area in most
states. Rizzo said he got the records from a source at a telephone
company, and the Illinois attorney general's office said no state
law was violated. A spokesman for Ameritech, the regional telephone
company based in Chicago, said the company does not provide
customer records to anyone without a court order and any employee
who violated the rule would be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo said he flew to New York and took a flight back to Chicago
in case Anderson watched the airport for his arrival. But Anderson
was not suspicious. A former banking consultant, he had contacted
dozens of journalists trying to expose what he believed were the
political roots of the savings and loan scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he gladly gave Rizzo his material on Hyde _ a
bound file containing 388 pages of court records, newspaper
articles and documents obtained through the Freedom of Information
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents were minutes of Clyde federal board meetings
that showed Hyde playing a more active role than he had
acknowledged publicly. In one instance, he approved an investment
in speculative options trading that eventually lost $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo, however, also wanted to know about Anderson, especially
any vulnerabilities he had. So, the detective said: ``I warned him
that Hyde was going to come after us and I had to make sure he
didn't have any skeletons. I got him telling me all his weak
spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo said he gave the file to Hyde and was paid by a political
ally of the congressman, not by his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, The Chicago Tribune disclosed Rizzo's duping of
Anderson. In his interview with The Times, Rizzo revealed that just
two months later, in December, he employed the technique again
because Hyde and his allies feared Anderson might use the
disclosure to disrupt the impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day before the impeachment trial started in the House, I
sent two guys back in,'' Rizzo said. ``They posed as reporters. We
wanted to know if Anderson was going to sue Hyde or make any other
noise. But he told them he wasn't going to sue. He was on a
crusade. It was hilarious.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde refused to be interviewed for this article, but a spokesman
disputed several aspects of Rizzo's account.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, Sam Stratman, said Hyde was told that Anderson
had been investigated, but that Rizzo did not deliver his findings
to the congressman. Hyde never met Rizzo and had no knowledge of
his techniques, he said. Stratman said $2,000 of $20,000 in fees
paid to Schirott was for Rizzo's services. Schirott did not return
numerous phone calls from The Times over several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the federal government settled its suit with the former
Clyde federal directors for $850,000. Hyde maintained he had no
responsibility for the thrift's failure and he did not contribute
to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is carrying on, working for $7.50 an hour at Enterprise
Rent-a-Car to provide time for his crusade, even though his wife
has pleaded with him to give up and return to his profession.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he said the congressman's investigation had strengthened
his resolve. ``I'm an innocent member of the public and the head of
the Judiciary Committee hired a detective to spy on me,'' he said
indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Compared with flashy Rizzo, Larry Preston Williams is a model of
decorum, given to three-piece suits and understatement.
</P>
<P>
   An ex-lawyer and former New Orleans police officer, he estimates
that political cases represent 15 percent of his business as a
private investigator. While clients occasionally send him after
national politicians, his usual target is a candidate for local or
state office in Louisiana and other southern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of cases has picked up in recent years,'' he said.
``The aggressiveness has picked up. The willingness to use
information publicly to simply obliterate the opposition forever
has increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will happily plow through a target's garbage but his
time is more often spent wading through public records looking for
lawsuits, unpaid taxes, property ownership, divorces, arrests and
the like. He charges $50 to $150 an hour, depending on the
complexity of the case. A routine investigation costs $3,000 to
$4,000.
</P>
<P>
   What turns up most often is mundane, too: candidates or
officials who misrepresent work history, education or military
service. Baby Boomers are particularly likely to fabricate service
in Vietnam or a Purple Heart, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a candidate for New Orleans City Council hired
Williams to investigate whether an opponent met residency
requirements. The results of his two-month inquiry filled a folder
two inches thick and ranged from letters from former employers
verifying employment dates to lists of credit cards and phone
records.
</P>
<P>
   Williams leaked the information to reporters, leading to
newspaper articles that questioned whether the candidate, Ellen
Hazeur, met the residency requirement. Voters did not seem to care;
Ms. Hazeur won.
</P>
<P>
   Williams compiled a thicker dossier on David Duke, the former Ku
Klux Klan leader whose Republican candidacies for the state
Legislature and Congress have roiled Louisiana politics for the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation turned up some early evidence linking Duke to
neo-Nazis, and his client, a prominent Republican, used the report
to orchestrate a campaign publicizing Duke's white supremacist
ties.
</P>
<P>
   For clients willing to spend $50,000 or more, Williams advises
hiring a detective to start digging a year before the election.
That enables them to start a trickle of negative information about
their opponent that builds to a crescendo just before the election.
He would not identify any clients who took that course.
</P>
<P>
   For W. John Hathaway, the negative information was not a trickle
but an explosion. Running for the Republican Senate nomination from
Maine in 1996, he watched in shock as two major newspapers
published articles the same day reporting he had been accused of
having a sexual relationship with a 12-year-old baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   Six years earlier, when he lived in Huntsville, Ala., a girl who
sat for his children had claimed she had a sexual relationship with
him. He denied the accusation. Two district attorneys and the state
attorney general investigated and decided not to prosecute at the
request of the girl's parents. In a recent interview, Hathaway
again denied the accusation and said he had expected it to remain
secret because no charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   But rumors began to circulate during the primary, in which
Hathaway was one of three Republicans vying for the seat left open
by William Cohen. The others were Robert Monks, an established
political figure in Maine, and Susan Collins, a political newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   As the primary approached, Monks became alarmed, he said in a
recent interview. His polls showed Hathaway the likely winner, and
nothing had surfaced about the baby sitter's accusation. He turned
to Lenzner, whom he had known for years, authorizing him to
dispatch detectives from IGI to Alabama to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't as if it was a secret,'' Monks recalled. ``It was a
piece of information that was something that people didn't want to
have anything to do with.''
</P>
<P>
   A person involved in the IGI investigation said detectives
interviewed the girl's mother and other people and provided a
report to the Monks campaign. Five days before the primary, The
Boston Globe and Portland Press Herald published articles about the
accusation, reporting that Hathaway had denied the charges and had
never been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   After the articles appeared, Hathaway accused Monks of leaking
the story. Monks admitted hiring a detective, but denied that his
efforts led to the articles. Even that admission took a toll on
Monks. He finished last, with Hathaway second and Ms. Collins, who
had refused to comment on the controversy, winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing blew up in Monks' face,'' said Christian
Potholm, a government professor at Bowdoin College in Maine.
``People felt that this was not something that a Bill Cohen or a
George Mitchell would have done.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether IGI played a role in either article.
Investigators usually turn over information to the client and let
the campaign decide how to handle it.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Kurkjian, the lead reporter on The Globe's article, said
he might have talked to an IGI investigator, but that an editor had
sent him to Huntsville on a tip. ``I had the story without them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Campbell of the Press Herald would not identify his
initial source. ``It didn't matter where it was coming from,'' he
said. ``I was more concerned with whether the rumors were
factual.''
</P>
<P>
   In the recent interview, Monks said his staff had discussed the
information with reporters. He still denied that the investigators
were behind the articles, but he acknowledged opening a Pandora's
box by sending them to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once someone had stuck their hand in the thicket,'' he said,
``the information began to flow.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   No incident better demonstrates the power of private
investigators than the runoff for Houston mayor in 1991 between Bob
Lanier, a millionaire businessman, and Sylvester Turner, a
Harvard-educated lawyer and state representative.
</P>
<P>
   Six days before the vote, Houston's ABC affiliate broadcast a
report questioning whether Turner had a role in an insurance scam
in which a former law client had faked drowning. It said Turner had
drawn up the man's will shortly before he disappeared and had been
involved in efforts to collect his insurance money. It quoted
Turner saying he was a victim of the scam and had cooperated with
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters from the University of Houston interviewing voters the
night the story aired watched Turner's numbers plunge. ``Until
then, the race was very close, with a slight but statistically
insignificant advantage to Turner,'' said Richard Murray, who
supervised the poll. ``We could see the direct effect. Turner
dropped eight points.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner blamed the report on Lanier, an accusation the campaign
and TV station denied. Turner never recovered and lost by the
eight-point margin.
</P>
<P>
   Turner later sued the station and its investigative reporter for
libel, and in trial in 1996 the link between the Lanier campaign
and the broadcast was finally discovered. A private investigator on
Lanier's campaign finance committee had delivered a one-page
summary of the allegations to the reporter and arranged for him to
receive court files about the faked death, according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   After the election, the investigator and a second detective who
also played a role in providing the story to the TV station
received a multimillion-dollar contract from the Lanier
administration to collect overdue parking fines.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that the broadcast was false and awarded Turner
$5.5 million, a figure the judge reduced to $3.25 million. Last
December, an appellate court set aside the verdict, ruling that
Turner was a public figure. Turner has appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Turner criticized the private investigators.
``They did not care anything about the person, or family, or common
decency,'' he said. ``They were hired to do a job _ and they were
successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
