<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9800 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-KAN-BUDADD-KAN &LR;      07-05 0186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDADD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to also move the following story for
use by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Tuesday, July 6. If you have any questions, please call The Star's
News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   PAC-DONATIONS (WASHINGTON) _ When it comes to how incumbents
raise money, wide differences exist among members of Congress from
Missouri and Kansas, data from the Center for Responsive Politics
show. The amount House incumbents received from individuals giving
$1,000 or less in 1997-98 ranged from 3 percent by U.S. Rep. Pat
Danner of Kansas City_ the lowest in all of Congress _ to 67
percent for Rep. Jim Talent, a St. Louis Republican who now is
running for governor. Political action committees accounted for 79
percent of Danner's money, but only 30 percent of Talent's. On
average, House incumbents got about 42 percent of their money from
PACs, which can give up to $5,000 to each candidate in the primary
and that much more in the general. By KEVIN MURPHY. Story will move
in the ``w'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-COX     07-05 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield contemplates life after boxing
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It hit Evander Holyfield one morning last week like a
Lennox Lewis jab _ flush and startling. Boxing does not last
forever. It's a simple concept, but not so much to a boxer.
Fighters fight. But until when?
</P>
<P>
   Not much longer for three-time heavyweight champion Holyfield,
who has charted a fitting conclusion to a career marked by
overachievement. At 36, there's not much more to conquer before
retiring to his palatial estate off the highway just south of
Atlanta named after him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with Holyfield, the exit would have to be something
grand, something symbolic of the caliber of his career and the
goodwill spirit of the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years at the most,'' he said. ``If it all happens
properly, it'll take just two years. Five more fights, maybe.
Lennox Lewis this year. Then the mandatory _ Henry Akinwande. Then,
it's probably David Tua. Then the No. 2-ranked guy. And then it's,
`Will Mike Tyson be ready?'
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing for sure, before that last fight, I'll take a year
off and travel the world being an ambassador to boxing as the
undisputed heavyweight champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield slid to the edge of his seat. A slight smile creased
his lips. He was excited. ``I'll go everywhere I can around the
world and put boxing where it should be. Give it the proper
perspective. I'll make people everywhere feel good about the game,
meet me as the heavyweight champion. I'll set a precedent, get
everybody hyped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'll have one more fight. Pay-per-view. See how many
people tune in. I want to do something so sensational I can't do
anymore. Then, I'll have a press conference saying, 'I'm ready to
clean my hands.' I don't want to go out a former champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield understands, however, that his grand plan could blow
up with more underwhelming performances like his last two fights.
He was so lethargic in stopping unknown Vaughn Bean last year and
so seemingly over matched in the controversial draw against Lewis
earlier this year that many observers say Holyfield already has
fought too long.
</P>
<P>
   He scoffs at the notion. Although no contracts have been signed,
Holyfield began pre-training Monday for a rematch with Lewis in Las
Vegas in November. He claims to be ``excited'' because he'll go
into the fight in his best physical condition ever.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield cited a poor diet heavy on carbohydrates as a reason _
not an excuse _ for his performance against Lewis that was short of
energy and effectiveness. ``For 14 years, I was taught wrong,'' he
said. ``I was carbo-loading the week before a fight as a marathon
runner would. But that's not the way to go for a boxer. I talked to
a nutritionist, Barry Seal, and it was amazing because he knew how
I felt even though he wasn't around me. He knew that I carbo-loaded
and the effect it had on my body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt lethargic. I was tired and sleepy and it took me more
energy to think. I would almost fall asleep in the dressing room
before a fight. . . . In the ring, if I fought an aggressive
fighter, it was easier to break out of it because I'll naturally
fight back. But if the guy was just in there, it took a lot to get
me going.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Holyfeld said his diet is less about carbohydrates and
more about Creatine and avoiding fats. ``I'm excited to go with a
totally different training method,'' he said. ``I'm just fortunate
the old way never really caught up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat remarkably, Holyfield's out-of-ring transgressions
seemingly have not caught up with him, either. Apparently, the
revelations about his personal life in the last year have not
significantly dimmed his public image. Indeed, he might even be
more beloved, which speaks for the genuine nature of the man.
</P>
<P>
   Days after the Bean fight, Holyfield made public that he'd
fathered nine children with six women, one while married to his
wife, Janice. Instead of becoming a recluse in the face of such a
revelation, Holyfield continued to make public appearances _ partly
because he remained in demand and partly because he simply would
not be ashamed of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my kids and the kids I speak to, 'A winner and a loser
have one thing in common: They make mistakes,' `` he said.
``Evander Holyfield certainly has made some mistakes. But if you
treat people nice, they'll give you a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Jim Thomas, believes Holyfield's disposition is at
the heart of his continued place as a ``good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The things he revealed are not really important to the extent
of his ability to help people,'' Thomas said. ``He views life as
being accountable in the eyes of God, not people. So, he continued
to do the things he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stature has not diminished at all, from what we can see.
He's still in high demand. Now, there are some individuals who
decided to turn off to Evander. And it's more women than men. But
it's a very, very small percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Holyfield: ``I lot of people are fickle because they judge
people by how they judge themselves. Most people who are successful
receive me with open arms because they understand people go through
ups and downs. Most of the people who admire or receive me are not
quitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in bondage to people. By that, I mean people
used to talk about me all the time when I was young because we were
poor and didn't have anything. It only hurt when it came from
people that were close to me. So the vast number of people who
criticize me for my mistakes don't know me, so it doesn't affect
me. But it's not about self for me. People appreciate more what you
do for them than what they do for you. I like giving and doing for
people, and they sense that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas cited a couple of international appearances by Holyfield
as examples of his popularity. ``We were in Monte Carlo for the
World Music Awards,'' Thomas said. ``There were stars all over the
place, including Janet Jackson. But people were coming up to me
saying, 'Forget Janet Jackson, I want to meet the heavyweight
champion.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Same thing in Trinidad when Evander judged the Miss Universe
contest. I can't tell you how popular he was. On the other said of
that, Evander's not fazed by all the attention. It's flattering,
but he's not driven by what others think of him. He believes he's
judged by how he is as a parent and how he treats people.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who treated more than 700 people to a barbecue at his
estate Sunday, supports all his children and considers them the
driving force in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a man if he doesn't raise his kids, and raise them
properly,'' Holyfield said. ``You'll be a miserable person. I put
my time in with my kids. Your future tends to be based on your
kids' lives. When I'm not speaking or making an appearance, I'm
with always with my kids. I follow them in the summer to their
track meets or soccer or whatever they're doing. They're always a
bright point for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He's going through a dark point with a divorce, however, that
could be lengthy and costly and certainly draining. He said he made
$54 million in the two years he's been married to Janice, and she
apparently wants a significant portion of that earnings. There's
the sticking point.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say what he was offering her as alimony, but
Holyfield wants to negotiate the terms with her, not lawyers. She
wants otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should depend on the two people what the settlement
is,'' he said. ``We can talk about anything, but when it gets to
that, she gets upset. She wants to go to court. Why drag me into
court on something we can settle ourselves? We need to settle it
out of court. Because of who I am and the money, there's all this
confusion going on. As a man with deep pockets, the system gets
you. If I didn't have money, it was be a divorce in 30 days. Done.
In a divorce situation, all he man have afterward is memories. The
woman has memories and money. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   But not something that will break him. He said he holds to his
spirituality as a source of strength. And his commitment to
uplifting boxing while executing his exodus keep him going.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good attitude takes you a lot farther than talent,''
Holyfield said. ``I don't think people still like or accept me
because I'm the heavyweight champion. It's the individual. I was
raised to treat people nicely. And that's what I do. Boxing's going
to be over soon, but I'll be the same person. You can say this
about me: 'The man knows how to be champion.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
