<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA STARTS NEW ERA WITH A BURST OF INVECTIVE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ South Africa's second
post-apartheid elections are over, but it looks like the
mudslinging may just be getting started.
</P>
<P>
   The first two weeks of President Thabo Mbeki's new
administration have been a feast of charges and countercharges,
with politicians calling each other everything from ``soulless,''
``mean'' and ``unforgiving'' to ``tamed baboons'' and ``toothless
Chihuahuas.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, whose African National Congress won nearly a two-thirds
majority in Parliament, has hardly been playing Mr. Nice Guy.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to Parliament on June 28, he gave a relentless
verbal beating to a tiny black Christian party that won less then 1
percent of the vote after it criticized an official of his African
National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in what many consider a particularly spiteful move, he
kept the official opposition party off the important Judicial
Services Commission, which, among other things, makes nominations
to the bench. He gave a seat instead to a leader of the Federal
Alliance party, which has only 2 of the 400 seats in National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Furious over Mbeki's move, Tony Leon, the head of the official
opposition, the liberal and largely white Democratic Party, called
the Federal Alliance leader, Louis Luyt, the former rugby magnate
who got the commission seat instead, the Afrikaans word for a
``tame baboon.'' Luyt responded by calling Leon a ``toothless
chihuahua.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Mbeki's party seem to be doing little better at
getting along. The former leader of the provincial government in
Mpumulanga, Mathews Phosa, has decided to sue the new one, Ndaweni
Mahlangu, for defamation.
</P>
<P>
   The series of insults from all sides was set off when Mahlangu,
who was hand-picked for his post by Mbeki and who had been in
office barely a week, proclaimed that all politicians lie and he
has no trouble with that. Then he seemed to implicate Phosa in a
scandal over the signing of illegal notes by the previous
administration.
</P>
<P>
   When Mbeki addressed Parliament last week, he lashed out at the
tiny African Christian Democratic Party for calling for Mahlangu's
resignation. Mbeki attacked the Christian Democrats on several
fronts, saying their support of the death penalty and opposition to
abortion puts forward a ``mean, angry, vengeful, soulless and
retributive theology.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mbeki was only working up to his grand finale, which was a
defense of Mahlangu, a former official in the apartheid-era
homeland system, which forced many blacks to move to small
segregated areas. Mahlangu has been under fire not only for the
remark about lying but also because he has appointed a number of
officials of questionable competence and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   When Mahlangu was being questioned about why he had appointed an
official who was involved in the scandal in which government-owned
parkland was used as collateral for loans, Mahlangu had seemed to
imply that Phosa was responsible for the scandal and for the other
official's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki did not address that aspect of the issue but defended
Mahlangu on the grounds that he had apologized for the remarks
about lying and should be allowed to get on with his job.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki said that the Christian Democrats, in calling for
Mahlangu's resignation, remain ``true to a theology which knows no
forgiveness, no compassion, no humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And so,'' Mbeki added, the party members ``stand up in this
House and declaim, `He is down! Crucify him! Crucify him! Crucify
him! Crucify him!'''
</P>
<P>
   While the small party was the focus of Mbeki's tirade, it has
hardly been alone in calling for Mahlangu's resignation. In the
last few days, theologians across the country have said that
remarks like his about lying cannot be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Leon's liberal Democratic Party also came under fire from Mbeki,
who said it was putting forward a ``soulless secular theology''
that would leave survival to the fittest and do nothing to reach
out to those who had been treated as ``subhuman'' under apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   But the real blow to that party came when the ANC's chief whip
read out the names of the six members of the Judicial Commission.
Instead of the expected Democratic representative, the whip
announced Luyt's name.
</P>
<P>
   Luyt, a fertilizer and beer magnate, became well known in South
Africa as a rugby franchise owner. But in recent years, he has also
become known as the man who dragged former President Nelson Mandela
into court to question his right to appoint a commission to look
into racism in rugby. Luyt went on to accuse about half of the
Constitutional Court of being biased against him.
</P>
<P>
   The General Council of the Bar of South Africa quickly slammed
Mbeki's choice, saying the appointment of Luyt was either ``not
considered or not in good faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
