<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking issue with Hemingway-as-commodity
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The publisher of Ernest Hemingway's posthumous novel ``True at
First Light'' may be able to fool some people, but not the late
writer's granddaughter. In a delightfully honest essay in GQ ($3),
titled ``The Snow Job of Kilimanjaro,'' Lorian Hemingway, author of
the memoir ``Walk on Water,'' criticizes the commercialization of
the family name and bemoans the publication of work her grandfather
did not consider ready for print.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to say that those who would abuse the concept of
literary integrity are guilty of high crime, but that they are
simply in the business of peddling Hemingway as if he were a QVC
home-shopping-network item,'' she writes. As an example, she cites
the new line of Hemingway furniture that reflects Papa's lifestyles
in Key West, Cuba and Idaho and a collection of children's books
and clothes. What's next, she asks: a Tickle-Me Erno doll?
</P>
<P>
   _ Music to our ears: Details ($2.95) spices up what could be
another dull list in an attitude-dripping article on the 49 Best
Albums of All Time. Instead of listing the usual suspects, Jeff
Ousborne has come up with such interesting categories as ``best
album to listen to while being pursued by the police at
ridiculously high speeds'' (James Brown's ``Greatest Hits'') or
``best album to encourage you to buy firearms'' (Jewel's
``Spirit''). Other gems include Frank Sinatra's ``In the Wee Small
Hours'' for ``best album for the denial stage of a breakup'' and
George Jones' ``16 Biggest Hits'' for ``best album recorded drunk,
drugged, armed, divorced and jailed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ More music to our ears: The Jacksonville band Limp Bizkit
isn't happy being merely a best-selling rap metal group with a hit
album. Singer-choreographer Fred Durst wants a multimedia empire _
and some respect. He lays out his plans in an over-the-top
interview in the August issue of Spin ($2.99). Elsewhere in the
magazine, Sarah McLachlan explains why she's not unhappy about
dropping the final curtain on the Lilith Fair concert tour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inside Iran: Much has changed in Iran since a group of
Americans were held hostage at the U.S. Embassy in Tehran.
Traveling throughout the country for National Geographic ($3.95),
author Fen Montaigne and photographer Alexandra Avakian found that
many Iranian women are losing patience with the restrictions of a
male-dominated society. Despite government efforts to shield
Iranians from ``corrupting'' Western influences, the Internet and
TV satellite dishes are shredding the Islamic curtain, Montaigne
reports.
</P>
<P>
   _ Showbiz buzz: As Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) notes in its
July 9 cover story, even cowboys get the blues. Especially when the
cowboys are in the summer stinker ``Wild Wild West.'' Is the movie
that bad, or is it simply negative word of mouth? Director Barry
Sonnenfeld blames the film's woes on that mysterious Hollywood
ether known as buzz. Entertainment Weekly doesn't buy that
argument. Elsewhere in the magazine, reviewer Owen Glieberman gives
the movie a barely passing grade of D+.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quick reads: In the August issue of More ($2.95), Rita Wilson
explains that she's determined to prove she's not just Mrs. Tom
Hanks. After putting her career on the back burner for four years
to focus on family, Wilson is back with two new movies: ``The Story
of Us,'' with Michelle Pfeiffer and Bruce Willis, and ``Runaway
Bride,'' with Richard Gere. ... Changing the world is hard, so why
bother? Utne Reader ($4.99) visits with activists and nonactivists,
from a hermit poet to doctors who volunteer for duty in a Third
World hell. ... The July/August issue of Gear ($3.50) is all about
sex, including a fascinating article _ ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' _
about female secret agents in Israel's Mossad. Apparently, in some
cases, sex appeal is more powerful than bullets. Using her charms,
one of the Mossad's more attractive agents enticed a Soviet-trained
MiG-21 pilot to defect to Israel _ with his plane.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
