<SLUG> BC-DIUGUID-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET PAST THE ILLUSION OF DIALOGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LEWIS W. DIUGUID  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years ago, Emanuel Cleaver had his Mayor's Task Force on
Race Relations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, President Clinton had his national dialogue on race.
Last week, The Kansas City Star and The Kansas City Call launched a
unique effort to report on and hold forums on race. This fall,
Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes plans to appoint a committee to work
on race.
</P>
<P>
   Race relations are continually probed too much and not at all.
That centuries-old paradox has deepened one of America's most
enduring problems. It's why racially motivated shootings and
killings like the ones in Illinois and Indiana still occur.
</P>
<P>
   John Hope Franklin, a historian who led Clinton's Race
Initiative Advisory Board, talked about our race problem in May
when he was in town to receive the Harry S. Truman Good Neighbor
Award. Franklin, the first African-American to get the honor,
praised former President Harry S. Truman for a 1947 report titled
``To Secure These Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a landmark report made by a landmark president
calling for a revolution in human and social relations,'' Franklin
said. If recommendations in it were followed, America wouldn't have
such trouble in race relations today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something wrong with this country, which wasted so
much time, energy and manpower to maintain a biracial society that
was not equal in any respect,'' Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting everyone to talk is a problem, Cleaver said at last
week's Star//Call forum.
</P>
<P>
   That issue also surfaced at a spring Diversity Forum that the
Coalition for Positive Family Relationships held at the University
of Missouri-Kansas City. About 60 persons attended, but only three,
including me, were men.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is resistance to talking about diversity,'' said Helen
Cohen with Parents, Families and Friends of Lesbians and Gays
Kansas City chapter. ``There is the appearance of talking about
diversity. I'm not sure how to get beyond the appearance of
acceptance.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryck Dean, associate executive director of Kansas City
Harmony, sat with Cohen on a panel that took up the questions: How
do you have a meaningful dialogue on diversity? What are the
biggest stumbling blocks?
</P>
<P>
   Dean, who is black, said: ``It dawned on me. I've never met a
racist. If you accuse somebody of being prejudiced, they'll
automatically deny it. I don't think people are being honest in
what their prejudices are and in how they discriminate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Botello, chairwoman of the Kansas//Missouri board of
Project Equality, said assumptions are the biggest obstacle to
improving relations among people who are different.
</P>
<P>
   Money is another, said Cohen. ``There are institutions that have
a stake in continuing racism and sexism and homophobia,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Star//Call panel and the coalition group did offer some
solutions. Diane Hershberger, Harmony's executive director, asked
people to leave their comfort zones to socialize with others who
are different.
</P>
<P>
   At the coalition meeting, people suggested that everyone listen
to radio stations and read books featuring other races, religions,
sexual orientation, ethnicities and cultures.
</P>
<P>
   People said more ``safehouses'' are needed for diversity
discussions where no one would be afraid to risk, be honest and
learn. They suggested that people become more politically active
and push for inclusiveness. Organizations should make sure their
mission and vision statements include diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition group said that for the next forum, each woman
should bring a man. That way more guys would also be enlightened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
