A9805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICKFILA-COWS-COX     07-05 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKFILA-COWS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Hippie heifers are hucksters in Chick-fil-A's new campaign
</P>
<P>
   By Shelia M. Poole
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Chick-fil-A cows are retro, man!
</P>
<P>
   In a groovy kinda way.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant company this week begins its summer promotional
campaign featuring the ever-popular ``Eat Mor Chikin'' cows donning
tie-dyed T-shirts, long hair, headbands and shades. And, yes, they
even give the peace sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This falls in with the mood of the country,'' said Chick-fil-A
spokesman Don Perry. ``Everyone is looking back. This is the end of
the century.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, however, the cows try to make sure it's not the end of
them.
</P>
<P>
   In the $1.5 million campaign, which runs through Aug. 31, the
cows continually urge consumers to ``Eat Mor Chikin'' in a uniquely
bovine twist on '60s jargon.
</P>
<P>
   The slogans, which will be heard in radio spots and seen on
billboards, include ``Peece, Luv, Chikin'' and ``Give Chikin A
Chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will offer a special Summer of Chikin plush cow for
$4.99.
</P>
<P>
   Participating restaurants also will have specially designed
peel-off game cards attached to medium and large drink cups.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can win a variety of menu items or merchandise, and
1,000 grand-prize winners will receive free Chick-fil-A entree
items for a year.
</P>
<P>
   The crafty cows, which were introduced in 1995, have proven to
be one of the most successful campaigns for the company, receiving
several national and international awards. The campaign was created
by Dallas-based The Richards Group.
</P>
<P>
   The latest campaign, focusing on the '60s, is one of the most
aggressive for the year, Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a creative stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRECO-SONGS-2TAKES-NY     07-05 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRECO-SONGS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 YEARS LATER, JULIETTE GRECO FINDS NEW AUDIENCES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Even with the harsh spotlight heightening the pallor of
her skin against the blackness of her dress, Juliette Greco looks
every bit the grande dame of the chanson francaise. She walks
regally to the microphone and starts singing, her arms soon
sketching in the air the very ardor of her words. In no time, the
audience warms to her. A few songs later, it is on its feet. By the
end, it won't let her go.
</P>
<P>
   It could all be put down to nostalgia. In her late teens, Ms.
Greco was heralded as the muse of Existentialism. She would hang
out with the likes of Jean-Paul Sartre, Jean Cocteau, Boris Vian
and Miles Davis in Left Bank bars and cafes crowded with poets and
artists. For an entire generation, she personified the post-war
bohemia of St.-Germain-des-Pres. Now, at 72, when she returns to
the stage, she is a treat for those who want to remember.
</P>
<P>
   What most pleases the petite, dark-eyed singer, however, is that
she is still a voice of today. When she sings in Paris or around
Europe and beyond, there are always many in the audience who who
are seeing her on the stage for the first time, many who belong to
the generation of her 25-year-old granddaughter. They are not
trying to recapture their youth through snatches of familiar
melodies. They want to experience her songs as love poems of today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get lots of letters,'' Ms. Greco said in her dressing room
during a recent week of sold-out concerts at the Theatre de l'Odeon
in the heart of St.-Germain in Paris. ``They're not strange,
they're very romantic. Full of sweetness, love, tenderness. It's
marvelous. They use the language of children, the language of
youth. It's very beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to a small bronze teapot on her makeup table. ``It
was a present last night,'' she said. ``It has a note inside.
`Madame, this is the first time I have seen you perform. I came
Wednesday and I am returning tonight. I loved your recital, it is
beautiful and you were moving. I will soon be 29 and I love you
very much. I admire what you do, you are very committed and I like
that.' Adorable, no?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every performer wants to be loved, every star needs
to be loved. But Ms. Greco does not count on old favorites' forever
drawing new fans. For her latest record, ``Un Jour d'Ete et
Quelques Nuits,'' which was well received when it was released last
December, she had a dozen songs written for her by the playwright
Jean-Claude Carriere and her husband, Gerard Jouannest, a composer.
</P>
<P>
   The songs are new, yet they fit squarely into the tradition of
the chanson francaise, that special storytelling genre of popular
music in which words are as important as melodies, a genre that
since World War II has had Charles Trenet, Edith Piaf, Yves
Montand, Jacques Brel, Serge Gainsbourg, Leo Ferre, Barbara,
Charles Aznavour and Ms. Greco among its most popular exponents.
</P>
<P>
   At her concerts here in late May and early June, she offered old
and new to the accompaniment of a five-piece band led by Jouannest
at the piano. ``Les Feuilles Mortes,'' written by Jacques Prevert
and Joseph Kosma and later made popular in English as ``Autumn
Leaves,'' is now something of a signature piece for her. She also
included old songs _ some written for her _ by Ferre, Gainsbourg
and Brel. But most were Carriere-Jouannest songs from her new
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like little plays,'' explained Ms. Greco, inviting a
visitor to uncork a bottle of chilled white Burgundy. ``They're
typically French. We're a people who express our love in songs, our
anger in songs, even our revolution in songs. That's peculiarly
French. It fits into our great anarchist tradition. But what's
interesting is that the chanson francaise is making a comeback. It
never disappeared, but it's returning with force.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Ms. Greco has not stopped singing in the style,
although she tours frequently outside France. (``I'm an export
product, a French luxury product,'' she said with a laugh.) When
she does return to Paris, she seemingly times her appearances for
maximum impact. Her last series of concerts at the Olympia in 1991
provoked enthusiastic rebirth notices for the chanson francaise.
This spring posters were again proclaiming ``the return of La
Greco.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, was special because she had finally achieved
a lifelong dream of performing in the Odeon, a dream born when she
was a teen-ager wandering the streets of wartime St.-Germain
fantasizing about a career as an actress, as a tragedienne, to be
more exact. She was already too old to fulfill her first dream of
becoming a dancer. The idea of becoming a singer was born somewhat
accidentally a few years later. At that moment, October 1943 in
German-occupied France, she had few options.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greco's father had left home when she was tiny. After her
mother was arrested for Resistance activities in the Dordogne,
Juliette came to Paris with her older sister, Charlotte, who was
also in the Resistance. One day, seeing the French police arresting
Charlotte, Juliette demanded to be taken along. A few weeks later,
she was freed, but both her mother and Charlotte were deported to
Nazi camps. They survived and were repatriated in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Alone in Paris and still only 15, Ms. Greco was helped by a
family friend who eventually arranged for her to attend acting
classes. Living in a pension with other aspiring young artists, she
grew up quickly. By the late 1940s, while she was hardly noticed
for her occasional small stage roles, her striking looks and
independent spirit had turned La Greco, as she was soon known, into
one of the attractions of St.-Germain's buzzing night life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bizarre, different,'' she recalled. ``I think I was a
bit shocking. I was all black and white. I had this pale face and
big black eyes, very long straight black hair with a fringe. No one
wore their hair like that in those days. I was dressed in black. I
wore men's clothes because the boys in the pension would hand me
down their old clothes. I had to roll up the trousers and it became
a fashion. Women began to wear men's shirts and jackets and
rolled-up trousers. That's how it started.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greco said she always had a good ear for music and would
occasionally sing at parties, usually Edith Piaf songs, which were
the rage at the time. Then in 1949, Le Boeuf Sur le Toit, a popular
prewar restaurant-cum-nightclub, was to reopen and she was invited
to join the team organizing the first show. She said she wanted to
sing. But what? She needed advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I went to see Sartre on Rue Bonaparte,'' she said. ``He had
always been nice to me. So had Simone de Beauvoir, very warm, very
affectionate. Anyway, Sartre told me to come back early the
following morning _ I hated getting up early _ and he would suggest
a few poems. I picked from these and he approved the choice. He
then said, `I'm going to give you a song I wrote called La Rue des
Blancs Manteaux.' He'd written it for his play `No Exit,' but he
said the music was bad, so he put me in touch with Joseph Kosma and
voila.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Voila it was, because, at Le Boeuf Sur le Toit, with the words
of renowned poets and the music of a fine composer, Ms. Greco made
her name overnight. Soon she was drawn into the world of the
chanson francaise and others began writing for her. It was an
intellectual world _ Ferre, for instance, would put Rimbaud and
Verlaine to music _ but this only added to her aura. To this day,
her early association with philosophers and intellectuals
contributes to her mystique.
</P>
<P>
   It is something she is willing to exploit for good causes, not
least the somewhat unsuccessful campaign to prevent St.-Germain
from being converted into a quarter of designer boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make use of my name because it's a name that frightens
people a bit,'' she said with amusement. ``It doesn't mean anything
to me, but I have an audience and when I open my big mouth people
listen. If I want to speak out about St.-Germain on the radio, the
stations say, `Please come, Madame Greco.' My name opens doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all that, she insists she is not interested in
nostalgia. ``I have had an exceptional life,'' she said. ``I've had
to fight a great deal to get what I want. But it's not yesterday
that interests me. I'm interested in today and tomorrow. I don't
like to repeat things. Every night the show is different. After
Paris, it is Italy, then Monte Carlo, which has all those ladies
who can't applaud because their rings are too heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   She certainly looks ready to keep on going. At the Odeon, for
example, she stood for an hour and 55 minutes and sang some 25
songs _ without an intermission. Each time she ends a show in
Paris, however, she also wonders whether it will be her last here.
``Perhaps this is the last time,'' she mused. ``If I don't find
something really new to sing in five years, I'm not returning to
Paris at the age of 76.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course she is already looking for something new.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
