<SLUG> BC-LOCKWOOD-LUGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockwood Greene chief resigns to `do something different'
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At age 61, Donald R. Luger intends to do something
most people dream about at 21.
</P>
<P>
   Luger, who is resigning as head of Lockwood Greene engineering
firm after three decades with the company, wants to be an
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very good about my 31 years at Lockwood Greene,'' said
Luger, who submitted his resignation last week. ``But I am in good
health, and I want to do something different. My desire to have my
own business has intensified as I have gotten older.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what that business might be is still up in the air, said
Luger, who has been president of the company for 17 years and is
also its chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   He has a master's degree in civil engineering, a license to
practice in five Eastern states, and an interest in developing
leadership and management skills for the profession. He says the
possibilities are many.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood Greene is based in Spartanburg, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The company has annual billings of $300 million and 45 offices
that employ more than 3,000 people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Constructed value of Lockwood Greene's engineering projects is
more than $5 billion a year. Its major projects have included the
Pratt &AMP; Whitney plant in Columbus, Ga. and the General Mills plant
in Covington, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Luger's handpicked successor is Fred M. Brune, who will take the
reins Aug. 1. Brune, 48, is a former Arthur Young accountant who
became Lockwood Greene's chief financial officer in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Brune was promoted to senior vice president of
corporate services, an umbrella that covered human resources,
marketing, finance and accounting, and information services.
</P>
<P>
   About halfway through Luger's tenure at Lockwood Greene,
Frankfurt, Germany-based Philipp Holtzmann, another large
engineering firm, bought 80 percent of the company. Holtzmann had
already acquired J.A. Jones Construction Co. of Charlotte, N.C.,
and Holtzmann U.S.A. has now been folded into Jones to form a
combination that will handle both engineering and construction
projects.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 Lockwood Greene employees own 20 percent of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
