<HEADER>
A9811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-SECURITYCOSTS-CO     07-05 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SECURITYCOSTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Security: How much does it cost for Bush to jet around applying
to voters for a new job?
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As Gov. George W. Bush wended his way across
California last week as the leading Republican front-runner for
president, Texas taxpayers were there at every political handshake.
</P>
<P>
   At least their pocketbooks were.
</P>
<P>
   His cadre of bodyguards comes courtesy of the Texas Department
of Public Safety officers and Texas Rangers, and Texans are footing
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   How much does that security cost as Bush jets around the country
applying to voters for a new job?
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides and DPS officials refuse to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``By policy, we don't discuss any aspects of security for the
governor,'' said Mike Cox, a DPS spokesman. ``All I can say is that
we are providing security for him like we have every Texas governor
since 1935. And obviously, at this point there is additional travel
involved as a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the cost, said Mindy Tucker, a Bush campaign
spokeswoman, ``it's not out of the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Democrat ex-governor) Ann Richards traveled for
political reasons for Bill Clinton in one of his races, the
protective detail followed her, as well,'' Tucker said. ``It's
common for them to protect the governor whether he is in the state
or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when Clinton was campaigning for the White House while
still governor of Arkansas, Arkansas state troopers accompanied him
until a Secret Service detail took over after the New Hampshire
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, Secret Service protection is afforded ``major
presidential candidates'' _ usually about the time primaries are
held.
</P>
<P>
   During June, Bush spent 12 days outside Texas _ part of a
whirlwind campaign tour that touched Iowa, Michigan, Pennsylvania,
New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Florida
and California, among other states, and helped Bush raise a record
$36.25 million in campaign donations to help cement his status as
the early favorite for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   By his side at each stop were plainclothes DPS officers and
Rangers, distinguishable by their suits and sunglasses, de rigueur
attire for bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   How many?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask DPS,'' said Linda Edwards, Bush's gubernatorial press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't ever discuss the size of the executive protection
detail,'' said Cox, although he acknowledged it was recently
increased in size because of Bush's increasing travel schedule, a
fact that has been widely reported.
</P>
<P>
   How much?
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't comment,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush remained in Texas until the Legislature adjourned May 31,
then began his presidential campaign journeys, Edwards said. While
campaigning for president, Bush continues to collect his
$97,890-a-year salary.
</P>
<P>
   How much is all the additional cross-country travel costing
Texas taxpayers? That information, too, is confidential, officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to talk to DPS,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't reveal that because that information could tend to
reveal numbers of personnel we have assigned to him,'' Cox said.
``We are very cautious in this regard. We don't go into any numbers
or discuss the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Inquiring taxpayers can forget perusing a copy of the state
budget to get around the official stonewalling. DPS officials said
the funding for Bush's bodyguards is well-hidden within the $90
million yearly budget of the agency's traffic enforcement division
_ which Cox says has more than 2,000 employees. The Texas Rangers'
annual budget is about $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the only other elected state official besides Bush
to have bodyguards on the payroll _ Attorney General John Cornyn _
was more forthcoming with fiscal details. Cornyn spokesman Ted
Delisi said the Internal Security Division has 19 employees and a
budget of $600,000 _ although the officers assigned to it provide
security at offices and do other jobs, with one only occasionally
protecting Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush aides would not discuss specific numbers, they
suggested privately that most of the expense to taxpayers would
come from overtime pay because Bush's DPS security detail travels
on planes and stays in hotels paid for by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be with him anyway, whether he was in Houston or
Dallas or Los Angeles,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Bush, awash in campaign riches, not paying his
security tab instead of leaving it to Texas taxpayers?
</P>
<P>
   Simple, Tucker said. ``It's DPS's responsibility to protect the
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
