<SLUG> BC-DETECTIVE-POLITICS-ABRIDGED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE INVESTIGATORS PLAYING BIGGER ROLE IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ill., La.)  (Eds: This is a short version of DETECTIVE-POLITICS.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeding an almost insatiable demand for negative information in
today's world of bruising politics, private investigators are
playing a larger _ though mostly hidden _ role in the public arena,
digging up dirt on everyone from regulators to elected national and
small-town officials.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's use of private detectives has been widely
reported. But an examination by The New York Times found that over
the past decade they have moved into every corner of public life,
hired by politicians and their surrogates ranging from Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., to the House Judiciary Committee chairman, Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and from the former mayor of New York, David
Dinkins, to aspirants for local city councils.
</P>
<P>
   The private investigators' thick reports usually are aimed at
discrediting critics and disposing of opponents. But they are also
used defensively, to identify and, if possible, to avoid potential
embarrassments.
</P>
<P>
   Today's breed of investigators include former police officers,
as always, but also former FBI agents, ex-CIA employees, former
prosecutors and, in a trend that raises new ethical questions,
ex-journalists, who can tap old news contacts to get negative
information published.
</P>
<P>
   Operating with little regulation or accountability, the
detectives spy on opponents by posing as reporters, or by sending
in operatives who work as volunteers in the campaign. In a world
where sensitive computer data can flow freely despite privacy laws,
some routinely obtain protected information ranging from phone
records to medical histories.
</P>
<P>
   They track down ex-spouses and former associates and employees,
often concealing the reason they are asking questions, and they go
through trash from offices, campaign headquarters and homes, a
practice known as ``Dumpster diving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a garbage pail I won't get in, not an angle I
won't aim a hidden camera,'' said Larry Preston Williams, a former
police intelligence officer in New Orleans, who sends every
statewide candidate in Louisiana an offer to dig up ``white lies''
and other information about opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take cases from Republicans, Democrats, conservatives,
liberals,'' Williams said. ``It's all information.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how frequently private detectives are used in
political campaigns. The Federal Election Commission says it cannot
monitor campaign spending on them because payments are routinely
lumped with fees to lawyers. And journalists who cooperate with
detectives often promise confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has, however, begun to examine some of
the techniques that private investigators and information brokers
use to obtain confidential information. In April the Federal Trade
Commission filed a landmark suit against a Colorado investigator
over the use of deceptions known as pretexts to obtain information
about private bank accounts, and on June 25 state authorities
indicted him on racketeering charges. Congress is considering
legislation to outlaw pretexts.
</P>
<P>
   Personal attacks have been part of political campaigns since the
nation's inception. But for most of this century unwritten rules
kept within bounds what was called ``opposition research.'' The
typical investigator was a campaign worker or occasionally a
moonlighting police officer. Inquiries focused on public
information such as voting records and court cases.
</P>
<P>
   Those rules vanished after allegations of marital infidelity
drove Gary Hart out of the race for president in 1988. Campaigns
veered into nastier and more personal areas, and as they did,
professional investigators replaced the amateurs and techniques got
more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy offered a rationale for hiring private investigators to
scrutinize his most recent opponent, Mitt Romney. ``Opposition
research is part of the modern campaign process,'' said a
spokesman, Will Keyser. ``In 1994, Sen. Kennedy's record was an
open book and his opponent's was largely unknown. It was important
and appropriate for the campaign to conduct thorough research into
all the available public information.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Rollins, a veteran Republican political consultant who
acknowledges using private investigators, said, ``Most people today
are trying to find as much dirt as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   This demand for dirt in politics arises during a boom era for
private investigators in the business world. Started by the
corporate takeovers of the early 1980s and fueled by computers,
corporate investigators have become an essential part of the
information economy. The spillover into politics was natural.
</P>
<P>
   But the best-known firms from the world of corporate snooping
say they avoid the political arena for fear that fallout from the
cases would damage their reputations and antagonize better-paying
business clients.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few major firms that solicits political cases is
Investigative Group International, the Washington company run by
Terry Lenzner, a former Watergate prosecutor. Though best known as
an investigator for Clinton's lawyers, he has also worked for
Republicans, including former Rep. Michael Huffington in his losing
Senate race in California against Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Lenzner created a division called Campaign
Facts to specialize in political investigations. He also maintains
a tiny law firm, Terry F. Lenzner PC, which several former
employees said is used partly to provide politically sensitive
inquiries an extra layer of confidentiality through attorney-client
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Lenzner was subpoenaed by Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel, to testify before a grand jury about inquiries
into Clinton's critics and two of Starr's prosecutors. Lenzner said
he was not a target of the grand jury but, stung by the
controversy, now even he is considering cutting back on political
work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lenzner said political cases represent only a
fraction of the firm's revenue, though he defended such work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I perceive it to be analogous to a hostile takeover case where
we are hired by a company to gather information to convince
shareholders to vote for our client,'' he said. ``You are looking
at substantive issues that are relevant to the voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, the House Judiciary chairman, turned to a private
detective when a critic was trying to draw attention to his role in
a failed savings and loan.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the detective, Ernie Rizzo, a former police
officer in a Chicago suburb, provided details of his work for Hyde
for the first time _ and described his disdain for politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are the easiest people in the world to set up,''
Rizzo said. ``They're all whores. You stay with them for a week and
you'll catch them doing something _ women or money or something.
Forget about the millions spent in political campaigns. You don't
need that. Everybody got to the top by stepping over somebody. Find
the weakest link and attack it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo, as a lone operator, is typical of detectives who handle
political work. A character who would be at home in a Damon Runyon
story, he is outgoing and flashy; his holographic business card is
emblazoned with the image of a spy and six phone numbers, including
one for his boat.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo said he was hired in late 1995 by James Schirott, a lawyer
defending Hyde in a federal suit against him and other former
directors of Clyde Federal Savings and Loan. The thrift's 1990
failure cost taxpayers $67 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schirott, he said, told him the congressman was concerned about
a man turning up at hearings on the suit. Hyde wanted to know who
he was and what he knew. The lawyer gave Rizzo a name, Tim
Anderson, and an address in Libertyville, a suburb of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I did was I pulled phone records,'' Rizzo
explained. ``I saw Anderson was making 30 or 40 calls a day to the
media. I told Hyde, but he still didn't know who he was. I saw the
media calls, so I decided to pretend I was from the media.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he telephoned Anderson, claiming to be a producer for
``20/20,'' the ABC news program. Anderson agreed to meet him near
O'Hare International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a target's phone records is often the starting point of
an inquiry, investigators say. While Rizzo was convicted of illegal
wiretapping in 1977 for taping conversations in divorce cases,
privacy experts say phone records fall into a gray area in most
states. Rizzo said he got the records from a source at a telephone
company, and the Illinois attorney general's office said no state
law was violated.
</P>
<P>
   A former banking consultant, Anderson had contacted dozens of
journalists trying to expose what he believed were the political
roots of the savings and loan scandal. Anderson said he gladly gave
Rizzo his material on Hyde _ a bound file containing 388 pages of
court records, newspaper articles and documents obtained through
the Freedom of Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents were minutes of Clyde federal board meetings
that showed Hyde playing a more active role than he had
acknowledged publicly. In one instance, he approved an investment
in speculative options trading that eventually lost $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo, however, also wanted to know about Anderson, especially
any vulnerabilities he had. So, the detective said: ``I warned him
that Hyde was going to come after us and I had to make sure he
didn't have any skeletons. I got him telling me all his weak
spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo said he gave the file to Hyde and was paid by a political
ally of the congressman, not by his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, The Chicago Tribune disclosed Rizzo's duping of
Anderson. In his interview with The Times, Rizzo revealed that just
two months later, in December, he employed the technique again
because Hyde and his allies feared Anderson might use the
disclosure to disrupt the impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day before the impeachment trial started in the House, I
sent two guys back in,'' Rizzo said. ``They posed as reporters. We
wanted to know if Anderson was going to sue Hyde or make any other
noise. But he told them he wasn't going to sue. He was on a
crusade. It was hilarious.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde refused to be interviewed for this article, but a spokesman
disputed several aspects of Rizzo's account.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, Sam Stratman, said Hyde was told that Anderson
had been investigated, but that Rizzo did not deliver his findings
to the congressman. Hyde never met Rizzo and had no knowledge of
his techniques, he said. Stratman said $2,000 of $20,000 in fees
paid to Schirott was for Rizzo's services. Schirott did not return
numerous phone calls from The Times over several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the federal government settled its suit with the former
Clyde federal directors for $850,000. Hyde maintained he had no
responsibility for the thrift's failure and he did not contribute
to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the congressman's investigation had strengthened
his resolve. ``I'm an innocent member of the public and the head of
the Judiciary Committee hired a detective to spy on me,'' he said
indignantly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
