<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-CHINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No secrets as U.S. prepares to meet China for Cup title
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Their emotions spent to an even greater
extent than their bodies, members of the U.S. women's soccer team
have just enough time to kick back before the Great Wall of a team
known as China enters their frame of reference.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from midfielder Michelle Akers' perpetually creaking
bones, the Americans are in relatively good physical shape going
into the Women's World Cup final showdown Saturday in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns of tournament organizers _ that there would be
plenty of empty Rose Bowl seats without the U.S. team playing for
the championship _ were alleviated as the dream matchup
materialized on Sunday. China crushed defending champion Norway
5-0, perhaps sending a message to an American team it has beaten
twice this year.
</P>
<P>
   A capacity crowd of more than 90,000 could be on hand to see if
both teams can match the thrills of their 1996 Olympic gold medal
match won by the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who had a light workout late Monday afternoon in
Southern California, resume full training today following a
draining 2-0 semifinal win over Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly took a toll on both teams,'' U.S. captain Carla
Overbeck said. ``Every game has been physically and emotionally
exhausting for us. You could see a great sense of relief in that
locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one could use the rest more than the 33-year-old
Akers, who relentlessly hounded Brazilian star Sissi, got kicked in
the nose, received a huge gash in her thigh and scored the second
goal on a late penalty kick. She was also issued a yellow card
after dropping a pesky opponent in the final moments.
</P>
<P>
   But Akers, who needed a double IV afterward to combat the
effects of chronic fatigue syndrome, wouldn't have had it any other
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to the point where you get as beat up as that,
another dink is not going to stop you,'' she said. ``It's sweet and
you want to savor it. This World Cup has been a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest, and toughest battle yet looms. Chinese striker
Sun Wen and midfielder Liu Ailing, who have thrived against the
U.S., scored two goals apiece on Sunday. The Chinese have the
speed, skill and mental tenacity of the Americans, and the
confidence from winning twice in three meetings this year, most
recently a 2-1 victory at Giants Stadium in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really want to play either one of them,'' U.S. coach
Tony DiCicco said before learning the outcome of the China-Norway
match. ``We're going to take a deep breath and prepare for the next
one.''
</P>
<P>
   And the anxiety of getting to the final, which U.S. players
admitted has been something of a distraction, is now behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy about this for now,'' forward Mia Hamm said. ``We
are where we've wanted to be. We're going to Pasadena.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
