<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-FOREIGN-AID-465&AMP;     07-05 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-FOREIGN-AID-465&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPARTING OFFICIAL SAYS PRESENT AID CUTS MAY CREATE FUTURE CRISES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The departing director of the government's major
foreign aid agency has criticized the Clinton administration for
allowing itself to be ``pushed around'' by Congress and warned that
congressionally-mandated cuts in foreign aid had created a crisis
for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, the director, J. Brian Atwood, took advantage of
his imminent departure as administrator of the Agency for
International Development to offer an unusually harsh assessment of
the administration and Congress, faulting them for an aid budget
that he called dangerously inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a crisis,'' said Atwood, who steps down on Friday
after six years at AID, which oversees economic and humanitarian
aid programs. ``There are a lot of people around the world who
depend on the United States, and we are just a very uncertain
trumpet right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a larger budget to help struggling nations, he said,
``you'll see democracies being defeated and radical leaders coming
into office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly,'' Atwood added, ``you could see more countries
becoming anarchies in Africa. You certainly could see that as a
possibility in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton administration, the overall budget has declined,
from $14.1 billion in 1993, when Clinton took office, to $13.7
billion this year, a decline that is more dramatic when inflation
is factored in. The Agency for International Development staff has
been cut in that period one-third, to 7,000.
</P>
<P>
   A bill that the Senate passed on July 1 would reduce the budget
by an additional 6 percent next year, to $12.9 billion. The United
States spends less on foreign aid as a percentage of its gross
national product than any other developed nation.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, a former career diplomat who has long been affiliated
with the Democratic Party, said the White House and State
Department understood the need for a larger aid budget, and he
praised Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the administration had overall not been willing to
put up enough of a fight against the Republican leadership in
Congress to restore money cut from the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have allowed ourselves to be pushed around too much,'' he
said. ``I wish that we had expended more political capital.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House had no comment on Atwood's remarks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Atwood also offered pointed criticism of Jesse Helms, the North
Carolina Republican who heads the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, accusing him of ``a negative exercise of power'' that
has hindered American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   He also contended that a fringe of conservative lawmakers had
taken control of American policy toward the United Nations,
resulting in the United States' owing an estimated $1 billion in
back dues.
</P>
<P>
   Many U.N. critics in Congress, Atwood said, practice ``backdoor
isolationism'' and ``didn't have a passport and bragged about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, Atwood withdrew his nomination to become ambassador to
Brazil, saying that it was clear that Helms would never allow his
committee to consider the nomination. The two men had clashed over
Atwood's success in blocking the senator's plans to merge the
Agency for International Development into the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ```I don't feel any malice toward Jesse Helms,'' Atwood said.
``I'm a fatalist about things, so I'm not angry in that sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Atwood said that he had decided to speak out critically,
because ``I'm passionately concerned about the direction the world
is heading.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we've become complacent,'' he said. ``And I believe
a large part of it is because of a failure of American
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Helms, Marc Thiessen, had no comment on the
criticism. ``We wish him well in all his future endeavors,''
Thiessen said of Atwood.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Atwood said it was startling that, at a time of historic
prosperity here, economic research indicates that the world's poor
are actually losing ground. He pointed to statistics that the ratio
of rich to poor around the world is 65 to 1, or for every $65
earned in industrial countries, $1 is earned in poor ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're fat and happy,'' he said of the United
States. ``And we're growing very complacent, because we think we
hear a lot about the democratic revolutions around the world. But
what we don't hear about is this growing gap between rich and poor.
And that is a poisonous mix. That is going to create crises in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood was also critical of the administration for not having
done more to defend the United Nations on Capitol Hill and to fight
for the full repayment of the back dues. The Senate has passed a
bill to repay $800 million in arrears in exchange for a commitment
that the United States will reduce its overall contribution to the
regular U.N. budget, from 25 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use the word unconscionable,'' he said of the government's
treatment of the United Nations,'' the official said, adding that
the cuts forced on the United Nations had wreaked serious damage,
notably to the Office of the High Commissioner for Refugees.
Atwood, who oversaw American humanitarian relief efforts in the
crisis in Kosovo, said the high commissioner's office had provided
``very bad leadership'' in the early weeks of the crisis, when
hundreds of thousands of Albanian refugees fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UNHCR was not doing its job in the early days,'' he said.
``They didn't have the resources. They didn't have the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I say that their management failure was the direct result of
our failures in providing them with resources,'' Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Groves, a spokeswoman for the high commissioner,
acknowledged that ``there were major problems in the early days''
of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We admit there were weaknesses,'' she said. ``I think that at
base you have to look at resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
