<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japan's Executives Say Business Mood Improves
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese central bank's quarterly assessment of business
sentiment showed that the perception of business conditions among
more than 9,000 executives who responded in June was still
negative, but improving. But the survey's so-called diffusion index
remained solidly negative, meaning that pessimistic executives
still widely outnumbered optimists. The benchmark Nikkei index of
225 Japanese stocks rose 1.13 percent, to 18,135.06 _ its highest
close in 21 months.
</P>
<P>
   Right Address, Return to Sender
</P>
<P>
   A new regulation from the U.S. Postal Service that requires
holders of private mail boxes to include the prefix p.m.B. in their
address has prompted a flurry of indignant letters to Congress. The
regulations also require box holders to submit their home addresses
to the post office. Around two million Americans rent boxes at
10,000 stores such as Pakmail and Mail Boxes Etc., often to lend
their business addresses prestige, sometimes because they have no
fixed address. Store owners and mailbox renters say the new rules
invade their privacy and pose a financial threat to their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   NTT Plans Global Effort
</P>
<P>
   Jun-ichiro Miyazu, the head of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone,
intends to use a new law to transform Japan's telecommunications
giant into a global player to battle with the likes of AT&AMP;T. The
new law, which took effect July 1 after a decade of dithering in
Japan's Parliament, reshapes NTT and permits it for the first time
to compete directly in overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet Profits, but Loses
</P>
<P>
   Cnet was one of the very first companies to build a business on
the World Wide Web, but it has rarely benefited from the special
dispensations that investors accord most Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bid for General Nutrition
</P>
<P>
   Royal Numico, Europe's top baby-food maker, said it was offering
$2.5 billion to buy General Nutrition Cos. as it sought to become
the global leader in specialized foods. Numico has been growing
through acquisitions, and said it saw the best opportunities in
nutritional supplements. Together with General Nutrition, Numico
will have $3 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   20 Questions for Madison Avenue
</P>
<P>
   Keith Richards a film critic? And 19 other questions about the
advertising business.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta's Top Bankruptcy Lawyer
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's new bankruptcy law _ designed by the International
Monetary Fund to give creditors a legal cudgel to force the
country's deeply indebted and well-connected corporate elite to pay
up _ has brought considerable success to one lawyer in particular.
</P>
<P>
   New Problem for Coke in Europe
</P>
<P>
   Faint traces of fungicide have been found on five cans of
Coca-Cola, the Ministry of Agriculture in the southwest German
state of Baden-Wuerttemberg said. Separate tests showed that
bacteria found in samples of a mineral water bottled by Coca-Cola
in Poland was not hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Markets Reopen
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States reopen Tuesday after being closed Monday in observance of
the Fourth of July. Most overseas markets were open Monday. Among
foreign stock market indexes, Russia's has had the strongest
performance so far this year, with a gain of 113 percent in dollar
terms in the first half. Belgium and Colombia were the laggards,
with declines of 21 percent. On Monday, the story on European
markets was oil, as crude oil surged in commodity trading in London
and Total Fina's bid for Elf Acquitaine lifted French stocks. Asian
markets were also higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
