<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9854 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ART-(TR     07-05 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AND RUSSIA RESOLVE DISPUTE OVER CHAIN OF COMMAND IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS with MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO and Russian military commanders resolved their
differences over Russia's role in the peacekeeping operation in
Kosovo on Monday, clearing the way for about 3,600 more Russian
troops to arrive in the Serbian province after weeks of wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   The first planeloads of Russian paratroopers could begin
arriving as soon as Tuesday at Kosovo's main airport west of the
capital, Pristina, alliance and Russian officials said. There they
will join several hundred Russian troops who have hunkered down
there since they entered Serbia on June 12, beating NATO
peacekeepers by hours.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four days, NATO effectively grounded the next
incoming Russian paratroopers by persuading Hungary, Bulgaria and
Romania to deny Russia permission to fly through their airspace, a
move that rattled the already uneasy relations between the alliance
and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia signed an agreement in Helsinki,
Finland, on June 18 to integrate the Russians into NATO's
operation. But the precise manner of how and where they would
operate and how they would report to NATO commanders became mired
in confusion, dispute and, some NATO officials suspected, intrigue
within the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   The military issues were settled Monday after two days of talks
in Moscow involving senior military officials for each side, led by
Russian Vice Adm. Valentin Kuznetsov, a senior official in the
defense ministry, and German Gen. Dieter Stockmann, who is chief of
staff to NATO's commander, Gen. Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there are absolutely no military obstacles for the
deployment of the Russians,'' a NATO official in Brussels said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The final disputes involved the Russians' place in NATO's chain
of command and the exact areas within the American, German and
French sectors in Kosovo where the Russian troops would operate.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians agreed, with great reluctance, officials said, to
serve under the nominal control of the allied commanders of each
sector where they will operate: American, German and French
generals and, in the case of the airport, a British one. But the
Russians reserved the right to refuse to carry out orders.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders also sought but did not get permission to
send troops into the Italian sector, which would have altered
boundaries that had been negotiated in painstaking detail.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difficulty in the talks stemmed from the fact that
after the Helsinki agreement, for reasons that are not clear, each
side had different maps showing different areas of operations for
Russia's troops, a Clinton administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the sense they were trying to reopen the Helsinki map,
but they essentially agreed to the map,'' the official said.
``There was just a little bit of confusion over what map.''
</P>
<P>
   For Russia, the involvement of its troops in making peace in
Kosovo has considerable significance, at home and abroad. After
Russia could do little to stop NATO's air war against Yugoslavia,
its traditional ally, the Russian deployment, beginning with the
surprise occupation of the airport, was seen as a boost to the
military's standing.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are also eager to do what they can to help the
Serbs, who have cultural, religious and historic links to Russia.
The areas within Kosovo where the Russians are to patrol include
those where there have been concentrations of Serbs, many of whom
have fled in the wake of violent retribution by Kosovo's Albanian
majority.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Russia is ultimately to send up to 1,000 troops to the German
sector in the southwestern part of Kosovo, 600 to 800 to the
American sector in the southeast, and another 600 to 800 to the
French sector in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Within the French sector, the Russians wanted to operate in the
northern city of Mitrovica, where Serbs are trying to declare a
``Serbian zone'' to block the return of Albanians. NATO's
negotiators rejected that, the alliance officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A contingent of 750 Russians will occupy the province's main
airport in Slatina, near Pristina, providing maintenance and
security; NATO forces will control air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With the Russians, the total peacekeeping force will eventually
total nearly 59,000. More than three weeks into the peacekeeping
mission, the NATO allies, along with a handful of other countries,
have sent in only about 29,000.
</P>
<P>
   The talks in Moscow dragged on for seven hours Monday and seven
hours on Sunday. And Russian and NATO officials said that despite
their agreement, they are likely to encounter more differences in
operational details in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   One possible area of future dispute is dual commands; under the
agreement, a parallel Russian chain of command will be established,
one that includes liaison officers in each sector, at NATO
headquarters in Kosovo, in Italy and at NATO's military
headquarters in Mons, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the structure was not all that different from the
arrangement for American troops, who operate under the British
officer in charge in Kosovo, Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, but
ultimately answer only to the American commander-in-chief,
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO's insistence, the agreement specifies that any sector
commander can send other peacekeepers into the Russian areas of
operation to carry out any order the Russians refuse to follow, the
officials said. NATO leaders had feared that without such language,
the Russian areas could be seen as de facto enclaves for the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for an example of the type of order the Russians might not
carry out, the administration official cited the arrest of Serbs
accused of committing war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Russian refuse an order,'' the official said, ``the
commanders will be able to order somebody else to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
