<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Immigration Counseling and Outreach Services, a nonprofit
agency assisting low income individuals with applications to the
INS, needs a newish computer (133 MHz processor) and laser printer
(at least 12 pages a minute). Donations are tax deductible (and can
be applied towards the donor's karma credit). _ Terri English
</P>
<P>
   A: Who can resist that kind of payoff? Readers , if you have
been itching to do good, here is your chance. Call executive
director English with your computer donations at (512) 451-8450.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My mom passed away leaving my younger sister and me as
co-executors of her will. My younger sister had durable power of
attorney to pay my mom's bills. She says there is no need to
probate the will, because her name is on all of mom's accounts and
the house was gifted to her. Is it legal not to probate a will and
have my sister divide up mom's accounts? Isn't a gifted house
taxable to my sister? As co-executor what are my responsibilities?
_ M.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Under limited circumstances, if all family members with an
interest in the estate enter into a settlement agreement, it is not
necessary to have the will admitted to probate,'' advises attorney
Tom Barton, board certified in state planning and probate law.
However, you sound somewhat suspicious of your sister's actions, so
you should have the will admitted to probate. A co-executor has the
authority to investigate the circumstances surrounding the alleged
gift of your mother's home, as well as any transactions entered
into by your sister on behalf of your mother. If your mother made a
valid gift of her home, it will not be ``taxable'' to your sister,
but it will be necessary to file a gift tax return reporting the
gift in the appropriate calendar year. No federal gift tax would be
due unless your mother previously made other significant gifts. Q:
What can I do to discourage the onslaught of slugs and snails _
especially around the dogs' food bowls? _ V.L. Hall
</P>
<P>
   A: For a natural approach, the Herb Bar recommends placing a jar
lid of beer near the bowl to divert the critters. Given a choice,
snails and slugs prefer brewskie to H2O. However, should you notice
Fido also prefers the beer, you may have to use salt or
diatomaceous earth near the bowl. Unfortunately, DE and salt are
ineffective when wet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My boys are itching for a Dallas Stars championship T-shirt!
The Stars Web page does not have T-shirts for sale _ a catalog, but
no mention of Stanley Cup merchandise. Help! They have watched the
Stars for years and stayed up till the very last game. Now they
won't let me rest until I find one. _ Monica Canestaro-Darby
</P>
<P>
   A: The NHL Web site has them. Surf over to www.nhl.com and check
out the product line: T-shirts to caps to a slice of the ice (1999
Stanley Cup Championship Clinching Game ice melted down and stored
in the clear plastic puck for a mere $39.99 _ hey, I do not make
this stuff up). Or, call (972) 831-2487. Either way, expect a long
delay before your memorabilia arrives, warns merchandising
assistant Leslie Turner. Demand. Demand. Demand. You San Antonio
Spurs fans, note apparel page http://store.nba.com or call (800)
711-3879.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the address of Lady Bird Johnson's daughter _ the one
who is married to Ian Turpin? (Lynda or Luci?) I want to ask her to
ask her mother to autograph a photo.
</P>
<P>
   _ J. Allison
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the younger daughter of President Johnson, Luci
Baines Johnson, in care of KLBJ radio, a Johnson family enterprise,
8309 N. IH 35, Austin, TX 78753. Contact Jane Greig, author of
``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
