<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9859 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN06-COX     07-05 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wet whiners: The natural order returns
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ There are fewer kinds of rain in Central
Florida than in most places.
</P>
<P>
   This is a true fact, but you will have to take my word on it. I
can cite no study and know of no commission on raindrops. But see
if this doesn't square with your observations. Take your time,
though. Don't base it on one or two soggy afternoons. This could
take all summer.
</P>
<P>
   You will find that rain in Central Florida is a lot like a
malfunctioning bathroom spigot I used to wrestle with in an old
apartment. It either sprayed like a fire hose or stubbornly refused
to do anything. All the way on or shut off. Binary weather.
</P>
<P>
   I have lived in places where there were 28 kinds of rain, much
of it wimpy and indecisive. You got specks-on-the-windshield sun
showers, mere morning mists or winter drizzles.
</P>
<P>
   In those climes, you look hard at the spots on the sidewalk to
make sure you are being rained upon. No such questions confuse the
Florida pedestrian. If the parking lot hasn't flooded, it hasn't
rained. If your brakes work right away, it hasn't rained. Big rain
in big drops or nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, it was nothing. A bigger nothing than
anyone had seen for years.
</P>
<P>
   That was the summer of brown lawns in town and fire in the
forest. For more than a month, the sky regularly turned a garish
mix of pink and black. The woods around Interstate 95 looked like
the exit ramp to Hell's outer circles.
</P>
<P>
   In Daytona Beach, even the Pepsi 400, stock-car racing's sacred
solstice, was moved to the fall. The natural order was unhinged.
Summer across Florida disappeared in a cloud of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   That seems like a very long time ago. These are events that have
passed from CNN to the History Channel.
</P>
<P>
   I drive past the old fire zones these days and they shine green
in the wet. The palmettos, vines and ground brush have taken over
from the pines and stretch for miles. Their vibrant and excessive
green has taken over from the more muted and tasteful color schemes
of pine forests. Clumps of survivor trees huddle in small, defeated
groups and old, charred wood remains standing here and there like
the masts of shipwrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year ago, this same place was a still-smoldering charcoal
sketch in blacks and grays. It was astounding how fast the green
took over.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the drive down this road seems longer now that large
chunks of forest have been erased. A comforting curtain of pine
used to hide the sad reality of encroaching new development, new
roads nearby, and the closeness of nearby traffic. Signs that warn
of impending gas stations and land for sale ominously popped up
after the charred timber was cleared.
</P>
<P>
   You drive out into this bright green open and the journey seems
longer because now you can see for miles.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not much for this open road. A tunnel through the trees
confers the comforting illusion of being miles from town. It fools
you into thinking you are really traveling. Actually going
somewhere, instead of merely schlepping across town.
</P>
<P>
   These flat miles of green only look like a ruin if you remember
what was there before.
</P>
<P>
   To a traveler, to someone who has forgotten the fire summer,
this looks like a fairly typical Florida roadscape.
</P>
<P>
   And it is easy to forget. People have been grousing about
steady, hard and regular afternoon rains. I feel simple-minded for
being thankful for it. For viewing with stupid satisfaction the
steam that comes off hot pavement in the drops of a downpour.
</P>
<P>
   Very bad things have to happen before people are grateful for
something as simple as rain. Which is why it is well to remember
what folks in this part of the state were doing this time last
year. Back when the interstates were jammed with evacuees. Back
when the area seemed like a firefighters' convention. Back when the
hardware stores were selling out of filter masks and air cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   If you have forgotten those events, you're likely to whine about
rain-outs over the 4th of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After a year, rain is once again an inconvenience and no longer
a deliverance. People are whining about the wet again. Which is how
things should be. Which is the natural order restored.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
