<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dreaming of a washtub on a hot summer day
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It was hot when I crawled into the hammock
last night, and it was still hot when I rolled out this morning.
That's where I sleep in warm weather _ in the treetops in a hammock
_ on an upstairs back porch that I had screened a few summers ago
to take advantage of cool northern nights.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past couple of days, the sun, usually little more
than a benign alarm clock or an occasional clothes dryer, has
become my enemy. It is relentless in its daily attempts to fry my
brains, and as the temperature soars, so does my annoyance level.
</P>
<P>
   This morning when the fireball's first rays spit into my
sleep-stuck eyes, I woke up overheated and swearing. Not a good way
to begin the day, I decided, so I lingered for a moment to have a
talk with myself.
</P>
<P>
   Self: Why are you so crabby?
</P>
<P>
   Crab: Because I'm HOT!
</P>
<P>
   Self: Big deal. You grew up in south Florida before air
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Crab: It's not supposed to be (SET ITAL)this(END ITAL) hot (SET
ITAL)this(END ITAL) far north.
</P>
<P>
   Self: Aww, get over it. Why not do what you did as a kid to keep
cool?
</P>
<P>
   Crab: You've got to be kidding. I don't even have a washtub.
</P>
<P>
   Bettye Harris and I grew up next door to each other in Miami. We
were the same age and went to the same school. We liked the same
music, the same food, and on occasion, even the same boy. And
Bettye had a washtub.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the old days (mid- to late-'40s), before slick
developers had folks believing that a house was not a home without
a swimming pool in the back yard, the typical south Florida place
came pool-less as well as central heat- and air conditioning-less.
There was an ocean for swimming, a sun for heat (we even used solar
panels for hot water), and come evening, the open windows let in a
welcome breeze. That was nature and we pretty much left it alone.
</P>
<P>
   But for little kids, it wasn't enough. We wanted the beach in
our back yards. We had a canal, but of course we weren't allowed to
swim in it because it had snakes, gators, and a swift current. It
was, after all, run-off from the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Venetial Pool was beautiful but too long a bike ride, and the
ocean was a bus and jitney away, so until we were older, those
options were out of the question. We had to make do with what we
had _ and that was usually the Harris's old washtub.
</P>
<P>
   Lazy afternoons, Bettye and I would be kicked back somewhere in
the shade, wishing we were 16 and had curly hair, when one of us
would come up with the idea. ``Wanna' play in the washtub?'' That
was our signal to spring into action. Bettye would head for her
dad's old slat-house and come dragging the galvanized tub across
the lawn by one handle. I'd pull over our garden hose, the one
connected to the well my father had dug for watering the yard. That
way we could let our ``ocean'' run without being reminded by our
parents that we weren't buying stock in the City of Miami's water
department. While the tub filled, we ran home for bathing suits and
towels.
</P>
<P>
   With a striped beach towel and an unlimited imagination, we'd
manage to turn our side yards into South Beach _ the place where
really cool high school kids with jalopies hung out making awkward
boy-girl talk and building human pyramids on the sand. As Bettye
and I folded ourselves into the washtub, arms and legs dangling
over the side into the itchy broadleaf St. Augustine grass, we'd
talk about what we imagined life would be like in three or four
years when we were old enough to ride in boys' cars and be a part
of the beach scene. We must have been quite a sight _ two scrawny
kids curled up in a No. 9 tub beating the heat and dreaming of a
life far beyond its rim.
</P>
<P>
   Today is plenty hot enough and I can't help wondering if one of
my friends has a washtub to fit. I'd supply the dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
