<SLUG> BC-Y2K-GEEWAX-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Global stomachache awaits
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This used to be a dangerous time of year for stomachs.
Backyard family reunions and church picnics often threatened
gastronomic health because Aunt Mabel would set out her potato
salad in the warm sun while grandpa was busy undercooking the
hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   But because of growing awareness of food poisoning, most people
now know to put the mayo dishes back in the cooler and scorch the
burgers until they're black.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, our food worries are far from over. In fact, in
the next century, we may face even more digestive threats because
of several factors, including the expanding global food trade,
rising use of pesticides, mass processing of meats and increasing
reliance on genetic manipulation of seeds and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Food safety was simpler 50 years ago when most Americans stuck
to diets centered around meat, potatoes, peas and carrots. Milk was
produced on local dairy farms and no one expected to eat fresh
strawberries in January.
</P>
<P>
   But our food choices have been expanding as more people have
moved here from Latin America, Asia, Africa and the Caribbean,
bringing with them a taste for different kinds of fruits, fishes,
vegetables and spices. With Thai restaurants now opening in
suburban shopping centers and salsa replacing ketchup as the most
popular condiment, even Mayflower descendents are switching from
pot roasts to ``foreign'' foods.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, rising affluence has spurred the demand for
imports. Not so long ago, slicing a banana into a bowl of cereal
was something of a luxury. Today, many consumers think nothing of
spending several extra dollars at the grocery store to brighten up
a winter breakfast of hot oatmeal with fresh berries from Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   In response to such demands, U.S. food importers are buying
massive quantities of grapes from Chile, cheeses from France, apple
juice from China, strawberries from Mexico and so on. Already
imports account for about a fifth of all we consume; experts expect
that figure to rise as more sophisticated communications systems
help link food producers with grocers.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, along with this increase in imports, we have seen
a rise in poisonings. In recent years, food-borne illnesses have
been traced to cantaloupes, raspberries and scallions from Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   But growers in poorer countries aren't the only ones who create
potential dangers. As the recent health-scare involving Coca-Cola
demonstrated, Europeans are deeply concerned about products they
perceive as ``American.'' They especially don't want to consume our
Made-in-the-USA genetically altered tomatoes or our growth-hormone
laden beef. Europeans consider much of what we eat to be unnatural
``Frankenstein food.''
</P>
<P>
   They also have good reason to fear U.S. pesticides. Consumers
Union, a nonprofit watchdog group, recently found that when it
compared foreign and American produce using USDA databases from
1994 to 1997, the U.S. crops almost always had higher levels of
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   In the new century, consumers enjoying the benefits of the
global grocery store of the techno age may well end up exposing
themselves to more pesticides, hormones, bacteria and genetically
altered foods.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most important issues for world leaders to settle in
coming years will be the development of global systems to oversee
the uniform labeling of food products, the settling of scientific
disagreements about health risks and the inspection of foods.
</P>
<P>
   All of that will be complicated and expensive, but will remain a
far better alternative to going back to green beans and meatloaf.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
