<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AltaVista opened new world that kept changing too fast
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Oh AltaVista, we hardly knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista (www.altavista.com) is the search engine purchased
last week by Massachusetts investment group CMGI from Compaq for
$2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista was around long before The New York Post was calling
CMGI Chairman David Wetherell the Warren Buffett of the Internet.
It was there long before Wetherell was holding press conferences
announcing plans to use AltaVista as a platform to showcase CMGI's
other Internet holdings. Yes, AltaVista was something besides an
annoying portal site that the cash-strapped computer company wanted
to unload. It was one of the first search engines that really,
truly searched the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by a group of engineers at Boston-based Digital
Equipment Corp., AltaVista debuted in the mid-'90s to an awestruck
audience of Web surfers. A columnist for the online 'zine Suck
(www.suck.com) raved about the joys of typing in the names of
long-lost friends and having the search engine turn up more
information than she could have found had she hired a private
dectective.
</P>
<P>
   Before it became common for a typical Internet search to turn up
20,000 entries to match even the most obscure topics, AltaVista was
turning up information and Web sites people didn't know existed.
AltaVista topped nearly everyone's bookmark list. Sometimes even
the totally unrelated personal home pages a search would turn up
were interesting.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine in 1999 how amazing it was to just type in
anything you wanted to find, anything you needed to know and have
this search engine track down not just two or three but thousands
of Web sites. In those days, it was quantity, not quality that
mattered, and AltaVista got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   But the Web experienced growing pains, and so did AltaVista. The
folks at Digital bought the rights to use the name AltaVista from a
software company in California, which shrewdly sold the computer
maker everything but the Web address, www.altavista.com. Because of
this, the search engine was forced to use the Web address
www.altavista
</P>
<P>
   .digital.com. Meanwhile, AltaVista the software maker was
gathering up millions of hits from innocent users looking for the
hot new search engine. Eventually Digital filed a lawsuit. The
results of that suit are obvious each time you type in
AltaVista.com and get the search engine, not a software company.
</P>
<P>
   Nifty as AltaVista was, times began to change. Business on the
Web is a little like the weather in New England _ if you don't like
it, just wait a minute. In 1997, a smallish search engine called
Lycos took a considerable amount of floor space at Internet World
in New York to demonstrate a new version of its search engine that
would return what it determined were the best sites on any specific
topic instead of every last site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants 30 million Web sites about the New York Knicks?''
they asked. ``What you need is three really good sites about the
New York Knicks.'' As it turned out, Lycos and Yahoo! and Snap and
all the search engines that followed began to direct users to sites
that were picked by people, not by a computer keyword search.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the novelty of AltaVista's pages of searches began to wear
thin. Digital's intital refusal to accept advertising on the site
while Yahoo! was loading a banner advertisement on nearly every
page didn't help much. While Yahoo! was establishing itself as one
of the hottest sites on the Web to search and to do business,
AltaVista was going nowhere fast.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being somewhat behind the curve as the search engine
evolved into a ``portal site'' that promised to do everything for
the user except make dinner, AltaVista remained one of the top
sites on the Web. In May 1999, it was the 10th most popular site,
according to Web measurement firm Media Metrix, thanks in part to
the eventual addition of translation software and the typical
``sticky'' portal products such as shopping, yellow pages, e-mail
and stock quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell told reporters that AltaVista, under CMGI's
leadership, will become a ``megaportal.'' The site will put more
emphasis on online shopping and intelligent agent technology that
will help identify consumer habits in the hopes of sending them to
the goods and services they are most likely to want. Sound
familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, we thought so. It sounds like just about every other
Internet site from Yahoo! AltaVista is just going to be another
search engine vying for the eyeballs, ad dollars and disposable
income of the ever-growing Web-surfing public.
</P>
<P>
   The days of the geek-driven search engine are gone. It was
probably inevitable. Besides, who has the time to wade through
thousands of listings that may or may not contain the information
you need?
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see what CMGI has in store for
AltaVista as it gets a millennium face lift and showcases some of
the CMGI Web sites. The Web's big winners focus now on helping busy
people get things done. But the days of random searches for obsure
information aren't totally over _ there's still eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
