 &HT;    Feel the rhythm in new book
 &HT;    By Theresa Walsh Giarrusso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Trace the history of African-American music through
beautiful artwork in the book ``I See the Rhythm,'' with paintings
by Michele Wood and text by Toyomi Igus (Children's Book Press,
$15.95). Given the Coretta Scott King Award for outstanding
children's book, ``I See the Rhythm'' explores slave songs, the
blues, ragtime, jazz, bebop and hip hop. Vibrant illustrations take
you from Africa to New Orleans to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sing for us!
</P>
<P>
   If you think you're all that _ call us and prove it! We have
free tickets to Nickelodeon's All That Music &AMP; More Festival, which
will feature Monica, 98 Degrees and BWitched on July 14 at Lakewood
Amphitheatre. Just call 404-222-1887 and sing part of a song from
one of the artists listed above. Don't forget to leave your name,
age and phone number. Deadline for entry is Wednesday. You must be
7 to 14 to enter. Our judges will award the tickets Friday based on
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
