<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Screen time is big time
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ American kids spend more time watching television and
playing video and computer games than they do in school, a new
study says. On the average, children spend 4 1/2 hours every day in
front of a screen, which adds up to 1,642 hours a year. The average
child spends 1,000 hours in school each year.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that nearly half of all homes with kids ages 2
to 17 have at least one television, a VCR, video game equipment and
a home computer. Three out of every five children ages 12 to 17
have a TV set in their rooms. The national study was conducted by
the Annenberg Public Policy Center.
</P>
<P>
   Dole running for president
</P>
<P>
   Republican Elizabeth Dole threw her hat into the ring last week
to run for president next year. She is the first Republican woman
to run for that office.
</P>
<P>
   Dole has been the secretary of transportation, the secretary of
labor and president of the American Red Cross. Her husband, former
Sen. Bob Dole, ran unsuccessfully for president three times.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Republicans have entered the race so far. They include Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, former Vice President Dan Quayle, Sen. John
McCain from Arizona and magazine publisher Steve Forbes. Bush, the
son of former President Bush, is leading in polls and in
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Does Earth have a `twin'?
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere out there, the Earth may have a ``twin'' planet
capable of supporting life, according to a report in the journal
Nature.
</P>
<P>
   David Stevenson of the California Institute of Technology said
Earth may have had one or more siblings when the solar system was
born, but they were thrown far away by gravity when they got too
close to Jupiter or other large planets.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson said these Earth-like planets may be capable of
supporting life, despite their distance from the warmth of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists agree that planets probably were ejected from
the solar system. But they have no idea whether they could support
life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
