<SLUG> BC-PC-BUSINESS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Linking convenience to high-tech key for businesses
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the digitally intertwined future, when the
Internet is expected to beckon to us from everywhere all the time,
NCR Corp. may have a way to capitalize on those minutes wasted
while waiting for the microwave to heat leftover linguine.
</P>
<P>
   NCR's Microwave Bank would allow electronic banking and shopping
with a touch screen in the oven door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kitchen is often the most frequently used room and
provides a versatile environment that is no stranger to
sophisticated consumer products,'' NCR's Knowledge Lab explains.
``We are exploring the evolution of one of the most familiar
devices in the kitchen _ the microwave.''
</P>
<P>
   Still in the testing phase, this convergence of old and new
appliances symbolizes the novel approaches companies are
considering to cash in on what PC visionary Michael Dell predicts
will be an ``information-addicted'' populace.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap and convenient devices will turn the masses into
digiterati, a term for well-equipped users, who will be able to buy
and sell stock, update the grocery list, avoid traffic jams, and
check weather, sports scores and e-mail while miles from their
personal computer back home.
</P>
<P>
   It's about connected convenience, say industry experts, and the
winners will be those products that conform to users' wants and
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In less than five years there will be more non-PC devices than
PCs connected to the Web,'' predicted Ann Marie Deroux, director of
IBM Corp.'s speech-recognition division.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of how different high-tech industries are addressing
the dawning of the Post PC Era:
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications and Internet Service
</P>
<P>
   In the post-PC era, the services and content of computer
networks, especially the Internet, become more important than the
devices that tie into the network.
</P>
<P>
   With that ``network-centric'' approach to the future, companies
involved in making communications equipment, providing
communications services or delivering Internet content are
preparing for a big surge in business.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what a few of the big players are doing:
</P>
<P>
   _Cisco Systems and other network equipment makers are rushing to
build the equipment that runs tomorrow's high-speed, Internet-based
communications networks that will handle both voice and data.
</P>
<P>
   _Internet giants America Online Inc. and Prodigy Communications
Corp. are making deals with key allies. Last week, both companies
began offering free computers to customers who agree to pay for
extended Internet service. AOL has also signed a deal to invest
$1.5 billion with Hughes Electronics to enhance the marketing of
high-speed Internet access by satellite. A Hughes subsidiary,
DirecPC, delivers Internet service by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   _Big telecom companies are jockeying for position. AT&AMP;T Corp.,
for instance, recently acquired two major cable systems, Media One
Group and Tele-Communications Inc. With the deals, AT&AMP;T is in
position to deliver local phone service, high-speed Internet
service, long-distance service and television programming all in
one package.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
