<HEADER>
A9868 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PC-CONSUMER06-COX     07-05 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PC-CONSUMER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet connections computer makers' new focus
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Bill Goins' laptop computer was a seemingly
indispensable tool.
</P>
<P>
   He lugged the Apple PowerBook 2400 across the country on
business trips, keeping in touch with his office via e-mail,
checking his calendar for meeting schedules and checking a database
for the phone numbers of business contacts.
</P>
<P>
   But when his laptop was stolen from an Idaho hotel room several
months ago, Goins had something to take its place, a brand-new
machine that fits in the palm of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   His new Palm VII hand-held computer _ which fits into a category
of products called personal digital assistants _ provides almost
everything his laptop did. With it, he has wireless access to the
Internet, e-mail, news headlines, meeting schedules, phone numbers
and even airline information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no longer tethered to that ball and chain that was my
computer,'' said Goins, who is part of a test group for the Palm
VII. The device won't be sold nationally until later this year.
``With this, I can do the majority of what I do in the office
wherever I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Change is sweeping through the computer industry and users like
Goins are in the vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Personal computers _ be they desktops or laptops _ are still a
necessary part of life. But their role in the digital world is
changing.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, tech companies are focusing not on the machines,
but how they connect to the increasingly ubiquitous Internet. And
as hand-held computers and similar devices become more common, more
users like Goins will be untethering themselves from their old PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers predict that hand-held computer device sales will
increase by a dizzying 47 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, traditional PCs' sales are expected to increase
by about 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the newest Internet-access tools look like Goins'
hand-held device. Wireless phones now allow Internet access. Pagers
can send e-mail. And in the future, look for everything from
kitchen appliances to automobiles connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   New PC alternative devices are expected to be used in 18 million
households by 2003, according to Forrester Research, of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Technology executives say what the numbers don't.
</P>
<P>
   IBM Chief Executive Louis Gerstner wrote shareholders in this
year's annual report that ``The PC Era is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems Chairman Scott McNealey calls it the start of
the Post PC Era.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, in a move that spoke louder than words, CompUSA
Inc. Chief Executive James Halpin announced that the Dallas-based
retailer would start selling more PDAs and other portable devices
and fewer lower-profit PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone buys the idea that the PC is going to subside in
importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that the PC is going away is a bunch of B.S.,''
Michael Dell, who founded the world's most profitable PC company,
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   But even Round Rock-based Dell Computer Corp. is changing the
way it does business.
</P>
<P>
   Dell today is emphasizing the Internet capabilities of its
computers. It is pushing harder than ever for alliances with
companies that deliver high-speed Internet access, and it will
deliver more consumer services, products and technical support over
the Net. Dell is also following rival Gateway 2000 in creating its
own Internet delivery service for customers.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent meeting with analysts, Michael Dell predicted just
how important the ongoing Internet revolution will be to his
company.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 years, he predicted, 1.4 billion PCs will function not as
desktops, but as servers for 14 billion Internet devices ranging
from hand-held computers to televisions. That would equate to about
two devices for everyone on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of the changing PC business, last week two major
providers of Internet access, America Online Inc. and Prodigy
Communications Corp., announced that they would offer consumers
free PCs _ if they agree to sign up for extended online service
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Services are eclipsing products,'' said Eric Schmitt, an
analyst with Forrester Research. ``The Internet-related service
over the wire is becoming more valuable than the hardware at the
end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Rob Enderle, an industry analyst at Giga Information Group
Inc.: ``We are at the front end of the most significant change that
has occurred in the computer industry since the emergence of the
PC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of turns the computer hardware industry on its ear.''
</P>
<P>
   A new era Crucial to the post-PC era are high-speed computer
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television systems are being outfitted to deliver
high-speed Internet service. Telephone systems are starting to
offer advanced Digital Subscriber Line service capable of
delivering the Internet at speeds that are 20 to 100 times faster
than today's conventional modems.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester projects that at least 20 million American homes will
have high-speed Internet access by 2003, compared with less than 1
million today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driving force going forward is bandwidth _ how fast a
connection you have to the Internet,'' said analyst David Goldstein
of Channel Marketing Corp. of Dallas. ``It's bandwidth, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   High-speed wireless networks are also in the offing. A group of
leading electronics and communications companies are collaborating
in a consortium called Bluetooth to develop a common and cheap way
to enable electronic devices, from computers to wristwatches, to
connect wirelessly to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester estimates that consumers in the United States will pay
more for their Internet service in 2001 _ a projected $16.5 billion
_ than they will for computer hardware.
</P>
<P>
   No one is predicting that desktop and laptop PCs will be
completely replaced anytime soon by smaller hand-held devices. But
prices for PCs are expected to decline.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester, for example, projects that average prices for
computers will drop $400 more by the year 2003. Lower prices will
translate to lower profits, driving some weak players from PC
manufacturing and forcing other companies to broaden their lines of
products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say more efficient PC makers like Dell will fare better
than competitors, but they expect that the entire PC hardware
industry will feel the impact of slowing sales and falling prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great joy in the PC hardware business is over,'' said
analyst Roger Kay with IDC Research in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Goins, who has worked in the personal computer industry for
nearly two decades, doesn't expect conventional PCs to disappear
any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is fond of his hand-held device, he still makes
extensive use of his desktop machines at the office and at his home
in Northwest Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But Goins does expect that alternative smart products, such as
his hand-held device, will continue to get better and better.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful device,'' he said of his Palm VII. ``But
it's just the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
