<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Special laptop found in hunt of computer show's treasures
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This was originally supposed to be a column about
what's new in SVGA, the future of computer visuals and how the glut
of cheap chips means you can build a workaday home PC around your
monitor.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before I stumbled into heaven for a few hours last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven, it turns out, was in the Cobb County Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   A flier had come in the mail for the Atlanta Area Computer Show
this past Saturday and Sunday. I tend to avoid any ``shows'' that
charge you to spend your own money, and this one cost $5 to get in,
$6 for both days.
</P>
<P>
   But because it was pouring rain, and I had never been to one of
them, I decided to go see what it was all about.
</P>
<P>
   When I parked, I noticed there were a lot of people carrying
computer cases and boxes of other stuff out to their cars. I had
half a notion that maybe I'd stumble across a cheap, old 486 or
something similar, so I took my checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   I had never been inside the Cobb Civic Center before. After
shelling out the five bucks, I found myself looking at a row of
tables that followed the perimeter of the building. The tables were
overflowing with every manner of hardware, software and
everything-in-between-ware.
</P>
<P>
   Wait, it gets even better.
</P>
<P>
   Those tables all overlooked the civic center floor, where there
were several more rows of tables full of stuff: glittering green
circuit boards, racks of CD-ROMs, boxes full of video accelerators,
sound cards, modems, network hubs, chips, cases, books.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I don't recall seeing was a mousepad, which
somehow lent an air of authenticity to the show.
</P>
<P>
   I was standing at the rail, looking down on this Dragoncon for
gearheads, when I spotted the tableful of laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   I had been thinking for some time that I needed a laptop, but
every time I looked at an ad, even the mom-and-pop outlets were
getting upward of $1,200 for new models.
</P>
<P>
   I knew what I wanted: a portable that could handle Word, for
desktop publishing stuff; Ultraedit, text editor I use for HTML;
Photoshop, for graphics work; Netscape, for, well, everything; and
all my little Internet toys, like WS-FTP, mIRC, Agent, etc.
</P>
<P>
   I'd also need a modem PC card, and I wanted a Pentium-class
machine with as much storage as possible.
</P>
<P>
   So I headed down the steps, merely to see what they had on that
tableful of laptops.
</P>
<P>
   The show was wondrous. It was a digital flea market ... and most
of the stuff was priced to sell quickly.
</P>
<P>
   One grandmotherly woman had a table full of plastic bins holding
nothing but computer cables of every shape, size, width and
persuasion. A friendly guy with a few display racks of CD-ROMs had
bargain-bin prices on current versions of big-name software, like
Win 95a and Win 95b (for those of us who avoid Win 98) and
two-for-ones on those CDs they use as filler (just think MultiMedia
Joke Kit) in retail store software bundles.
</P>
<P>
   There were tables of nothing but motherboards ... past and
present. Some vendors dealt in antiques, and if they didn't have
your particular obscure item, they knew who on the floor did. (One
poor guy was selling brand spanking new midtowers with 400 MHz and
450 MHz chips starting at over $1,000. Nobody stopped at his
table.)
</P>
<P>
   I was there for laptops. That first table I spotted had older
Pentiums from 75 MHz up to about 133 MHz for anywhere between $425
and $750. Some had external CD-ROMs, others had no CD drive at all.
There were familiar brands and totally obscure brands. All of them
weighed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   I ferreted out another laptop dealer with some nice-looking
Apple powerbooks, but apparently even old Macs cost too much. A
third dealer had the one I ended up buying _ a titanium-encased
Panasonic MKIII CF-41 that you could use to hammer in a nail.
</P>
<P>
   It has a built-in floppy drive, built-in CD-ROM (under the
keyboard, which may or may not be a good thing), a 1-gig hard
drive, 16 megs of RAM, Win 95b and Office 97.
</P>
<P>
   A 75 MHz version of it was on the table priced at $475, but the
dealer also had a 120 MHz version off to the side that he was
testing out with ``You Don't Know Jack 2.'' He said he'd give me
that one for $500.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   I also had to find someone selling PCMCIA modem cards, and
picked up a Compaq 28.8 and pigtail cable for $35.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the hardware for sale, the laptop came without
paperwork and the bare minimums: a power adapter and two power
cables (but a docking station was a nice plus).
</P>
<P>
   In all, a pretty neat deal, I thought. And this time I
remembered to boot up before signing the check.
</P>
<P>
   The show returns in August and September.
</P>
<P>
   There's also supposed to be a larger version at the Georgia
National Fairgrounds that I want to shop.
</P>
<P>
   When I got home, I stuck the laptop in my shoulder bag, grabbed
the docking station and met my wife coming out the door on her way
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
