<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Webby Awards seeking nominees
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Webbies are going democratic.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, people can nominate Web sites for
consideration in the March 2000 Webby Awards, the fourth time the
Web's best sites have been honored.
</P>
<P>
   The International Academy of Digital Arts &AMP; Sciences is adding
two categories this year, one for personal Web sites and one for
sites about activism. Other categories include arts, community,
commerce, education, fashion, film, finance, games, health, humor,
living, music, news, politics and law, print and e-zines
(electronic magazines), science, sports, technical achievement, TV,
travel and weird. Sites are judged on content, structure,
navigation, visual design, functionality, interactivity and overall
experience.
</P>
<P>
   To nominate a site, visit www.webbyawards.com. Entries are
accepted through Sept. 16. Entries cost $50 per Web site, per
category.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for the contest, dubbed the Oscars of the
Internet, your site must be live and open to traffic. Detailed
rules are listed on the Web site. Nominees will be announced in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Transparent mouse among new models
</P>
<P>
   The mouse is going see-through.
</P>
<P>
   Fellowes, an Itasca, Ill., company, is selling two new models.
One, called TechMouse, is transparent. The two-button mouse works
with Windows 98 or iMac systems and comes with a 6 1/2-inch cable
and a USB connector. The mouse, which carries a three-year
warranty, sells for about $18.
</P>
<P>
   Fellowes' GelMouse is housed in gel that conforms to your hand.
The device has three buttons that can be programmed. It works with
Windows 95, Windows 98 and Windows NT and retails for about $30.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Bell NEC computer thin, stylish
</P>
<P>
   Packard Bell NEC has come out with the PC's answer to the iMac:
a more stylish version of the traditional, bulky beige computer
box.
</P>
<P>
   The Z1 uses about as much space as a sheaf of paper. The machine
is mostly monitor. It comes with a 15-inch flat-panel monitor and
keyboard. The computer has a 450-megahertz Intel Pentium III
processor, 96 megabytes of memory, an 8.4-gigabyte hard drive and a
DVD drive.
</P>
<P>
   The machines come with a 3.5-inch disk drive. They are
pre-loaded with Windows 98, Microsoft Word 97, Intuit's Quicken
Basic 98 and Microsoft Money 99.
</P>
<P>
   The Z1 sells for about $2,500. It is expected to be in stores in
early August.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento, Calif.-based Packard Bell NEC said the all-in-one
system takes up the least amount of space of any desktop computer
on the market. The machine, highlighted by a two-toned metallic
cover and arched base, is 10 inches square. The reduced size is the
result of a combination of desktop and laptop technology.
</P>
<P>
   The system is interestingly upgradeable. Users can upgrade their
hard drive using an integrated module, which will be available as
an accessory later this year. The module connects to the hard drive
in the Z1's base. Once docked, the user runs the hard disk copy
software to create a copy of the original hard drive. Once the
disks are swapped, the upgrade is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Web site provides for range of communications
</P>
<P>
   If you want the benefit of being able to communicate in as many
ways as possible but don't have the money to buy the software or
hardware, a new Web site might help.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.MessageBlaster.com, lets someone on the Internet
contact people by e-mail, voice, pager, fax, regular mail or
next-day mail. Once the message is sent, it lets you track the
receipt of the message and receive replies.
</P>
<P>
   The feature requires no software and no contract. A customer
would need a credit card to set up an account. The price is 15
cents for a message delivered over phone lines. E-mail is free, but
the fees for regular mail and overnight delivery are marked up.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Billerica, Mass., was founded in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
