<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whereas, you may need legal aid, and whereas ...
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few of my best friends are lawyers. However, they
were my best friends before they became lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with lawyers, in my view, is that there are too many
of them. Lawyers have their place in the scheme of things, just as
forest fires, scorpions and sharks have.
</P>
<P>
   But the balance of nature regarding lawyers has become skewed,
leaving many of them with nothing better to do than silly things
like accusing publishers of computer legal programs of practicing
law without a license.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what became of these lawsuits, but at least one
such program survived and flourishes; it is Quicken Family Lawyer
2000 Deluxe. At least that's what the box says. When the
installation program comes up on screen, it has become Parsons
Technology Family Lawyer 2000 Deluxe. Ah well, a rose by any other
name, etc.
</P>
<P>
   It's been years since I last looked at one of these programs.
This one, at least, still does all the same things _ a seemingly
endless number of letters _ dunning, threatening, supplicating and
placating; living wills, dead wills and various medical requests;
bills of sale and a lot of things you would never think you'd need
a lawyer to do, like letters to confirm hotel reservations.
</P>
<P>
   However, it does all these things a good deal more gracefully
than those older programs. Like the income tax programs, it begins
with an interview to determine your name and address, your marital
status and the names, addresses and status of your children. Then
it presents its entire list of possibilities, with the ones it
believes of most interest to you check-marked.
</P>
<P>
   Since I truthfully told the program I was married and not either
divorced or contemplating divorce, all the programs of special
interest to me turn out to be connected to my demise.
</P>
<P>
   I went through the process of making out a ``Will _ Parent With
Adult Children.'' Once again, this is accomplished through an
interview process. You are given the opportunity to disinherit any
or all of the offspring you listed in the beginning, and to
disinherit your spouse, for that matter, although the program warns
you can't get away with that in some states.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions have to be made on what should be done if no one can
tell who died first _ you or your spouse _ and then you get the
opportunity to bequeath certain things to certain people, ad
infinitum et nauseam.
</P>
<P>
   The basic value of this program is in helping you prepare a
will, a living will to provide instructions on whether to keep you
alive by way of machinery, and other fairly common legal documents
like powers of attorney. Many of the other papers it will produce
don't seem to have much to do with real legal documents.
</P>
<P>
   There is a brief but useful law dictionary, defining G-man and
T-man (didn't know those were legal terms, did you?) and everything
else from ab initio to yellow dog contract.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the American Bar Association Family Law Guide, but
that will cost you another 20 bucks to unlock and use.
</P>
<P>
   This is a well-executed program. As to whether you would find it
useful, or whether any of this stuff will hold up to your
disinherited children's outraged lawyer _ well, you don't expect me
to stick my neck out, do you?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
