<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEVILS-LAKE-ART-2TAKE     07-05 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVILS-LAKE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACRE BY ACRE, DEVIL'S LAKE TAKES OVER 200-SQUARE-MILES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo and a graphic are being sent. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEVIL'S LAKE, N.D. _ Jim Yri, a tall, sunburned farmer with
movie star looks and the folksy style of Jimmy Stewart, has battled
North Dakota blizzards and wheat fungus and, lately, appallingly
low crop prices. But now he is in a struggle with a lake that he is
afraid he just might lose.
</P>
<P>
   The lake, the namesake for this little town, began rising seven
years ago when it was just a sliver on the horizon beyond Yri's
white clapboard farm house west of here.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he shrugged it off as no more than the natural
consequence of especially heavy snowfall and rain. But each year
the lake has climbed higher and now the water is in his yard,
creeping toward his basement, like some incredible science-fiction
monster, threatening to drive him off the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``You plow a field and come back a week later and the water has
taken the field,'' Yri (pronounced Erie) said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   He and thousands of other people around Devil's Lake on the
rolling prairie of northeastern North Dakota are caught up in a
strange, gradual flood like nothing modern America has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Inch by inch, the lake has been swelling across a gently sloping
basin without an outlet, forcing nearly 400 families to move their
homes as it swallowed up 80,000 acres of farmland, three state
parks, miles of country roads and perhaps a million trees. Devil's
Lake has tripled in size and now sprawls over nearly 200 square
miles, making it more than eight times the size of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike river floods that crush towns in a flash, the destruction
at Devil's Lake has come one or two houses at a time, acre by acre,
utility pole by utility pole, never with a single surge stunning
enough to make the national news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people realize the severity of what's happening
here,'' said Tom LaMotte, the owner of several businesses in
Devil's Lake, a town of 10,000 people that is still above water
because the rising lake is being held back by a man-built wall of
rock and earth.
</P>
<P>
   Devil's Lake and the Great Salt Lake in Utah are among a very
few lakes without natural drainage. Their waters rise and fall
depending on rain and snow and the saturation of surrounding lands,
scientists say, and North Dakota has been in a prolonged wet cycle.
The Great Salt Lake flooded in the mid-1980s with less damage than
is now being experienced at Devil's Lake, officials say, and while
the Salt Lake has risen over the last three years, it has caused
little harm.
</P>
<P>
   The slow-motion destruction by Devil's Lake, coupled with
gnawing uncertainty about what the lake will do next _ level off
and create a booming resort area or keep rising and destroying _
are straining the economy and people's nerves. If being forced to
leave were inevitable, many people would leave now. But no one
really wants to go. Most of them have been here all their lives.
</P>
<P>
   They like the quiet beauty of the lake, the vermilion explosions
at sunset and the serenity of communities where homes and cars are
seldom locked. A good many people recognize that if the lake ever
does settle down, their property values are likely to skyrocket
because of the resort possibilities. Still, nearly everyone would
have been happier if the lake had just remained a nice place to
visit on a Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state agencies have poured more than $300 million
into temporary measures: building dikes, keeping roads open and
moving homes out of harm's way. In early June, President Clinton
authorized spending tens of millions for more of the same. But
people are beginning to grumble that the money has been wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of building up the roads a little more every year,
they should be finding some permanent solution,'' said Jarvis
Haugeberg, who runs the grain elevator on a shrinking peninsula in
Church's Ferry, 20 miles to the northwest. ``But they just keep
making new studies and arguing about what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Fred Bott of Devil's Lake, along with just about everyone
else around here, argues for hacking an opening in one side of the
lake so that it can be drained to a tolerable level, into the
Sheyenne River. But environmental groups and people in several
North Dakota towns worry that any significant drainage could bring
flooding elsewhere, and that the sulfate-laden waters of Devil's
Lake could contaminate streams and the water supplies of other
communities. Canadians also oppose the drainage, as the Sheyenne
runs into the Red River, which flows into their country.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps of Engineers agreed in early June that an outlet
should be built. But the corps proposed waiting to release water
until Devil's Lake had risen another seven feet, something the
engineers think could take until 2006 but many residents fear could
happen much more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota officials could hardly believe their ears when they
heard the corps' proposal. Gov. Edward T. Schafer and the state's
three members of Congress said that letting the lake rise that much
higher would inundate an additional 75,000 acres and could cost up
to $200 million more for dikes and roads.
</P>
<P>
   So the debate continues. So does the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always eating at you,'' Yri said as he and his wife,
Diane, talked the other evening in their kitchen. ``There's a lot
of mental depression around here. You just don't feel like doing
anything. Why bother? Next week it will be under water.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind kicked up the other day, Mrs. Yri said, churning up
waves that seemed bent on wrecking the house. It was more than she
could bear and she ran screaming to her husband. ``What are they
going to do,'' she recalled demanding. ``What are they going to
do?'' Yri held her tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They,'' Yri said, ``are not going to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   At her small, white-shingled home in the village of Minnewaukan,
at the edge of the lake, 20 miles west of here, Elizabeth Stensby,
a 72-year-old widow, says she keeps asking herself, ``Can I stay or
do I have to leave?''
</P>
<P>
   Her house, where she raised six children, was eight miles from
the lake when it started rising. Now the water is edging into her
backyard. A golf course just across the highway has gone under
water and the town has trucked in sand to make a beach. A few
blocks away, the lake is advancing on the high school football
field and the main classroom building. Allan Nord, a carpenter who
lives near the high school, is talking about opening a bait shop.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2043EDT &QL; 
