</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Choosing between a singing pig and a Pavarotti
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine what it would be like if your best friend
owned a pig that could sing.
</P>
<P>
   You'd be able to invite everyone over on a Saturday night and
have the pig perform _ maybe Shubert's ``Trout.''
</P>
<P>
   At first it would really be neat. Everyone would forgive the pig
for not having a voice like Frank Sinatra or Ella Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   But pretty soon the novelty wouldn't be enough and _ when you
really wanted to hear music _ you'd turn to someone who was less of
a swine and more a singer.
</P>
<P>
   In the technology world, there are plenty of pigs that can sing.
There's a temptation to create a product just because it is
technologically possible without regard for whether the new
technology is better than the old.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes these gizmos are nifty and impressive but just aren't
as useful as the technology they attempt to replace. Enough
philosophizing _ let's listen to some pigs that sing off-key.
</P>
<P>
   _ Using your computer as an answering machine is dumb. Many PCs
come with software to let your PC's modem answer the call and then
use the PC's hard disk to record the incoming messages as voice
files. Truth is, it works. But so does a $30 answering machine _ in
fact, the cheap answering machine works better. It also doesn't
require keeping your PC on 24 hours a day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several companies, including Panasonic, now make tiny DVD
players. For right under $1,000, you can watch a DVD movie on its
5.8-inch screen. But imagine, if you will, watching ``Saving
Private Ryan'' that way, or picture a basketball game played by
ants (some users report that they can't even read the title on the
little screen). To be fair, this sucker will also hook up to your
regular TV. But if that's what you want, get one of the $300 AC
models that are meant to work that way.
</P>
<P>
   _ E-books. We'll be looking at them in more detail in a later
edition of this column. Maybe you already know, these are
electronic gizmos that allow you to download the text of a book and
then view the book on the screen. You'll pay about $500 for the
most popular reader _ the Rocket eBook. Then you'll pay about $20
for each book you buy. Would you rather buy a $6 paperback you can
read in the bathtub and then lend to your buddy, or do you want to
spend $20 on an e-book and read it on a machine? Also, if you drop
the paperback or hardback, it will make a loud slapping sound and
then work just fine. If you drop the eBook, it also will make a
loud sound, and you'll be about $500 poorer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Using your computer monitor to watch TV. You can get TV cards
that let you attach an antenna or a cable connection and receive TV
signals and then watch them on your computer monitor. Now think
about it. I can either sit down in my leather reclining chair and
watch TV on my big-screen monitor, or I can sit at a desk chair and
watch TV on my PC's 17-inch monitor. Duh.
</P>
<P>
   These are my singing pigs. I'm not telling you that they'll be
your pigs. There's almost certainly someone out there with a
special circumstance just made for one of these gadgets. But you
probably aren't that person. Save your money and, instead, get a
good CD recording of Ella or Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEVILS-LAKE-ART-2NDTA     07-05 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVILS-LAKE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
DEVIL'S LAKE, N.D.: bait shop.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1993, Devil's Lake has risen nearly 25 feet, to a level
higher than it has been in more than 100 years, scientists said.
The wall of clay and rocks holding it back from the town, built
mainly in the last three years, is seven miles long. Without the
wall, most of the town's small, brown-brick business district and
its wide, tree-shaded streets and modest homes would be roof-deep
in water, said state Sen. Vern Thompson. Yet for many people, the
dike is as unnerving as it is protective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anything that was constructed as quickly as the dike, you
wonder, `Is it really secure?''' said Paul Keating, the owner of
the local Radio Shack franchise. ``It's holding back 30 miles of
water, 25 feet deep. The big dams and reservoirs are concrete. This
is just dirt. If we get a major thunder storm, how much lightening
can it take? What would a tornado do to it? You read about the
bombing in Oklahoma and the high school shooting in Colorado.
What's to stop somebody from sabotaging the dike?''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross has been giving classes in what to do in a flood
emergency. Its evacuation plan links everyone's address to the
nearest landmark to help rescue teams find them.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Rutten, who manages a water-tower painting business with
her husband, Tim, says she always drives with her windows rolled
down so that she can ``bail out'' in case her car goes into the
water. A bank receptionist says she has taken no special
precautions, but she knows that if the dike breaks, she has three
minutes to get out of her house. Mrs. Yri has enrolled her children
in swimming classes.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, at Radio Shack, like many small-business men in Devil's
Lake, is barely surviving. For some merchants, sales are down at
least 25 percent this year. Investors are holding back on starting
new projects.
</P>
<P>
   For people as far as 50 miles away, going shopping in Devil's
Lake used to mean a fairly pleasant drive through fields of wheat
and barley and sunflowers. Now those roads that have not
disappeared entirely have become scary causeways with waves chewing
at their edges. Heavy trucks loaded with rock and clay thunder
along from dawn to dusk and construction detours often turn a
20-minute trip into an ordeal of an hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is suffering. Contractors working on the dikes
and roads and moving endangered houses are doing very well. They,
in turn, are making the cash registers ring for other businesses,
with their workers buying fuel, staying in motels and recreational
vehicle parks and eating in local restaurants. Fishing and duck
hunting have never been better. So tourism is up. Rooms that often
languished at the Woodland Resort are now booked solid. One farmer
has converted his flooded land into a fishing camp and the Sioux
Indians at the Spirit Lake Nation reservation, on the southern
shore, are building a nearly 200-slip marina just behind their
gambling casino.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   No one here wants to seem ungrateful for the government help
they have received, but many people say they cannot help thinking
that if Devil's Lake was not such a small community, if it was not
in the middle of nowhere and if it could muster a bit more
political clout, the lake problem would have been solved by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus being hit by a train doesn't have enough passengers,''
said Rick LaFleur, who runs a family business that distributes
jukeboxes and pinball machines.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Yri has begun to wonder whether he can keep working the land the
way his father did before him. He has sold off the last of his 50
beef cattle because the water has taken their grazing land and he
is talking about moving his house to higher ground. But he worries
that the water will take the main roads and put him out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the roads, we're an island,'' he said. ``People felt
the lake couldn't keep rising, but it just keeps coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
