<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9880 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JESSE-JAMES-KAN &LR;      07-05 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSE-JAMES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WOMAN SEEKS PROOF SHE'S RELATED TO JESSE JAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JERRY BERRIOS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Betty Dorsett Duke was 7 when she was first told
that paternal great-grandfather James L. Courtney was the legendary
outlaw Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, now 52, wants to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas court is scheduled to decide this month whether Duke
will be allowed to have Courtney's remains exhumed so his DNA can
be compared with a known descendent of Zerelda James Samuel, Jesse
James' mother.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, who lives in Liberty Hill, Texas, started her mission in
1996 after she found a family photograph that showed her
great-great-grandmother was missing her right arm. Zerelda James
Samuel did not have a right arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would really, really shock me if I'm wrong,'' Duke said in
a recent telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   However, many of Duke's relatives think she is wrong and are
opposing the exhumation of Courtney's remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never in my life heard such a false thing,'' said H.C.
Shelton, 84, Courtney's grandson. He lives in Junction City, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton says numbers and dates prove his grandfather was not
James.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said Courtney was more than 6 feet tall and
weighed more than 200 pounds. Shelton said that according to one
James historian, Phillip Steele, James was 5 feet 9 inches tall and
weighed 150 pounds or less.
</P>
<P>
   Duke says descriptions of James vary.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton also said Courtney enlisted in the Union Army in
Warrensburg, Mo., in 1864 with his father's signature, Stephen
Courtney _ not with the name of Robert James, Jesse's father.
Shelton said he had documents, including James Courtney's original
Civil War discharge, as proof.
</P>
<P>
   Duke says she thinks her great-grandfather faked his Civil War
involvement as part of his cover.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents, Shelton submitted dates of James' robberies
and entries from his grandfather's diary. For example, on April 29,
1872, according to Shelton's letter, James was in Columbia, Ky.,
and Shelton's grandfather was in Falls County, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is check the dates,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse James was born in Kearney, Mo., in 1847. He is said to
have died April 3, 1882, after being shot in the back of the head
by fellow gang member Bob Ford in St. Joseph, Mo. James was 34.
</P>
<P>
   Duke said her great-grandfather came to Texas about 11 years
before faking his death. He assumed the Courtney name and married
Mary Ellen Barron. Duke said her great-grandfather died in 1943 at
the age of 96. He is buried in Blevins (Texas) Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Duke says a forensic expert at the Austin Police Department has
said Duke's photographs of Courtney closely match known photographs
of James.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton says the photograph Duke uses is not Courtney, but
Courtney's brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton says that he knew his grandfather and that he has never
heard Courtney was James.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, no other branch of the Courtney family
believes her story,'' Shelton said about Duke.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Starrs doesn't believe Duke, either.
</P>
<P>
   Starrs, a forensics and law professor at George Washington
University, led the exhumation of remains from James' grave at
Mount Olivet Cemetery in Kearney in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 110 percent certain that it's Jesse James,'' Starrs said
from his office in Washington. ``There is no doubt that it is Jesse
James.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Barr, who was confirmed as James' great-granddaughter
through the 1995 exhumation, isn't bothered by Duke's claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the right to do that,'' Barr said from her Overland
Park home. ``It's a free world.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr says there has never been any doubt of her family's
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   But Duke is adamant that Courtney was James.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers a car trip in her childhood when her father spun
stories of Courtney riding into a Texas town with saddlebags filled
with gold. Her father also talked about Courtney riding with the
Younger gang and being skilled with a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just chalked it up to a tall, Texas tale,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she found the photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``History needs to be corrected,'' Duke said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
