<HEADER>
A9883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-WOMEN-2TAKES(TRI     07-05 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-WOMEN-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE OPENLY WOOING WOMEN VOTERS, WHO SEEM TO PREFER BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Fla., Tenn., Texas)   (Eds: Words in bold can be italic.)  
(nk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first thing Al Gore mentioned in every speech
last week was that his oldest daughter was past her due date and
about to make him and his wife of 29 years grandparents. (Wyatt
Gore Schiff, 6 pounds 3 ounces, finally arrived on the Fourth of
July, a fact sure to become a bragging point in future speeches.)
</P>
<P>
   The second thing he told crowds was that he had been reared by a
mother who grew up poor, got on a bus to Nashville with her blind
sister in tow, waited tables for quarter tips and, in 1936, became
one of the first women to graduate from Vanderbilt Law School.
</P>
<P>
   When he listened as a child to the daily back and forth between
his parents, ``it was clear to me that men and women were equal _
if not more so,'' Gore said to great effect, drawing whoops from
his listeners at every stop.
</P>
<P>
   In his run for the White House, the vice president is
aggressively pursuing female voters _ that increasingly important
bloc that so far seems to favor Texas Gov. George W. Bush slightly
_ and the pitch is not terribly subtle.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever possible, Gore is introduced to his audiences by a
woman. (Christine Meyer, the mother of a 3-year-old cancer
survivor, did the honors before his Philadelphia speech supporting
cancer research last week. ``I said my husband is really the
speaker,'' Ms. Meyer said in an interview, ``but they said no, we
want you to do it. They wanted a mom's perspective.'')
</P>
<P>
   The vice president steps onstage to the tune of ``Rock This
Country,'' a country song by a female vocalist, Shania Twain. A
campaign video focuses primarily on him as husband and father, with
his daughter Karenna Schiff repeatedly assuring viewers that her
dad is  &UR; so funny. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Then comes his standard stump speech, chock full of talk about
day care, early-childhood education and gender equality. ``This
pledge,'' he says, ``is in honor of my mother: An equal day's pay
for an equal day's work.'' He promises also to ``fight for the
ability to balance work and family'' and ``to shield our children
from gun violence.'' And his biggest applause line is usually his
vow to ``make sure we have high-quality preschool available for
every child.''
</P>
<P>
   This wildly woman-friendly agenda is not a poll-tested new focus
for the vice president. Gore has worked on these issues throughout
his public life, co-sponsoring early versions of the Family and
Medical Leave Act in the Senate and a series of bills on women's
health in the House as far back as the early 1980s. He opposed
federal financing of abortion early in his House career, but has
been a supporter of abortion rights for many years and was a Senate
co-sponsor of a bill that would have made a federal statute of Roe
vs. Wade. He has surrounded himself with accomplished women who
have become some of his closest aides, and is considered by his
staff to be an unusually family-friendly employer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his campaign  &UR; is  &LR; without question reacting to polls
suggesting that at least at this early date, American women, who
have heavily favored Democrats in recent elections, seem to prefer
Bush, an opponent of abortion. David Beckwith, a Bush spokesman,
said the governor's ``compassionate conservatism'' appealed to
everybody. Even when Bush ran for governor in 1994 against a female
incumbent, Ann Richards, there was virtually no gender gap,
Beckwith noted: 49 percent of Texas women who went to the polls,
like 53 percent of the men, supported Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Though women favored Bill Clinton over Bob Dole by 16 percentage
points in 1996, one recent CNN poll had them backing Bush over Gore
by 11 points. (The vice president was farther behind among men, by
21 points.)
</P>
<P>
   Political consultants from both parties see the Gore numbers at
least in part as evidence of displaced anger over the president's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear Gore is carrying some Clinton baggage,'' said one
Republican consultant, Susan Molinari, a former congresswoman from
New York. ``For whatever reason, Clinton just has the energy to
deflect that stuff, and Gore doesn't. People seem to resent Gore
more for Clinton's actions. It's like two brothers, and the good
one the mom says: `You should know better. You should have stopped
him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even Gore's new pollster, Celinda Lake, who coined the term
``waitress moms'' to describe the blue-collar women who could have
the power to decide elections, agrees that the Lewinsky scandal
appears to be suppressing the vice president's numbers with women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a delayed reaction to the Clinton factor that's
unfair to Gore,'' said Ms. Lake, who specializes in tracking female
voters and was brought on last week to help the campaign figure
them out. ``But to women, the personal is political. As they get to
know him, they'll see he's quite un-Clintonesque in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the vice president expressed surprise that
anyone could think he might somehow wind up taking the fall for the
Lewinsky scandal. ``I don't buy it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly his campaign is working hard to make sure that does
not happen, recruiting women to fill the seats at his events, to
come and hear his direct appeals. ``Working to close that gap,''
Ms. Lake said, ``is one of the most important tasks of the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After receiving from the headquarters of Gore's Pennsylvania
campaign ``three begging phone calls indicating they need women,''
Maureen Kelly, a Pittsburgh lawyer, agreed to attend a fund-raising
luncheon last week, at a discounted rate. Patricia McGrail, another
lawyer, attended with her and also got a discount, paying $300, she
said, for the $1,000 ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kelly, who said the campaign had asked her for the names of
other women who might be interested in hearing Gore speak,
responded positively to his remarks, and said: ``I feel bad for
him. People are going to associate him with Clinton, when in fact
he embodies the values most women want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In private, Gore talks about the important women in his life
with a respect that does suggest, as several women who heard him
speak last week said, that ``he gets it.'' As he chatted on Air
Force Two, in a conversation that was initially off the record, the
vice president's mind was on his pregnant daughter. Would he cancel
his schedule when she went into labor?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``You want to run to the hospital and
be right there with her, but then again. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Got to give her her space,'' he said, laughing at himself.
``Her mother has perfect pitch on this stuff, so I guess I'll just
follow her lead.''
</P>
<P>
   (Gore also disclosed that while environmentalists are split over
Pampers vis-a-vis cloth diapers, he favors the easy way out.
``That's not a hard call,'' he joked. ``Global warming is hard.
Pampers are easy.'')
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Most of the women attending Gore campaign events at this point
are active Democrats, of course. But during three days of almost
nonstop campaign events last week, a number of women said,
essentially, that they felt he was pandering, yes, and maybe even
desperate _ yet also totally sincere.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While commentators have primarily looked at the ways in which
Gore is not enough like Clinton as a campaigner, his audiences
seemed to be focusing more on what the vice president said than how
he said it. They liked the story about his mother, and they loved
the line ``I'm running to make America not just better off, but
better.''
</P>
<P>
   At a reception in Philadelphia, one supporter, Lynne Gold-Bikin,
said she had been appalled by the poll numbers showing women
favoring Bush _ ``that  &UR; Texan &LR; ,'' &UR;  &LR; as she called him.
</P>
<P>
   ``How any woman,'' she said, ``could prefer the governor of the
state that pushes Tom DeLay and Dick Armey, who are so anti-woman I
can't even think about it, over this man who is pro-choice and has
this wonderful, exciting wife? I don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, at yet another fund-raising luncheon, Mayor Alex
Penelas announced to Gore: ``The real person who should be
introducing you is my wife. If you say you're not voting for Al
Gore, she'll punch you in the nose. And she's the Republican in the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   When she did come to the microphone, Mrs. Penelas was as
believable as she was enthusiastic: ``Most people I tell them my
father was Basque, they say, `What is that?' '' When she told Gore,
however, ``he told me all about their customs, he gave me an
education on the Basque people _ now I say, that's knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore took it from there, and started in with how excited he was
about becoming an  &UR; abuelo  &LR; _ a grandfather _ racing through this
one Spanish word as if someone had told him the key to fluency was
talking fast.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Elsa Lopez, a single mother among his listeners, said
she felt he had been talking to her. ``We need quality day care,
not some ranch to farm these kids out on. Education, and choice _
my daughter just turned 4, but I  &UR; decided  &LR; to have her _ these
things are all key,'' said Ms. Lopez, a former Republican who now
works for the teachers' union and said she was thrilled to have
received a free ticket to the $1,000 event.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Not all women were wowed, of course, by the vice president's
focus on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept bringing up women's issues,'' said Ms. McGrail, the
Pittsburgh lawyer, who is a Democrat and the mother of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like he was dealing with soft issues,'' she said. ``I'm
44 years old; I'm too old for that. I wanted to hear about
something more relevant to my life, like economic development.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the presentation she heard seems to have convinced Ms.
McGrail that Gore is probably too sensitive to lead the country,
and at this point she is thinking of supporting Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not because she's a woman,'' Ms. McGrail said, ``but because I
think she'd be a strong leader. She's tough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
