<SLUG> BC-URBAN-SCOUTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOUTS REACH OUT TO INNER-CITY KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ERICA WOOD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At 14, Roman Lee had a choice: He could go
the way of his four older brothers and quit the Boy Scouts, or he
could follow his mother's wishes and stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed and he's glad. Of the five brothers, he was the only
one to attain the rank of Eagle Scout and graduate from college.
</P>
<P>
   He says the only difference between him and his brothers, who
have struggled with severe problems, is that he stayed in Boy
Scouts and they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom looked for an outlet to provide positive male role
models,'' Lee said of his single mother. ``The different activities
provided something to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Pioneer Trails District executive for the Kansas City
area Scouts, Lee has become the role model. He is passing on
lessons he learned as one of Kansas City's first urban Boy Scouts
of America, a branch created in 1988 to address the lack of
leadership and money in inner-city troops.
</P>
<P>
   The program, Scoutreach, was designed to draw more inner-city
children. By many accounts, it has succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Marks, finance and marketing director for Boy Scouts of
America Heart of America Council, says the number of urban Scouts
in the Kansas City area has grown from 328 in 1988 to 9,092 at the
end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Inner-city parents are hard to attract because many work several
jobs or lack transportation. So the organization hires some of them
as paid paraprofessionals who are responsible for eight troops. In
a typical Boy Scout program, a volunteer leader oversees one troop.
</P>
<P>
   Some boys receive financial aid to buy uniforms and go camping.
</P>
<P>
   Lee says he has seen boys' grades and behavior improve once they
get involved in Scouting. They learn leadership and gain
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Moten, a fourth-grader, said that in Cub Scouts the
leaders talked about drugs and what to do if someone offers them to
you.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the Scouts do fun things.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-year-old Quinn Hernandez said he got involved because of
camping trips. ``I knew we would have a whole lot of adventures,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Allen, Pack 27 cubmaster and assistant scoutmaster for
Troops 608 and 34, says an inner-city Scouting program provides a
vital service.
</P>
<P>
   Parents such as Tmeda Pollard say Allen has become the positive
male role model that was missing in her son's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he'll stick with it,'' Pollard said. ``He looks up to
his leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts understand that inner-city kids face many problems,
said Alex Zaragoza, Kaw District executive for the Kansas City,
Kan., area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the mentality that if we don't do something about it, the
streets will take them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee stresses that urban Scouts do the same things as other
Scouts. They camp, swim, earn Merit Badges and learn the Boy Scout
oath.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Cub Scouts recently came together during two
weeklong day camps.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hernandez of Kansas City, Kan., came to Cub World in
Bonner Springs with her two sons, Quinn and Anthony. She said
Scouting had taught them responsibility and kept them out of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps with the transition into being a young man,'' she
said. ``He (Anthony) came back (from an overnight camp) a whole
different kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Hernandez, a seventh-grader, said Scouting got him out
of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like knowing what you're doing while outdoors and learning
how to handle people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boys who camped out in Swope Park were equally excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun, and you get to do a lot of stuff,'' said 10-year-old
Dannen Powell of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Craig, senior Kaw District executive, said adults often told
him Scouting had made their children happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's making a difference in the child's life with them being
more positive, being able to travel to places they normally
wouldn't, being able to meet other people that are different from
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
