<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz planning second trip to DL
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The long look on John Smoltz's face after his 7-6 loss
to the New York Mets on Sunday was a look into his future. After a
visit with team orthopedist Joe Chandler during Monday night's
game, Smoltz was expected to return to the disabled list with a
sore elbow for the second time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz has made seven starts since he went on the DL in May.
He's been effective in all but two of them, but his elbow won't let
him do any more right now despite his effort to pitch through the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I had to do the last five starts. Now we have to
take a different option,'' Smoltz said before Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz said he's been targeting the All-Star break as a chance
to rest his elbow again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I didn't think I needed as much time,'' he said.
``This time I realize I need to rest. . . . I'd like to come back
this time a little more complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, though, there's no indication a set amount of time
will help.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the frustrating part,'' Smoltz said. ``I could sit out
two months and have the same thing happen all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, the Braves likely will turn again to Bruce Chen,
who's 6-3 with a 3.77 ERA in AAA Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez waits
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Javy Lopez will not come off the 15-day disabled list
today, the first day he's eligible to return to action, because his
sprained right knee is still too sore for him to catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling good,'' Lopez said. ``I can do everything, but I
can't squat right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez hit Monday for the first time since he injured his knee
attempting to steal a base in Arizona on June 20. He plans to try
to catch today, wearing a knee brace under his shin guard. He has
been wearing a knee-saver pad behind his left knee, which he had
surgery on after the 1997 season, and will now wear one on his
right knee, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a matter of how I feel with the brace on and how I
feel with the knee saver,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox doesn't plan to rush him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Javy might not play until after the All-Star break,'' Cox
said. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Grip change
</P>
<P>
   A little tinkering with Bret Boone's grip on the bat and a
couple home runs might finally have him on the right track. Boone
ended his homer drought of 169 at-bats with a pair of home runs off
Orel Hershiser on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a tough situation the last month,'' said Boone,
who was .178 during June with only four RBIs. ``Hopefully that was
a sign I'm coming around. . . . A lot of that starts off as a
little physical thing, then mentally it gets frustrating and you
try to do a little more than you should. Next thing you know,
you're in a slump.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone said he returned to a grip that allows him ``to create a
shorter path to the ball,'' something he used last year but got
away from.
</P>
<P>
   All-star snub?
</P>
<P>
   When the starting position players for the National League
All-Star team are announced today, the Braves won't have a starter
among them for the first time since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan, Chipper Jones and Kevin Millwood are all
possibilities to be invited by manager Bruce Bochy as reserves.
Those will be announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a popularity contest for starters,'' said Tom Glavine,
who started back-to-back All-Star games in 1991 and 1992. ``But
most of the guys who are starters (this year) are probably
deserving. The only one that I question is Craig Biggio. He's had a
good year, but Jay Bell has had a phenomenal year. It's still a
popularity contest. That hurts a lot of guys who have to be picked
and won't be and deserve to be there. But it's the fans' game. They
ought to see who they want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
