<HEADLINE>
FUTURE STARS WILL MEET AT FENWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Baseball's biggest names will converge on Boston's
Fenway Park next week for the midsummer classic.
</P>
<P>
   But we're not necessarily talking about Griffey!off, Maddux or
Piazza!off. Instead, some of the names to watch are Berkman, Penny
and Pickering.
</P>
<P>
   Household names? Not today. But the concept behind the inaugural
All-Star Futures Game on Sunday is to give baseball fans a glimpse
of tomorrow's superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Aa a tuneup to next Tuesday's Major-League All-Star Game, The
Futures Game will showcase the top prospects from every
organization. The participants will be divided into teams of
American-born players and a World squad representing 15 countries,
including Taiwan, the Netherlands and Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   The players were not selected solely on statistics, which is
often the case in all-star games. They were chosen more for their
major-league potential.
</P>
<P>
   Take pitchers Ryan Anderson (Seattle Mariners) and Mark Mulder
(Oakland A's). Anderson has been hit hard in Double-A (5-9, with a
4.87 ERA), and Mulder is a very ordinary 4-5 at Triple-A Vancouver.
But the young left-handers are projected as major-league
superstars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is always about `tomorrow' and the Futures Game will
showcase baseball's tomorrow,'' said National Association of
Professional Baseball Leagues president Mike Moore. ``We are
excited about this opportunity for the fans to see present and
future major-league all-stars in the same city.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25-man rosters include Triple-A players on the verge of
getting their major-league assignments, such as Cal State
Northridge product Adam Kennedy (St. Louis Cardinals).
</P>
<P>
   Several teen-agers who dominate the low minors will participate.
Shortstop Rafael Furcal (Atlanta Braves), 18, of Single-A Macon
(Ga.), has stolen 68 bases in 80 South Atlantic League games.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Rick Ankiel (Cardinals), 19, is considered the minors'
top prospect and has joined Kennedy at Triple-A Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   JetHawks pitcher and World all-star Chris Mears (Seattle
Mariners), a 21-year-old Canadian, admits this is a priceless
opportunity to take the mound at Fenway Park and pitch to the best
young hitters in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice honor to be selected. Hopefully there's much more
to come for me,'' said Mears, who is 19-5 the past year-and-a-half,
primarily at low Single-A. ``There's still a lot of work to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball wants fans to see the matchups. ESPN2 will
broadcast the Futures Game by tape delay at 5 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game presents a tremendous opportunity for these
exceptionally skilled players to showcase their skills in a
national setting,'' said Jimmie Lee Solomon, executive director of
minor-league operations for Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Add Futures: The 30 major-league organizations had at least one
propsect chosen for the game. Both the Dodgers and Angels have two
represenatives who will play for the World Team.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' participants are Double-A San Antonio pitcher Luke
Prokopec (Australia) and Single-A San Bernardino left fielder
Chin-Feng Chen (Taiwan).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' players are Double-A Erie pitcher Ramon Ortiz
(Dominican Republic) and shortstop E.J. t'Hoen (Netherlands).
</P>
<P>
   Grade A's: The Oakland A's are marketing their youth movement in
every way possible, and that suits Oakland's first-round pick Barry
Zito just fine. The USC and Pierce College product was the
eighth-overall selection in last month's draft and made his
professional debut Thursday for Single-A Visalia.
</P>
<P>
   The A's are depending on their farm system to turn around around
the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a young team as a whole in the organization,'' Zito said.
``I'm very excited about the A's ... It's a team that's going to be
very strong in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Check swings: Eric Munson (USC) was off to a respectable start
with the West Michigan Whitecaps of the Midwest League. The third
overall pick of the Detroit Tigers, Munson was hitting .243 and
making an impact defensively. In his first professional start at
catcher, Munson helped teammate Adam Bernero toss a one-hitter over
Lansing. ``I give Eric a lot of credit. He's not used to me, yet he
did a great job back there,'' Bernero said. ``He handled my pitches
well.''... The batting leaders in the independent Northern League
included several players with local ties. Madison's Chris Vasquez
(College of the Canyons) was second at .369. Sioux City's Chad
Thornhill (CSUN) was fifth at .354, and Bryan Warner (Glendale
College) was eighth at .349. Ex-Dodgers Billy Ashley (.352 for St.
Paul) and 39-year-old Mike Marshall (league-leading .375 for
Schaumburg) are among the Northern League's Top 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
