<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9891 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETS-AT-WORK-ART-2TAK     07-05 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-AT-WORK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GROWING POPULARITY OF BRINGING DOGS TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In most respects, Kratz &AMP; Jensen is a sleek,
efficient Manhattan public relations firm, with white ceiling fans,
brushed aluminum accents and ample windows overlooking the Flatiron
district. Look closely, however, and something altogether
unexpected flashes by. Was that a tail?
</P>
<P>
   Every Friday, the company allows staff members to bring their
dogs to the office, and a dozen of the 50 employees arrive with a
briefcase in one hand and a leash in the other. David Kratz, the
founder, got the idea after he started bringing Derby, his standard
poodle, to the office a couple of days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it, so I think it's only fair that others can bring
their dogs in, too,'' he said. ``Dogs are the perfect company men.
They like to be with the group. They're pack animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was only a matter of time before the dog's snout
pushed its way into the corporate tent. The national observance
last month of the first Take Your Dog to Work Day, sponsored by Pet
Sitters International, a membership group in King, N.C., suggests
office dogs are on the rise. After all, many offices these days are
as formal as backyard barbecues, and Americans, who are known for
anthropomorphizing their pets, are cosseting and training their
dogs as never before.
</P>
<P>
   Employees say they bring their dogs to work because they hate to
leave them home alone, and they are more than willing to sacrifice
coffee breaks for trips to the fire hydrant. Once at the office,
they say, dogs help relieve stress and provide security for people
who keep late hours.
</P>
<P>
   It can also make one's life seem less compartmentalized. ``The
dog is my continuity _ a symbol of the seamlessness of work and
home and social life,'' said Barbara Brooks, the communications
director at Manhattanville College in Purchase, whose Labrador
retriever, Charlotte, can be found nestled under her desk three or
four days a week.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, dogs are not making their debut in the hushed,
button-down environs of large investment banks and law firms. But
they are leaving their paw prints at smaller, more creative
companies and nonprofit institutions. Some companies, like the
online services firm Talking Dog Media in Seattle, even have an
``open dog policy'' as a way to attract employees.
</P>
<P>
   Usually someone makes the first move: the boss or a high-ranking
employee arrives with dog in tow, and others follow. At
Manhattanville College, for instance, there seems to be a
contagion, with the dean of students bringing her cairn terrier to
the office, the athletic director his chow, the head librarian her
Scottish terrier, the head of health services her poodle and the
director of development her dachshund.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brooks found out about the opening for her position from the
vice president of student affairs and dean of students, Mary
Corrarino. The two had first met at a dog run in Manhattan. When
Ms. Brooks drove to Manhattanville for her interview, she was
surprised to see Annie, Ms. Corrarino's cairn terrier, in the
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of working in higher education and living in
Westchester County was very appealing,'' Ms. Brooks said. ``The
notion of having my dog curled up at my feet was terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone applauds the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's loathsome,'' said Judy Jacksina, the owner of the
Jacksina Company, a public relations firm representing Broadway and
Off Broadway shows. ``There are so many pressures at work, and if
you're the other person in the office, it's not fair. Can we all
bring cats? What about goldfish? Where does it stop?''
</P>
<P>
   Most dog-friendly companies require that dogs be well mannered,
housebroken and free of fleas. Many employees who do not have dogs
do seem to genuinely enjoy having a colleague's or boss' dog
underfoot. Others, however, say they merely tolerate the office
mascot.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lees, the business manager of the Buddhist magazine
Tricycle, has survived a decade of dogs in her Manhattan office,
all belonging to the editor in chief and founder, Helen Tworkov.
</P>
<P>
   First there was Moses, a German shepherd who was ``affectionate
and wise'' but who growled at Ms. Lees on her first day of work.
Then there was Max, an ``extremely annoying and very needy''
dachshund. Now there is Mambo, a ``big mutt with a lot of
personality'' who ``ran around like crazy'' in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rule, I don't like it,'' Ms. Lees said of sharing office
space with her boss' pet. ``While I find the dogs charming, it's
disruptive. We've occasionally had soiled carpets and lunches
scarfed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Human resources administrators say the practice of allowing dogs
in the workplace can pose health risks for employees who are
allergic to animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When do the rights of one employee begin to infringe on the
rights of another employee?'' asked Donna M. Thiessen, past
president of the National Human Resources Association, a
professional organization based in Milwaukee. ``You don't need your
dog to do your job, but you do need to be free of allergic
symptoms. I don't know how companies balance that.''
</P>
<P>
   At Talking Dog Media, the answer is simple: people averse to
dogs need not apply. ``In the interview we ask people whether they
like dogs and if they are allergic to dogs,'' said Jean Miller, a
spokeswoman for the multimedia and educational software company.
``If you don't like dogs or you're allergic, this is not the
company for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there was a bark at her doorstep. ``No,'' Ms. Miller
told Zecke, a Shetland sheepdog pup. ``You have to go to your
mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy'' is the company president, Lisa Khatib, who began
welcoming all dogs after she discovered that an employee was
leaving two bichons frises in the car. ``It's become a perk,'' Mrs.
Khatib said. ``It did not start out that way, but it's one of those
happy accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   While dogs are trotting off to the office, other pets, whether
cats, birds or gerbils, continue to be left largely at home. Cats,
of course, are commonly spotted in the city's corner bodegas and
greasy spoons, where they prowl for mice.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say house cats in particular are much less adaptable
than dogs to the workplace. ``You can't take a cat daily because a
cat is too spooked by strange environments,'' said Dr. Wallace
Sife, a Brooklyn psychologist who specializes in the loss of a pet.
``You'd have to keep it in the cage the entire time, and the whole
purpose of bringing a pet is for a pleasant exchange during the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, dogs have become increasingly common sidekicks
for small business owners like Diane Mancher, whose public
relations firm, One Potato Productions, specializes in book
publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The pit bull terrier-Doberman pinscher mix makes Ms. Mancher and
the four account executives in her office feel protected. ``We're
all women, and we have a lot of messengers and delivery guys,'' she
said. ``Occasionally, they ask for a drink or want to use the
bathroom. When they see the dog, they are a lot less chatty and
pushy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some dogs have better attendance records than their owners. When
the theatrical agent Gary Krasny was out with pneumonia in April,
his 4-year-old bichon frise, Emma, showed up at his Times Square
office every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boyfriend or a colleague would pick her up in the morning
and take her home at night,'' he said. ``She can't stand it when
she stays home. She's a working dog.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no dog has received more attention in Manhattan than
Boomer, the golden retriever who belongs to Parks Commissioner
Henry J. Stern. But of late, the most publicized office dog in the
city is Lil, a bichon-wheaten terrier mix and the constant
companion of Marilyn Mode, the deputy commissioner for public
information of the New York City Police Department. It seems that
Lil's every misdeed, whether swiping a lunch or nipping a
sergeant's foot, is reported by the Newsday columnist Leonard
Levitt, who covers the police department.
</P>
<P>
   It was big news last year when an anonymous letter was sent to
the city's Health Department complaining of Lil's presence, and
Police Commissioner Howard Safir, after asking the legal department
to look into it, then declared that Lil could stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hours are rather unpredictable, and the commissioner
indulges me,'' Ms. Mode said in a recent interview. But she has
grown weary of Levitt's sardonic scrutiny of 20-pound Lil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Roosevelt said about Fala,'' she said, referring to
President Franklin Delano Roosevelt and his beloved Scottish
terrier. ``When FDR was accused of sending a gunboat back to pick
up Fala, he said he was used to the press taking shots at him and
his family, but he resented their going after Fala. Well, Lil
resents it, and so do I.''
</P>
<P>
   MBS Associates, a marketing firm in Montrose, which promotes
animal adoptions and pet products, participated in last month's
Take Your Dog to Work Day. The firm sponsored contests like ``best
dressed,'' ``most congenial,'' ``best trick'' and ``most
obedient.'' The president, Mal B. Schwartz, who has a mutt named
Dvorak, is thinking of allowing dogs every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy should be explored,'' he said. ``It adds to the
camaraderie around the office. People feel really good about it.
You know, there's more to working than getting work done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
