<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9893 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-CLASH-TWOTAKE     07-05 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-CLASH-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVING WEST SIDE NEIGHBORHOOD WORRIES SOME RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Despite everything, you still see Adolfo
Celedon in the old neighborhood. Walking the streets he has known
for 50 years, feeding the cats, chatting up the few friends who are
left.
</P>
<P>
   Some nights, he parks his minivan in front of the two-story
brick house at 1637 Jefferson St. that was home for much of his
life. Parks it, takes a long look at the old place, then ambles
down the hill to his new home. His new home, Celedon says, isn't a
safe place to park a car at night.
</P>
<P>
   Celedon's old West Side neighborhood is improving in many ways.
His former house, like many in the area, is being renovated inside
and out.
</P>
<P>
   Appraisals have increased, in some cases dramatically. The value
of a rehabbed house on the 1600 block of Summit Street, one block
from Celedon's old house, went from less than $5,000 in 1994 to
more than $80,000 this year. During the same time, another house in
that block went from an appraised value of $16,000 to $45,851.
</P>
<P>
   New people are moving into what has long been a working-class,
largely Hispanic community, slowly changing the character of the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody wins when urban neighborhoods change this way,
when property values go up and cafes and art galleries sprout in
corner storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   Among the losers: Longtime neighborhood residents such as the
65-year-old Celedon. People who suddenly find themselves searching
for affordable housing after spending their lives in close-knit
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Displacement is a central negative effect of gentrification,''
said Neil Smith, a professor of urban geography at Rutgers
University. ``It especially affects older residents on fixed
incomes.''
</P>
<P>
   And it may become a bigger problem as long-stagnant, inner-city
housing markets _ such as Kansas City's West Side _ continue to
rebound, said Chris Walker, director of Community and Economic
Development for the Urban Institute, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   It can happen in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   Renters can be priced out of the neighborhood as rents rise or
when apartments are converted into condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners can be the victims of higher property tax bills they
can't afford to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Increased code enforcement in blossoming neighborhoods can leave
financially strapped homeowners with fines to pay and repairs to
make _ and feelings of having no choice but to sell. That's a
particular concern on the West Side. A recent community meeting
drew about 60 residents and revealed deep neighborhood divisions on
the issue of code enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   An official in Mayor Kay Barnes' office is exploring how to
address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But however displacement happens, it can send a once-ordered
life reeling.
</P>
<P>
   Celedon's new place is just a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   A room on the second floor of the Roslin Hotel. A spare,
40-watt-bulb type of place. A dresser, an end table. A compact
refrigerator and a toaster oven in one corner. A mini TV on the one
chair, so Celedon's visitors, when he has them, have to perch on
the big metal bed that dominates the room. He shares the bathroom
down the hall. No shower; just a tub, a toilet and a sink beneath a
dirty mirror whose frame is held together by duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it has the one amenity that counts _ it's as close to the
old neighborhood as he can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the feeling in my body, in my head,'' Celedon said.
``That's where I spent most of my years. Me, my mother, my wife,
all the people in the neighborhood. I liked the West Side.''
</P>
<P>
   Celedon arrived on the West Side from Mexico as a teen-ager in
June 1949, after his mother married a man who had a house there.
</P>
<P>
   He learned English and built a life. He worked on the railroads,
trained as a welder, got married. Celedon, his wife, Ernestina, and
Celedon's mother settled in the house on Jefferson Street.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Celedon's mother died. Ten years later, Ernestina, a
diabetic, succumbed to a series of strokes. Celedon eventually
retired.
</P>
<P>
   But Ernestina's illness had left him with debts. Bills piled up.
And the neighborhood changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People moved in,'' he said. ``They're always talking about the
home repair because they have the money to do it. A lot of people,
they don't have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The people spending money to fix up the houses like the
neighborhood's economic diversity, said Kathy Marchant, who moved
into the neighborhood in 1982 and opened the Bluebird Cafe, a
vegetarian restaurant, in 1994 at 1700 Summit St.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a diverse group of people trying to build something,''
Marchant said. ``It's the healthiest urban environment I've ever
lived in.This should be a model for urban redevelopment.''
</P>
<P>
   She chafed at using the word ``gentrification'' to describe
what's happening on the West Side.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
