<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9896 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-CLASH-2NDTAKE     07-05 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-CLASH-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVING WEST SIDE NEIGHBORHOOD WORRIES SOME RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... happening on the West Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That implies, `We don't care about your life,' &UR; '' Marchant
said. ``Rich guys moving in on the poor guys. And I don't perceive
that happening here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Brooks, a friend of Celedon's who has lived in the
neighborhood for 45 years, doesn't share Marchant's perception.
Brooks doesn't have a problem with his new neighbors fixing up
their houses. But he said it can cause problems for some of the
older neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're putting some big money into some of those houses,''
Brooks said. ``It puts a hurting on the little man who can't afford
it. Next thing you know, city codes come out. They write you up,
write you up, write you up, you have to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Increased code enforcement is often the first sign of impending
displacement, said Joyce Probst of the Chicago Rehab Network, a
housing group that has studied displacement in that city.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Code enforcement) is one of the more subtle ways people are
made to feel uncomfortable in an area they've lived in a long
time,'' Probst said.
</P>
<P>
   Code enforcement is thriving on the West Side, according to a
May report by the city's Neighborhood and Community Services
Department. The code inspection area based at the West Side
Community Action Network center had the highest average monthly
number of cases during the preceding six months of any of the seven
inspection areas based at such centers.
</P>
<P>
   The West Side averaged 169 code enforcement cases per month,
according to the report. The next-highest average was 154, in the
Gracemor area. The average monthly number of cases for all seven
areas was 117.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think code enforcement is being used as a tool over
there to drive out the less fortunate,'' said Donovan Mouton,
Barnes' neighborhood advocate. ``Maybe the bar of expectation has
been raised a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Celedon said he did his best to keep his place up, doing the
little things he could do himself. It wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   A code enforcement officer cited him for an overgrown back yard.
Then, Celedon couldn't afford to properly fix his leaking roof,
which heavily damaged the inside of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Scared, Celedon sold his house last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have no money, you're forced to sell the house for
whatever you can get, because someone will turn you in to city
hall,'' Celedon said. ``I didn't have the money to do it. I didn't
want to move out of the neighborhood. I wanted to stay until I got
old.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to discount fear as a reason for selling a house after
nearly a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   But experts say fear is a powerful motivator among immigrants
once code enforcement officers start citing a neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not know this isn't a felony,'' said Walker of the
Urban Institute. ``This is not going to get you sent back to
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   On the West Side, longtime residents say code enforcement has
focused on long-ignored violations.
</P>
<P>
   The community meeting last month only highlighted the
differences between longtime residents and newcomers when it comes
to code enforcement. Several older residents said newcomers were
trying to impose their own high-end aesthetics on the West Side.
Newcomers pointed out that code enforcement laws were designed to
promote safety.
</P>
<P>
   Larry and Nancy Dunaway have lived in their Jefferson Street
house for 23 years. They were fined $71 for having an old Ford
Mustang on a ramp in their back yard. The fine angered the
Dunaways, but they're more worried about Nancy Dunaway's parents,
who have lived in the house across the street for 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmie and Mabel Goss are in their 70s, retired and in poor
health with little money. Most of the time, you can find them on
their front porch, watching what little of the world passes their
part of Jefferson Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they do is sit over there and worry,'' Larry Dunaway said.
</P>
<P>
   To Celedon, neighborliness seems to have been lost in the
transition. Nowadays, he said, people just don't seem willing to
lend a hand to a struggling neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect them to give me money,'' Celedon said. ``But
give me a hand, like in the old days. There was good people. People
would help.''
</P>
<P>
   Some help might be on the way. Mouton, of the mayor's office,
said he hopes to start a local committee soon to offer city or
community assistance to those cited for code violations who seem to
want to make the needed repairs.
</P>
<P>
   There are other ways to combat displacement.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has set aside money to help struggling homeowners
pay for repairs of code enforcement violations. Many local
nonprofit groups, including the West Side Housing Organization,
offer low-interest loans for home repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Other solutions could include exemptions from increased property
taxes for longtime homeowners, and rent control at some apartments,
Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to look at any creative ideas that reach a common
solution, that give people the freedom to live where they want
to,'' Mouton said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Mouton added, folks have to take care of their properties.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, nothing can guarantee that people won't be
displaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people of different backgrounds find it difficult to live
together, the people of the lower economic status will be slowly
eased out,'' Probst said. ``That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Celedon is not quite sure what to do with himself. He thinks of
looking for a new place; he considers moving back to Mexico. He
sits on the bed, writing poetry and songs in Spanish. He has
drawers full of poems and songs.
</P>
<P>
   Celedon worries about other folks still living in the
neighborhood, people like Jimmie and Mabel Goss. He hopes they
don't suffer the same fate he did. And he hopes the new neighbors
see the wisdom of helping out the older residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the neighborhood to improve,'' he said, ``they need
to help each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
