<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOTAL-ELF-ART-NYT &LR;      07-05 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOTAL-ELF-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOTAL FINA IN HOSTILE BID FOR ELF ACQUITAINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Total Fina SA announced a hostile bid
Monday for Elf Acquitaine SA worth nearly $43 billion, setting off
the third big takeover battle in France this year, this time in the
oil industry,
</P>
<P>
   Elf Acquitaine, an oil refiner and chemicals conglomerate,
quickly denounced the offer and lined up a stable of investment
banks to plot its defense. Its response set the stage for a raucous
new corporate battle that follows the one between France's biggest
banks and the recent battle between two French financiers for
control of Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and analysts began betting on an extended battle that
could very likely lead to a counteroffer from Elf Acquitaine or to
rival bids from other oil companies, and shares of Elf Acquitaine
surged 21.5 percent on the Bourse in Paris Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As in the three-way takeover battle between the big French
banks, Total's offer reflects both how much and how little French
business has changed in the last year or so.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the hostile bid marks another outbreak of
politically incorrect corporate behavior in a country where
takeovers have traditionally been negotiated quietly behind closed
doors. Yet, Total Fina's executives are banking in part on French
nationalist instincts to win their case. Elf Acquitaine was once
owned by the French government, and Paris retains a so-called
``golden share'' to veto any merger it does not like.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with a number of huge-scale combinations recently
among the world's biggest oil companies, Total is portraying itself
as the only partner for Elf Acquitaine that would enable it to keep
up with the competition and still remain in French hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is necessary today to join forces to assure the
continued solid growth and to take our place as an oil major of the
first rank at a time when the industry is restructuring on a global
scale,'' said Total Fina's chairman, Thierry Desmarest.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from years of extremely low oil prices, British
Petroleum acquired Amoco for $55 billion and is now trying to
acquire ARCO. And Exxon is in the process of acquiring Mobil for
more than $80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Total Fina is itself the result of an $11 billion merger
between Total SA of France and Petrofina SA of Belgium. The
exchange of those shares closed last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If Desmarest is successful with his new bid, the combination of
Elf Acquitaine and Total Fina would have sales around $67 billion
and be the fourth-largest oil company after Exxon-Mobil, BP Amoco
and Royal Dutch/Shell.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Paris on Monday, Desmarest said he was
optimistic about winning the government's approval.
</P>
<P>
   But Elf Acquitaine is almost certain to lobby for a government
rejection. The company has been laying its own plans for
acquisitions as part of a broader corporate restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the two companies said executives had exchanged
ideas for months, ever since British Petroleum announced its
agreement to acquire Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   When the talks failed to produce a deal, Desmarest moved on his
own. Advised by Credit Suisse First Boston, Merrill Lynch and
Paribas Capital, Total Fina began earnest planning for the takeover
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the company said it would offer four of its own shares
for three of Elf Acquitaine.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a premium of about 15 percent over the Elf
Acquitaine closing price on Friday of 145.9 euros, or $149.40. The
stock closed Monday at 177.30 euros, while Total Fina shares edged
up four-tenths of 1 percent, to 128.5 euros. The surge in the Elf
Acquitaine shares essentially eliminated the premium over current
prices, reflecting investors' belief that Total or some other
company would be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Elf Acquitaine's management poured cold water on
the plan. ``The offer has not been the subject of any study or
discussions with Elf's management, and is therefore considered as
being hostile,'' the company said in a terse statement Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of investment banks from Wall Street and Europe sought
the right Monday to advise Elf Acquitaine on its takeover defense.
Among those offering their services were Goldman, Sachs; Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter; Lazard Freres, and Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Cantelaube, an oil industry analyst with Credit Lyonnais
Securities in Paris, said Total Fina's offer was hardly generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be getting Elf for a very cheap price,'' he said.
Partly for that reason, he added, Total's bid is probably just the
first salvo in a long battle. ``This will go on for a long time and
there will be a lot of turns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Total paid a substantially higher premium of nearly 37
percent when it acquired Petrofina. But Christophe de Margerie,
Total's president for production and exploration, said that Elf
Acquitaine's stock had already appreciated somewhat in the last
several months as a result of takeover speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarest said he had tried without success in the last three
months to persuade the Elf Acquitaine chief executive, Phillippe
Jaffre, on the wisdom of a friendly merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make him more sensitive to the advantages of this
approach,'' he said at a news conference in Paris. ``I was not
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the deal is approved, the combined company would be half
the size of the combined Exxon and Mobil. Together, Total and Elf
Acquitaine produce about 2.1 million barrels of oil and oil
equivalents a day, compared with about 4.3 million barrels produced
by Exxon and Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarest contended that a merger with Elf Acquitaine would
yield about $1.2 billion a year in savings and ``synergies.'' The
two companies both have operations in the North Sea, Iran and in
other areas, though Total has been more focused on the Middle East
and Far East. Total has much smaller operations in the United
States, including about 2,000 gasoline stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we like about the deal is not only the potential for
synergies, but for growth,'' de Margerie said during a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's move is not the first time that Desmarest, 54, has
made a bold move. Two years ago, Total was one of the first Western
oil companies to strike a major refining deal with Iran, defying
U.S. Government protests. Since then, Elf Acquitaine and others
have followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarest attracted considerable attention earlier this year
with his purchase of Petrofina, a move that made Total slightly
bigger than Elf Acquitaine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
