<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAC-DONATIONS-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE CAMPAIGN DONATIONS TO MISSOURI AND KANSAS SENATORS AND
CONGRESSMEN ORIGINATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Reps. Pat Danner and Karen McCarthy of Kansas
City breezed back into office last fall with plenty of money from
political action committees but virtually nothing from individuals
giving less than $200 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what the two Democrats wanted.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to how incumbents raise money, wide differences
exist among members of Congress from Missouri and Kansas, data from
the Center for Responsive Politics show.
</P>
<P>
   The amount House incumbents received from individuals giving
$1,000 or less in 1997-98 ranged from 3 percent by Danner _ the
lowest in all of Congress _ to 67 percent for Rep. Jim Talent, a
St. Louis Republican who now is running for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Political action committees accounted for 79 percent of Danner's
money, but only 30 percent of Talent's. On average, House
incumbents got about 42 percent of their money from PACs, which can
give up to $5,000 to each candidate in the primary and that much
more in the general.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four area senators, Missouri Republican John Ashcroft
took the least (24 percent) from PACs dating back to 1993, while
Kansas Republican Pat Roberts took the most (50 percent) since his
jump from the House in 1996. The Federal Election Commission
numbers indicate incumbent senators seeking re-election overall
took 25 percent from PACs in the last two-year cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Although recent proposals on campaign finance reform have
focused on large, corporate ``soft money'' contributions that
benefit candidates indirectly, PACs still get significant attention
from critics and candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, people should have a problem if a candidate is
relying overwhelmingly on special-interest PAC money for their
campaign,'' said Eric Schmeltzer, spokesman for Public Campaign, a
Washington group advocating public funding for candidates who limit
private contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians, however, said there is little difference
between getting contributions from individuals and from PACs.
Danner said PACs are a way for people in various professions,
unions or causes to be supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a conglomerate of small donors who otherwise couldn't
make an impact or a statement,'' McCarthy said. ``Those are your
teachers and your nurses. They gather together to make
contributions that are meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy received about 60 percent of her campaign money in
1997-98 from PACs. As for individual contributions, she received
only 2 percent from people giving $200 or less but 30 percent from
those giving $200 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast, Rep. Ike Skelton, a Lexington, Mo., Democrat,
received 23 percent of his individual contributions from people who
gave $200 or less and 18 percent from those giving $200 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always gotten small donations. It's a matter of seeking
donations from everyone,'' Skelton said. ``People, whether they
write a $25 check or a $100 check, want to be part of the process.
I really appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said that instead of taking money from small
contributors last year, she threw them a party at a Westport bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a conscious decision not to raise money from small
donors in this election cycle,'' McCarthy said. ``They had been so
important in my first election, we just wanted to thank them.''
</P>
<P>
   Danner, who also didn't have a strong opponent last fall, said
she had no reason to raise money from individuals. In the 1995-96
election cycle, 21 percent of her money came from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
