<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9904 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAC-DONATIONS-2NDTAKE     07-05 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAC-DONATIONS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE CAMPAIGN DONATIONS TO MISSOURI AND KANSAS SENATORS AND
CONGRESSMEN ORIGINATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... money came from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have a serious enough (election) challenge, I'll go
back to my contributors and they'll be there for me,'' Danner said.
``I don't believe in asking for money just to be asking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Danner had fund-raisers in Washington and collected more than
$190,000 from political action committees over the 1997-98 period.
She raised money in Washington so people wouldn't wonder about her
intent to run again, she said, adding it was also to build reserves
in case she has significant opposition in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   A potential contender, Kansas City Councilwoman Teresa Loar,
expressed no surprise that Danner raised so little from individuals
and so much from PACs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few people here really have any contact with her,'' said
Loar, a Northland Republican. ``I've yet to run into anyone who's
had any contact with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Loar said she also disagrees that PAC money is basically money
from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``PAC money is special-interest money,'' Loar said. ``I'm not
opposed to PAC money, but I've been in politics long enough to know
that those who give money will come knocking at your door.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that PACs expect something for their money is evident
in that they give much more to incumbents than to challengers, said
Tony Raymond of Public Disclosure Inc., a group that analyzes
campaign spending data.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a cynical look because they only support the party in
power,'' Raymond said.
</P>
<P>
   PACs gave $158 million to incumbents in House and Senate races
in the last election cycle and only $21.5 million to their
challengers.
</P>
<P>
   A few members of Congress, such as Republican Rep. Jim Leach of
Iowa, have a policy against taking any PAC money. Leach would like
to abolish PAC money, although that is not part of major campaign
reform now being weighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The congressman believes that the way special interests work
corrupts the system and if you don't tie yourself to PACs by
accepting their money, your vote is never in question,'' Leach
spokesman Doug Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   But David Rehr, president of the National Association of
Business PACs, said that PACs are not seen anymore as a
special-interest evil, as proven by the absence of bills to limit
their influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members are more educated about what PACs are,'' Rehr said.
The fact that donations to PACs must be disclosed eases concern, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, facing a re-election challenge from Missouri Gov. Mel
Carnahan, said he wasn't aware he received almost three times as
much from individuals as from PACs since first running in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm low on PACs or high on people,'' Ashcroft
said. ``No money goes into PACs that individuals don't give.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' chief of staff and former campaign manager, Leroy
Towns, said he didn't know that Roberts has raised a comparatively
high 50 percent of his money from PACs since running in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's harder to raise the kind of dollars from
individuals in Kansas that you might raise in California or more
urban states,'' Towns said.
</P>
<P>
   Among contributions from individuals, 34 percent of Roberts'
money has come from people outside of Kansas. That compares to 31
percent for the other Kansas senator, Sam Brownback. In Missouri,
Ashcroft raised 18 percent from individuals from out of Missouri,
compared to 36 percent for Republican Kit Bond.
</P>
<P>
   House members tend to receive a smaller percentage of money from
out-of-state than do senators, but not always. Skelton, for
example, got 35 percent of his individual contributions from
non-residents of Missouri. McCarthy got 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics calculated the percentages
but had no figures that were expanded to include money from PACs.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Public Interest Research Group is lobbying for
campaign reforms that would include a law against raising more than
25 percent of funds from outside of election districts, including
PAC money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be appropriate for small contributors in a district
to form a PAC,'' said Derek Cressman, democracy campaign director
for the group. ``We're not opposed to PACs, but the reality is a
great amount of money is coming from outside the districts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
