<SLUG> BC-SOC-ARRIVAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GETS ROUSING WELCOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Moments after the United States women's national
team arrived from China after capturing the 1991 Women's World Cup,
U.S. coach Tony DiCicco admitted he could count the handful of
supporters there to greet them at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   That was eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If Team USA's arrival from San Francisco to Los Angeles
International Airport for Saturday's Women's World Cup championship
against China at the Rose Bowl is any indication of what lies ahead
-- get ready for a wild week.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. defeated Brazil 2-0 at Stanford Stadium Sunday while
China routed Norway 5-0 in the other semifinal, setting up
Saturday's rematch of the 1996 Olympic Gold Medal match, won by the
United States, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   There were hundreds of young fans at the airport Monday, hoping
to get a glimpse of Mia Hamm, Briana Scurry, Michelle Akers, or
whoever their favorite player might be.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Julie Foudy captured the moment with a video camera
as the team passed by fans under an arch of balloons and past a
line of young girls restrained by rope's. As a band played, girls
wearing World Cup shirts pressed yellow sunflowers into some
players' hands and chanted ``U-S-A, U-S-A.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day has been kind of a surprise at the level of support
and notoriety this team is experiencing,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco
said. ``This was awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt like Ricky Martin, but I felt like a coach of
a very, very successful team. A team that's won the hearts of
America and a team that hopefully will win the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, the U.S. must beat a sound Chinese team, a
team that has beaten the U.S. twice in the past year and one that
Norwegian coach Per-Mathias Hogmo says has a good chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that China will be the favorite for me, they
already beat the USA twice, so I think they will be the favorite in
the final,'' Hogmo said, ``But they will meet a very enthusiastic
American team so I think it will be an interesting fight.''
</P>
<P>
   China coach Ma Yuanan, speaking after Sunday's victory, is
looking forward to the meeting with the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best team we've had in a few years,''
said Yuanan. ``Next Saturday, the U.S. will be stronger than (what
we faced) tonight. I want the team (that beat the U.S. on April
25th) to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States was scheduled to practice Monday at
Pomona-Pitzer College, but DiCicco decided to give his players the
day off instead.
</P>
<P>
   They will resume training this morning in preparation for
Saturday's final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we need some rest,'' said midfielder Carla Overbeck.
``It's a sense of relief and accomplishment (to get to the final)
knowing the quality and caliber of team's that were in this
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're relieved, you're ecstatic and we're going to enjoy it a
little bit before training again for the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a big sigh of relief, because many have counted on the
U.S. to reach the final for the tournament to be considered a
success.
</P>
<P>
   At least the first indication of that came Monday as tournament
organizers announced that the Rose Bowl was sold-out for Saturday's
final.
</P>
<P>
   Now the only piece missing is an American championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thankful this team is still playing in the
tournament,'' said striker Mia Hamm. ``We've known from day one it
wasn't going to be easy and it hasn't been easy. I think that 3-2
game against Germany really stretched us and I think this game
(against Brazil) stretched us. Now we just have to get ready for
one more.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ Associated Press contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
