<SLUG> BC-SOC-TICKETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLOUT EXPECTED FOR U.S.-CHINA GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The remaining tickets for Saturday's 1999 FIFA
Women's World Cup championship at the Rose Bowl between the United
States and China were gobbled up Monday as Marla Messing, president
and CEO of the WWC organizing committee, announced that a sell-out
crowd of 85,000 is expected -- a record for a women's only sporting
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a sell-out of the final, our biggest day is still to
come,'' said Messing. ``But I think we can say that the tournament
has been a smashing success. This Saturday, the Rose Bowl will be
awash with pageantry, music and tens of thousands of World Cup fans
who are united in their passion for this event. It will be an
occasion to remember for women's sports.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States, 1991 Women's World Cup champions and 1996
Olympic Gold Medalists face China, Silver Medalists in Atlanta and
winner of two of its last three games against the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's match is a doubleheader, featuring a third place game
between Norway and Brazil. Between matches, the closing ceremonies
will be conducted, featuring a performance by singer/actress
Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   For the tournament, an average of more than 35,000 have attended
Women's World Cup matches, including over 22,000 for dates not
involving the United States. There have been three crowds of more
than 65,000, including 78,972 at Giants Stadium and 73,123 at
Stanford, Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
