<HEADER>
A9908 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SOCCER-COLUMN-LAD     07-05 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM HAS CAPTURED AMERICA'S HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You can't compare what's happening here to the
1994 World Cup. We were guests at our own party then, enjoying the
drum-beating sounds of the Brazilians and the soccer-crazed fans
from the rest of the world who showed us a thing or two about
passion and loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   There were real tears of pain for the losers, so bad that one
fella from Italy said he would wait a couple weeks before going
home after the Italians lost to Brazil in the final. He said his
country needed time to mourn.
</P>
<P>
   We're certainly not at that point, and maybe we'll never have
that kind of patriotism that hurts so much when you lose. But we
have the U.S. women's national team and regardless of what happens
Saturday when they face China for the Women's World Cup title at
the Rose Bowl, we're going to remember the summer of 1999 -- the
year we fell in love with our American ladies.
</P>
<P>
   Forget for a minute they represent beauty and power, femininity
and toughness, models and role models.
</P>
<P>
   What we love about this team is the kid in their eyes, the
innocence of pure enjoyment that came with winning back in the AYSO
days at your city park. You remember how excited the parent's were
at those games too, most of whom were learning about this sport for
this first time.
</P>
<P>
   That is what these women are all about. You feel the multi-year
friendships they have with one another, and understand what every
backflip, scream and goal scoring dance means to them -- just as
you did your teammate in the sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to knock men's soccer to enjoy them. Some have
suggested they show more skill than team's in Major League Soccer,
or that they're more exciting than our U.S. men's team -- and at
some levels, both may be true.
</P>
<P>
   They make this game look so graceful, easy at times because
they've spent over a decade together honing their team game -- and
even blind, they could find each other on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that, in a day when athletes are lucky to stick around
with the same team for a season, this team has become women
together, sharing as much of their lives off the field as they do
on.
</P>
<P>
   You have to appreciate that.
</P>
<P>
   Why is David Letterman plugging them nightly? Why was President
Bill Clinton checking his watch, hoping the referee would end last
week's game against Germany so the U.S. team could advance? Simple.
They have jumped on the wagon for the same reason's as your
neighbor next door, or the friend you have that hates soccer. This
U.S. team is a throwback to what team sports once was -- sacrifice
instead of all-star appearances, championship dreams instead of
money.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this is Lake Placid all over again. It's not the
Olympics, but we're watching what feels like our buddies from the
neighborhood enjoy the time of their lives in front of sold-out
crowds and millions of television viewers.
</P>
<P>
   In a day when multi-million dollar basketball athletes turn down
invitations to play for our Olympic team because their off-season
schedules are too busy, or tennis standouts turn down U.S. Davis
Cup invitations because of overwork -- thank God we have our U.S.
women's soccer team to show us what representing your country is
all about.
</P>
<P>
   In a day athletes ask children for money in exchange for
autographs and humanitarian award football players get caught
soliciting sex before Super Bowl's -- thank God we have something
pure, something better than that, even if it's for such a short
time.
</P>
<P>
   You want dirt on this team, look on their jerseys, complete with
grass stains and blood. That's how we like it, a team with guts,
one that thrives on pure emotion and players who want to win as
much as the painted-faced kids in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad it has to end this weekend. We're going to miss our
girls of summer. Maybe we'll see them on cereal boxes in month's
ahead or hopefully they will go on a victory tour leading to the
2000 Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, thanks for the lesson's learned. You showed our
kids and their parents what team sports are all about again. And
thanks for showing our mega-rich athletes that fans care more about
commitment and hard-work than anything else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
