<SLUG> BC-R-PRIVATE-MAILBOXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE MAILBOX SERVICES CALL NEW POSTAL RULES UNFAIR  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn.)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHAEL BRICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vincent Cobb never knows what he will find in the
six-by-nine-inch mailbox he rents for his modest consulting
business. But recently, even he was surprised when, among the usual
bills, proposals and letters, he found a disturbing notice: All his
mail is wrongly addressed, and as soon as October he may open the
box to find nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   On Cobb's letterhead, the box is Suite 373 of a tony Wilshire
Boulevard address in Santa Monica, Calif. But under new Postal
Service regulations, Cobb's mail must bear the label PMB, for
private mailbox. Otherwise it will be marked ``Undeliverable as
Addressed'' and returned to the sender. On top of that, mailbox
renters must disclose their home addresses to the Post Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an impossibility,'' Cobb said. ``I don't know who's
going to send me mail.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes have prompted a flurry of indignant letters to
Congress from people who receive their mail through stores like
Pakmail and Mail Boxes Etc. Around 2 million Americans rent boxes
at 10,000 such stores, up from 7,000 a decade ago, often to lend
their business addresses prestige, sometimes because they have no
fixed address. Store owners and mailbox renters say the new rules
invade their privacy and pose a financial threat to their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   To comply with the regulations adopted in March, stores are
gathering new applications from all customers. To rent a mailbox,
customers must now submit two forms of identification showing their
home addresses, which will be kept on file and reported to the
Postal Service. Law enforcement agencies and credit card companies
asked for the requirements, citing rampant mail fraud.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate flares, the Postal Service is benefiting from an
uncanny fluke of timing. Concerns about mail fraud gained credence
in recent weeks after the government issued a warrant for the
arrest of Martin R. Frankel, the money manager accused of pulling
off the most elaborate mail fraud ever. Frankel used Mail Boxes
Etc. to receive mail for several dummy corporations, court records
show.
</P>
<P>
   Few people dispute that the new safeguards will take a bite out
of crimes like identity theft, in which a person rents a mailbox in
someone else's name and applies for credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   But small business owners worry about the cost. Even if they
notify everyone who regularly sends them mail, every business card
they have handed out without a PMB will have been for naught.
</P>
<P>
   The letter-writing campaign has spawned a lobbying group now
plying Congress to overturn the regulations. Rep. Ron Paul,
R-Texas, has filed a resolution that would nullify the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a small-business man, spending $5,000 or $10,000 for
new stationery can just ruin your business,'' said Michael
Sullivan, a spokesman for Paul.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service adopted the regulations over the objections
of 8,097 letter writers, most of them small business owners. Only
10 comments favored the changes, although those came from weightier
authors like American Express and the Secret Service. A spokesman
for the Postal Service said fighting fraud outweighed the right to
use ``suite'' on a letterhead. While not the criminal kind, that
small deception is a bit of a fraud in itself, added Norm
Schrestrom, spokesman for the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a cloak of anonymity,'' he said. The uproar over PMB
``will be much ado about nothing once people get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, dissension reigns. Given that the Postal
Service competes with the stores for business, conspiracy theories
abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a huge burden on the actual small businesses, people
using the service and people providing the service,'' Sullivan
said. ``One can only conclude that it is to drive these out of
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has owners of Mailboxes Etc. stores doing verbal
somersaults as they phrase their criticism of the regulations. The
stores are franchises with separate owners, but 250 of them have
secured deals with the Postal Service to buy stamps at a discounted
rate, making them loath to rock the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy concerns have made for some unlikely bedfellows.
Last week, both the National Coalition Against Domestic Violence
and the National Coalition for the Homeless denounced the plan to
require home addresses. Abused spouses do not want their addresses
known, while the homeless have no addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Since adopting the regulations, the Postal Service has noticed
that the plan contradicts privacy rules spelled out in its own
charter. On Friday, the service proposed revisions that would allow
only law enforcement agencies to obtain home addresses. But
conflicting proposals under consideration now would still have the
PMB requirement take effect by October 1999 or April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, mailbox renters envision all manner of
catastrophes if their mail is returned. Many business owners
receive their personal mail in the rented boxes as well, and some
fear they could miss anything from a tax form to a product recall
notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to contact 1,500 to 2,000 people that I know
of,'' said Rick Merritt, a computer consultant who has dropped
everything to run the hastily assembled group Postal Watch. ``The
real problem is the ones I don't know of.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the changes argue that the Postal Service has no
right to decide what mail will be delivered. Small business owners
said that marking their mail ``Undeliverable'' would mislead the
person who shelled out 33 cents for the stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Extending the grace period to April seems to have pleased no
one. Instead of switching to PMB in the proposed six months, Cobb
is considering simply ignoring the new rules out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to do that in theory, but I'm not going to be the
first to jump off the pier,'' he said. ``As soon as somebody has
provable damages, there will be a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, small business owners have done their homework.
Merritt went so far as to look up the laws regarding suing the
Postal Service. He is pretty sure he can clear up to $1,000 plus
legal fees the first time he can prove the regulations cost him a
piece of mail.
</P>
<P>
   After the money, it is that presumed stigma that vexes box
holders most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do in fact have an office on Wilshire Boulevard,'' Cobb
said. ``It's six by nine inches, but it's mine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
