r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPLANE-BUILDER-TWOT     07-05 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPLANE-BUILDER-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE OF FLIGHT KEEPS 86-YEAR-OLD AIRPLANE BUILDER YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATES CITY, Mo. _ When he was 15, Andy Anderson decided to build
an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1929, and he lived outside a small town in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a lot of spare airplane parts lying around.
</P>
<P>
   But the desire to fly above the fields burned in this farm boy.
He remembered the summer day 11 years earlier when a plane flew
over Dow City. The town celebrated on Main Street. Horses
scattered. People greeted the pilot like a hero.
</P>
<P>
   So when the time came to stop dreaming and start building, Andy
made do with parts from a blacksmith, lumberyard and hardware
store. He used an engine from an old motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   His plane flew.
</P>
<P>
   Not high or far, but it got off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll still fly,'' Anderson, now 86, said Thursday at his
hangar south of Bates City, Mo., in rural Lafayette County. That
homemade plane sits inside, crammed with another dozen or so he has
built or is building.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has flown for more than 70 years. He's barnstormed and
crop-dusted all over the country. But, in a way, he hasn't traveled
far. The grassy runway he uses now isn't much different from that
Iowa field where he soared 20 feet above the ground when Hoover was
president.
</P>
<P>
   In the evenings, after a day of cutting metal and gluing wood
for wings and fuselages, Anderson flies. As he soars above
cornfields and cow pastures, he thinks what he would like to build
next; what he could do to make a plane fly better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm old, but I still have a boy's ideas,'' he said. He
estimates he's built more than 100 planes.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration says Anderson, who's never
had a flying lesson, is among the last of his kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done things that we read about in books,'' said Walt
Hutchings, a supervisor in the FAA's Kansas City office.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the agency gave Anderson the ``Charles Taylor
Master Mechanic Award,'' named for the man who built the Wright
brothers' first engine.
</P>
<P>
   FAA safety inspector Jerry Garrison has visited Anderson's
runway and hangar often.
</P>
<P>
   ``That old man can dream something up, draw it out on paper,
build it, and it will fly,'' Garrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson shares his knowledge and past with his grandson and
great-grandson, Mark and ``Young Andy'' Anderson, who live next to
the hangar.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in this family flies. Mark Anderson built his first
plane when he was in high school. He's taken his planes to shows
and won first prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Mark's son, Andy, 13, has started work on a glider.
</P>
<P>
   It's practically genetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad flies, I fly, my son flies _ we do this because of
him,'' Mark said of his grandfather. ``We all grew up around itwe
heard the stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us ever wanted to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark's son, Young Andy, put it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``He (his great-grandfather) told me if I didn't like airplanes,
he would kick my rear,'' the boy said. ``And then he said he'd kick
my rear again just so I wouldn't forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gonna help me build my glider.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9915 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPLANE-BUILDER-2NDT     07-05 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPLANE-BUILDER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE OF FLIGHT KEEPS 86-YEAR-OLD AIRPLANE BUILDER YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... build my glider.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Anderson knows he's doing things most people his age quit
doing 20 years ago _ or never did at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not going to some old-folks home and sit there like a
wilted carrot,'' he said. ``I've got too many things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   People who love airplanes have heard of this man. They've seen
his planes in museums, and they come from all over the country to
visit his hilltop hangar. He says he'd get more work done if people
would leave him alone.
</P>
<P>
   He also restores old cars and trucks. And during the winter, he
writes poetry.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS)I wonder how I lived, but I don't want to boast
</P>
<P>
   I flew the old Eagle by the seat of my pants.
</P>
<P>
   You know, that's what counted the most _
</P>
<P>
   All those stunts and flying I did by chance.(END ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   One day in the late 1920s, the undertaker in Dow City saw Andy
Anderson running down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy! Come here, boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy stopped. The undertaker cupped his hands together and held
them to the youngster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got you right here, Andy. If you don't stop messing with
those airplanes, I'm gonna close 'em up.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy smiled. He already had been in the air and knew there was
no coming down. He'd built a glider. He worked at his grandparents'
lumberyard and instead of taking money, he took his pay in boards.
The yard man sawed them into 1-inch slats.
</P>
<P>
   The story of that first glider has become family lore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started running down this hill and just about the time he
thought he couldn't run no more, that glider took him up,'' Mark
said. ``That was the first time he flew.''
</P>
<P>
   His second glider could be pulled by a car.
</P>
<P>
   Andy's next project was a Model T powered by a propeller. He put
the engine on backward so he could mount a propeller that he had
carved from a large piece of oak.
</P>
<P>
   He drove his ``contraption'' around the yard until his father
made him take it apart.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the airplane with the motorcycle engine, and he's been
flying ever since.
</P>
<P>
   To get ideas for his early planes, he scraped together enough
gas money to drive to Kansas City, where he watched workers build
the American Eagle at a factory near what's now the Downtown
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd buy me five hamburgers for a nickel apiece and a Dr.
Pepper, and I'd sit there all day and watch them build those
planes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1930s, he was able to buy an Eagle. That's when he
started barnstorming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in those days, small towns would have a ball game on
Sunday afternoon. We'd land and give rides,'' Anderson said. ``I
gave a lot of people their first plane ride.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, he moved to Missouri, where he and his wife raised
three children.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson crop-dusted and worked as an air mapper for the state.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Phyllis, died in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   That fall, he married a schoolteacher 36 years his junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dark, and she couldn't see me very good,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he and Diane Anderson live near the hangar. Other family
members live nearby. The dog is Piper. The cat is Scout.
</P>
<P>
   Diane teaches school. Andy builds replicas of vintage planes.
</P>
<P>
   And he writes his poems.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS)Someday we will know where pilots go
</P>
<P>
   When their flight on earth is through
</P>
<P>
   Where air is clean and planes will gleam
</P>
<P>
   And skies are always blue.(END ITALICS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
