<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTDOG-CONTESTED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT DOG CONTEST MAY TURN ON A QUARTER OF A DOG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(pr) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Steve Keiner, an Atlantic City engineer, won
this year's Fourth of July hot-dog-eating contest at Coney Island,
his victory was touted as perfect for a patriotic day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to bring it back to the United States,'' he said of
the mustard-yellow leather belt that is awarded to the champion in
the Nathan's Famous contest. It had been in the hands of winners
from Japan for the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   But within hours, Keiner's victory was under scrutiny. Editors
at the cable television station New York 1 said the videotape
showed that Keiner had begun to eat before the starting signal. The
corpulent Keiner, who swallowed 20\ hot dogs in 12 minutes, edged
out ``Hungry'' Charles Hardy, the second-place winner, by a quarter
of a dog.
</P>
<P>
   The starting signal _ a shouted ``Go!'' _ was preceded by a
countdown from 10. On a slow-motion replay of the videotape, Keiner
appears to be taking a bite at ``one.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, a 320-pound correction officer, said by telephone Monday
from his home in Brooklyn, ``I've been cheated.'' He said he could
easily have eaten another half of a hot dog during the split
second. He called for a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   But George Shea, a spokesman for Nathan's Famous, which has been
running the annual contests since 1916, said the rules prohibited
rematches. The judges, he said, cannot use instant replays, and the
contestants ``eat with such speed and ability, it can be difficult
to keep track of.'' But reviewing each play on tape would impede
the eating and kill the spontaneity, he said. Keiner denied making
a false start. ``I did not start before anybody else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike DeVito, the 1993 champion, supported Keiner's claim. ``This
guy's a legitimate winner,'' he said. ``We're talking about a split
second, if anything.''
</P>
<P>
   While DeVito said he trained regularly, buying four or five
pounds of spare ribs and other heavy meats at Wall Street delis and
wolfing them down in his office at Goldman, Sachs, where he is a
controller, Keiner said that all he had done to prepare was skip
breakfast Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   There have been questionable maneuvers by hot-dog-eating
contestants in the past, Shea said. Once, at a regional contest in
Yonkers, a contestant soaked the hot-dog buns (which is permitted)
and pushed them through a sieve (which is not), making compact
dough balls. And in 1989, Shea said, a competitive eater was
disqualified after surreptitiously shoving a hot dog onto someone
else's plate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
