trousers with embroidery, red zippered jacket and pink T-shirt, at
Byblos. (Corina Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MILAN, Italy -- July 5, 1999 --
2SUB-MILAN-MENS-FASHION-1, 7-05 -- From left, Jacket knit top and
cotton trousers from Calvin Klein; Giorgio Armani's charcoal
zippered coat over jersey shirt and nylon pants; skinny pants and
``La Medusa'' baseball shirt from Donatella Versace. (Corina
Lecca/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1999 -- HEATWAVE, 7-05 -- A
municipal employee cools off people waiting in line to enter a
public pool on Monday. Because of safety regulations limiting
attendance to the pool at 900, hundreds of people waited over an
hour in 100 degree heat to get in. (James Estrin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LIBERTYVILLE, Ill. -- July 5, 1999 --
DETECTIVE-POLITICS-3, 7-05 -- Tim Anderson stands across the street
from where Libertyville Savings and Loan once had its offices.
Feeding an almost insatiable demand for negative information in
today's world of bruising politics, private investigators are
playing a larger though mostly hidden role in the public arena,
digging up dirt on everyone from regulators to elected national and
small-town officials. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- July 5, 1999 -- SCI-HERBS-SURGERY, 7-05 --
Mounting evidence suggests that herbal remedies may have dangerous
interactions with anesthesia. Alarmed by what they see as the
potential for mishaps with patients taking herbal remedies for
everything from depression to memory loss, anesthesiologists have
begun urging people to stop taking the herbs and supplements before
having surgery. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- July 5, 1999 -- DETECTIVE-POLITICS-2, 7-05
-- Terry Lenzner, a former Watergate prosecutor and founder of the
Investigative Group International, Inc., during testimony before
the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee on campaign fund-raising.
At left is Loren Berger, Lenzner's senior investigator. One of the
few major firms that solicits political cases is the Investigative
Group International. Though best known as an investigator for
President Clinton's lawyers, Lenzner has also worked for
Republicans, including former Rep. Michael Huffington in his losing
Senate race in California against Dianne Feinstein. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ADDISON, Ill. -- July 5, 1999 -- DETECTIVE-POLITICS-1,
7-05 -- Ernie Rizzo, a former police officer in a Chicago suburb
and currently a private detective, outside his home recently next
to his car. Feeding an almost insatiable demand for negative
information in today's world of bruising politics, private
investigators are playing a larger though mostly hidden role in the
public arena, digging up dirt on everyone from regulators to
elected national and small-town officials. ``Politicians are the
easiest people in the world to set up,'' Rizzo said. ``They're all
whores. You stay with them for a week and you'll catch them doing
something.'' (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1999 -- REDDEN-LINCOLN-CENTER, 7-05
-- Nigel Redden, the Lincoln Center Festival director, after a
dress rehearsal of ``The Peony Pavilion'' at La Guardia High
School, where it will be presented three times, each time in six
episodes spread over three or four days. Redden, 48, has spent most
of his career throwing together elements as disparate as Chinese
opera and American gospel at festivals in the United States and
abroad. ``I guess the unifying thread is festivals,'' he says.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CAPE HATTERAS, N.C. -- July 5, 1999 --
SCI-LIGHTHOUSE-MOVE, 7-05 -- Erosion brought waves so close to the
Cape Hatteras Lighthouse that people feared a storm might destroy
it. The lighthouse is being slowly moved, and if all goes well, by
August there will once again be at least 1,500 feet of sand and
scrub pine between the structure and the waves. (National Park
Service/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BELA CRKVA, Yugoslavia -- July 5, 1999 --
KOSOVO-FUNERAL-3, 7-05 -- Ethnic Albanians weep while some hold
photos of relatives killed by Serbs during funeral services on
Monday. The surviving villagers of Bela Crkva paid their last
respects to more than 60 victims of a March massacre. (Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BELA CRKVA, Yugoslavia -- July 5, 1999 --
KOSOVO-FUNERAL-2, 7-05 -- Surviving villagers of Bela Crkva bury
the remains of more than 60 victims of a March massacre on Monday.
The well-documented account of the massacre here, along with
reports of other massacres in a chain of villages in the region,
marked the beginning of the violent Serbian campaign that seemed
designed to purge Kosovo of its ethic Albanians, 90 percent of the
population. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BELA CRKVA, Yugoslavia -- July 5, 1999 --
KOSOVO-FUNERAL-1, 7-05 -- An ethnic Albanian woman weeps as she
displays photos of relatives killed by Serbs during funeral
services on Monday. The surviving villagers of Bela Crkva paid
their last respects to more than 60 victims of a March massacre.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) JONES BEACH, N.Y. -- July 5, 1999 -- BEACH-FLOATER, 7-05
-- Real estate is scarce on Jones Beach as seen in this aerial view
on Monday. In New York as well as throughout much of the nation,
the sweltering heat turned outings into a brow-wiping roast.
(Librado Romero/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1999 -- GISELLE-DANCE-REVIEW, 7-05 --
Diana Vishneva and Andrian Fadeyev of the Kirov Ballet in
``Giselle.'' The corps or literally, the body, of the Kirov Ballet
is the star of the Russian company's current production of
``Giselle.'' (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1999 -- PIGOTT-ICEMAN, 7-05 -- Tim
Pigott-Smith, who is portraying the failed anarchist Larry Slade in
the critically hailed revival of Eugene O'Neill's ``Iceman
Cometh.'' Pigott-Smith's 14 episodes of fame came in the
mid-1980's, when his portrayal of the sadistic police
superintendent Ronald Merrick in ``The Jewel in the Crown'' made
him the villain British and American television viewers loved to
hate. In the ensuing 14 years, Pigott-Smith has had a busy career,
but fame has not been part of it. And, he said, he doesn't miss
it.(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1999 -- PETS-AT-WORK-3, 7-05 -- David
Kratz sits next to his dog Derby during a staff meeting in the
Manhattan offices of his public relations firm Kratz &AMP; Jensen.
Leash-toting employees say they bring their dogs to work simply
because they hate to leave them home alone. Once at the office,
they say, dogs help relieve stress and provide a measure of
security for those who keep late hours. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1999 -- PETS-AT-WORK-2, 7-05 --
Marilyn Mode, right, deputy police commissioner for public
information, meets with Police Commander Michael Collis in his
office along with her poodle Lil Diamond at police headquarters in
Downtown Manhattan. Fido at the office? More people are taking
their dogs to work, with some companies even designating days to
bring in the pooch. But not everyone in the workplace is happy
about the pet-friendly trend. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PURCHASE, N.Y. -- July 5, 1999 -- PETS-AT-WORK-1, 7-05 --
Robin Roy, director of development for Manhattanville College, gets
a lick from her puppy Kokopelli, a three-month old Dashund. Fido at
the office? More people are taking their dogs to work, with some
companies even designating days to bring in the pooch. But not
everyone in the workplace is happy about the pet-friendly trend.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GREENWICH, Conn. -- July 5, 1999 -- WEICKER-POLITICS ,
7-05 -- Lowell Weicker, the former senator and Connecticut
governor, talks about running for president as a third-party
moderate candidate in the backyard of his home last week.
Operatives for Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota are trying to entice
Weicker to offer himself as a Reform Party nominee for president.
And Weicker, 68, sounds very much like a man who is willing to be
enticed. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- July 5, 1999 -- SCI-INTERN-READING, 7-05 --
``The House of God,'' by Dr. Stephen Bergman, chronicles a year in
the life of a medical intern training at one of the best hospitals
in the country. Though the book, first published 21 years ago under
Bergman's pen name, is virtually unknown outside the of the health
care field, it is passed from one medical intern to the next and
has sold more than two million copies. (Tony Cenicola/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SEVASTOPAL, Russia -- July 5, 1999 --
SCI-DOLPHIN-VIOLENCE, 7-05 -- A child is assisted in feeding a
dolphin in the Russian naval base on the Crimean in 1997. Everybody
loves dolphins, those playful models of animal wisdom, celebrated
for protecting shipwrecked sailors and spending their days
frolicking happily in the waves. But recently, scientists,
following a trail of bloody clues, are discovering that dolphins
are far from the happy, peaceful creatures that humans think they
know. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
