<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 07/05/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1999 -- HOTDOG-CONTESTED, 7-05 --
Steve Keiner's victory at this year's Fourth of July hot-dog-eating
contest at Coney Island is being contested; editors at the cable
television station New York 1 say the videotape shows that he had
begun to eat before the starting signal. George Shea, a spokesman
for Nathan's Famous, which has been running the annual contests
since 1916, says the rules prohibit rematches and the judges cannot
use instant replays. ``I did not start before anybody else,'' says
Keiner. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) GANDA SINGH WALA, Pakistan -- July 5, 1999 --
INDIA-PAKISTAN-PUNJAB, 7-05 -- Despite watching Indian television,
Nasreen, a homemaker on Pakistani side of border, relates the
official Pakistani version of Kashmir events. Nasreen, who
estimates that she is 45, says she believes that Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee of India wanted to win a war with Pakistan to
help his party win the national election in September. ``Pakistan
wants peace,'' she says. ``It is India that wants war.'' (Celia W.
Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) TOKYO -- July 5, 1999 -- NTT-COMPETE, 7-05 -- Junichiro
Miyazu, president of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, during an
interview last month in Japan. His company is preparing to compete
in the global telecommunications market. (Stuart isett/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SANTA MONICA, Calif. -- July 5, 1999 --
PRIVATE-MAILBOXES, 7-05 -- A new postal regulation may prevent
Vincent Cobb from using a prestigious address for his consulting
business, by requiring that any incoming mail be labeled PMB, for
private mailbox. ``This is an impossibility,'' Cobb says. ``I don't
know who's going to send me mail.'' (Marissa Roth/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
