Mounting evidence suggests that herbal remedies may have dangerous
interactions with anesthesia. Alarmed by what they see as the
potential for mishaps with patients taking herbal remedies for
everything from depression to memory loss, anesthesiologists have
begun urging people to stop taking the herbs and supplements before
having surgery. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- July 5, 1999 -- DETECTIVE-POLITICS-2, 7-05
-- Terry Lenzner, a former Watergate prosecutor and founder of the
Investigative Group International, Inc., during testimony before
the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee on campaign fund-raising.
At left is Loren Berger, Lenzner's senior investigator. One of the
few major firms that solicits political cases is the Investigative
Group International. Though best known as an investigator for
President Clinton's lawyers, Lenzner has also worked for
Republicans, including former Rep. Michael Huffington in his losing
Senate race in California against Dianne Feinstein. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ADDISON, Ill. -- July 5, 1999 -- DETECTIVE-POLITICS-1,
7-05 -- Ernie Rizzo, a former police officer in a Chicago suburb
and currently a private detective, outside his home recently next
to his car. Feeding an almost insatiable demand for negative
information in today's world of bruising politics, private
investigators are playing a larger though mostly hidden role in the
public arena, digging up dirt on everyone from regulators to
elected national and small-town officials. ``Politicians are the
easiest people in the world to set up,'' Rizzo said. ``They're all
whores. You stay with them for a week and you'll catch them doing
something.'' (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1999 -- REDDEN-LINCOLN-CENTER, 7-05
-- Nigel Redden, the Lincoln Center Festival director, after a
dress rehearsal of ``The Peony Pavilion'' at La Guardia High
School, where it will be presented three times, each time in six
episodes spread over three or four days. Redden, 48, has spent most
of his career throwing together elements as disparate as Chinese
opera and American gospel at festivals in the United States and
abroad. ``I guess the unifying thread is festivals,'' he says.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CAPE HATTERAS, N.C. -- July 5, 1999 --
SCI-LIGHTHOUSE-MOVE, 7-05 -- Erosion brought waves so close to the
Cape Hatteras Lighthouse that people feared a storm might destroy
it. The lighthouse is being slowly moved, and if all goes well, by
August there will once again be at least 1,500 feet of sand and
scrub pine between the structure and the waves. (National Park
Service/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
