<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNET-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      07-05 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNET-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: INVESTORS' ODD CNET LOGIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cnet was one of the very first companies to build a business on
the World Wide Web, but it has rarely benefited from the special
dispensations that investors accord most Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Look, for example, at how the market reacted when Real Networks,
another of the oldest Web concerns, announced a deal with the WebTV
unit of Microsoft Corp. on Thursday. Though the deal will bring in
no revenue for Real, its stock reacted with the usual e-euphoria,
surging 27 percent in two days, to $89.94.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that reaction with Cnet's announcement on Wednesday of a
new $100 million ad campaign _ the sort of bold play for growth
that usually titillates Web investors: Cnet's stock dropped by 14
percent Thursday and Friday, to $49.82. The investors' complaint?
Cnet, which has been making that rarest of Internet results, a
profit, would now lose money for a year because of the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if Cnet were the only freeway driver doing the speed
limit as everyone else zoomed by at 90 mph. Then, just as it
decided to push just a little harder on the gas, it was the one
with the red lights flashing in its rearview window.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet was founded by Halsey Minor in 1992 _ before most investors
had even heard of the Internet _ to create a series of online
services and television programs about computers. And Minor had to
work much harder to raise money _ and then to placate his investors
_ than Internet companies do today. It is hard to imagine today,
but for Cnet's first few years, Wall Street kept complaining that
it was growing rapidly but losing money.
</P>
<P>
   To calm its critics, Cnet tightened its belt, and for the last
four quarters it has managed to be in the black. Meanwhile, a
series of savvy investments produced a stash of stock and cash
worth more than $800 million. Most notably, its decision to build
an Internet portal called Snap, widely derided by investors at the
time as expensive folly, has been transformed through a series of
deals involving NBC and the Internet company Xoom into stock worth
$425 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet, moreover, has the proven business model of a trade
publication. It publishes articles of interest to people who buy
computers _ both individuals and corporate decision makers _ then
sells advertising to those who want to reach these prospects. The
Internet allows the company to serve both buyer and seller better
than a magazine can. A consumer can read reviews of computers,
select a model, compare prices for that machine at various
retailers, and click off to vendors' sites to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   And although Cnet has hardly spent anything on marketing since
it bought some of the first banner ads ever on Yahoo, it has still
managed to become the 17th most popular Internet service, with 8
million monthly visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the company assembled analysts in San Francisco
to unveil its expansion into new markets _ consumer electronics and
corporate information systems _ and the new ad campaign. Unlike
most Internet companies, Cnet could tap its own cash reserves for
marketing rather than spending money raised from investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured the best return we could earn on our cash was to
invest it in growing our own business,'' Douglas Woodrum, the
company's chief financial officer, said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were generally pleased, and on Wednesday, Cnet's stock
rose by $3.50, to $57.625. The company, wrote Lanny Baker of
Salomon Smith Barney, has ``established itself as one of the few
Internet companies with a defensible, profitable, working business
model.'' The ad campaign, he estimated, would bring in enough new
viewers to boost revenue by 25 percent by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But by Thursday, as word hit the broader market of the shift
from profit to loss, Cnet's shares plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you announce changes that hurt the near term only to
improve the long term, people tend to just focus on the near
term,'' Woodrum said. ``We're not going to let that stop us from
doing what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Losses, however, have never dampened investor interest in Real
Networks, for the simple reason that it has never made any money.
Real Networks lost $16 million last year on sales of $65 million.
By contrast, Cnet earned $3 million on sales of $56 million.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by Rob Glaser, a former Microsoft executive, Real
developed a technology that has become the standard for audio and
video programming on the Internet, with an 85 percent share of all
multimedia Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   That is an enviable achievement. But the company has the sort of
convoluted business model so common among Internet companies: It
gives its Real Player software away free and makes money selling an
upgraded software player with more features and selling advertising
on its Web site and on the player itself. The company also sells
the ``server'' software used by operators of Web sites that want to
broadcast in Real formats.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, Microsoft, which once owned 10 percent of Real Networks,
has decided to compete by promoting its own audio and video player.
This caused enough trouble that Glaser testified in a Senate
hearing last year that Microsoft was trying to ``break'' Real's
products.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the announcement last Thursday that WebTV would update the
existing software, used by its interactive television service, to
play the most recent Real Networks formats, was seen by investors
as a sign of some sort of peace offering. It could well be. But
Microsoft is quite adept at continuing to do routine business with
companies it is nonetheless intent on destroying.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it is hard to see how anything in the WebTV deal comes
close to adding the $1.5 billion in market value that investors
accorded Real Networks last week. There is no money changing hands
between Real and Microsoft, and the Web TV version of the player
does not even present an opportunity to sell upgrades or
advertising. At best, the Web site owners that use Real's software
will be more satisfied because they now get access to the 800,000
Web TV users. But it is unclear how this might improve revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, the peculiar logic of the Internet investor
takes no apparent note of such details, and Real Network speeds off
in the fast lane while Cnet eats its dust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
