<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-PUNJAB     07-05 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-PUNJAB-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PAKISTANI VILLAGE, DISTRUST OF INDIANS AS RAW AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (With INDIA-PAKISTAN-ASSESS)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GANDA SINGHWALA, Pakistan _ The rains came on Sunday to this
parched Punjabi village, pelting the shiny black hides of water
buffalo and the barefoot boys who joyously stretched out their arms
to welcome the drenching coolness.
</P>
<P>
   But the gaiety with which the villagers greeted the monsoon
contrasted with their grim fatalism about the fighting that has
raged for two months between Pakistan and India in Kashmir, the
Himalayan land just to the north of Punjab that both nations want
for their own.
</P>
<P>
   History lies heavy in Ganda Singhwala, two to three miles from
the Indian border. Here the distrust of Pakistanis for Indians, of
Muslims for Hindus, is as raw as a fresh stab wound.
</P>
<P>
   The old men, toothless and stooped, tell and retell grisly
stories of Partition in 1947, when India and Pakistan were carved
from the British empire, and Hindus and Sikhs on the one hand and
Muslims on the other slaughtered each other by the hundreds of
thousands. Punjab, too, was divided, into Indian and Pakistani
states.
</P>
<P>
   Khushi Muhammad, 94, has raised children and grandchildren on
his bitter memories. A Muslim, he fled predominantly Hindu India
for the new Islamic nation of Pakistan and recalls the caravans of
ox carts that passed through his new hometown, stacked with the
dead bodies of Muslim men, women and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot forget it,'' he said, hands resting on a wood cane.
``This fire can never be extinguished.''
</P>
<P>
   The next generation has its own harsh memories of the wars that
these closest of enemies waged in 1965 and 1971, with fighting
along the border that moved perilously close to this village.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the heavy shelling and bombing started in 1965, we had to
leave,'' said Nazir Begum, 60, who is married to a shopkeeper who
repairs bicycles. ``I am fearful there will be another war. But I
pray Allah will be with the Pakistan army.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ganda Singhwala seems ordinary in most every way, these
are not ordinary times. Situated so close to the Indian border, it
was crawling with men who work for civilian and military
intelligence agencies. Some carried Kalashnikov rifles. Others had
walkie-talkies. More than 12 tramped along behind visitors,
monitoring the questions asked and answers given.
</P>
<P>
   This region is unusual in another way. An embankment studded
with concrete bunkers runs along the Pakistani side of the border,
and is matched by a floodlighted fence on the Indian side. The
bunkers serve as a Berlin wall between the two countries. The
people on each side live parallel lives that do not intersect.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite having been cut off from each other for more than 50
years, Ganda Singhwala bears a haunting resemblance to most any
northern Indian village.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, after the rains stopped and 110-degree heat
rose again from the labyrinthine brick lanes, men dressed in loose
tunics and undershirts gathered on wood cots to pass the time.
Ox-drawn carts rolled down the rutted muddy main street. In small
internal courtyards, women hospitably poured cups of tea for
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   People described themselves as having almost nothing in common
with Indians. ``We are Muslims, so there's a big difference between
the two cultures,'' said Muhammad's granddaughter Riffat Yasin, 22.
``We worship only one God. They have several idols, and they call
them gods.''
</P>
<P>
   Each day, Miss Yasin and her mother, Nasreen, who has just one
name, turn on their aging television set with the broken knobs to
watch the news on Doordarshan, the Indian government station.
``It's all fabricated,'' Miss Yasin said.
</P>
<P>
   They and other villagers offered the official Pakistani version
of events as their description of reality. They said the men who
were fighting in majority Muslim Kashmir were not Pakistan army
soldiers who had invaded Indian territory, as the Indians contend,
but indigenous freedom fighters who are trying to win Kashmir's
right to be part of Pakistan, created as a homeland for the
subcontinent's Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Nasreen, who estimated that she was 45, said she believed that
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee of India wanted to win a war
with Pakistan to help his party win the national election in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan wants peace,'' Nasreen said. ``It is India that wants
war.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of miles away, near the border, several farmers sat in
the shade on their cots, musing on India's motives. They said they
felt that a grave injustice was committed at the time of partition,
when Kashmir should have become part of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kashmir belongs to the Muslims,'' said Sardar Said Muhammad,
65, who owns 400 acres of fertile land and 50 head of water
buffalo. ``The Hindus have nothing at stake there.''
</P>
<P>
   The farmers had more recent grievances, as well. They said
Indians had sneaked through the gates of the fence that India built
along the border to steal hundreds of their water buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad and another farmer, Muhammad Ali, 60, agreed that the
Indians were up to no good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hindu mentality is that no single Muslim should survive
and all of Kashmir should be captured by India,'' Muhammad said.
``The Hindus and Americans are on the same side. They are
supporting each other, because they are both big powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali offered his opinion about India, saying: ``They're powerful.
They're bullying. They have a greed for territory. They don't want
Pakistan to exist. They want to obliterate us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
