<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BAMBILAND-NYT &LR;      07-05 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BAMBILAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MILOSEVIC FIELD OF DREAMS: BAMBIPARK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POZAREVAC, Yugoslavia _ Neither war against the Western world,
nor missiles in his father's house, nor scurrilous rumors that he
skipped the country to avoid fighting in Kosovo have kept President
Slobodan Milosevic's only son, Marko, from realizing his theme park
dream.
</P>
<P>
   The dream goes by the name of Bambiland.
</P>
<P>
   At least that was the original name chosen by Marko, a high
school dropout who has become Serbia's best connected and perhaps
least loved 25-year-old entrepreneur playboy.
</P>
<P>
   The pounding that Serbia took during the Kosovo war from
American bombs _ his father's presidential mansion in Belgrade was
hit by cruise missiles _ soured Marko on the Disneyesque
connotations of ``Bambiland.'' At some point during the 11-week
war, he reportedly decided that the name did not sound sufficiently
Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   So when the park, actually more of a sports area, had its grand
opening on Sunday night _ with Marko's mother, Mirjana Markovic,
the feared wife of the Yugoslav president, in attendance along with
a crowd of several thousand _ it was christened Bambipark.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition newspapers have pointed out that ``park'' is no more
Serbian than ``land.''
</P>
<P>
   The name Bambi is another matter. Although it does echo the
beloved Disney film of the same name, it has a Serbian link. Bambi
is the name of a large government-owned food processing company
based here in Pozarevac, the childhood home of both of Marko's
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Bambipark is a six-acre recreation area, costing about $380,000,
for basketball, volleyball, skateboarding and in-line skating. It
costs about 70 cents to get in.
</P>
<P>
   Marko was offered a chance Monday to explain the business
venture to a reporter. Dressed in a black T-shirt and black slacks
and talking intermittently on a tiny cellular phone, he happened to
be sitting inside Bambipark at the noon hour beside a kiddy pool
and beneath a Coca-Cola umbrella. He was drinking juice and did not
seem in a particular rush.
</P>
<P>
   But meeting the press is not a simple matter for Marko.
Newspapers and magazines in Serbia have often teased him for his
habit of wrecking other people's expensive cars, for dying his
black hair a punk white, for occasionally bullying people in bars
in Belgrade and for having used daddy's connections to become rich.
</P>
<P>
   He owns Madona, which advertises itself as the largest
discotheque in the Balkans. American intelligence officials say he
is a major cigarette smuggler. He also owns a radio station
licensed to him by his father's government.
</P>
<P>
   He has found ways of getting even with hurtful reporters. He
sued an opposition newspaper in Belgrade for making fun of him,
using draconian press laws passed last year. In January a court
ordered the newspaper to pay him $15,000 for ``inflicted moral
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the question of whether he evaded risky military service
in Kosovo, a matter that generated many disparaging comments among
Serbs who had to fight, the young Milosevic was defended by his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote an open letter to the British foreign secretary, Robin
Cook, denying press reports that Marko or her daughter Marija had
fled the country during the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Marko, she said, ``is in uniform and cares about his small new
family.'' The state television later showed Marko here in Pozarevac
in a sort of military uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the war, Marko has told sympathetic newspapers
and the state television that he never let anxiety about NATO
bombing interfere with the construction of Bambipark. It
represents, he told reporters, ``the proof of care for the young
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   As a break from the rigors of supervising the building of
Bambipark, he also became deputy chairman of the horse show
organizing board in the Serbian town of Ljubicevo. He has changed
the opening ceremony of the horse show to make it less
``stereotyped,'' Radio Pozarevac reported.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat drinking his juice near the kiddy pool, the evidence
of what he and other investors have accomplished with Bambipark was
all around him, though there were only a few children playing
there, since it was uncomfortably hot at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Marko was asked if he would like to explain why he felt the need
to build this place. ``You are the aggressor,'' he replied. ``You
burned down my house, and I am not going to speak with you or give
you any interview, even about Bambipark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
