<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NTT-COMPETE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-05 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NTT-COMPETE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTING TIME FOR NTT'S GLOBAL AMBITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Junichiro Miyazu heads Asia's biggest company, Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corp., and he is about to make it even
bigger.
</P>
<P>
   A serious, owlish man, Miyazu intends to use a new law to
transform Japan's telecommunications giant into a global player to
battle with the likes of AT&AMP;T. The new law, which took effect July
1 after a decade of dithering in Japan's Parliament, reshapes NTT
and permits it for the first time to compete directly overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may fail from time to time, but we ought to explore as many
new businesses as we can,'' Miyazu, the president of NTT, said in
an interview. ``Great changes are now taking place in the world of
information and communications, such as the Internet and
multimedia, and NTT won't be able to survive just on what it has
done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   So NTT is setting up operations around the world, and taking
stakes in companies that provide services related to the Internet
and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   In April, it announced a collaboration with AT&AMP;T to provide
consulting services on networks to large companies. More recently,
it has been gobbling up investments in Asian telecommunications
carriers _ for example, a 15 percent stake in Philippine Long
Distance Telephone Co. and a stake in Sri Lanka Telecommunications.
It aims to become the dominant telecommunications company across
Asia, growing along with the world's most populous region.
</P>
<P>
   But many doubt that NTT's strategy will work, and for the
moment, NTT's plans are striking less for their business acumen
than for their obliviousness to market principles. NTT is
struggling to adjust to a new era of free markets, yet its business
plans still seem designed not by marketing executives but rather by
politicians and bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts had hoped that the new law would be a Japanese
parallel of the breakup of AT&AMP;T, but instead it confirmed NTT's
monopoly on local calls, retained its status as a semi-official
company and simply gave it the additional power to venture abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Thus critics say that the new law and NTT's restructuring
represent a major lost opportunity that will leave Japanese
telecommunications hobbled by a monopolist company that will never
compete effectively around the world. NTT is one of the world's
largest corporations, as measured by its stock market value of
roughly $186 billion, but the lumbering company has been widely
criticized for extremely expensive service in Japan, which has
slowed the emergence of Internet services. The critics say that
retaining the monopoly will just mean more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a step backward,'' said Yusai Okuyama, the
wiry and fiery chairman of DDI Corp., one of Japan's most
innovative telecommunications companies. If there is no fair
competition, he said, DDI ``will be worse than negligible; under
those circumstances, we will never be able to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Okuyama and other rivals worry that with NTT's continuing
monopoly in the local telephone business, long distance and
international carriers will still be beholden to NTT because they
must connect to its local and highly expensive network.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is as openly critical, but many argue that after
all these years Japan's restructuring of telecommunications is
feeble at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their first baby step toward globalization,'' said
Timothy Wiest, president of Primus Telecommunications in Japan.
``It's not that the rest of the world is shaking in their boots.
It's that the rest of Japan can see that the monopolist is moving
to monopolize international business from Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of years, the small carriers have been
jostling to join up with partners to insure their market toeholds,
however tiny. The reorganization, they fear, will now give NTT the
chance to snatch away their painstakingly groomed business.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, NTT Communications, the new subsidiary that will
shape the long distance and global business, has ambitious plans to
mimic an American-style approach. It wants to outfit Japan's giant
conglomerates with tailored telecommunications networks and
services in high-speed data transmission, multimedia and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, NTT can go to Japan's large conglomerates, like
Mitsubishi Corp., and say that NTT can now offer one-stop
telecommunications shopping, so that that there is no need to buy
long distance and international service from competitors like DDI,
KDD or Japan Telecom Co.
</P>
<P>
   Okuyama said he is convinced that DDI, which operates in the
markets for long distance, international and mobile phones, must
find a foreign partner by the end of this year to compete. But he
also insisted that DDI has some advantages NTT lacks, namely
agility and speed.
</P>
<P>
   With 60 million subscribers in Japan and 138,200 employees, NTT
is run more like a bureaucracy than probably any other Japanese
company, and it answers to a national law that governs its
operations. Even Miyazu acknowledges the challenges, and said there
are no plans to move aggressively into the North American market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not that arrogant to hope that NTT will become a
household name in the United States,'' Miyazu said.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry of finance owns 59.2 percent of NTT, and
bureaucrats have shaped the company. From the telegraph to the
telephone, Japanese have grown up knowing only NTT, but over the
years the smaller players have nibbled at the fringes of NTT's
domain, such as in city-to-city calls.
</P>
<P>
   NTT is spreading overseas just as foreign carriers are banging
at the doors to get into Japan. Just weeks ago, Cable and Wireless
of Britain won a battle against NTT to buy a tiny local
international carrier, International Digital Communications, in
which it already had a minority stake.
</P>
<P>
   But NTT seems to be picking its fights. International Digital,
which had patiently negotiated standard telephone lines with over
200 countries, had close ties to NTT, but some executives say it
did not exactly fit in with NTT's international strategy. Instead,
they say, NTT Communications wants to concentrate on providing big
Japanese multinationals with customized telecommunications
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to secure our market in Japan and in Asia,'' said
Tatsuo Kawasaki, vice president of global strategy at NTT
Communications. ``Otherwise, global players like AT&AMP;T and Deutsche
Telekom will move into the Japanese market. And that means we would
lose our cash cows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
