<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-3M-OUTLOOK-ART-2TAKES     07-05 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3M-OUTLOOK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS DON'T LIKE THE NUMBERS ON 3M'S POST-IT NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. _ Here at the technology center of the Minnesota
Mining and Manufacturing Corp., scientists are tinkering with
stickier adhesives, longer-lasting abrasives, glare-free reflective
signs _ indeed, with improvements on virtually every product, from
the esoteric to the mundane, that 3M makes.
</P>
<P>
   The road to product nirvana, the scientists say, is a hot new
technology called microreplication, a way to place thousands of
identical microscopic shapes on the surfaces of all kinds of
materials, from sandpaper to flat-panel computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microreplication is reinventing our core businesses,'' said
Robert S. Finocchiaro, who runs the microreplication project.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood is a bit more somber across the street, where the
corporate types are. Try as they will, they cannot shake Wall
Street's perception of 3M as a boring, low-technology drone whose
glory days ended with Scotch tape and Post-it notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put it next to a machinery company, and the stock
performance looks the same,'' said B. Alexander Henderson, who
follows 3M for Prudential Securities Research.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not just image, though; it is performance. For
two years, 3M has consistently missed earnings estimates, and its
revenues, half of them from foreign shores, have been stuck at $15
billion. Its shares, which sold near $100 in July 1997, drifted to
$70 by April. The stock has rebounded some, closing at $86.9375 on
Friday, but many 3M watchers say the rise comes from investor
disaffection with Internet stocks and hopes for an Asian economic
recovery, not from confidence in 3M's management.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't have the killer instinct when it comes to
financial returns,'' said Jack L. Kelly, who follows 3M for
Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Is 3M, once a darling of Wall Street, now just another badly
managed also-ran? Or is it still a new-product machine that had a
bad case of the hiccups last year?
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the company have accused Livio D. DeSimone, 3M's
chairman since 1991, of everything from losing 3M's innovative
touch to refusing to cut costs to mismanaging inventories to
sticking with humdrum products too long. Some have even put
pressure on the board to ask DeSimone, who turns 63 this month, to
step down before the mandatory retirement age of 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows an incredible amount about product, but he just
doesn't have a good enough grip on daily operations,'' one analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
   DeSimone _ widely known as Desi, a variation on the start of his
last name _ tries to take the criticism in stride, but it clearly
annoys him. He says he is cutting costs, tightening procedures and
getting products to markets faster.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeSimone, a chemical engineer who has been with 3M for
32 years, concedes that maybe he should have bitten those bullets
sooner, he maintains that more of 3M's fiscal woes can be traced to
the strong dollar and the weak Asian economies than to his
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became dumb all of a sudden in 1998,'' he said. ``Well, no
one thought I was dumb in 1997, and hopefully, I'll be seen as
smart again in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors aren't so easily persuaded. ``The U.S. still accounts
for half of revenues, too, and the economy here isn't bad,'' said
one portfolio manager.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly of Goldman, Sachs said, ``Too often, they try to sweep
everything under the convenient rug of currency problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The company does have fans. Perkin-Elmer, the life-sciences
concern now known as the PE Corp., chose 3M in February as a joint
venture partner for genetic analysis. Robert Sprague, a manager at
the Xerox Corp., cites 3M's extensive manufacturing experience as
the reason Xerox picked 3M to manufacture its ``electronic paper''
_ reusable rubbery sheets embedded with billions of tiny
electrically charged balls that can be written on with an
electronic wand.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he feels the stock is fully valued, Jonathan
Rosenzweig, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, said of 3M,
``They have a knack for taking something that exists, changing it a
bit and leveraging it into an entirely new product.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, trying to categorize 3M at all is an exercise in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1902 to mine corundum, an abrasive mineral, the
company quickly shifted to processing the leftover grit into
sandpaper and grinding wheels. Over the years it branched out into
industries as unrelated as thermofaxing, the copying method that
preceded xerography, and adhesives. It has pulled out of many
businesses, including copiers and a bank it once owned, but it
still makes 50,000 products, ranging from optical fibers to wound
dressings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 3M is not a classic conglomerate, one that could easily
be broken up. Its 40 divisions are as technologically intertwined
as an arterial network. ``People who ask how dressings mesh with
adhesives don't realize that both are sticky,'' DeSimone said.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones lists 3M under diversified technology, while the Value
Line Investment newsletter groups it with diversified chemicals.
Jeffrey J. Zekauskas, a chemical analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co., said,
``3M technologies, especially in electronics, are relevant to the
analysis of specialty chemical companies.'' Still, no chemical
analyst covers 3M.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is watched by the same people who track Xerox, Kodak
and other image and document processing companies _ a business 3M
left when it spun off Imation a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   DeSimone would like 3M, which pumps 6 percent of revenues into
research _ higher than most industrial companies _ to be described
an innovator, pure and simple. ``We're a specialty materials
company that takes related technologies into seemingly unrelated
end-products,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microreplication may be the premier example. It involves placing
identical three-dimensional structures on a surface, changing how
that surface reflects light, wears down or otherwise acts
differently from the undoctored version.
</P>
<P>
   For example, old-style abrasive belts for metalworking must be
replaced as soon as the abrasive surface is worn away. 3M now uses
microreplication to pile cutting surfaces on top of one another, so
that when the top surface is worn down, a fresh cutting surface
emerges. The company says its new belts, sold under the name
Trizact, last up to five times as long as older products.
</P>
<P>
   Innovation is nothing new at 3M. It was here that Post-it notes
were born when one employee, frustrated at losing the strips he
used to mark text in his church hymnal, enlisted the aid of
another, who was trying to develop a seemingly oxymoronic product,
a nonbinding adhesive.
</P>
<P>
   Innovation has not been limited to products. 3M was one of the
first companies to install a dual-career ladder, a now-popular
method for promoting researchers without forcing them out of their
labs into management. (Some 3M scientists complain they are still
paid less than their management counterparts; 3M says the
complaints are baseless.)
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are allowed to devote 15 percent of their time to
projects that pique their interest, even those on which management
has pulled the plug. That has caused some analysts to criticize 3M
for undisciplined management, but DeSimone defends the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to encourage innovation, you have to close your
eyes when people are so excited about a project that they refuse to
stop,'' he said, noting that Thinsulate, a big-selling clothing
insulation material, resulted from a project he had officially
scuttled.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   When researchers do come up with something promising, they are
encouraged to shop it around to all the businesses. A
pharmaceuticals researcher invented a dosage dispenser that mixes
two drugs together; the adhesives division adapted it to mix pastes
that dry as they are applied. A non-heat-generating lighting system
developed in Japan, primarily for use in supermarket coolers, is
selling well for architectural lighting in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers hold an annual event, patterned on a trade show but
open only to 3M people, where they run booths displaying their
latest inventions.
</P>
<P>
   The automotive division picked up a new way to make headlights
when some adhesive researchers displayed a multilayer film. ``Many
of the `Eurekas!' at 3M come from this forum,'' said William E.
Coyne, senior vice president for research.
</P>
<P>
   By some measurements, 3M's innovation formula has been wildly
successful. The company received 611 patents last year, the 11th
most of any American company. Management has long insisted that 3M
derive one-third of revenues from products that are no more than
four years old, and 10 percent from products that are new each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, innovation could not protect 3M's financial results last
year. Its revenues dipped to $15.02 billion from $15.07 billion in
1997. Operating income fared even worse, dropping to $2.04 billion
from $2.68 billion. Net income and per-share earnings were
practically halved _ $1.18 billion, or 2.88 a diluted share, in
1998, down from $2.12 billion, or $5.06 a share, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the dollar is strengthening against every currency,
geographic diversity is a burden as well as a strength,'' said
Ronald O. Baukol, 3M's executive vice president in charge of
international operations.
</P>
<P>
   DeSimone has tried hard to shore up the numbers. Last year _
much too late, some analysts say _ he promised to cut 4,500 jobs by
the end of 1999, bringing total employment down to 71,500. He sold
some small businesses and closed some factories overseas. Now, he
is trying to set up the remaining factories to make a greater
variety of products, so that 3M can more easily shift production to
countries with favorable currency exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, he has introduced a program, called
Pacing Plus, to single out research projects with the potential to
yield huge revenues _ to ``change the nature of competition,'' as
3M puts it _ and speed them to market. Products from this program,
like parts for inkjet printer cartridges and environmentally safe
fluids for cleaning electronic components, accounted for $1 billion
in revenue last year, and Coyne predicted that a third of 3M's
revenues would come from such projects _ probably most employing
some form of microreplication _ by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent too much time on products that provide
incremental, not significant, growth,'' Coyne said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 3M is taking pains to see that smaller projects are not
eclipsed. Its three-year-old Corporate Enterprise Department
finances technologies, like a technique for time-releasing insect
pheromones that might one day be used in pesticides, that no
division is ready to take to market.
</P>
<P>
   The company is even licensing innovations it cannot immediately
use _ an unusual move for the generally secretive company. It
licensed a method for making flexible printing plates to DuPont and
it is looking for a licensee for a process for making glass panels
for flat-screen televisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago we would have made the panels ourselves, but now we
realize it's silly to go into glass manufacturing,'' Finocchiaro
said.
</P>
<P>
   Will 3M, once a regular on lists of most admired companies,
regain its Wall Street sheen?
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that it is finally on the right track. But
skeptics still outnumber converts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, 3M has changed,'' Henderson of Prudential said, summing
up the prevailing Wall Street view. ``But the question remains: has
it changed enough?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
