</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ADDRESSING AN ATTITUDE PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As I begin to write this, the morning newspaper is
slipped under the door of my hotel room. There is a huge photo of
Steffi Graf, running two-thirds the length of a broadsheet page.
Pete Sampras has been reduced to a small, one-column head shot,
along with the last few paragraphs of the accompanying story.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, the respected seven-time champion, bowed out after losing
the final on Sunday to Lindsay Davenport. The only man who would
have upstaged Graf was Tim Henman, England's own. He lost his
semifinal to Sampras, who then dominated Andre Agassi for a sixth
Wimbledon title, the modern men's record. But while Sampras oiled
his cannon serve in the first set, Graf was somberly saying she
wouldn't be back. So right until the very end, women drove the
Wimbledon news.
</P>
<P>
   They have been the sport's fascination for a couple of years.
Wimbledon is to tennis what the Kentucky Derby is to horse racing,
commanding attention that is not reflective of the sport's
diminished popularity, especially in the States. But throughout the
year, the men have become accustomed to being the last paragraph or
two of those wire service reports out of tour stops like Key
Biscayne and Indian Wells. ``And in men's semifinal action ... ''
begins the afterthought, week after week.
</P>
<P>
   The women have the young comers, the fading icons, the
developing rivalries, and something else that seduces and becomes
irresistible to the sports news media. Unlike the strong, silent,
ground-stroking men, the teen-age girls burst on the scene
accompanied by that peculiar sports species, the professional
tennis parent. The kids come wearing family dysfunction on their
sleeves, like another endorsement patch.
</P>
<P>
   At this Wimbledon came the emergence of a fresh batch of teens
whose parents have managed to make as much news as they. Alexandra
Stevenson, Jelena Dokic and Mirjana Lucic were announced to the
world as part phenomenon, part social-work study. Mom said this.
Dad did what?
</P>
<P>
   As great a player as Graf has been, until her father made a mess
of her financial life and landed in jail, she was more appreciated
than celebrated. The standard by which we define marketability or
basic appeal has become warped. The parents seem to know that
outrageous behavior will help their kids get noticed. In her finest
hour Sunday, Davenport felt compelled to practically apologize for
being ``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wimbledon, the subject of equal pay arose again, sponsored by
that former chauvinist, John McEnroe. Having once declared women
unworthy of announcing televised men's matches, McEnroe now argues
that women get more attention, so they should be paid as much. It
is a fair point, albeit one that is countered by the cyclical
nature of popularity and that the men play best-of-five sets, the
women two of three.
</P>
<P>
   The far more important issue as women's sports proliferate as
never before is how female athletes are viewed through the looking
glass of institutions that have forever been run by men, for the
benefit of men. Forget equal pay. For a week, I have been unable
able to find a single word in the London papers on the Women's
World Cup. I know England isn't represented, but they tell me this
is the Mecca of soccer. What gives?
</P>
<P>
   It is obviously much better for female athletes in the States
than England, or elsewhere, but our attitudes are still generally
shaped by those who believe that a women's sports story needs some
spicing up, a good knee whacking, or some dressing up, as the NBA
demonstrated with its grand opening idea of selling a women's
league by dolling up a few stars, a la Cindy Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Most women I know in the sports news media are all too familiar
with these preconceived notions, with stereotyping, with resistance
to the notion that the forces of change can't be stopped. Football
stadiums are filled for the Women's World Cup, for a team of
mature, ``normal'' women, but try raising the subject with your
snickering drive-time host. It's only about ratings, he'll tell
you. Sure it is.
</P>
<P>
   When men want to look hard enough, there will always be a way to
define women as everything but what they wish to be. Samantha
Stevenson, mother of Alexandra, has courageously raised a
well-rounded daughter under very difficult circumstances, but
there's also a cautionary element to her tale: she is a female
sports journalist who had a relationship with a superstar athlete
she covered.
</P>
<P>
   What will those who campaign for the exclusion of women from the
locker room do with that bit of news? Charlie Ward may be
discussing it with Reggie White right now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
