<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9953 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEATWAVE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-05 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATWAVE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STIFLING HEAT RETAINS ITS GRIP ON EAST COAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A second day of 100-degree temperatures from the Carolinas to
New England turned the holiday Monday into a torturous test of
endurance and ingenuity, with thousands of relief-seekers fleeing
beaches that scorched their feet, only to find that some highways
had buckled in summer's ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   Temperature records for July 5 withered from Washington, where
it was 102, to Portland, Maine, which recorded a balmy 94. New York
City and Atlantic City set records at 101 degrees, Bridgeport,
Conn., hit 100 and Philadelphia tied its record at 100.
</P>
<P>
   But parks officials up and down the East Coast said beaches were
emptier than expected, as visitors moved their chairs and blankets
closer and closer to the water's edge, then finally gave up and
left for the air-conditioned comfort of the great indoors.
</P>
<P>
   The usual traffic nightmare for vacationers leaving the Hamptons
on Long Island became hours worse than usual when part of the
Sunrise Highway, the main route out, buckled in the heat, shutting
lanes for hours.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the heat got so bad that recreation officials
at Hamilton Park on the Lower East Side of Manhattan had to ration
pool time to 15 minute shifts for some 500 youngster.
</P>
<P>
   But it could have been worse. At least pool employees sprayed
the melting masses with rubber hoses.
</P>
<P>
   But for the elderly and homebound, the heat posed serious
problems. The Emergency Medical Service answered 124 heat-related
calls, up from 53 on Sunday, and several were for life-threatening
cases of heat stroke, in which a patient's body temperature reaches
105 degrees. Paramedics plunged many of these patients into
bathtubs and poured ice or cold water on them to bring their body
temperatures down.
</P>
<P>
   City officials were urging caution and common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get people to go to the movies, go to the
mall, go to a store _ anything,'' said Zachary Goldfarb, a deputy
fire chief.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who remained outside to enjoy the last few hours
of the long holiday weekend, the plan was simple: find a breath of
fresh air and do not move.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Perry, 49, a laborer, said it was too expensive to run the
air-conditioner 24 hours a day, so he found some tree-lined shelter
on a bench in Manhattan's Riverside Park. ``AC is OK, but it
doesn't beat coming out and finding a shady spot in Mother Nature.
This is it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sea Bright, N.J., Gina Melson, wearing a bikini and dialing a
cell-phone, gladly took advantage of the shore town's ordinance
allowing local vendors to deliver to their wares to the smoldering
legions on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go pick lunch up,'' said Ms. Melson, 36, a medical
biller. ``But they'' _ she pointed at her sunbathing friends _
``they said: `Are you crazy? Why walk when you can phone?'''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters said the oppressive weather could last through
Tuesday night, when a cold front slogging its way up the coast from
the Carolinas will finally accomplish what no amount of ice or
air-conditioning was able to over this blistering Fourth of July
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more day,'' said Edward Yandrich, a meteorologist for the
National Weather Service. ``I'm not even going to list the top 10
things you do in weather like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Yandrich's reticence, many city dwellers had no problems
carping about a day on which subway platforms transmogrified into
people-packed convection ovens and the sibilant whizz of soda cans
being popped open could be heard on any given street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine standing in a sauna with a fireplace, and the fire is
roaring, and you're doing jumping jacks _ in a mink coat,'' said
Doug Szabo, 26, an investment banker, who was lugging a new
air-conditioner toward his home on the Upper West Side of
Manhattan. ``Well, it's about 10 degrees hotter than that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, D.C., even scoops of ice cream were not enough to
spell relief. ``It's too hot to go out and get ice cream,'' sighed
Rod Long, manager of a Baskin-Robbins store on Connecticut Avenue.
``We've only had 140 customers since 11 a.m.'' _ about half his
normal load.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning and into Monday, the same weather conditions
spawned violent thunderstorms in upstate New York and Massachusetts
as cold fronts from Michigan and Canada tangled with the outskirts
of the warmer regional air, said Jeff Warner, a meteorologist from
Pennsylvania State University.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of customers in upstate New York and in the city lost
power as power lines went down in some areas and an armada of
air-conditioners and electric fans clicked into use in others,
utility officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrendous,'' sniffed Ron Rubinow, 68, who spent a
toasty weekend with his sister in East Hampton. ``All the food's
gone bad. I couldn't get the electric garage door open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just say this: It isn't good,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
