A9962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOURDEFRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-05 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COSTLY COLLISION FOR 3 AT THE TOUR DE FRANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Australia, Estonia, Switzerland, The Netherlands,
Belgium, Texas)  By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. NAZAIRE, France _ What was expected to be a humdrum flat
stage in the Tour de France, just another showcase for the
sprinters, instead turned into a catastrophe for three major
contenders Monday, all of them losing more than six minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They were Alex Zulle, a Swiss with the Banesto team; Ivan Gotti,
an Italian with Polti, and Michael Boogerd, a Dutchman with
Rabobank. All were victims of a crash on a narrow and wet causeway
across a bay and could never catch up with a group of 70 riders who
made the crossing safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that the Tour has to be played out that way,''
said Zulle, who has finished as high as second in the race.
</P>
<P>
   In a more expected loss, Lance Armstrong of the U.S. Postal
Service team gave up the overall leader's yellow jersey to Jaan
Kirsipuu, an Estonian with Casino. Kirsipuu, the winner on Sunday
of the first of 20 daily stages, made up his 16-second deficit on
the Texan by winning three intermediate sprints and then finishing
second across the line in the shipyard city of St. Nazaire.
</P>
<P>
   With 6 seconds deducted from his overall time at each sprint and
12 seconds for his finish, Kirsipuu now leads Armstrong, in second
place, by 14 seconds. Stuart O'Grady, an Australian with Credit
Agricole, is third, 22 seconds back.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong had hoped to keep the jersey for one more day but
admitted that the cost of defending it was wearing, emotionally and
physically, on his teammates. They have had to work hard to chase
down rivals on breakaways and to stay in high alertness throughout
the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Texan said his team tried to have George Hincapie, another
American, win the sprints and deprive Kirsipuu of the bonuses,
``but he's just too fast right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hincapie was third in two of the three sprints and O'Grady, who
also has yellow-jersey ambitions before the race reaches the
mountains in a week, was second three times, gaining four seconds
on each occasion.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, it was the sprinters' finish everybody
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Steels, a Belgian with Mapei and the winner of four Tour
stages last year, outsped Kirsipuu and Mario Cipollini, an Italian
with Saeco and the usual king of the sprinters. Steels was timed in
3 hours 45 minutes 32 seconds, a speed of 29 miles an hour over the
109 miles from Challans.
</P>
<P>
   That speed, stoked by the U.S. Postal Service and other teams
with yellow-jersey dreams when the race ends in Paris on July 25,
left behind the part of the 180-man pack that was either involved
in or trapped behind the crash on the causeway at around Mile 50. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Passage du Gois, the two-lane crossing is under
Atlantic waters for all but six hours daily, before and after low
tide, in good weather, like today's overcast and sprinkly
conditions. In bad weather, it lies so low in the water that is
crossable only at dead low tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the passage,'' said Armstrong, who was in the Tour in
1993 when the road was last used. ``But it was just crazy. The
slightest wheel movement and you were sliding.''
</P>
<P>
   The pack entered the 2.4-mile causeway in a long parade that was
watched by hundreds of spectators standing barefooted on mud flats
where others were gathering shellfish, cockles and mussels. Barely
a mile in, a dozen riders near the midpoint of the pack began
falling and there was no way around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was well placed,'' said Zulle, who has a
reputation for being ill placed. ``But I was stopped. Once I got
started again I could see the big group in front but I couldn't
make it across to them.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason was that the contenders in the front group, including
Armstrong, Abraham Olano of ONCE, Pavel Tonkov of Mapei and Bobby
Julich of Cofidis, realized that they had a chance to leave some
formidable rivals far behind and spurred their teammates into
hyperspeed.
</P>
<P>
   Some 25 miles later, what had been perhaps a 20-second gap had
grown to two minutes. And 35 miles after that, at the finish, it
was 6:03. The chasers must have lost heart, with Zulle, Boogerd and
Gotti knowing that their hopes had curdled.
</P>
<P>
   Zulle, one of the Festina Six who confessed to the use of
illegal drugs after the nine-man team was expelled from last year's
Tour, now trails by 6:24. Gotti, the winner of the Giro d'Italia
last month, is 7:04 behind and Boogerd, fifth in the last Tour and
the winner of the Paris-Nice race in March, is 7:19 behind. Gotti's
teammate, Richard Virenque, the controversial French star, was in
the front group, 1:05 behind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
