<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN MEXICO, RULING PARTY AND OPPOSITION BOTH MAKE A
POINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For years now, opposition politicians have argued
that the Institutional Revolutionary Party, which by hook or crook
has won every presidential election since the 1920s, could not win
another one if the race were even halfway fair and open.
</P>
<P>
   After a comfortable victory by the party, known as the PRI, in
elections Sunday for governor of the state of Mexico, Mexico's most
populous state with 7.1 million registered voters, those
politicians have been proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   With a full-bore mobilization of its political machine, the PRI
managed to carry Arturo Montiel Rojas, 55, a candidate described
even by his own party as undistinguished and inarticulate, to the
governorship. Final results of the first official count showed that
Montiel took 40.7 percent of the vote, while the closest contender,
Jose Luis Duran Reveles of the National Action Party, or PAN, took
34.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A third candidate, Higinio Martinez Miranda, 43, of the Party of
the Democratic Revolution, polled 21.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The results removed any doubt that the presidential election to
be held on July 2, 2000, will be a real contest. Thanks to often
hard-fought reforms since the last national vote, in 1994,
President Ernesto Zedillo and the opposition have created a
relatively solid democratic framework for the balloting. Now the
PRI has shown that even under the new rules it can win once again.
</P>
<P>
   But so could the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that the two major opposition parties were
going down in defeat in the state of Mexico, an unlikely 11th-hour
opposition coalition of four parties, including the PAN and the
Party of the Democratic Revolution, snatched the governor's post
from the PRI in the small western coastal state of Nayarit.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition candidate, Antonio Echevarria, 55, won with 51.7
percent of the vote. The PRI candidate, Jose Lucas Vallarta Robles,
67, took 42.8 percent, a strong showing that would have allowed him
to win easily if the opposition had been divided.
</P>
<P>
   The day's results sent an unmistakable message that the
opposition could greatly improve its chances of taking national
power next year for the first time in seven decades by forming an
alliance behind a single candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But the case of the Nayarit coalition suggests little about
whether the opposition can forge an alliance at the national level.
In tiny Nayarit, a slow-living desert state with only 557,000
registered voters, the opposition had no strong candidates and
almost no following before this year. Its luck changed when
Echevarria, long the state PRI's richest and most savvy strongman
and fund-raiser, fell out with the governor, also from the PRI, and
bolted the party.
</P>
<P>
   Echevarria's political ideas, however, had little to do with his
success at uniting the opposition behind him. What counted was his
sheer pull at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about winning power for power's sake,'' said Joaquin
Lopez Doriga, a television commentator.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the two major opposition parties both have
strong-willed national leaders who are expected to become
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Vicente Fox Quesada of Guanajuato, known for his tough
country-style talk and cowboy boots, will probably run for the PAN,
a Catholic, business-oriented party. Some recent polls are casting
him as the front-runner at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano of the left-of-center Party of the
Democratic Revolution won the race for mayor of Mexico City in 1997
and is widely believed to have triumphed in the presidential vote
of 1988, losing it only by fraud.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine the scenario that would see one of them
stand graciously down in favor of the other.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the state of Mexico, which borders Mexico City on
three sides, also showed a decline in the popularity of Cardenas'
party. It dropped 13 percentage points since the elections in July
1997, when Cardenas was chosen mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials argued that the choice of Martinez, who turned
out to be a colorless candidate, may have affected their showing as
much as dissatisfaction with Cardenas' performance.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI seemed to be using the state of Mexico elections to test
several of the limits it will face in the big race next year. The
party mounted an abrasive but convincing campaign against crime,
which has overwhelmed many cities in the state. Montiel called
criminals ``rats'' who did not deserve the protections of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign, PRI party workers used a variety of
tactics to pressure voters or reward them for their vote, from a
massive drive to get photocopies of voter credentials to
election-day food hand-outs and outright payments to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Under both state and federal elections laws, these practices are
not illegal. ``Our problem is that vote-buying and coercion are
gray areas in the legislation,'' said Emilio Zebadua, a member of
the Federal Elections Council, which will oversee the presidential
contest.
</P>
<P>
   But if the results are close in the race for president, the
PRI's shenanigans could provoke an angry reaction from the
opposition. ``We will certainly see these tactics next year, and
they will stain the election,'' said Jose Antonio Crespo, an
elections analyst. ``And they could become a source of serious
conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-BLOOMINGTON-     07-05 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-BLOOMINGTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN SHOOTINGS LEFT MARK ON INDIANA COLLEGE TOWN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Ind. _ When a bust of Adolf Hitler was left on the
doorstep of a Jewish organization on Holocaust Remembrance Day this
year, there was little doubt around town who had delivered it.
</P>
<P>
   When well-tended lawns were repeatedly littered with pamphlets
advocating white supremacy, there was no mystery who had done the
leafleting.
</P>
<P>
   And when more than 500 people marched through downtown to oppose
hate speech, there was no question whose words they were opposing.
In fact, any uncertainty was erased when the one-man hate squad who
was the prime focus of the rally showed up in person to denounce
it.
</P>
<P>
   In little more than a year in Bloomington, Benjamin Nathaniel
Smith made a major impression _ almost universally negative _ on
this pleasant college town an hour south of Indianapolis. Before
moving back to his home state of Illinois seven weeks ago, Smith
spent his days here antagonizing religious, political, police, and
community leaders with what they called racist ravings. Nights and
weekends were given over to a loner's existence in an apartment
surrounded by black neighbors at whom he glared in stony silence.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 21, apparently killed himself late Sunday night while
being chased by police near Salem, Ill., 250 miles south of
Chicago. That ended a three-day, two-state shooting spree in which
authorities say he shot at nearly two dozen people _ all black,
Jewish or of Asian descent _ killing two and wounding nine.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Smith's assault began Friday night when he
wounded six Orthodox Jews as they left their northern Chicago
synagogue. Police said he then killed former Northwestern
University men's basketball coach Ricky Byrdsong, who is black,
while Byrdsong was walking with his children in Skokie, Ill., just
north of Chicago. That same night, police said, Smith also fired at
two Asian-Americans in nearby Northbrook; neither was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, two black men were fired upon and an Asian-American
man was injured in separate shootings in Springfield, Decatur, and
Urbana, Ill., authorities said. Smith was not charged in those
shootings but was considered the prime suspect before his death,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith then ended his bitter relationship with Bloomington on
Sunday by making it the last deadly stop on his apparent rampage.
That morning, Smith parked his light blue Ford Taurus outside the
Korean United Methodist Church of Bloomington and shot four times
into a crowd of worshipers as they were going to services, said
Police Chief Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Two bullets hit Won Joon Yoon, 26, killing the Korean immigrant
who came to Bloomington to seek a doctoral degree at Indiana
University. It was July Fourth and witnessses told police they were
certain the gunshots were firecrackers until their friend fell to
the sidewalk, fatally wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Taurus then sped out of town. Twelve hours later, Smith was
dead, still armed with the .22-caliber and .380-caliber handguns
police said matched the caliber of the guns used in the assaults.
Authorities said Monday they were tracing the source of the guns.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's end came after he carjacked a van at gunpoint at a rural
gas station in Marion County, Ill., said Sheriff Gerald L.
Benjamin. He said Smith apparently shot and wounded himself twice
as officers followed the van in a slow-speed chase. The van crashed
and Smith shot himself again while struggling with deputies,
Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Smith left a trail of shock and mourning all along his
path, his actions reverberated particularly hard in Bloomington,
where Smith's white supremacist beliefs reached full flower after
his arrival in spring 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Smith came to this city of 67,000 to attend Indiana University
as a criminal justice major, reportedly after he was expelled or
suspended from the University of Illinois. At 6 feet tall and 135
pounds, Smith was a gangling young man whose most notable physical
features were a tattoo on his chest that said ``Sabbath Breaker''
and what acquaintances said was an ever-ready scowl.
</P>
<P>
   He also brought with him the teachings of the World Church of
the Creator, a white supremacist organization based in East Peoria,
Ill., to which Smith belonged until May. The organization, which is
run from the home of its leader, Matt Hale, advocates ``crowding''
what it calls ``mud races'' off the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Hale Monday were not answered, but in an interview with
Reuters he said Smith's actions may have been provoked by the fact
that Hale was denied membership to the Illinois state bar on
Friday. Hale, who said his goal was to defend white supremacists in
court, said he never encouraged Smith to use violence to further
their goals.
</P>
<P>
   The World Church's message was generally unwelcome in
Bloomington, where more than half the residents are university
students and where the police station is adorned with the words,
``Bloomington, A Safe and Civil City.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Smith spent his first weeks in Bloomington putting
racist leaflets on cars at the university. That drew the attention
of Richard McKaig, the dean of students, who met with Smith on May
26, 1998, to discuss campus rules about posting leaflets. Smith
came with his own agenda, to complain about ``people harassing him
for exercising his free speech rights,'' McKaig said Monday. The
dean called it ``a businesslike discussion'' but noted that Smith's
``views about race were as bizarre as any I've ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith moved his efforts off-campus and, during Independence Day
weekend in 1998, he papered lawns and windshields with literature
from the World Church, alarming community leaders and attracting
the notice of police. He also came to the attention of groups that
track hate speech, including the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said his department's first contact with Smith came on
July 3, 1998, when a patrol car stopped him while he was
distributing fliers. Explaining his mission in an interview
published the next day in a student newspaper, Smith said: ``I
think it's pretty clear that our government has turned against
white people.'' It was a view he repeated in other public forums,
including radio call-in shows and letters to local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Smith never displayed violent tendencies and was
never charged with a crime in Bloomington. ``The only thing we
could have gotten him for was littering,'' Kennedy said. Smith did,
however, have a record of arrests in Illinois dating to 1995,
including resisting a peace officer.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Smith did the leafleting on his own and spent
most of his time in Bloomington by himself, though Kennedy said
police hope to speak with a woman who is believed to have helped
Smith distribute World Church literature. He said she is not a
suspect and that no one else is being sought in connection with the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Though there was no evidence Smith attracted followers in
Bloomington, his leaflets were deeply troubling to political,
religious, and community leaders. They responded by forming an
organization called Bloomington United, whose purpose was to find a
community response to hate speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dealing with a person who was trying to terrorize us
psychologically, and we came together in response,'' said Jeffrey
Willsey, a leader of the group and director of Bloomington's Safe
and Civil City Project.
</P>
<P>
   The group began its opposition to Smith with its own signs, some
of which can still be found on lawns: ``No hate speech. Not in our
yards, not in our town, not anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, last November, the group organized a march through
Bloomington to further denounce Smith. Mayor John Fernandez said in
an interview that he told the crowd: ``Our community must stand
together and reject messages of hate and division. We must find
strength in our differences.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor looked out over the crowd, and at the very front he
saw Smith, frowning and carrying a sign: ``No hate speech means no
free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith next came to authorities' attention in April, when the
bust of Hitler was found at the Helene G. Simon Hillel Center at
Indiana University. Attached was a note: ``Happy Holocaust
Remembrance Day. Thanks to the man who made it all possible.''
Smith had been seen in the area of the center that same day, said
Rabbi Sue Shifron, the center's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no question in my mind it was from him,'' Shifron
said. ``It was very frightening, which of course was his intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith's activities made him well known among
Bloomington's most active and powerful residents, he was virtually
anonymous to his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   During his time in Bloomington, Smith lived in a small apartment
complex called Touchdown Terrace in the shadow of Indiana
University's football stadium. It was a $370-a-month apartment with
all the charm of a roadside motel room. It is now vacant and being
used by the complex as a model for prospective tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Black tenants live on both sides of Smith's former unit as well
as in the apartment above. Several said they were unaware of his
racist beliefs. In retrospect, though, they said that might explain
why the windows to his apartment were smashed four or five times by
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say hello in passing, but we never communicated,'' said
Tyrese Alexander, who lives next door. ``He'd roll his eyes at me
and say nothing. But I couldn't imagine it was in his nature to do
such terrible things. I guess it means I should get to know my
neighbors better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
