<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALLSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR VOTES ARE IN, AND JETER COMES UP SHORT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mass., Wash., Texas, Fla., Md.)   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Derek Jeter, who had been considered the favorite to
start at shortstop in next Tuesday's All-Star Game in Boston, was
not ambushed in the Cleveland crusade that elected four members of
the Indians, but he did suffer from the apparent apathy of Yankees
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra, the hometown favorite in Boston, edged Jeter
Monday by about 20,000 votes in the closest race in the balloting
for the American League team. Garciaparra, whose offensive
performance this season has been good but not as good as Jeter's,
won with a late rally, coming from 30,000 votes behind in the final
week of vote counting, which included all Internet votes.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who was apparently aided by a Red Sox campaign in
the Internet phase of the voting, received 1,089,974 votes to
1,069,528 for Jeter. Omar Vizquel of Cleveland, who moved up
quickly in the final weeks of voting, finished third with
1,038,362.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie to you; I'd love to start the game,''
Jeter said after learning the results. ``But it's not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Joe Torre, Jeter's manager and the AL manager for the
second time in three years, had talked about the emphasis placed on
the All-Star balloting in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do more politicking and lobbying in other ball parks as
far as passing out the ballots and collecting the ballots,'' Torre
said. ``We don't do that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter said: ``It's true. You go to Cleveland and you got stuff
on the scoreboard every half-inning. They don't do some of those
things in New York. In different cities they stress voting for the
All-Star Game more than they do in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Yankees should do more to get out the vote, Torre
said, ``If you want your players to get as many votes or more votes
than other people.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the clubs that do promote their players and the voting,
the manager said, ``If they want to spend the time to get their
players in the game, good for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was disappointed in the results, Jeter did not
complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans vote; you count 'em and see who starts,'' he said.
``The fans are going to vote for who they want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the terrific season he is having, Jeter was asked if
the results were somewhat of a slap at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it shows the fans don't appreciate what you're
doing,'' he said. ``I just think it shows that the fans that voted
basically split it up. It was pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter is among the top four AL hitters in nine offensive
categories. Garciaparra, entering Monday's games, was among the top
three in four categories and the top 10 in three other categories.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter was second in hitting with a .377 average, Garciaparra
third at .366. Jeter was second with a .461 on-base percentage,
Garciaparra tied for ninth at .420. The Red Sox shortstop was third
with a .634 slugging percentage, Jeter tied for fourth at .630.
They were tied for third in extra-base hits with 42 each.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who was selected as a reserve for last year's game and
will go, Torre indicated, in that capacity next week, said there
was some consolation in losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I started,'' he said, ``they'd probably have booed me
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. of Seattle was the leading vote-getter for the
fourth successive season and seventh over all, receiving 2,918,055
votes. Roberto Alomar, the Indians' second baseman, was second with
2,793,891. Manny Ramirez and Kenny Lofton of Cleveland will join
Griffey in the starting outfield. First baseman Jim Thome was the
other member of the Indians who was elected to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Cal Ripken of Baltimore was elected for the 15th
time and the 11th time in succession. Other starters will be Ivan
Rodriguez of Texas at catcher and Jose Canseco of Tampa Bay as the
designated hitter. (This was the first time the d.h. was on the
ballot.) Other than Canseco, the only only players who weren't
elected last year were Garciaparra and Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will have no starters for the second successive
season.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez of Texas, who said he would not go to the game as
a reserve because he objected to the Cleveland voting, placed fifth
among outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   POSADA APOLOGIZES TO UMPIRES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada woke up Monday, realized he had made a serious
mistake and apologized to the umpires last night for critical
comments he made about the home-plate umpire in Sunday's game, Greg
Kosc.
</P>
<P>
   Kosc, who was forced to leave the game at Yankee Stadium between
the Yankees and the Baltimore Orioles because of heat exhaustion
and dehydration, was hospitalized overnight and returned home
Monday. He thus was not in the umpires' room when Posada went to
apologize, but the catcher expressed that sentiment to Larry
Barnett, the crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't have said what I said,'' Posada told reporters.
``I was mad. There was a lot of frustration inside of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada was upset at being called out on a questionable third
strike the inning before Kosc, 50, left the game. It reached a
record 100 degrees in New York on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line, the guys are not in shape,'' Posada said
after the game, referring to umpires. ``It was hot; I can
understand it's hot. You've got to be able to go through the game.
They're not prepared; they're not in shape. It's a shame. He gets
hot, the zone gets bigger. One doesn't go with the other one.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett said Kosc was told to see his own doctor and to have his
blood-sugar level checked. ``His sugar was extremely high,''
Barnett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
