<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT TO ENABLE RUSSIA TO SEND TROOPS TO KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia is ready to resume sending troops to Kosovo,
officials said, after Russian and NATO negotiators solved a dispute
Monday over the role of Moscow's peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement had threatened to put new strains on Russia's
shaky relationship with the Western alliance, after NATO blocked
Russian transport aircraft from flying to Kosovo last week.
</P>
<P>
   Russian and NATO officials said that military transport flights,
which have been waiting on the runway of an airport 200 miles
northeast of Moscow, could begin transporting paratroopers and
equipment to the Balkans as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials outside the 11-hour negotiations
revealed no details of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sides also confirmed that there are no obstacles to the
deployment of Russian peacekeeping forces in Kosovo,'' the Russian
Defense Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   General Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme commander, said the
agreement does not provide for Russian troops to expand into the
Italian-patrolled sector of Kosovo, as Russia had wanted. That
would have allowed Russia to station troops in contiguous zones,
which NATO ruled out because it does not want Russian troops to
have their own sector.
</P>
<P>
   With 700 troops already in Kosovo, Russia is expected to
increase its contingent to 3,600. US officials said last week they
directed Hungary, Bulgaria and Romania to close their airspace to
the flights after Moscow and NATO were unable to work out
differences over the role of the Russian peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's move provoked angry comments by military and diplmatic
officials, and cut into some of the pride Russians took from their
surprise deployment of 200 troops at Pristina's airport on June 12,
which upstaged the entrance of NATO peacekeepers into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, which had objected strongly to NATO's airstrikes against
Yugoslavia and played a key diplomatic role in reaching a
settlement to the conflict, rushed its troops into Kosovo to assure
itself a major role in the peacekeeping operation. But some saw
NATO's move to refuse Russia airspace as a humiliating reminder of
Russia's subordinate position to the alliance in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are showing us who is boss, who is stronger,'' commented
Russian legislator Vladimir Lukin.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has insisted it does not want its troops to take direct
orders from alliance generals.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, quoted by the Associated Press, said that Russian troops
would not have to follow NATO instructions on certain issues, such
as matters that contradict Russian law, like the apprehension of
war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers' control of Kosovo is one of the factors that
has fueled Serb anger at Milosevic's government _ on top of the
destruction wrought by NATO's 78-day air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   There were these other developments:
</P>
<P>
   --An Army specialist struck by a car in Skopje, Macedonia, over
the weekend became the first US soldier to die in NATO's Kosovo
peacekeeping mission, US military officials said Monday. Specialist
Anthony W. Gilman, 23, of Michael, Ill., was hit by the car Sunday
afternoon after he stepped into traffic to place a warning triangle
on a road to alert approaching motorists to the site of a previous
accident. Two people in the car that struck Gilman also died. Their
identities were unavailable Monday.
</P>
<P>
   --Up to 10,000 chanting protesters took to the streets in a
southern Serbian town Monday _ the latest sign of growing anger at
President Slobodan Milosevic's government.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how deep the discontent may be, Monday's protests
in Leskovac, 120 miles southeast of Belgrade, were not organized by
an opposition party _ they were inspired by a technician at the
local TV station.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, technician Ivan Novkovic came on during a break in a
broadcast of a basketball match and accused the local governor _ a
member of Milosevic's party _ of abusing his authority. Novkovic
urged people to rally Monday to demand his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands responded, chanting ``Thieves, thieves!'' and
``Changes, changes!'' while police made no attempt to stop the
march.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a member of any political party. My moves were
motivated solely by my conscience as a citizen,'' Novkovic told the
Danas independent daily.
</P>
<P>
   --Milosevic's government has also been shaken by Kosovo Serbs
fleeing the province in the face of revenge attacks by ethnic
Albanians for Serb forces' atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The UN refugee agency estimates that more than 71,000 Kosovo
Serbs have fled the province since March 1998, but has no figures
for how many have left after the NATO deployment began. Belgrade
claims more than 100,000 Serbs have left Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Kosovo's Serb community Monday demanded the
peacekeepers investigate crimes against Serbs in the province and
alleged the existence of prison camps in Kosovo holding Serbs. ``We
have clear indications'' that the camps exist, Serb Orthodox Bishop
Artemije and Kosovo Serb politician Momcilo Trajkovic said in a
letter to the private Beta news agency.
</P>
<P>
   They did not give any evidence about the camps or say where they
were located.
</P>
<P>
   --Sadako Ogata, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees on a visit
to Kosovo, expressed concern Monday for the Serb and Gypsy
minorities, but said the return of ethnic Albanian refugees was
going smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   So far, about 589,600 of the more than 860,000 refugees have
come home to Kosovo since NATO troops began deploying June 12, the
UN refugee agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Many have returned to find their homes burned and relatives
killed _ sparking reprisal attacks against Serbs and their
property.
</P>
<P>
   --Former Senator Bob Dole, completing a trip as the head of the
International Commission on Missing Persons, visited a mass grave
site near Pec Monday that held the bodies of 97 ethnic Albanians
thought to have been murdered by Serb security forces during the
NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine reported Monday that President Clinton has
authorized the CIA to help topple Milosevic, who has been indicted
for war crimes. CIA computer hackers will try to meddle with
Milosevic's private financial transactions, deposit cash with
opposition organizations in Yugoslavia, and recruit dissidents in
the government and military, Time said.
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
