<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Braves dig deep for late-game win over Marlins
</P>
<P>
   By Carroll Rogers
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have apparently had it with those last-minute losses
in games they should have won.
</P>
<P>
   They've had three of them on the road trip and nearly another
one to start a seven-game homestand Monday night. But against the
N.L. East bottom-dwelling Marlins, the Braves dug a little deeper
and fought back for a 6-5 win, this after losing leads of 3-1, 4-3
and 5-4 in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the last of those leads in the top of the ninth
inning, the Braves came fighting back by loading the bases with one
out in the bottom of the inning on a Bret Boone single, a wild
pitch, an intentional walk to Chipper Jones and a walk by Brian
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Gerald Williams who singled just out of the
reach of Bruce Aven in left field to score Boone for the win.
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Rocker had not allowed a run all season at Turner
Field but came up with one on Monday to blow his second save in his
last three outings.
</P>
<P>
   He had a 5-4 lead heading into the ninth inning _ thanks in part
to Bret Boone's third home run in the last two days _ when he
loaded the bases on a pair of singles to Mike Redmond and Luis
Castillo and a walk to Dave Berg. He had a Bruce Aven 0-2 but then
lost him on a run-scoring walk to tie the game 5-5. Kevin McGlinchy
relieved him and coaxed the final out on a pop fly by Kevin Millar.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone commenced making up for lost time on Monday night
hitting his third home run in his last two games, after a stretch
of 43 games without one.
</P>
<P>
   His shot to left field off Brian Edmondson in the seventh inning
gave him his third home run in his last nine at-bats, this after
going 169 at-bats without one, and the Braves a 5-4 win over the
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Boone hit two home runs in the Braves 7-6 loss to the Mets on
Sunday night, but he made sure this one counted as it put the
Braves on top for the third time in the game in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   It allowed the Braves to win a game started by Odalis Perez for
the first time since June 8 and start this seven-game homestand on
a winning note with their fourth win in five tries against the
Marlins this season.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
