<HEADER>
A0066 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-05 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO REASON TO HAMM IT UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I went to Los Angeles International Airport to
greet the U.S. women's World Cup team Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Me and a cast of tens.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I was surrounded by so many pony-tailed pixies was
last fall, when I watched my favorite goal-goal girl, the
9-year-old daughter of friends, leave her heart and soul on a pitch
in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could say the effort and enthusiasm of all those mini
Mias left an indelible impression on me that day. Their postseason
game, after all, mattered as much to Cecilia and her teammates as
Saturday's World Cup final against China does to the U.S. squad.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, what sticks in my mind more than anything is the
beet-faced father who ran up and down the sidelines alongside his
daughter, commenting crassly on her every miscue _ even after time
ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Sad to say, overzealous adults got into the act again Monday,
turning a show of support into a vaudeville act. The best female
players on the planet were upstaged by people old enough to know
better.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm and Co. couldn't have prepared themselves for it _ the
past two weeks have been one continuous revelatory reel for the
U.S. squad _ but when they disembarked from United Airlines Flight
2029, they were stepping into a scripted Hollywood scene.
</P>
<P>
   It apparently dawned on none of the Oz-like characters working
the hype-machine levers that what the most ogled, most celebrated
group of women since the Spice Girls really needs at this point is
rest, not more adoration.
</P>
<P>
   A chartered airplane and a chartered bus waiting on the airplane
tarmac to whisk them away surely would have played well with U.S.
team members, who are starting to show the fatigue of this pajama
party with America, now in its third week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it wouldn't have played nearly as well on the 5
o'clock news, which explains why youth teams were summoned to Gate
88 in the United terminal and handed Women's World Cup T-shirts to
wear over tank tops and jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 minutes before the U.S. team's commercial flight from
San Francisco was scheduled to touch down, a woman prepped the
giddy girls (and a few bored-looking boys) as though they were a
Tonight Show studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters were told that as soon as they saw the first U.S.
player pop out of the jetway, they were to begin chanting, ``Go
U-S-A.''
</P>
<P>
   Then flags and flowers were distributed among the kids along
with explicit instructions. The flowers were to be presented to the
players as they passed through the solid double-line procession on
their way to the baggage-claim area.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers at nearby gates waiting to board flights to San Jose,
San Franciso, Phoenix and Portland feigned disinterest. A few left
their seats and mingled with the soccer crowd, but the majority
seemed more fixed on their destinations than Team Destiny.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't really change when the plane bellied up to the gate
and its newly recognizable passengers spilled into the boarding
lounge and surged toward the street. Once the players moved past
the assembled throng, the cheering and clapping gave way to a few
muffled whispers of, ``Hey, isn't that....''
</P>
<P>
   The players looked relieved that people in the terminal were
going about their business and leaving them alone. (The lone
exception was Hamm, who had four journalists hoist television
cameras on their shoulders and form a moving wall in front of her,
the better to record every step and smile and sigh). But one woman,
decked out in World Cup garb, couldn't stand that more of a ruckus
wasn't being raised. She had to lift her arms over her head and
start clapping and chanting, ``C'mon. USA, All the Way. Clap with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   You go to airports and you expect to be hit up by missionaries
shaking change jars. But soccer zealots?
</P>
<P>
   Trying to summon sentiments out of the stale air does a
disservice to the U.S. team, which is good and gracious enough to
grab the public's attention on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't fall in love with athletes who compete for the love
of their sport and not for the money, who have bigger vocabularies
than egos?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, these made-for-the-media moments are absolutely the only
thing about the U.S. women's World Cup team that is contrived.
</P>
<P>
   The players' ebullience and earnestness and eloquence is not the
product of a publicist's imagination. It is not a marketing hook.
It is not spin.
</P>
<P>
   What you see is what you get.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women are guileless in a good way. They're as genuine
as the leather orb they boot and even tougher, which makes them a
ball to watch.
</P>
<P>
   In the players' hands, the sport is scintillating. As for the
people on the sidelines, they ought to stay in the background where
they belong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
