u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      07-05 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WIMBLEDON TO REMEMBER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ There was a spectacular final-round swan dive by the
three-time defending champion and a stealthy final-round swan song
by a seven-time champion. There was the re-ignition of an
all-American rivalry between two peers who believe that older and
balder means better, and the Grand Slam initiation of three female
prodigies with nothing more in common than family histories making
for headlines and tennis smarts bordering on the phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   With a full cast of champions who elevated their games, and
emotions, to a fever pitch, and plot lines that seemed stolen from
a soap opera, the final Wimbledon of the 20th century was a dandy.
</P>
<P>
   History was made, youth was served, and Boris Becker, the German
who won Wimbledon at 17 and couldn't resist one last crack at it at
31, finally retired for real. Even John McEnroe got into the act,
but just as he had back when Bjorn Borg administered residual
thumpings, McEnroe went away mad _ stung that Steffi Graf
jettisoned their mixed doubles campaign two victories short of a
title because she feared it would compromise her quest for an
eighth _ and final _ Wimbledon singles crown.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras and Lindsay Davenport buddied up and won the
singles championships in straight sets, then did a victory jig at
the Champions Ball on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Like a tired little homing pigeon, Andre Agassi, Sampras'
final-round victim, jumped on the casino scion Steve Wynn's private
jet and zipped back to Las Vegas. Steffi Graf, the 30-year-old icon
who decided her final-round loss to Davenport would be her last
appearance at Wimbledon, where she had won her past seven finals,
was as circumspect about her travel plans as she had been about her
retirement. She simply left the grounds in her rental car.
</P>
<P>
   When the tournament began, Davenport noticed the odds were
against her at 15-1 but restrained herself from taking that bet
``because I was afraid I'd get thrown out of tennis or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who homed in on those long odds was, she said, ``a
genius.'' Davenport settled for a six-figure prize and the No. 1
ranking, something the 29-year-old Agassi achieved, except that his
didn't come with a title attached.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, as he has for six of the last seven years, Sampras
put on his tennis whites like a suit of armor, brandished his
racquet like a mace and defended his favorite turf from pretenders
and usurpers like a king defending a castle. Against Agassi, in a
Sunday final that sparked like a family reunion, Sampras surprised
even himself by elevating his game to the fifth dimension for
history's sake, and for his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the best match I ever played through my whole
career,'' the 27-year-old Sampras said. ``I'm not going to win
Wimbledon every year. But I've raised the bar so high that if I
don't do it, then something's wrong, and I guess that's kind of a
compliment in some ironic way. But as long as I feel like I can
play my game, yeah, I feel like I'm `the man' at Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   This year ``the man'' finished up like a Roman candle: he lit up
the court and incinerated his incredulous opponent. He even dared
to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Three points away from the most historic Wimbledon championship
claimed by anyone in any century, Sampras performed his swan dive,
a valiant horizontal leap in vain pursuit of the biting crosscourt
forehand pass his desperate archrival flashed past him as a
reminder that he would not succumb quietly.
</P>
<P>
   En route to a record sixth Wimbledon championship and a 12th
career Grand Slam title, tying Roy Emerson's milestone, Sampras
chased after Agassi's brilliant shot like a hound on a scent.
</P>
<P>
   When gravity caught up with him after his volley failed, Sampras
touched down hard on the battered grass of Center Court. It left a
nasty red welt on his serving elbow. But instead of hobbling him,
it hurled him to new heights. With blood trickling down his arm, he
fired off the final two aces that secured the championship and
reconfirmed his place among, and perhaps above, predecessors like
Rod Laver, Don Budge, Fred Perry and Emerson. ``It was worth it,''
Sampras said about his flight. He may have lost the point, but he
definitely made his point: Wimbledon 1999 belonged to him.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sampras and Agassi, who made his own brand of history last
month at the French Open by joining those aforementioned champions
of yesteryear as the only member of his generation to capture all
four Grand Slam events, looked to the next Grand Slam, the U.S.
Open, as soon as this one ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fastened my seat belt six weeks ago, and I'm glad I did,''
Agassi said. ``It's going to be a wild ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the final electricity was generated by Sampras and
Agassi, the women grabbed their share of the marquee. The first
shocker came in the first round, with 129th-ranked, 16-year-old
Jelena Dokic's subjugation of top-seeded Martina Hingis, who
simultaneously declared her independence from her mother/coach,
Melanie Molitor.
</P>
<P>
   Dokic, Mirjana Lucic and San Diego's Alexandra Stevenson, the
first female qualifier to reach Wimbledon's semifinals, and their
various parents made headlines throughout the second week.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say about this Wimbledon is that it's the weirdest
Wimbledon I've ever played,'' Sampras said. And the best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
