</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-LEADER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED CHURCH OF CHRIST ELECTS NEW HEAD AND RESTRUCTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ohio)  (mk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United Church of Christ, a denomination that traces some of
its roots back to the Puritans, elected as its new president Sunday
the Rev. John Thomas, a minister widely known for his work in
ecumenical relations.
</P>
<P>
   His election took place at the denomination's biennial business
session, the General Synod, as part of a restructuring of the
church's top offices that has been in the works for more than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, 48, will succeed the Rev. Paul Sherry as president of
the 1.4 million-member denomination on Oct. 1. Since 1992, he has
served as Sherry's assistant for ecumenical concerns. Thomas' title
will become general minister and president on July 1, 2000, as part
of the changes adopted by the synod, which has been meeting in
Providence, R.I., since last week. The synod will conclude Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the restructuring, the number of officials in the
denomination's leadership will be reduced from more than a dozen to
five, and their responsibilities will be made more broadly equal.
At the denomination's head will be a collegium of officers made up
of five members who will take office next July.
</P>
<P>
   Four other candidates to round out that group were recommended
to the synod's delegates by search committees within the
denomination. The four _ elected like Thomas without opposition
Sunday _ were the Rev. Jose ``Joe'' Malayang, as executive minister
of local church ministries; Edith Guffey, as associate general
minister; Bernice Powell Jackson, as executive minister of justice
and witness ministries, and Dale Bishop, as executive minister of
wider church ministries. All are leaders in the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said that the United Church of Christ, whose national
agencies and local congregations are autonomous, has never had a
strictly top-down form of leadership, but the new structure ensures
that the denomination will move even further from that hierarchical
model.
</P>
<P>
   He said the idea of the president within the collegium could be
compared with a ``more ancient understanding'' of church
leadership, prevailing among Eastern Orthodox churches, in which
the ecumenical patriarch of Constantinople is first among equals
among the patriarchs of national Orthodox churches.
</P>
<P>
   The United Church of Christ, whose headquarters is in Cleveland,
was founded in a 1957 merger of the Congregational Christian
Churches and the Evangelical and Reformed Church.
</P>
<P>
   As ecumenical officer, Thomas was a principal figure in forging
one of the most important ecumenical documents of recent years, the
``formula of agreement,'' in 1997. The document created the basis
for formal, close cooperation among more than 10 million of the
nation's Protestants by establishing full communion between the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and three denominations from
Protestantism's Reformed tradition, the Presbyterian Church (USA),
the United Church of Christ and the Reformed Church in America.
</P>
<P>
   Under the provisions of the agreement, the denominations agreed
to recognize one another's sacraments and clergy members and to
collaborate in missionary work and major social service projects.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a native of Stamford, Conn., who is married with two
children and is a 1975 graduate of Yale Divinity School, said the
United Church of Christ would continue to reach out to other
Christian communities, including immigrant groups.
</P>
<P>
   He said other concerns for the denomination include speaking out
with a Christian viewpoint in an increasingly secular culture,
attending to the needs for ``exciting worship and spiritual depth''
in local congregations, and developing an understanding of the
nation's religious pluralism so that the denomination is
cooperative, rather than competitive, with other faith groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
