<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON'S PLAN FOR NEUTRALIZING THE CARPETBAGGING ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Listening to New Yorkers'' discussions that Hillary Rodham
Clinton is planning for the exploratory phase of her Senate
campaign will focus on familiar political issues: health care,
public schools and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, though, there is a more fundamental mission to these
forums, and it has less to do with the problems facing the nation
than with the problems confronting Mrs. Clinton's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The real goal, Mrs. Clinton's advisers acknowledge, is less to
educate her than to address what they see as her most serious
vulnerability _ that she is seeking to represent in the Senate a
state where she has never lived.
</P>
<P>
   This is a case where what a candidate says may not matter, and
according to her advisers, Mrs. Clinton plans to say very little of
substance in the months ahead, starting with the six ``Listening to
New Yorkers'' forums that she has scheduled this week in central
New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, her intention, aides said Monday, is to spend so much
time in New York, with a procession of cookie-cutter forums
intended to produce a daily diet of television images, that her
trips to the state become as routine as a visit by the first lady
can be. In that way, her aides hope that Mrs. Clinton, a native of
Illinois, will become as familiar a part of the state's political
geography as, say, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a couple of weeks, people are going to look and say, `She's
still out there,''' Mandy Grunwald, one of Mrs. Clinton's
strategists, asserted. ``And a couple of weeks later, they're going
to look again and say she's STILL out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Mrs. Clinton, who will formally register an exploratory
committee for her campaign with federal election officials Tuesday,
can succeed at this strategy is open to question but is critical to
her ambitions in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Giuliani, the Republican who is also interested in
running for the seat, are dubious that she can, as are some
independent political analysts following the race.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a factor working in her favor: The calendar.
There are 16 months until the vote to replace Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, the Democrat who is not running for re-election in 2000,
and that is a huge stretch of time in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, such a long campaign presents the risk of
overexposure or campaign missteps. But it might also give the first
lady enough time so that by next year she can, with some
credibility, claim ties to a state where she has never lived a day.
And even if she cannot quite get away with that assertion, it is a
reasonable bet that over time, the issue of carpetbagging will lose
some of its edge: that an attack that seems highly potent today
will seem stale and familiar, particularly if it remains as much in
the spotlight as it has been so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   And from this perspective, Giuliani's relentless focus on Mrs.
Clinton's residency seems an odd bit of political strategy, as even
Giuliani's own supporters have begun to acknowledge. It is not that
they think he should not raise the topic. But by doing it so soon,
he may actually be helping to inoculate Mrs. Clinton from attacks
on the issue next year, when they will really matter.
</P>
<P>
   It may only be a matter of time until the press, and the public,
tire of this topic and move on to other ones, which will make it
harder to move the carpetbagger question back to center stage when
the 2000 campaign comes around.
</P>
<P>
   There is, one of the mayor's friends said, no grand strategy
being executed: It is only Giuliani being Giuliani. Another
adviser, Bruce Teitelbaum, the head of Giuliani's political action
committee, maintained that Giuliani was only responding to the
inquiries of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani certainly seems to encourage the questions.
</P>
<P>
   He has, for example, decided to make a fund-raising trip to
Little Rock, Ark. Little Rock is known for many things in American
politics, including being the former home of a certain first lady,
but fund-raising is generally not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Giuliani's trip will provide the grist for a few
more articles about Mrs. Clinton and carpetbagging, which may well
be exactly what Mrs. Clinton needs right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
