<HEADER>
A0080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-MARKETS-NYT     07-05 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MARKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY OF JAPANESE BUSINESS SHOWS PESSIMISM ABATING 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese central bank's quarterly assessment of
business sentiment suggested Monday that while executives have not
yet heaved sighs of relief about the nation's economy, they are
breathing easier.
</P>
<P>
   The survey from the Bank of Japan, known as the tankan index,
showed that the perception of business conditions among more than
9,000 who responded in June was still negative, but improving.
</P>
<P>
   The results fell within the range of estimates by economists,
who had anticipated that huge government spending on public works
projects and loan guarantees for small and midsized enterprises, as
well as an improvement in other Asian economies that import
Japanese goods, would help assuage any lingering fears of much
worse times to come.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Nikkei index of 225 Japanese stocks rose 1.13
percent Monday, to 18,135.06 _ its highest close in 21 months.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey's so-called diffusion index remained solidly
negative, meaning that pessimistic executives still widely
outnumbered optimists. This index _ the difference between the
percentage of companies that consider business to be improving and
those that regard it as worsening _ rose to a minus 37 from minus
44 at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current level is still below the trough reached in the
1986 and 1992 recessions,'' said Russell Jones, chief economist at
Lehman Brothers here. ``Also, what's clear is that the overhang of
excess capacity, both in the physical sense of production capacity
and in terms of labor, is huge and remains a big depressant on the
economy going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jones and others say that the economy has stabilized
after hitting bottom at the end of last year. The government is
expected to throw more money into the system in the fall, since
private industry is as yet in no condition to begin fueling its own
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Japanese industry shown any signs of embarking on the
kind of large-scale cutbacks that many here say is needed. A senior
official at the central bank noted that total employment among
businesses responding to the survey dropped 1 percent between March
and June, and among large companies, there was no change at all. In
the March survey, employment dropped an average of 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My big worry is that employment restructuring is not taking
place in a big way,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``I'm afraid that Japanese corporations are delaying
reductions in manpower that they've promised, thanks to an
improvement in business prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other officials, he is concerned that nascent recovery will
stifle the urge to cut work forces and pare down businesses.
``Essentially what you're seeing reflected in the tankan is an
improvement in mood and outlook,'' he said, ``and that may not be a
good thing for the economy at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the central bank moved to curb some of the enthusiasm
its report aroused, again intervening in the currency market to
sell yen and restrain the currency's rise after the tankan survey's
release. Indeed, traders were preparing last week for a rush of
foreign investment if the survey lived up to economists'
predictions, which would drive the yen's value up against the
dollar and hurt major Japanese exporters.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's intervention showed some results. The yen settled in
London trading at 122.26 to the dollar, off from Friday's New York
rate of 120.96 to the dollar. (American markets were closed for the
Independence Day holiday.)
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the government released first-quarter gross domestic
product data last month suggesting that the economy was on track to
grow 7.9 percent, the central bank has repeatedly moved to rein in
the yen. Neither the government nor private economists think the
economy is really that robust, and economists said that Monday's
survey offered a more realistic assessment of economic prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the very good numbers we saw a few weeks ago, the
tankan was a lot more modest,'' said Tadashi Nakamae, president of
Nakamae International Economic Research. ``I think it's more in
line with the reality, although corporate managers are still overly
optimistic about the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey suggested that companies expect profit to rise rather
sharply, even while anticipating flat revenue. But without sharper
job cutbacks, there is little chance that they will be able to
squeeze significantly greater profits from their sales,
particularly since expansion plans have declined more sharply than
economists anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists suggested that the expectations of greater
profitability could indicate that plans for corporate revamping,
thus far vague, will be further-reaching than many thought.
``Either they're incredibly optimistic, or intending to reduce
labor costs and investment sharply,'' Jones said. ``It could be
indicative of quite a lot of restructuring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
