<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES' SURHOFF MAKES HIS CASE FOR ALL-STAR DESIGNATION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ B.J. Surhoff, the day after he beat the Yankees with
a tie-breaking grand slam, again propelled the Baltimore Orioles
past the Yankees, 9-1, Monday in 100-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff, the Orioles' hitter with the most productive career
performance against Andy Pettitte, set up their first run with a
first-inning single, then drove home the fourth run with a
fourth-inning single against the troubled left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with Jason Grimsley pitching in the seventh inning,
Surhoff sealed the victory by whacking a three-run home run an
estimated 419 feet over the center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Yankees Manager Joe Torre apparently had
already decided that Surhoff deserved a spot as a reserve on the
American League All-Star team, which will be named Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff, who has never been on an All-Star team in his 13-year
career, clinched a spot by raising his batting average to .342, his
RBIs to a team-leading 69, his home run total to a team-leading 20
and his number of hits to a league-leading 118.
</P>
<P>
   But just in case Torre had any lingering question, Surhoff
erased it in the sixth inning, after Doug Johns, a nondescript
member of the Orioles' ineffective relief corps, had relieved Mike
Mussina.
</P>
<P>
   With Yankees runners at first and second, two out and the
Orioles ahead, 4-1, Chili Davis lashed a line drive to left field
that appeared to have a good chance of reaching the fence for a
two-run double. But Surhoff raced back, reached up as the ball
whizzed overhead and snared it, keeping the ball from its
appointment with the fence.
</P>
<P>
   His two-way effort made it easy for Mussina to gain his 10th
victory, even though he pitched only five and one-third innings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, the Yankees won't have to worry about losing to
Mussina at Yankee Stadium until 2005. Mussina is in his eighth
season as one of the best pitchers in the American League, but he
couldn't prove it by his performance over the years against the
Yankees. Against the rest of the league, Mussina has a 124-71
record, a .636 winning percentage. When he walked to the mound to
start Monday night, though, he was saddled with a 3-8 record and a
.273 winning percentage against the Yankees. Worse, the only time
he had defeated the Yankees at their park was the first time he
pitched in New York, way back in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mussina allowed the Yankees only two hits in the first four
innings, then gave up a pair of singles in the fifth. But he
retired Chuck Knoblauch on a fly to center field for the third out
and maintained his 4-1 lead. But when the Yankees stroked a pair of
one-out singles in the sixth, Manager Ray Miller decided Mussina
had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Surhoff bailed out Mussina with his fine running
catch, and minutes later Cal Ripken slugged his 11th home run of
the season, a two-run shot against Grimsley. Surhoff added his
three-run home run in the next inning, and the Orioles, whose
losing streak had reached a season-high 10 games, somehow emerged
with a split of their four-game visit to New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
