<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0091 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-TOMJANOVICH-HNS &LR;      07-05 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TOMJANOVICH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Citing medical reasons, Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich withdrew
Monday as head coach of USA Basketball's 1999 men's senior national
team that will compete in the Olympic qualifying tournament July
14-25 in Puerto Rico.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rudy is recovering from extreme physical exhaustion,'' said
Rockets team physician Jim Muntz. ``We have advised rest, and in
light of this he will not be able to coach the USA men's senior
national team in the pre-Olympic Tournament of the Americas.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich, complaining of dizziness and weakness, was checked
into Memorial Hospital by Muntz on Friday and released Sunday. But
Tomjanovich said Monday he simply wasn't yet up to the three-week
coaching stint that would be demanded by the USA national team,
which will have preliminary workouts this week in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed to say that I won't be able to fulfill
my obligation to USA Basketball,'' Tomjanovich said. ``It's really
a great honor and something I was looking forward to. But I've
overworked myself, and I find myself really physically and mentally
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent a couple of days in the hospital and conferred with
my doctor, and the prescription is three or four weeks of rest. I'm
really disappointed, and I'm going to do my best to recharge myself
and get ready for the upcoming season.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia 76ers coach Larry Brown was named to succeed
Tomjanovich as head coach of the national team, but Tomjanovich is
still scheduled to coach the Dream Team in the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not been given any indication by USA Basketball that
this will affect his (Tomjanovich's) status for 2000,'' said
Rockets spokesman Tim Frank, ``should the team qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   With a team that includes players like San Antonio's Tim Duncan,
Seattle's Gary Payton, Minnesota's Kevin Garnett and the Phoenix
tandem of Jason Kidd and Tom Gugliotta, the team is almost a sure
bet to qualify. The U.S. squad needs only to finish among the top
two teams at the qualifying tournament to get a bid to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich has been going nonstop for almost two years, the
leading contributor to his condition.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rockets were eliminated from the 1998 NBA playoffs,
Tomjanovich was supposed to lead a team of NBA stars in last
summer's World Championships of Basketball in Athens, Greece. When
the NBA players boycotted the tournament because of a
league-imposed lockout, Tomjanovich took a team composed of college
and Continental Basketball Association players and led them to a
bronze medal, even though most experts predicted Team USA would be
quickly eliminated from the competition.
</P>
<P>
   After taking home the bronze medal, Tomjanovich and his staff
returned to the uncertainty of the lockout, which was not resolved
until January. Tomjanovich was forced to put in long hours
preparing for the season, especially since the Rockets got involved
in trade talks concerning Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   The recent NBA draft and overtures from Toronto concerning
possibly trading for Hakeem Olajuwon meant even more work for
Tomjanovich and his staff. As a result, Tomjanovich removed himself
from the NBA's Select Committee, which was assembled to discuss and
analyze possible rules changes to speed up the game and increase
scoring. Tomjanovich did not attend last month's Select Committee
meeting in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And now he has removed himself from the USA national team.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that after being named head coach, he immediately
called and got input from Tomjanovich on the offensive and
defensive sets he wanted to employ.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was first told about this possibility, I was hopeful
that Rudy would be back in a couple of days,'' Brown said. ``But
that's not the case. I'm shocked. I called him and got filled in on
the things he wanted to do. The way I'm looking at it is that I'm
just filling in until he gets back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to have as much input as possible. Really, I was
just looking forward to learning from Rudy. I always feel as though
I benefit from those situations like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad. I was looking forward to being an assistant to Rudy
and learning a lot. This is tough. I'm just hoping he'll get well
and gets back real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments were echoed by USA Basketball executive
director Warren Brown, who announced the coaching change Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first thought is with Rudy and his quick recovery,'' Brown
said. ``We're extremely fortunate that this team has an outstanding
coaching staff, and we are confident that Larry, Gene (Keady) and
Tubby (Smith) will be able to guide this squad to an Olympic
qualifying berth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-99 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990705.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0092 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRIVEBY-SHOOTER-ART-2     07-05 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVEBY-SHOOTER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
CHICAGO: was established.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the Fourth of July weekend in 1998, Smith was openly placing
2,000 flyers under windshields in a wide area of Bloomington. The
text, from the World Church of the Creator, extolled the ``Great
White Race'' and assailed what it called ``a deceitful, alien
government, a controlled media, and a suicidal religion.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Bloomington, John Fernandez, encountered Smith
twice, at a rally and on a radio call-in show. ``All indications
were that he didn't have any history of violence,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Smith began to give interviews. He offered his views on violence
to Lisa Sorg, managing editor of the Bloomington Independent, as
they sat in the Encore Cafi in Bloomington last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we can legally come to power through nonviolence,''
Smith said, ``but Hale says if they try to restrict our legal means
then we have no recourse but to resort to terrorism and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had received death threats, but wasn't afraid. ``I'm
more afraid for my race than myself,'' he said. ``Nature isn't
concerned with the individual, but with the species.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he still spoke with his parents, but didn't have the
friends at home that he used to have. He calls his former friends
``race traitors.''
</P>
<P>
   While some members of the Church of the Creator wanted to
partition the nation into areas for different minorities, he told
Ms. Sorg that he wanted to expel racial and religious minorities.
``They won't be very happy to leave, but they'll probably end up
wanting to leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his career goal was to be a lawyer. This spring he
testified for Hale, the World Church leader, who has tried
unsuccessfully to receive a law license in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorg said that Smith came across as very calm, his voice
flat, his eyes dead. He seemed to have an almost reverential
devotion to Hale almost like a ``schoolgirl crush,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By November 1998, the community had decided to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was civic pornography,'' said Jeffrey Willsey, an
organizer of a group called Bloomington United, that formed in
response to the leafletting. ``We felt that because it was in our
yards, and there was a clear attempt to psychologically intimidate
our community, it was important to respond to it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Smith wrote again to the student paper in November, saying that
the community march did not prove that he was a minority of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that there has been no massive rejection of the
World Church's materials or ideas,'' Smith wrote. ``The rally was
the product of a diverse gang of special interests groups, none of
which represent the silent white majority of the student body. Most
students do not want a ban of `hate speech.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the pamphlets were not hateful. ``Being familiar
with the literature, I must argue that it is not so much `hate
literature' as much as truth that reflects poorly on nonwhites,''
Smith wrote. ``The World Church stands for free speech and open
dialogue and is willing to debate the issues at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   His writings and distribution of pamphlets sparked a campus
debate on tolerance. The anthropology faculty wrote a letter to the
editor to quarrel with some of the racial history in Smith's
pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
   Smith lived in Touchdown Terrace, a somewhat run-down, 30-unit
student apartment complex with many minority residents. His
neighbors said he glared at minorities but did not act violently.
His only difficulty was that someone kept breaking the windows of
his car and his apartment, as often as once a week, apparently in
retaliation for his writings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about Benjamin `August' Smith, the person in my Race
and Ethnicity class last semester,'' said Tyrese Alexander, 23, a
black student who lived a few doors down from Smith. ``But I had no
idea I was living next to him.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what set off last week's violence, but Hale, the
World Church leader, believes that he knows. Hale's latest attempt
to become a lawyer in Illinois was rebuffed on Friday by a state
panel. Smith had testified for Hale at a hearing in April, praising
Hale's legal means.
</P>
<P>
   ``He testified that he might be in jail now if it wasn't for
me,'' Hale said. When asked if the adverse decision on Friday might
have sparked the killings, Hale said, ``I do. I very much do.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the accused killer is dead does not make
Bloomington feel safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben Smith may have taken his own life, but there's still far
too much hatred out there, in the community, in the world,'' said
Rabbi Sue L. Shifron, a founder of Bloomington United.
</P>
<P>
   ``While he may be gone, the organization that he was a part of
and hundreds of other organizations are still out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
